(309, 'From the importing country’s point of view, a tariff is better than a quota because[]', 'a tariff has a smaller effect on imports than does a quota.[]', 'a tariff has a larger effect on imports than does a quota.[]', 'the tariff generates tax revenue for the government.[]', 'both reduce imports but only quotas increase price.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(310, 'All of the following are used as arguments against free trade EXCEPT[]', 'free trade makes consumers worse off.[]', 'free trade can threaten national security.[]', 'free trade can destroy domestic jobs.[]', 'infant industries must be protected from free trade.[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(311, 'The General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT)[]', 'was enacted to lower trade barriers among European countries.[]', 'was enacted to lower trade barriers among the United States, Canada and Mexico.[]', 'was enacted after World War I in response to high tariffs imposed during the war.[]', 'is a series of continuing negotiations that has the goal of promoting free trade.[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(312, 'In the absence of externalities the invisible hand of the marketplace[]', 'induces people to act in a manner inconsistent with self-interest.[]', 'is unable to resolve inherent inefficiencies in the market system.[]', 'leads to a market outcome that maximizes total benefit to society.[]', 'increases the transactions cost of contracting between parties to an exchange.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(313, 'An externality exists when[]', 'a firm sells its product in a foreign market.[]', 'markets are not able to reach equilibrium.[]', 'the government intercedes in the operation of private markets by forcing the market to adjust to the balance of supply and demand.[]', 'a person engages in an activity that influences the well-being of a bystander and yet neither pays nor receives payment for that effect.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(314, 'An externality will[]', 'cause markets to allocate resources efficiently.[]', 'usually be characterized as a form of market failure.[]', 'strengthen the role of the “invisible hand” in the marketplace.[]', 'always require the producer to compensate society.[]', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(315, 'An optimal tax on pollution (a negative production externality) would be one in which[]', 'a benevolent social planner is able to maximize production.[]', 'producers internalize the cost of the pollution.[]', 'producers choose not to produce any pollution.[]', 'the value to consumers at market equilibrium exceeds the cost of production (including tax).[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(316, 'The figure reflects the presence of a[]', 'negative consumption externality.[]', 'positive consumption externality.[]', 'negative production externality.[]', 'positive production externality.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(317, 'According to the figure, which price and quantity combination represents the social optimum?[]', 'P1, Q0.[]', 'P3, Q0.[]', 'P1, Q1.[]', 'P2, Q1.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(318, 'Internalizing a negative production externality will cause the supply curve faced by an industry to[]', 'shift to the left.[]', 'shift to the right.[]', 'remain unchanged.[]', 'shift either right or left, depending on the industry.[]', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(319, 'To enhance the well-being of society, a social planner will encourage firms to increase production when[]', 'there is excess supply in the market.[]', 'the firms are producing basic goods.[]', 'technology spillovers are associated with production.[]', 'negative externalities associated with production are imposed only upon consumers.[]', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(320, 'A positive production externality will cause a market to produce[]', 'a quantity that is socially desirable.[]', 'more than is socially desirable.[]', 'less than is socially desirable.[]', 'more than is market optimal.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(321, 'Internalizing a positive production externality through a government subsidy will cause industry supply to[]', 'remain unchanged.[]', 'increase by an amount equal to the subsidy.[]', 'increase by an amount less than the subsidy.[]', 'decrease by an amount greater than the subsidy.[]', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(322, 'A positive consumption externality occurs when[]', 'Jack’s consumption is not beneficial to John.[]', 'Jack receives personal benefits from his own consumption of a certain good.[]', 'Jack’s benefit exceeds John’s benefit when they each consume the same good.[]', 'Jack receives a benefit from John’s consumption of a certain good.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(323, 'A negative consumption externality will cause a private market to produce[]', 'more than is socially desirable.[]', 'less than is socially desirable.[]', 'less than is market optimal.[]', 'the socially desirable quantity.[]', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(324, 'When dealing with externalities, the market equilibrium can be moved closer to the social equilibrium by[]', 'taxing negative externalities and subsidizing positive externalities.[]', 'taxing both positive and negative externalities.[]', 'subsidizing both positive and negative externalities.[]', 'None of the above, because government has no corrective policy with regards to consumption externalities.[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(325, 'Firms that are involved in different types of business could be evidence of an attempt to[]', 'increase private profit at the expense of consumers.[]', 'internalize some forms of positive externalities.[]', 'increase the marginal external cost of production.[]', 'reduce the impact of government regulation on their business.[]', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(326, 'All remedies for externalities share the goal of[]', 'increasing the allocation of resources.[]', 'decreasing the allocation of resources.[]', 'moving the allocation of resources toward the market equilibrium.[]', 'moving the allocation of resources toward the social optimum.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(327, 'Dick owns a dog whose barking annoys Dick’s neighbor Jane. Suppose that the benefit of owning the dog is worth $500 to Dick and that Jane bears a cost of $700 from the barking. Assuming Dick has the legal right to keep the dog, a possible private solution to this problem is that[]', 'Jane pays Dick $650 to get rid of the dog.[]', 'Dick pays Jane $650 for her inconvenience.[]', 'Jane pays Dick $500 to get rid of the dog.[]', 'There is no private solution that would improve this situation.[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(328, 'Which of the following is true of the Coase theorem ?[]', 'The bargain outcome will be inefficient.[]', 'Interested parties can reach an outcome in which everyone is better off.[]', 'Interested parties will need an arbitrator in order to reach an agreement that is efficient.[]', 'Government intervention is necessary to solve the problem of externalities.[]', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(329, 'Employing a lawyer to draft and enforce a private contract between parties wishing to solve an externality problem is an example of[]', 'a sunk cost.[]', 'an implicit cost.[]', 'a transaction cost.[]', 'an opportunity cost.[]', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(330, 'Pigovian taxes[]', 'are rarely preferred to direct regulation.[]', 'are frequently used to discourage imports.[]', 'encourage consumers to avoid sales taxes by shopping on-line.[]', 'give factory owners an economic incentive to reduce pollution.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(331, 'A Pigovian tax[]', 'is a form of regulation.[]', 'allocates pollution to those factories that face the highest cost of reducing it.[]', 'works well for all types of externalities.[]', 'is deemed inferior to regulatory policy by most economists.[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(332, 'In some cases, pollution permits may be better than a Pigovian tax because[]', 'the government can set a maximum level of pollution using permits.[]', 'pollution permits allow for a market solution while a Pigovian tax does not.[]', 'pollution permits are never preferred over a Pigovian tax.[]', 'pollution permits generate more revenue for the government than a Pigovian tax.[]', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(333, 'Which of the following is NOT true concerning tradable pollution permits?[]', 'Tradable pollution permits are a scarce resource.[]', 'Tradable pollution permits can be traded in a market governed by supply and demand.[]', 'Tradable pollution permits eventually lead to an efficient elimination of all pollution.[]', 'Tradable pollution permits will be sold by firms that can reduce pollution at low costs.[]', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(334, 'Which of the following policies is government most inclined to use when faced with a positive externality?[]', 'permits[]', 'taxation[]', 'subsidies[]', 'usage fees[]', 3, 3, 'easy');
INSERT INTO `econ_easy` (`Qno`, `Question`, `Option1`, `Option2`, `Option3`, `Option4`, `Answer`, `marks`, `Complexity`) VALUES
(335, 'Externalities occur when[]', 'one person’s actions affect the well-being of a bystander.[]', 'the government imposes taxes.[]', 'increases in the price of oil cause gasoline prices to rise.[]', 'higher wages result in increased spending.[]', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(336, 'Private markets fail to account for externalities because[]', 'externalities don’t occur in private markets.[]', 'sellers include any costs associated with externalities in the price of their product.[]', 'decision makers in the market fail to take into account the external effects of their behavior.[]', 'the government can easily correct any adverse effect externalities may have on the market.[]', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(337, 'A beekeeper places his hives of bees in an orchard so that the bees can gather nectar to produce honey. As a result, the bees pollinate the orchard which increases the yield of fruit and also causes[]', 'a positive externality that benefits only the beekeeper.[]', 'a negative externality since the bees are a hazard to the orchard owner.[]', 'a positive externality that benefits only the owner of the orchard.[]', 'positive externalities that benefit both the beekeeper and the orchard owner.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(338, 'When negative production externalities are present in a market[]', 'private costs will be greater than social costs.[]', 'social costs will be greater than private costs.[]', 'government regulation to resolve the problem is necessary.[]', 'the market will not be able to reach any equilibrium situation.[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(339, 'A fertilizer plant emits a very foul odor (a negative externality) during the production process. If the government forces the plant to internalize the externality, then the[]', 'supply curve for fertilizer would shift to the right (down).[]', 'supply curve for fertilizer would shift to the left (up).[]', 'demand curve for fertilizer would shift to the right (up).[]', 'demand curve for fertilizer would shift to the left (down).[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(340, 'When a market experiences a positive consumption externality,[]', 'the demand curve does not reflect the value to society of the good.[]', 'too much of the good is being produced.[]', 'the government can internalize the externality by imposing a tax on the product.[]', 'the private value is greater than the social value.[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(341, 'Internalizing an externality refers to[]', 'the fact that sellers only consider their private costs when making a decision.[]', 'the fact that buyers only consider their private benefits when making a decision.	[]', 'altering incentives so people consider the external effects of their actions when making a decision.[]', 'government establishing agencies such as the Environmental Protection Agency to enforce regulations.[]', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(342, 'The government can internalize a positive production externality by[]', 'taxing production which would decrease supply.[]', 'taxing production which would increase supply.[]', 'subsidizing production which would decrease supply.[]', 'subsidizing production which would increase supply.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(343, 'Technology spillover means that[]', 'it is the government’s responsibility to subsidize firms which are engaged in high-tech research.[]', 'a firm’s research yields technological knowledge that can then be used by society as a whole.[]', 'those firms engaged in technology research may be taxed by the government if that research causes negative externalities in the market.[]', 'when firms invest in the latest production technology, the cost of that technology ‘spills over’ to the prices consumers must pay for the product.[]', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(344, 'When a market experiences a positive production externality, we can expect a[]', 'smaller market output and a higher market price than optimal.[]', 'greater market output and lower market price than optimal.[]', 'greater market output and higher market price than optimal.[]', 'smaller market output and lower market price than optimal.[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(345, 'If the government wanted to ensure the market reaches the social optimum in the presence of a technology spillover, it should[]', 'impose a Pigovian tax on any firm producing a technology spillover.	[]', 'offer tax credits to consumers that are adversely affected by the new technology.[]', 'subsidize producers by an amount equal to the value of the technology spillover.[]', 'provide research grants to those firms not currently engaging in research to increase competition in the industry.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(346, 'When production externalities exist, policymakers can sometimes improve market outcomes by[]', 'taxing both positive and negative externalities.[]', 'subsidizing both positive and negative externalities.[]', 'taxing negative externalities and subsidizing positive externalities.[]', 'taxing positive externalities and subsidizing negative externalities.[]', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(347, 'When action is taken to remedy externalities, the goal is to[]', 'increase total production in the economy.[]', 'move the allocation of resources closer to the social optimum.[]', 'eliminate the externalities without affecting market outcomes.[]', 'hold the government accountable for eliminating these market failures.[]', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(348, 'The Coase theorem suggests that private markets may not be able to solve the problem of externalities[]', 'when the number of interested parties is large and costs are high.[]', 'if government does not become actively involved in the process.[]', 'if the firm in the market is a monopoly.[]', 'when market participants do not want the externality to be eliminated.[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(349, 'Roger enjoys an oak tree in his yard, but its leaves blow onto his neighbor Nancy’s yard each fall which she must clean up. If the benefit of the tree is worth $400 to Roger and the cost to Nancy of the tree is $600, which of the following statements would be true?[]', 'Nancy can pay Roger $200 to get rid of the tree.[]', 'Roger can pay Nancy $500 for her inconvenience.[]', 'Nancy can pay Roger $500 to get rid of the tree.[]', 'There is no private solution that would improve this situation.[]', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(350, 'Private solutions may not always be possible if negotiating and enforcing these solutions involve high[]', 'Pigovian taxes.[]', 'opportunity costs.[]', 'deadweight losses.[]', 'transaction costs.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(351, 'If only a few people are affected by an externality, then it is likely that[]', 'Pigovian taxes will provide the most efficient solution to the externality.[]', 'command-and-control regulation will provide the most efficient solution to the externality.[]', 'a private solution to the inefficiency will occur.[]', 'a private solution will be very difficult to negotiate.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(352, 'Emission controls on automobiles is an example of a[]', 'Pigovian tax on automobiles, based on how much they pollute.[]', 'command-and-control policy to increase social efficiency.[]', 'policy that reduces pollution by allocating resources through market mechanisms.[]', 'policy to reduce congestion on urban freeways.[]', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(353, 'A Pigovian tax is a tax[]', 'that will move the market away from the optimum quantity.[]', 'on pollution regulations.[]', 'that is enacted to correct the effects of a negative externality.[]', 'that special interest groups lobby for in order to decrease the cost of producing goods and services.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(354, 'A comparison between a Pigovian tax and tradable pollution permits shows that[]', 'both policies will effectively eliminate a positive externality in a market.[]', 'a Pigovian tax sets the price of pollution where pollution permits set the quantity of pollution.[]', 'levying a Pigovian tax is always preferable to issuing pollution permits.[]', 'a Pigovian tax fixes the acceptable pollution quantity where pollution permits allow for increases in pollution levels.[]', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(355, 'When one firm sells its pollution permit to another firm, each of the following will occur EXCEPT[]', 'both firms benefit.[]', 'social welfare is enhanced.[]', 'government revenue increases.[]', 'the total amount of pollution remains the same.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(356, 'What should policymakers do if they wish to encourage production (such as medical research) that provides a positive externality?[]', 'place taxes on the sale of prescription drugs[]', 'provide subsidies to firms engaged in medical research[]', 'impose years of trials and testing on selected medical procedures[]', 'ensure only the most qualified researchers are employed by issuing licenses to work at these firms[]', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(357, 'A good is excludable if[]', 'it is not a normal good.[]', 'people can be prevented from using it.[]', 'the government regulates its availability.[]', 'one person’s use of the good diminishes another person’s enjoyment of it.[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(358, 'If one person’s use of a good diminishes another person’s enjoyment of it, the good is[]', 'rival.[]', 'normal.[]', 'excludable.[]', 'exhaustible.[]', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(359, 'Goods that are nonexcludable and nonrival are[]', 'common resources.[]', 'natural monopolies.[]', 'private goods.[]', 'public goods.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(360, 'The market does not provide national defense because[]', 'the fixed cost of national defense is too high.[]', 'the resources to operate national defense are not available in the private sector.[]', 'it is impossible to prevent any single person from enjoying the benefit of national defense.[]', 'all of the above[]', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(361, 'The fish in the ocean are an example of a[]', 'private good.[]', 'public good.[]', 'common resource.[]', 'natural monopoly good.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(362, 'Due to the externalities associated with public goods and common resources,[]', 'private markets will lead to an efficient allocation of resources.[]', 'private markets will correct for the gain or loss in consumer surplus.[]', 'government intervention can potentially raise economic well-being.[]', 'all of the above[]', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(363, 'Market failure associated with the free-rider problem is a result of []', 'a problem associated with pollution.[]', 'a project in which costs exceed benefits.[]', 'losses that accrue to providers of the product.[]', 'benefits that accrue to those who don’t pay.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(364, 'Basic research is a public good because it[]', 'is a rival good.[]', 'is difficult to exclude those who might benefit from it.[]', 'is used to develop public goods.[]', 'always benefits developed countries at the expense of developing countries.[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(365, 'If everyone benefits from helping the poor,[]', 'taxing the wealthy to raise the living standards of the poor can potentially make everyone better off.[]', 'government intervention can only make things worse.[]', 'eliminating taxes aimed at redistributing income will necessarily make rich people better off.[]', 'private markets can adequately provide charity programs to help the poor despite free-rider problems.[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(366, 'A lighthouse is typically considered a good example of a public good because[]', 'there is rarely another lighthouse nearby to provide competition.[]', 'all passing ships are able to enjoy the benefits of the lighthouse without paying.[]', 'a nearby port authority cannot avoid paying fees to the lighthouse owner.[]', 'the owner of the lighthouse is able to exclude beneficiaries from enjoying the lighthouse.[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(367, 'Which of the following suggests that individuals do not place an infinite value on human life?[]', 'sky-diving[]', 'road intersections without stop signs[]', 'cars that are manufactured and purchased without the latest safety features[]', 'all of the above[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(368, 'Some goods can be either common resources or public goods depending on[]', 'the marginal cost of the good.[]', 'whether the good is rival.[]', 'how policymakers deal with the good.[]', 'none of the above.[]', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(369, 'One way to eliminate the Tragedy of the Commons is to[]', 'limit access to the commons.[]', 'increase access to the commons.[]', 'increase law enforcement in public areas.[]', 'provide more public land for recreation.[]', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(370, 'Overuse of common resources can potentially be resolved by governments that[]', 'subsidize use.[]', 'deregulate use.[]', 'convert the common resource to a private good.[]', 'all of the above[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(371, 'If a road is congested, then use of that road by an additional person would lead to a[]', 'positive externality.[]', 'negative externality.[]', 'natural monopoly problem.[]', 'free-rider problem with rush hour drivers stuck in traffic.[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(372, 'In an attempt to improve the pollution problem outside the central city of Singapore, the Singapore government[]', 'charges a premium tax on gasoline.[]', 'allows only motorcycle and bicycle transportation.[]', 'auctions off the right to license new cars.[]', 'does not allow taxis to travel outside the central city.[]', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(373, 'Excessive fishing occurs because[]', 'fishermen have other marketable skills and do not fear exploitation of fish reserves.[]', 'fishermen rely on government managers to worry about fish populations.[]', 'each individual fisherman has little incentive to maintain the species for the next year.[]', 'fishermen are concerned about the population dynamics of fish biomass, not current harvest rates.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(374, 'The U.S. government protects fish by[]', 'subsidizing the fishing industry.[]', 'heavily taxing competing industries.[]', 'increasing taxes on fishing poles and lures.[]', 'selling fishing licenses and regulating fish lengths.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(375, 'Why do elephants face the threat of extinction while cows do not?[]', 'There is a high demand for products that come only from the cow.[]', 'Cattle are owned by ranchers, while elephants are owned by no one.[]', 'There are still lots of cattle that roam free, while most elephants are in zoos.[]', 'Cattle are a valuable source of income for many people and elephants have no market value.[]', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(376, 'A good solution to saving the tiger from extinction would be to[]', 'tax the sale of tiger hides.[]', 'outlaw the sale of tigers or any part of them.[]', 'give the tigers’ habitat to someone.[]', 'regulate the traditional use of Asian medicines that use tiger liver.[]', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(377, 'To most economists, the best solution to the overcrowding problem at Yellowstone National park is to[]', 'increase financial aid from the government.[]', 'place daily quotas on the number of vehicles that enter the park.[]', 'increase entrance fees to the park.[]', 'temporarily close down damaged sections of the park.[]', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(378, 'When a good does not have a price attached to it, private markets[]', 'are characterized by market failure.[]', 'can sometimes be improved by the government.[]', 'cannot ensure that the good is produced and consumed in the proper amounts.[]', 'all of the above[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(379, 'Fire protection is a good example of a natural monopoly good because[]', 'it is rival.[]', 'it is nonexcludable.[]', 'it is always provided by the government.[]', 'protecting an extra house is unlikely to reduce the protection available to others.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(380, 'According to experience, the most effective solution to highway congestion is to[]', 'build more roads.[]', 'discourage urban sprawl by subsidizing urban apartment rents.[]', 'set a price for access to roads, which is paid by those who use them.[]', 'limit access to roads during the most congested times of the day.[]', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(381, 'A common theme among examples of market failure is[]', 'the good being provided always harms society in some systematic way.[]', 'there are regulations that prohibit the efficient functioning of private markets.[]', 'some item of value does not have an owner with the legal authority to control it.[]', 'cost–benefit analysis is likely to lead to implementation policies that promote private provision of goods and services.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(382, 'Two characteristics of any private good are[]', 'excludable and nonrival.[]', 'excludable and rival.[]', 'nonexcludable and rival.[]', 'nonexcludable and nonrival.[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(383, 'What is meant by the non-excludability characteristic of public goods?[]', 'The government produces a good whether or not anyone wants to purchase the good.[]', 'The marginal cost of producing another unit of a good is zero.[]', 'Only the rich can afford a good so the poor are excluded.[]', 'The nature of a good allows individuals who do not pay for the good to consume it.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(384, 'A good that is both nonrival and excludable would be a[]', 'common resource good.[]', 'natural monopoly.[]', 'public good.[]', 'private good.[]', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(385, 'Which characteristic is associated with both public goods as well as common resources?[]', 'rival[]', 'nonrival[]', 'excludable[]', 'nonexcludable[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(386, 'Which of the following will NOT occur when a person uses a common resource?[]', 'It causes an externality.[]', 'Others will be worse off.[]', 'No one else will be able to use the common resource.[]', 'The person will probably not be charged for using the common resource.[]', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(387, 'Which of the following would NOT be considered a private good?[]', 'clothing[]', 'pizza[]', 'Palm Pilot[]', 'cable TV[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(388, 'If the provision of public goods were left to the private sector[]', 'the outcome would be more efficient, because the government is notoriously inefficient.[]', 'more of the public goods would be produced than society desires.[]', 'the free-rider problem would cause less than the efficient quantity to be produced.[]', 'the government would be forced to raise taxes.[]', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(389, 'A free rider is a[]', 'person who will only purchase a product on sale.[]', 'person who receives the benefit of a good but avoids paying for it.[]', 'supplier who can produce a good at no cost.[]', 'person who takes advantage of tax loop-holes to lower his taxes.[]', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(390, 'Public goods such as national defense are provided by the government because[]', 'it is impossible for private markets to produce public goods.[]', 'products provided by the government can be produced more efficiently.[]', 'free riders make it difficult for private markets to supply the socially optimal quantity.[]', 'if the good were produced in private markets, most likely too much of the product would be produced.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(391, 'If the government decided to build a new highway, the first step would be to conduct a study to determine the value of the project. This study would be called a[]', 'fiscal analysis.[]', 'monetary analysis.[]', 'welfare analysis.[]', 'cost–benefit analysis.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(392, 'It is apparent that externalities are present in a market whenever[]', 'a shortage exists.[]', 'the price is higher than equilibrium price.[]', 'private costs differ from social costs.[]', 'the seller is not making a profit.[]', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(393, 'Each of the following explain why cost–benefit analysis is such a difficult job EXCEPT[]', 'there is no price with which to judge the value of a public good.[]', 'surveys are often biased and unreliable.[]', 'it is difficult to identify all factors that influence the costs and benefits of public goods.[]', 'government projects rarely have sufficient funding to complete projects on time.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(394, 'To increase safety at a bad intersection, you must decide whether to install a traffic light in your hometown at a cost of $10,000. If the traffic light reduces the risk of fatality by 0.5 percent and the value of a human life is about $10 million, you should[]', 'install the light because the expected benefit of $50,000 is greater than the cost.[]', 'install the light because the expected benefit of $20,000 is greater than the cost.[]', 'not install the light because the expected benefit of $10,000 is only equal to the cost.[]', 'not install the light because the expected benefit of $5,000 is less than the cost.[]', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(395, 'When trying to determine if Americans would be willing to spend $1 billion to successfully restore salmon in the Snake River, the Army Corps of Engineers would be determining[]', 'moral value.[]', 'existence value.[]', 'restoration value.[]', 'public value.[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(396, 'Suppose twenty ranchers jointly own 5000 acres. Their cows graze on the land during spring and summer. The land becomes over-grazed. This is an example of[]', 'the Tragedy of the Commons.[]', 'an assignment of pollution rights.[]', 'negligence.[]', 'a positive externality.[]', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(397, 'The Tragedy of the Commons can be corrected by[]', 'providing more of the resource for public use.[]', 'assigning property rights to individuals.[]', 'providing government subsidies for the resource.[]', 'making certain everyone in the economy has access to the resource.[]', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(398, 'If the use of a common resource is not regulated,[]', 'it cannot be used by anyone.[]', 'the economy will end up with too much of a good thing.[]', 'it becomes a private good.[]', 'it will be overused.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(399, 'Knowledge is a good example of a[]', 'public good.[]', 'private good.[]', 'common resource.[]', 'natural monopoly good.[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(400, 'In an attempt to remedy the presence of a negative externality such as pollution in a market, the government may choose to impose a[]', 'Pigovian tax.[]', 'subsidy.[]', 'command-and-control policy.[]', 'Coase theorem solution.[]', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(401, 'If a road is congested, then use of that road by an additional person would lead to a[]', 'negative externality.[]', 'positive externality.[]', 'natural monopoly problem.[]', 'free-rider problem with rush hour drivers stuck in traffic.[]', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(402, 'The reason why elephants are endangered and cows are not is because[]', 'cows are not as valuable as elephants.[]', 'elephants are a common resource and cows are a private good.[]', 'cows are a common resource and elephants are a private good.[]', 'it is legal to kill cows, but not elephants.[]', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(403, 'It is common knowledge that many U.S. national parks have become overused. One possible solution to this problem is to[]', 'increase entrance fees.[]', 'conduct a study to determine the carrying capacity of the individual parks.[]', 'reduce the national park service budget.[]', 'All of the above are possible solutions.[]', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(404, 'National parks have become “overrun and overtrampled” primarily because[]', 'park administrators have not historically been the best managers of park resources.[]', 'national parks are treated as free goods by their visitors.[]', 'fees charged at national parks are used by the government to provide other public goods and not for park upkeep.[]', 'the entrance fee to national parks today is comparable to the fee charged at Disney World.[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(405, 'One problem that occurs when the government places a tax on gasoline is that it[]', 'does nothing to reduce traffic on the highways.[]', 'does not affect driving behavior at all.[]', 'does nothing to internalize the congestion externality problem.[]', '	discourages driving on congested roads, but also on noncongested roads that have no congestion externality.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(406, 'In all cases, the market fails to allocate resources efficiently because[]', 'the government refuses to intervene in private markets.[]', 'property rights are not well established.[]', 'individuals in private markets become too greedy.[]', 'only the government can allocate resources efficiently.[]', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(407, 'In designing a tax system, policymakers have two objectives:[]', 'equity and revenue.[]', 'revenue and debt reduction.[]', 'equity and efficiency.[]', 'revenue and expenditure.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(408, 'The most common explanation for Social Security payments accounting for a larger share of federal government expenditures is[]', 'falling payroll tax receipts.[]', 'increases in life expectancy.[]', 'increases in birth rates among teenagers and the poor.[]', 'people becoming eligible for Social Security benefits at an earlier age.[]', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(409, 'In general, the two most important taxes for state and local governments are[]', 'sales taxes and property taxes.[]', 'sin taxes and gasoline taxes.[]', 'income taxes and estate taxes.[]', 'excise taxes and corporate taxes.[]', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(410, 'The biggest single expenditure for state and local governments is[]', 'Social Security.[]', 'education.[]', 'transportation.[]', 'unemployment compensation.[]', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(411, 'The largest source of revenue for the federal government is the[]', 'property tax.[]', 'corporate income tax.[]', 'individual income tax.[]', 'import and export tax.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(412, 'As government debt increases,[]', 'a trade-off with government deficits is inevitable.[]', 'government must spend a larger share of its revenue on interest payments.[]', 'evidence suggests that spending on social insurance programs will be reduced.[]', 'all of the above[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(413, 'A tax on the wages that a firm pays its workers is called a(n)[]', 'payroll tax.[]', 'excise tax.[]', 'income tax.[]', 'consumption tax.[]', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(414, 'When government receipts exceed total government spending during a fiscal year the difference[]', 'is a budget deficit.[]', 'is a budget surplus.[]', 'is the national debt.[]', 'becomes federal tax refunds.[]', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(415, 'When taxes are imposed on a commodity,[]', 'there is never a deadweight loss.[]', 'these taxes are considered nondistortionary.[]', 'tax revenue will rise by the amount of the tax multiplied by the before-tax level of consumption.[]', 'some consumers alter their consumption by not purchasing the taxed commodity.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(416, 'The U.S. income tax[]', 'encourages saving.[]', 'has no effect on saving.[]', 'discourages saving.[]', 'will reduce the administrative burden of taxation.[]', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(417, 'When a taxpayer attempts to legally reduce her tax liability, she is engaging in[]', 'tax evasion.[]', 'tax avoidance.[]', 'a tax return compensation plan.[]', 'activities outside the intent of tax law.[]', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(418, 'When tax laws give preferential treatment to specific types of behavior it is called[]', 'a political payoff.[]', 'tax evasion.[]', 'a tax loophole.[]', 'compensation for the benefit of society.[]', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(419, 'As tax laws become more complex,[]', 'compliance costs are most likely to decrease.[]', 'the administrative burden of taxes is increased.[]', 'the government always collects more in tax revenue.[]', 'the amount of tax revenue lost to tax evasion always decreases.[]', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(420, 'If marginal tax rates increase, the[]', 'average tax rate will be falling.[]', 'deadweight loss from taxes will rise.[]', 'deadweight loss from taxes is unaffected.[]', 'deadweight loss from taxes will be reduced.[]', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(421, 'The extra taxes paid on an additional dollar of taxable income is called the[]', 'average tax liability.[]', 'average tax rate.[]', 'marginal tax liability.[]', 'marginal tax rate.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(422, 'If the government were to impose a tax that assigned everyone the same tax liability, it would be[]', 'an equitable tax.[]', 'a lump-sum tax.[]', 'supported by the poor.[]', 'all of the above.[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(423, 'The benefits principle of taxation can be used to argue that the wealthy should pay higher taxes than the poor on the basis that[]', 'the poor are more active in political processes.[]', 'police services are more frequently used in poor neighborhoods.[]', 'there is more crime in rich neighborhoods than poor neighborhoods.[]', 'the wealthy benefit more from services provided by government than the poor.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(424, 'When the marginal tax rate exceeds the average tax rate, the tax is[]', 'progressive.[]', 'regressive.[]', 'proportional.[]', 'non-egalitarian.[]', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(425, 'The “flypaper theory” of taxation suggests that[]', 'taxes are never paid by the most wealthy citizens.[]', 'the benefits principle of taxation is not a viable option for policymakers.[]', 'the individual or corporation who actually pays the tax cannot share the burden of the tax.[]', 'the individual or corporation who actually pays the tax is able to shift the burden of the tax to others[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(426, '“A $1,000 tax paid by a poor person may be a larger sacrifice than a $10,000 tax paid by a wealthy person” is an argument based on the[]', 'regressive tax argument.[]', 'horizontal equity principle.[]', 'ability-to-pay principle.[]', 'benefits principle.[]', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(427, 'Vertical equity states that taxpayers with a greater ability to pay taxes should[]', 'contribute a larger amount.[]', 'be less subject to administrative burdens of a tax.[]', 'be less subject to tax distortions that lead to deadweight losses.[]', 'contribute a decreasing proportion of each increment in income to taxes.[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(428, 'Which of the following is a tax system in which all taxpayers pay the same percentage of their income in taxes?[]', 'regressive[]', 'progressive[]', 'proportional[]', 'horizontal equity[]', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(429, 'When the government levies a tax on a corporation,[]', 'all the burden of the tax ultimately falls on owners.[]', 'there are very few distortions to individual incentives.[]', 'it is meeting all of the requirements for vertical equity.[]', 'the corporation is more like a tax collector than a taxpayer.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(430, 'The essence of most proposals for a flat tax are captured in[]', 'a single, low tax rate applied to all income above a certain level.[]', 'an initial low flat tax rate that increases as a taxpayer’s income increases.[]', 'a single tax rate with many exemptions that provide incentives to people who save.[]', 'a lump-sum tax that all taxpayers must pay, and then a fixed low tax rate for all income above a certain level.[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(431, 'Incentives to work and save are reduced when[]', 'income taxes are higher.[]', 'Pigovian taxes are implemented.[]', 'consumption taxes replace income taxes.[]', 'all of the above[]', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(432, 'Which of the following statements is correct?[]', 'Since 1980, government revenue as a percent of GDP has declined in the United States.[]', 'When government revenues exceed government spending, government is said to be running a deficit.[]', 'National defense is the largest outlay for the federal government.[]', 'As a nation gets richer, its tax burden typically increases as well.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(433, 'State and local governments receive the largest portion of their tax revenues from[]', 'social insurance taxes and excise taxes.[]', 'sales taxes and property taxes.[]', 'estate taxes and income taxes.[]', 'corporate income taxes and sales taxes.[]', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(434, 'A person’s tax liability refers to[]', 'the percentage of income that a person must pay in taxes.[]', 'the amount of income tax a person owes to the government.[]', 'the amount of tax the government is required to refund each person.[]', 'deductions that can be legally subtracted from a person’s income each year.[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(435, 'The government finances the budget deficit by[]', 'borrowing from the public.[]', 'printing currency in the amount of the budget deficit.[]', 'selling government services for a large profit to the public.[]', 'requiring that budget surpluses occur every two years to pay off the deficits.[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(436, 'Which component of federal government spending is the largest?[]', 'national defense[]', 'health and education[]', 'Social Security[]', 'interest on the debt[]', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(437, 'With a progressive income tax, marginal tax rates rise as income rises. This means that in general,[]', 'rich families will benefit at the expense of poor families.[]', 'every family will pay the same percentage of their income in taxes.[]', 'lower-income families will pay a larger percentage of their income in taxes.[]', 'higher-income families will pay a larger percentage of their income in taxes.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(438, 'A tax levied on the total amount spent in retail stores is called a[]', 'sales tax.[]', 'excise tax.[]', 'corporate tax.[]', 'proportional tax.[]', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(439, 'The deadweight loss associated with a tax on a product occurs because[]', 'the revenue generated by the tax will be wasted by the government.[]', 'those purchasing the product will now have to pay a higher price for the product.[]', 'costs to firms will increase since they will be responsible for collecting the tax.[]', 'some consumers will choose not to consume the product that is taxed.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(440, 'When the government places a tax on labor earnings, one result is that people[]', 'will have less incentive to work.[]', 'try to save more of the income they get to keep.[]', 'will choose to work more in an attempt to replace the loss from the tax.[]', 'tend to start their own business so their income will not be considered labor earnings.[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(441, 'Tax evasion is[]', 'a legal way to keep from paying taxes.[]', 'always illegal.[]', 'filing taxes after the April 15th deadline.[]', 'the same thing as tax avoidance.[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(442, 'Each of the following is a reason why tax loopholes exist EXCEPT[]', 'ambiguities in tax laws.[]', 'special treatment of specific types of behavior.[]', 'preferential tax treatment for some business activities.[]', 'the lack of consistent interpretations of the tax laws by the Supreme Court.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(443, 'The marginal tax rate for a lump-sum tax[]', 'is always zero.[]', 'is usually positive.[]', 'is usually negative.[]', 'can be either positive or negative, depending on the amount of income earned.[]', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(444, 'One way to reduce the administrative burden of the tax system is to[]', 'require taxpayers to keep adequate financial records throughout the year.[]', 'simplify the tax laws.[]', 'hire a part-time accountant or tax attorney.[]', 'change the April 15th tax deadline to give taxpayers additional time to file their tax returns.[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(445, 'If the government taxes the first $50,000 of a person’s income at 20% and all income above $50,000 at 50%, then a person making $80,000 would be required to pay how much in taxes?[]', '$10,000[]', '$15,000[]', '$20,000[]', '$25,000[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(446, 'If the government were attempting to get people to save more of their income they might choose to impose a[]', 'consumption tax.[]', 'lump-sum tax.[]', 'progressive tax.[]', 'regressive tax.[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(447, 'A well-designed tax system addresses both[]', 'equity and government revenue.[]', 'equity and efficiency.[]', 'government revenue and debt reduction.[]', 'government revenue and expenditure.[]', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(448, 'If Shannon earns $60,000 a year and pays $12,000 in taxes while Sean earns $90,000 yearly and pays $18,000 in taxes, this income tax system would be[]', 'lump-sum.[]', 'proportional.[]', 'regressive.[]', 'progressive.[]', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(449, 'Lump-sum taxes are rarely used in the real world because they[]', 'have high deadweight losses.[]', 'have high administrative burdens.[]', 'are very inefficient.[]', 'take the same amount of money from both poor and rich.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(450, 'The “marriage tax” refers to[]', 'the increase in income exclusion a married couple faces over two single people.[]', 'the tax that must be paid in most states to receive a marriage license.[]', 'a couple’s tax liability increasing as a result of getting married.[]', 'married couples with the same income always pay the same amount of income taxes.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(451, 'The greater the resources devoted to complying with tax laws the[]', 'higher the administrative burden of a tax.[]', 'lower the deadweight loss of a tax.[]', 'lower the administrative burden of a tax.[]', 'more regressive the tax system becomes.[]', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(452, 'The concept that each citizen should make an ‘equal sacrifice’ and pay taxes according to how well that person can shoulder the burden is called[]', 'the benefits principle.[]', 'vertical equity.[]', 'the ability-to-pay principle.[]', 'horizontal equity.[]', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(453, 'The argument that might be used to require wealthier taxpayers to pay more in taxes for law enforcement because they own more and therefore have more to protect than poorer taxpayers would be based on[]', 'vertical equity.[]', 'horizontal equity.[]', 'the ability-to-pay principle.[]', 'the benefits principle.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(454, 'Horizontal equity refers to the idea that[]', 'taxpayers with a greater ability to pay taxes should pay larger amounts.[]', 'taxpayers with similar abilities to pay taxes should pay the same amount.[]', 'all taxpayers should pay the same fraction of income regardless of ability.[]', 'taxpayers should pay taxes based on the benefits they receive from government services.[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(455, 'The corporate income tax[]', 'satisfies both equity and efficiency considerations.[]', 'does not distort the incentives of customers since it is imposed on corporations.[]', 'is the best example of why the flypaper theory of tax incidence is correct.[]', 'falls ultimately on the owners, workers and customers of the corporation.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(456, 'Which of the following statements would NOT be used by an advocate of the flat tax?[]', 'The flat tax would eliminate many of the deductions allowed under the current income tax.[]', 'Because the flat tax is so simple, the administrative burden of the tax would be greatly reduced.[]', 'Flat taxes have no deadweight loss.[]', 'The flat tax is more like a consumption tax which would increase the incentive to save.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(457, 'Total revenue necessarily equals[]', 'total output multiplied by the average cost of output.[]', 'total output multiplied by sales price of output.[]', '(total output multiplied by sales price) – inventory surplus.[]', '(total output multiplied by the average cost of output) – inventory shortage.[]', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(458, 'An example of an implicit cost of production would be the[]', 'cost of raw materials for a printing company to print books.[]', 'income an entrepreneur could have earned working elsewhere.[]', 'cost of a delivery truck in a business that rarely makes deliveries.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(459, 'In economics, the field of industrial organization answers which of the following questions?[]', 'Why are consumers subject to the law of demand?[]', 'Why do firms experience falling marginal product of labor?[]', 'Why do firms consider production costs when determining product supply?[]', 'How does the difference in the number of firms affect prices and efficiency of market outcomes?[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(460, 'According to this scenario, what is the explicit cost of purchasing the factory for the first year of operation?[]', '$10,000[]', '$20,000[]', '$30,000[]', '$40,000[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(461, 'According to this scenario, what is the opportunity cost of purchasing the factory for the first year of operation?[]', '$10,000[]', '$20,000[]', '$30,000[]', '$40,000[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(462, 'The marginal product of labor can be defined as (where . denotes “change”)[]', '	profit//labor.[]', '	output//labor.[]', '	labor//total cost.[]', '	labor//output.[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(463, 'Diminishing marginal product of labor would arise when[]', 'workers are discouraged about the lack of help from other workers.[]', 'only new workers are trained in using the most productive capital.[]', 'crowded office space reduces the productivity of new workers.[]', 'union workers are told to reduce their work effort in preparation for a new round of collective bargaining talks.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(464, 'The slope of the total product curve reveals information about the[]', 'marginal product of workers.[]', 'average product of workers.[]', 'maximum product of workers.[]', 'total product of workers.[]', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(465, 'According to the figure, which of the statements below best captures information about the underlying production function?[]', 'Output increases at an increasing rate with additional units of input.[]', 'Output decreases at an increasing rate with additional units of input.[]', 'Output increases at a decreasing rate with additional units of input.[]', 'Output decreases at a decreasing rate with additional units of input.[]', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(466, 'According to the figure, which of the statements below concerning production is most consistent with the shape of the total cost curve?[]', 'Producing an additional coffee mug always has a higher cost than producing the previous coffee mug.[]', 'Producing an additional coffee mug is always less costly than producing the previous coffee mug.[]', 'Producing an additional coffee mug always has the same cost as producing the previous coffee mug.[]', 'None of the above is correct for all quantities.[]', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(467, 'Which of the following costs will be zero if a firm produces zero?[]', 'average cost[]', 'variable cost[]', 'opportunity cost[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(468, 'The cost to produce an additional unit of output is the firm’s[]', 'average variable cost.[]', 'marginal cost.[]', 'average opportunity cost.[]', 'total productivity cost.[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(469, 'Average total cost equals[]', '(fixed costs + variable costs)/quantity produced.[]', '(fixed costs + variable costs)/change in quantity produced.[]', 'change in total costs/quantity produced.[]', 'change in total costs/change in quantity produced.[]', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(470, 'If we assume that marginal product of labor is always decreasing, average total cost[]', 'and average fixed cost are always falling.[]', 'and average fixed cost are always U-shaped.[]', 'and average fixed cost are always rising.[]', 'is U-shaped and average fixed cost is always falling.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(471, 'If marginal cost is rising[]', 'average total cost must be falling.[]', 'average fixed cost must be rising.[]', 'marginal product must be rising.[]', 'marginal product must be falling.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(472, 'Average total cost is very high when a small amount of output is produced because[]', 'average fixed cost is large.[]', 'of diminishing marginal product.[]', 'variable costs are spread over only a few units of output.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(473, 'At all levels of production beyond the point where the marginal cost curve crosses the average variable cost curve, average variable cost[]', 'falls.[]', 'rises.[]', 'does not change.[]', 'All of the above are possible, it depends on the shape of the marginal cost curve.[]', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(474, 'According to the figure, which of the lines is most likely to represent average total cost?[]', 'A[]', 'B[]', 'C[]', 'D[]', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(475, 'According to the figure, which of the lines is most likely to represent marginal cost?[]', 'A[]', 'B[]', 'C[]', 'D[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(476, 'According to the figure, this particular firm is necessarily experiencing increasing marginal product when line[]', 'B is falling.[]', 'C is falling.[]', 'D is falling.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(477, 'According to the figure, line D is necessarily U-shaped because of[]', 'the fact that decreasing marginal product follows increasing marginal product.[]', 'the fact that increasing marginal product follows decreasing marginal product.[]', 'diminishing marginal product.[]', 'increasing marginal product.[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(478, 'When a factory is operating in the short run,[]', 'it cannot alter variable costs.[]', 'total cost and variable cost are usually the same.[]', 'average fixed cost rises as output increases.[]', 'it cannot adjust the quantity of some inputs.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(479, 'According to the figure, suppose the firm currently operates on the minimum of ATCB. If it increases production, but not all the way to N, then short-run average total cost[]', 'and long-run average total cost increase.[]', 'and long-run average total cost decrease.[]', 'rises and long-run average total cost is unchanged.[]', 'is unchanged and long-run average total cost increases.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(480, 'According to the figure, this firm experiences diseconomies of scale at what output levels?[]', 'output levels above N[]', 'output levels between M and N[]', 'output levels below M[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(481, 'Economies of scale arise when[]', 'an economy is self-sufficient in production.[]', 'individuals in a society are self-sufficient.[]', 'workers are able to specialize in a particular task.[]', 'fixed costs are large relative to variable costs.[]', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(482, 'Susan’s firm produces 2,000 beach towels and sells them for $10 each. Her total cost of producing these towels is $10,000. Her total profits[]', 'are $30,000.[]', 'are $20,000.[]', 'are $10,000.[]', 'cannot be computed from the information provided.[]', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(483, 'Alan produces modems. Included in his cost are (i) what it costs him to purchase parts and (ii) the salary he could have earned if he had worked for Microsoft instead.[]', 'both (i) and (ii) are explicit costs[]', 'both (i) and (ii) are implicit costs[]', '(i) is an explicit cost, (ii) is an implicit cost[]', '(i) is an implicit cost, (ii) is an explicit cost[]', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(484, 'Alberto produces futons in a warehouse he paid for with $500,000 of winnings from a game show. He could instead have saved the money and earned interest on it. Economists would[]', 'consider this interest a cost and accountants would report it as a cost.[]', 'consider this interest a cost, but accountants would not report it as a cost.[]', 'not consider this interest a cost, but accountants would report it as a cost.[]', 'not consider this interest a cost and accountants would not report it as a cost.[]', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(485, 'Accounting profits equal total revenues minus[]', 'explicit costs. Economic profits equal total revenues minus implicit costs.[]', 'implicit costs. Economic profits equal total revenues minus explicit costs.[]', 'explicit and implicit costs. Economic profits equal total revenues minus implicit costs.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(486, 'A firm’s economic profit is equal to revenue less[]', 'explicit costs.[]', 'implicit costs.[]', 'money costs.[]', 'total opportunity costs.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(487, 'Which of the following is most directly a statement about the production function?[]', 'Alberto sells 1,000 futons for $700 each.[]', 'The opportunity costs for Susan to produce 10,000 beach towels is $15,000.[]', 'If he works for forty hours, Alan can make about 100 modems.[]', 'Bartholomew finds he maximizes profits by producing 10,000 hats.[]', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(488, 'Marginal product will be positive and diminishing if the production function slopes[]', 'downward and becomes flatter as more workers are hired.[]', 'downward and becomes steeper as more workers are hired.[]', 'upward and becomes flatter as more workers are hired.[]', 'upward and becomes steeper as more workers are hired.[]', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(489, 'Diminishing marginal product occurs[]', 'as additional workers have to share existing equipment and space.[]', 'as additional workers expect greater hourly wages than previous workers.[]', 'both a and b are correct[]', 'neither a nor b is correct[]', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(490, 'If a firm faces diminishing marginal product, then to produce an additional unit of output requires adding[]', 'more workers than were added to produce the previous unit, so total cost rises more than it rose to produce the previous unit.[]', 'more workers than were added to produce the previous unit, so total cost rises less than it rose to produce the previous unit.[]', 'fewer workers than were added to produce the previous unit, so total cost rises more than it rose to produce the previous unit.[]', 'fewer workers than were added to produce the previous unit, so total cost rises less than it rose to produce the previous unit.[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(491, 'Which of the following is correct if there is diminishing marginal product of labor? (i). As the number of workers hired increases, the production function gets steeper. (ii). As the quantity of output produced increases, the total cost curve gets flatter.[]', 'both (i) and (ii) are correct[]', 'neither (i) nor (ii) is correct[]', '(i) is correct, but (ii) is incorrect[]', '(ii) is correct, but (i) is incorrect[]', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(492, 'As the quantity of output increases, the total cost curve becomes[]', 'steeper because of diminishing marginal product.[]', 'steeper because of diminishing total product.[]', 'flatter because of diminishing marginal product.[]', 'flatter because of diminishing total product.[]', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(493, 'Which of the following is a fixed cost for the Peapod Vegetarian Restaurant?[]', 'the cost of fresh produce[]', 'the wages of servers[]', 'the rent paid on the lease[]', 'the cost of napkins[]', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(494, 'It costs a firm $4,400 to produce 23 units and $4,800 to produce 24 units If they are currently producing 24 units, their average total cost[]', 'and marginal cost are $200.[]', 'is $200 and their marginal cost is $400.[]', 'is $400 and their marginal cost is $200.[]', 'and their marginal cost is $400.[]', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(495, 'Sandy produces umbrellas. Her current production is 300 a month. Her average fixed cost is $2. Her average variable cost is $5. It follows that her total cost is[]', '$600.[]', '$900.[]', '$1,500.[]', '$2,100.[]', 4, 3, 'easy');
INSERT INTO `econ_easy` (`Qno`, `Question`, `Option1`, `Option2`, `Option3`, `Option4`, `Answer`, `marks`, `Complexity`) VALUES
(496, 'For levels of output above the efficient scale, as output increases average total cost[]', 'and average fixed cost both increase.[]', 'and average fixed cost both decrease.[]', 'increases and average fixed cost decreases.[]', 'decrease and average fixed cost increases.[]', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(497, 'A logging company produces timber at a point where marginal cost is $30 and average total cost is $45. It follows that[]', 'average cost is falling.[]', 'average cost is rising.[]', 'marginal cost is falling.[]', 'marginal cost is rising.[]', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(498, 'Which of the following cost curves would not typically fall and then rise as output increases?[]', 'AFC[]', 'ATC[]', 'AVC[]', 'MC[]', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(499, 'Which of the following curves will always be below the ATC curve?[]', 'the AFC and MC curves[]', 'the AFC and AVC curves[]', 'the AVC and MC curves[]', 'the AFC, AVC, and MC curves[]', 2, 1, 'easy');
INSERT INTO `econ_hard` (`Qno`, `Question`, `Option1`, `Option2`, `Option3`, `Option4`, `Answer`, `marks`, `Complexity`) VALUES
(1, 'Which would increase the capital stock of El Salvador and provide returns to U.S. investors?[]', 'U.S. foreign direct investment in El Salvador.[]', 'U.S. foreign portfolio investment in El Salvador.[]', 'Both of the above are correct.[]', 'Neither of the above is correct.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(2, 'U.S. foreign direct investment[]', 'raises both U.S. GDP and U.S. GNP.[]', 'raises neither U.S. GDP nor U.S. GNP.[]', 'raises U.S. GDP, but not U.S. GNP.[]', 'raises U.S. GNP, but not U.S. GDP.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(3, 'Which of the following is NOT correct?[]', 'Many economists would advise governments in less-developed economies to implement policies that encourage investment from abroad.[]', 'Lowering population growth rates can increase per-capita real GDP.[]', 'Some economists argue that education is particularly important because human capital has positive externalities.[]', 'In the long run, increases in the savings rate lead to increases in real GDP growth.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(4, 'Which of the following statements is correct? []', 'In general, a given level of investment in a poor country will lead to greater economic growth than the same level of investment in a rich country.[]', 'If a nation invests more, its economic growth rate will be permanently higher.[]', 'A nation must have abundant natural resources if it is to experience rapid economic growth.[]', 'Increased economic growth through increased investment does not have an opportunity cost.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(5, 'Generally speaking from society’s viewpoint, the returns to research and development undertaken by firms[]', 'is a public good.[]', 'is a private good.[]', 'should never be supported by government.[]', 'will never occur if a system of patents is not put into place.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(6, 'Suppose a German-owned automobile company opens a new car plant in Wayne, Nebraska.[]', 'This foreign direct investment increases U.S. real GDP more than it increases U.S. real GNP.[]', 'This foreign direct investment increases U.S. real GNP more than it increases U.S. real GDP.[]', 'This foreign portfolio investment increases U.S. real GDP more than it increases U.S. real GNP.[]', 'The foreign portfolio investment increases U.S. real GNP more than it increases U.S. real GDP.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(7, 'Which of the following can increase real GDP per person?[]', 'a decrease in population growth[]', 'foreign investment from abroad[]', 'policies to encourage international trade[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(8, 'When a country saves a smaller portion of its GDP, it will have[]', 'more investment, and so have more capital and higher productivity.[]', 'more investment, and so have less capital and lower productivity.[]', 'less investment, and so have more capital and higher productivity.[]', 'less investment, and so have less capital and lower productivity.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
