(100, 'Tom Crown operates a company that produces paintings for motels. Tom decides that if he pays his workers more that his profits will increase. Which of the following is a likely and logical explanation for his decision?[]', 'By paying higher wages, he will be able to charge more for the paintings his workers produce.[]', 'By paying higher wages, incompetent workers are less likely to apply.[]', 'By paying higher wages, workers are less likely to shirk.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(101, 'The theory of efficiency wages implies that if it became easier to accurately evaluate the workers’ abilities, wages[]', 'and unemployment would rise.[]', 'would rise and unemployment would fall.[]', 'would fall and unemployment would rise.[]', 'and unemployment would fall.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(102, 'Anything that makes the efficiency wage rise relative to the market-clearing wage will[]', 'increase both the quantity demanded and the quantity of labor supplied.[]', 'decrease both the quantity demanded and the quantity of labor supplied.[]', 'increase the quantity demanded and decrease the quantity of labor supplied.[]', 'decrease the quantity demanded and increase the quantity of labor supplied.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(103, 'Among experienced professors the ones with the least skills are most likely to be searching for jobs and as a result schools are likely to be skeptical of applications from all experienced professors. If workers have much say in who gets hired, they may find it in their best interest to avoid suggesting the hire of workers that may be superior to them.[]', 'Both examples illustrate adverse selection.[]', 'Both examples illustrate moral hazard.[]', 'The first example illustrates adverse selection, the second illustrates moral hazard.[]', 'The first example illustrates moral hazard, the second illustrates adverse selection.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(104, 'Which of the following would reduce the natural rate of unemployment?[]', 'The Internet provides more readily available information about available jobs.[]', 'Congress increases the minimum wage.[]', 'Union membership increases.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(105, 'Which of the following laws would increase the natural rate of unemployment?[]', 'Congress abolishes the minimum wage.[]', 'Congress passes laws that make it harder to find out about job candidates’ past job history.[]', 'Congress passes a law that makes all states adopt right-to-work laws.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(106, 'Barter[]', 'is more efficient than money.[]', 'makes trading easier than money.[]', 'allows greater specialization than money.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(107, 'Which of the following best illustrates the unit of account function of money?[]', 'You list prices for candy sold on your Web site, sweet-treats.com, in dollars.[]', 'You pay for tickets to a WNBA game with dollars.[]', 'You keep $10 in your backpack for emergencies.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(108, 'U.S. currency is currently []', 'commodity money with no intrinsic value.[]', 'fiat money with no intrinsic value.[]', 'commodity money with intrinsic value.[]', 'fiat money with intrinsic value.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(109, 'Since the U.S. government has decreed that U.S. currency is legal tender,[]', 'people may not legally make trades with anything else.[]', 'people are more likely to accept the dollar as a medium of exchange.[]', 'the government must hold enough gold to redeem all currency.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(110, 'M1 includes[]', 'savings deposits.[]', 'money market deposit accounts.[]', 'currency.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(111, 'Credit cards are[]', 'a method of deferring payment.[]', 'used as a medium of exchange.[]', 'part of the M2 money supply.[]', 'equivalent to debit cards.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(112, 'Which of the following might explain why the United States has so much currency per person?[]', 'Currency may be a preferable store of wealth for criminals.[]', 'U.S. citizens are holding a lot of foreign currency.[]', 'People use credit and debit cards more frequently.[]', 'All of the above help explain the abundance of currency.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(113, 'Which Federal Reserve Bank president is always a voting member of the FOMC?[]', 'Boston[]', 'New York[]', 'Chicago[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(114, 'The Federal Open-market Committee is made up of[]', '5 of the 12 presidents of the Federal Reserve Regional banks, and the 7 members of the Board of Governors.[]', 'the 12 presidents of the Federal Reserve Regional banks, and the Chair of the Board of Governors.[]', 'the 12 presidents of the Federal Reserve Regional banks, and the 7 members of the Board of Governors.[]', '7 of the 12 presidents of the Federal Reserve Regional banks, and the 5 members of the Board of Governors.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(115, 'The Fed can influence unemployment in []', 'the short run, but not the long run.[]', 'the short and long run.[]', 'the long run, but not the short run.[]', 'neither the short nor long run.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(116, 'On a bank’s T-account,[]', 'deposits are assets, reserves are liabilities.[]', 'reserves are assets, deposits are liabilities.[]', 'both deposits and reserves are assets.[]', 'both deposits and reserves are liabilities.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(117, 'If the reserve ratio is 5 percent and a bank receives a new deposit of $500, this bank[]', 'must increase its required reserves by $500.[]', 'will initially see its total reserves increase by $25.[]', 'will be able to make a new loan of $475.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(118, 'If the reserve requirement is 10 percent, the Last Bank of Hope[]', 'is holding excess reserves of $1,000.[]', 'is in a position to make a new loan of $2000.[]', 'has required reserves of $2,000.[]', 'has less reserves than required.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(119, 'If the Last Bank of Hope is holding only the amount of reserves required, the reserve requirement is[]', '100 percent.[]', '80 percent.[]', '20 percent.[]', '12.5 percent.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(120, 'If the reserve ratio is 25 percent, the money multiplier is[]', '2.[]', '4.[]', '5.[]', '8.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(121, 'If the reserve ratio is 15 percent, an additional $2,000 of reserves will increase the money supply by[]', '$1,500.[]', '$3,000.[]', '$13,150.[]', '$13,333.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(122, 'Which list contains only actions that decrease the money supply?[]', 'lower the discount rate, make open-market purchases[]', 'lower the discount rate, make open-market sales[]', 'raise the discount rate, make open-market purchases[]', 'raise the discount rate, make open-market sales[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(123, 'To increase the money supply, the Fed could[]', 'sell government bonds.[]', 'decrease the discount rate.[]', 'increase the reserve requirement.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(124, 'In a fractional reserve banking system, an increase in reserve requirements []', 'increases both the money multiplier and the money supply.[]', 'increases the money multiplier, but decreases the money supply.[]', 'decreases both the money multiplier and the money supply.[]', 'decreases the money multiplier, but increases the money supply.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(125, 'When the Fed increases the discount rate, banks will borrow []', 'less, banks will lend more, and the money supply will decrease.[]', 'less, banks will lend less, and the money supply will decrease.[]', 'more, banks will lend more, and the money supply will increase.[]', 'more, banks will lend less, and the money supply will decrease.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(126, 'The interest rate the Fed charges on loans it makes to banks is called the[]', 'discount rate.[]', 'federal funds rate.[]', 'prime rate.[]', 'FOMC rate.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(127, 'During the stock market crash of October 1987, the Fed[]', 'nearly created a financial panic by not acting as a lender of last resort.[]', 'nearly created a financial panic by raising the discount rate.[]', 'prevented a financial panic by providing liquidity to the financial system.[]', 'prevented a financial panic by raising reserve requirements.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(128, 'If the reserve ratio is 10 percent, and banks do not hold excess reserves, when the Fed purchases $10 million of government bonds, bank reserves []', 'decrease by $10 million and the money supply eventually decreases by $100 million.[]', 'decrease by $10 million and the money supply eventually increases by $100 million.[]', 'increase by $10 million and the money supply eventually decreases by $100 million.[]', 'increase by $10 million and the money supply eventually increases by $100 million.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(129, 'If banks choose to hold more excess reserves,[]', 'required reserves in the banking system increase.[]', 'the money multiplier will increase.[]', 'the discount rate will increase.[]', 'the money supply falls.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(130, 'The Fed can directly protect a bank during a bank run by[]', 'increasing reserve requirements.[]', 'selling government bonds to the bank.[]', 'lending reserves to the bank.[]', 'doing any of the above.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(131, 'Giving up a dollar bill to purchase an ice cream cone best illustrates money’s function as a[]', 'store of wealth.[]', 'unit of account.[]', 'medium of exchange.[]', 'standard of value. []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(132, 'Which of the following provides a store of value? []', 'U.S. currency []', 'stocks in Microsoft Corporation []', 'bonds issued by Mrs. Paul’s Corporation []', 'All the above are correct. []', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(133, 'Of the following assets which is the most liquid? []', 'stocks in Intel Corporation[]', 'a painting by van Gogh []', 'a used car[]', 'fine jewelry []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(134, 'Which of the following types of currency has intrinsic value? []', 'commodity money[]', 'fiat money []', 'both commodity money and fiat money []', 'neither commodity money nor fiat money []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(135, 'Which of the following is not contained in M1? []', 'currency[]', 'demand deposits []', 'savings deposits[]', 'traveler’s checks[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(136, 'M2 is []', 'smaller and less liquid than M1. []', 'smaller but more liquid than M1. []', 'larger but less liquid than M1. []', 'larger than and more liquid than M1. []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(137, 'Credit cards are a[]', 'store of value. []', 'method of deferring payments. []', 'medium of exchange included in both M1 and M2.[]', 'All of the above are correct. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(138, 'Which of the following pairs correctly list a function of the Fed and the part of the Fed directly responsible for the function.[]', 'income tax policy—Board of Governors[]', 'conduct open-market operations—The Chair of the Board of Governors[]', 'lender of last resort—New York Federal Reserve Bank[]', 'check clearing—regional Federal Reserve Banks[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(139, 'Which part of the Fed meets about every six weeks to discuss the economy and make changes in monetary policy?[]', 'the Board of Governors[]', 'the FOMC[]', 'the regional Federal Reserve Banks[]', 'the Central Bank Policy Commission[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(140, 'If the Fed makes open-market purchases it will[]', 'increase the money supply which will increase the price level. []', 'increase the money supply which will decrease the price level. []', 'decrease the money supply which will increase the price level. []', 'decrease the money supply which will decrease the price level. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(141, 'FOMC policy decisions have an important influence on the economy’s[]', 'rate of inflation in the long run and level of employment in the short run. []', 'rate of inflation and level of employment in the long run. []', 'rate of inflation in the short run and level of employment and long run. []', 'employment in the short run, but have no influence on inflation in either the short or long run. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(142, 'The First National Bank of Tinyville has $10,000 of reserves. If it is holding no excess reserves, and the reserve ratio is 10%, its deposits are[]', '$90,000.[]', '$99,000.[]', '$100,000.[]', '$110,000.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(143, 'Which of the following items is a liability to a bank? []', 'loans[]', 'reserves[]', 'deposits[]', 'an interest-bearing asset owned by the bank []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(144, 'If R is the reserve ratio, which of the following is the correct way to find the money multiplier?[]', '1 – R[]', '1/R[]', '1/(1 – R)[]', '(1+R)/R[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(145, 'The higher the reserve requirement ratio the[]', 'more of each deposit banks may lend out, and the larger the multiplier.[]', 'more of each deposit banks may lend out, and the smaller the multiplier.[]', 'less of each deposit banks may lend out, and the larger the multiplier.[]', 'less of each deposit banks may lend out, and the smaller the multiplier.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(146, 'The Fed’s most frequently used tool of monetary control is []', 'open-market operations. []', 'changes in reserve requirements. []', 'changes in the discount rate. []', 'bank runs.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(147, 'In 1991 the Federal Reserve lowered the reserve requirement ratio from 12% to 10%. This should have []', 'increased both the money multiplier and the money supply. []', 'increased both the money multiplier and the money supply. []', 'decreased the money multiplier and increased the money supply. []', 'increased the money multiplier and decreased the money supply. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(148, 'Suppose the Federal Reserve System purchases one-hundred thousand dollars of government bonds. If the reserve requirement is 10%, the Fed’s purchase[]', 'increases the money supply by 90 thousand dollars. []', 'increases the money supply by one million dollars. []', 'decreases the money supply 90 thousand dollars. []', 'decreases the money supply by one million dollars. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(149, 'An increase in the discount rate []', 'increases the money supply, while an increase in the reserve ratio decreases the money supply. []', 'or an increase in the reserve ratio increases the money supply. []', 'or an increase in the reserve ratio decreases the money supply. []', 'decreases the money supply, while an increase in the reserve ratio increases the money supply. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(150, 'If the Federal Reserve wished to increase the money supply it could make open-market[]', 'sales or raise the discount rate. []', 'sales or decrease the discount rate. []', 'purchases or increase the discount rate. []', 'purchases or decrease the discount rate. []', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(151, 'Which of the following will increase the money supply, but leave the money multiplier unchanged? []', 'an increase in the discount rate.[]', 'open-market sales.[]', 'an increase in the reserve ratio.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(152, 'An increase in the discount rate encourages banks to borrow[]', 'more from the Fed and increases the money supply. []', 'less from the Fed and reduces the money supply. []', 'more from the Fed and reduces the money supply. []', 'less from the Fed and increases the money supply. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(153, 'During World War II people chose to hold relatively more currency and relatively fewer checking deposits. This should have []', 'increased the money multiplier and the money supply. []', 'increased the money multiplier and decreased the money supply. []', 'decreased the money multiplier and increased the money supply. []', 'decreased the money multiplier and decreased the money supply. []', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(154, 'In the nineteenth century when there were bank runs, banks would make relatively fewer loans and hold relatively more excess reserves. This should have []', 'increased both the money multiplier and the money supply. []', 'decreased both the money multiplier and the money supply. []', 'increased the money multiplier and decreased the money supply. []', 'decreased the multiplier and increased the money supply. []', 2, 2, 'hard');
INSERT INTO `econ_hard` (`Qno`, `Question`, `Option1`, `Option2`, `Option3`, `Option4`, `Answer`, `marks`, `Complexity`) VALUES
(155, 'Which of the following concerning U.S. inflation is false?[]', 'Low inflation was viewed as a triumph of President Carter’s economic policy.[]', 'There were long periods in the nineteenth century during which prices fell.[]', 'The U.S. public has viewed inflation of even 7 percent as a major economic problem.[]', 'U.S. inflation has varied over time, but international data shows even more variation.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(156, 'There was hyperinflation during []', '1880 to 1896 in the United States.[]', 'post World War I Germany.[]', 'the 1970s in the United States.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(157, 'When the price level rises, the number of dollars needed to buy a representative basket of goods[]', 'decreases, so the value of money rises.[]', 'decreases, so the value of money falls.[]', 'increases, so the value of money rises.[]', 'increases, so the value of money falls.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(158, 'When the money market is drawn with the value of money on the vertical axis, the money demand curve slopes[]', 'upward, because at higher prices people want to hold less money.[]', 'upward, because open-market purchases make more money available.[]', 'downward, because at higher prices people want to hold more money.[]', 'downward, because at higher prices people want to hold less money.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(159, 'When the money market is drawn with the value of money on the vertical axis, the value of money increases if[]', 'money demand shifts right or money supply shifts left.[]', 'money demand shifts left or money supply shifts right.[]', 'either money demand or money supply shifts right.[]', 'either money demand or money supply shifts left.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(160, 'When the money market is drawn with the value of money on the vertical axis, the price level increases if[]', 'money demand shifts right or money supply shifts left.[]', 'money demand shifts left or money supply shifts right.[]', 'either money demand or money supply shifts right.[]', 'either money demand or money supply shifts left.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(161, 'A decrease in the money supply creates an excess[]', 'demand for money that is eliminated by rising prices.[]', 'demand for money that is eliminated by falling prices.[]', 'supply of money that is eliminated by rising prices.[]', 'supply of money that is eliminated by falling prices.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(162, 'Hubert spends $60 on a portable CD player.[]', 'Both the $60 and the CD player are real variables.[]', 'Both the $60 and the CD player are nominal variables.[]', 'The $60 is a nominal variable and the CD player is a real variable.[]', 'The $60 is a real variable and the CD player is a real variable.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(163, 'Steve lowers the hourly wage he pays his employees $1. The employees figure that, even accounting for the decrease, they can purchase more goods with what they earn in an hour than they could a year ago. It follows that []', 'the workers’ real and nominal wages have risen.[]', 'the workers’ real wage rose and their nominal wage fell.[]', 'the workers’ real wage fell and their nominal wage rose.[]', 'both the real and nominal wages fell.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(164, 'According to the classical dichotomy, which of the following is influenced by monetary factors?[]', 'nominal interest rates[]', 'real GDP[]', 'employment[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(165, 'According to the classical dichotomy, when the money supply doubles, which of the following also double?[]', 'the price level[]', 'nominal wages[]', 'nominal GDP[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(166, 'Monetary neutrality implies that an increase in the quantity of money will increase[]', 'the price level.[]', 'employment.[]', 'the percentage of their income people save.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(167, 'Velocity is computed as []', '(P 	 M)/Y.[]', '(Y 	 M)/P.[]', '(P 	 Y)/M.	[]', '(Y 	 M)/V.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(168, 'The equation of exchange alone implies that an increase in M could result in[]', 'an increase in the price level.[]', 'an increase in real GDP.[]', 'an increase in nominal GDP.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(169, 'If velocity and output were nearly constant,[]', 'the inflation rate would be much higher than the money supply growth rate.[]', 'the inflation rate would be much lower than the money supply growth rate.[]', 'the inflation rate would be about the same as the money supply growth rate.[]', 'Any of the above could be correct, more information is needed.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(170, 'The inflation tax[]', 'is an alternative to income taxes and government borrowing.[]', 'taxes those who hold the least amount of money most.[]', 'is the cost to the government of printing currency.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(171, 'If the money supply growth rate permanently increased from 10 percent to 20 percent we would expect that inflation and nominal interest rates would both increase[]', 'by more than 10 percentage points.[]', 'by 10 percentage points.[]', 'but by less than 10 percentage points.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(172, 'An increase in the money supply growth rate increases []', 'inflation, nominal interest rates, and real interest rates.[]', 'inflation and real interest rates, but does not change nominal interest rates.[]', 'inflation and nominal interest rates, but does not change real interest rates.[]', 'nominal and real interest rates, but does not change inflation.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(173, 'Shoeleather costs refer to[]', 'the cost of more frequent price changes induced by higher inflation.[]', 'resources used to maintain lower money holdings when inflation is high.[]', 'the distortion in resource allocation created by distortions in relative prices due to inflation.[]', 'the distortion in incentives, created by inflation, by taxes that do not adjust for inflation.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(174, 'Menu costs refer to []', 'the distortion in incentives created by inflation when taxes do not adjust for inflation.[]', 'the cost of more frequent price changes induced by higher inflation.[]', 'resources used by people to maintain lower money holdings when inflation is high.[]', 'the distortion in resource allocation created by distortions in relative prices due to inflation.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(175, 'You buy stock and its price rises more than the price level; before taxes you made a nominal[]', 'and real gain, and you pay taxes on the nominal gain.[]', 'and real gain, and you pay taxes only on the real gain.[]', 'gain and real loss, yet you pay taxes on the nominal gain.[]', 'gain and real loss, the real loss means you pay less tax.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(176, 'Given a nominal interest rate of 20 percent, in which case would you earn the highest after-tax real interest rate?[]', 'Inflation is 5 percent; the tax rate is 20 percent.[]', 'Inflation is 4 percent; the tax rate is 30 percent.[]', 'Inflation is 3 percent; the tax rate is 40 percent.[]', 'The after-tax real interest rate is the same for all of the above.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(177, 'Which of the following inflation costs matter even when actual and expected inflation are the same?[]', 'menu costs[]', 'inflation induced tax distortions[]', 'relative price variability[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(178, 'In 1898, prospectors on the Klondike River discovered gold. This discovery caused an unexpected price level []', 'decrease, which helped creditors at the expense of debtors.[]', 'decrease, which helped debtors at the expense of creditors.[]', 'increase, which helped creditors at the expense of debtors.[]', 'increase, which helped debtors at the expense of creditors.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(179, 'In order to maintain stable prices, the central bank must[]', 'tightly control the money supply.[]', 'keep unemployment low.[]', 'sell indexed bonds.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(180, 'Which of the following concerning U.S. inflation is incorrect? []', 'Over the last 60 years the average inflation rate was about 5%. []', 'In the nineteenth century there were periods of deflation. []', 'Inflation was relatively low in the 1990s. []', 'Farmers were especially hurt by the high inflation of the late 1800s.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(181, 'The quantity theory of money is helpful for explaining []', 'hyperinflation only. []', 'moderate inflation only. []', 'Both moderate inflation and hyperinflation. []', 'Neither moderate inflation nor hyperinflation. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(182, 'When the price level falls, 1/P[]', 'increases and the value of money increases. []', 'increases and the value of money decreases. []', 'decreases and the value of money increases. []', 'decreases and the value of money decreases. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(183, 'The money supply curve shifts right if []', 'the Fed sells bonds in the open market. []', '1/P rises. []', 'the Fed buys bonds in the open market. []', 'Both a and b are correct.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(184, 'As the price level increases, people want to hold a[]', 'larger quantity of money as shown by moving along the money demand curve. []', 'larger quantity of money as shown by shifting the money demand curve. []', 'smaller quantity of money as shown by moving along the money demand curve. []', 'smaller quantity of money as shown by shifting money demand curve. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(185, 'The quantity of money supplied is balanced with the quantity of money demanded by adjustments in the[]', 'interest rate in both the long run and the short run.[]', 'price level in both the long run and the short run.[]', 'interest rate in the long run and adjustments in the price level in the short run.[]', 'price level in the long run and adjustments in the interest rate in the long run.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(186, 'A decrease in the equilibrium quality of money and an increase in the equilibrium value of money could be created by []', 'an increase in money demand. []', 'an increase in money supply. []', 'a decrease in money supply. []', 'a decrease in money demand.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(187, 'Suppose the economy is initially in monetary equilibrium. The Federal Reserve then increases the money supply. As a result the quantity of money demanded will[]', 'exceed the quantity of money supplied, and the price level will fall.[]', 'exceed the quantity of money supplied, and the price level will increase.[]', 'be less than the quantity of money supplied, and the price level will fall.[]', 'be less than the quantity of money supplied, and the price level will increase. []', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(188, 'Which of the following both cause the price level to decrease? []', 'an increase in money supply and an increase in money demand. []', 'an increase in money supply and a decrease in money demand. []', 'a decrease in money supply and an increase in money demand. []', 'a decrease in money supply and a decrease in money demand. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(189, 'Which of the following is an example of a real variable? []', 'the income of your economics professor[]', 'the dollar value of the economy’s output[]', 'the quantity of rice produced by a rice farmer[]', 'the profits earned by Ford Motor Company in 2000 []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(190, 'If there is monetary neutrality which of the following change when the money supply changes? []', 'real interest rates[]', 'the price level[]', 'employment[]', 'building and modernizing of factories. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(191, 'Today most economists accept Hume’s conclusion of monetary neutrality as an accurate description of the economy in[]', 'both the long run and the short run.[]', 'neither the short run nor the long run. []', 'the short run only.[]', 'the long run only.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(192, 'The economy of Empe produces only compact discs. In a recent year they produced 6,000 compact discs at a price of $12 each. They had a money supply of $6,000. For that year the velocity of money in Empe []', 'was 1/12.[]', 'was 1.[]', 'was 12.[]', 'cannot be determined from the information given.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(193, 'According to the quantity equation, other things the same, the price level would increase if either the money supply[]', 'or the velocity of money increased. []', 'or the velocity of money decreased. []', 'increased or the velocity of money decreased. []', 'decreased or the velocity of money increased. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(194, 'Consider the following two assumptions. The velocity of money is stable over time. Factory supplies and production technology primarily determine the economy’s output of goods and services. []', 'Both assumptions are important to the quantity theory of money. []', 'Neither assumption is important to the quantity theory of money. []', 'Only the first assumption is important to the quantity theory of money. []', 'Only the second assumption is important to the quantity theory of money. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(195, 'Data on hyperinflation indicates, []', 'that money supply growth was much greater than inflation. []', 'that money supply growth was about the same as inflation. []', 'that money supply growth was much less than inflation. []', 'no close relationship between money supply growth and inflation. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(196, 'An analysis of countries experiencing rapid rates of inflation indicates that inflation is generally: []', 'caused by strong labor unions.[]', 'the result of restrictive macropolicy, which pushes up interest rates.[]', 'caused by the impulse buying of consumers, who continue to purchase the same goods even when prices go up.[]', 'the result of allowing the money supply to grow too rapidly.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(197, 'The inflation tax refers to the tendency[]', 'of real interest rates to rise when money supply growth rises. []', 'for the value of dollars people hold to fall as the government prints more money. []', 'for people to pay more income tax as prices rise. []', 'All of the above are correct. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(198, 'According to the Fisher effect, when the rate of money supply growth increases[]', 'both real and nominal interest rates should increase.[]', 'both real and nominal interest rates should decrease. []', 'real interest rates should increase and nominal interest rates should be unchanged. []', 'None of the above is correct. []', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(199, 'Inflation was higher in Argentina in the 1980s than in the 1990s. If the Fisher effect is correct, we would expect to observe that in Argentina[]', 'nominal interest rates were higher in the 1980s than in the 1990s.[]', 'nominal interest rates were higher in the 1990s than in the 1980s.[]', 'real interest rates were higher in the 1980s than in the 1990s.[]', 'real interest rates were higher in the 1990s than in the 1980s.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(200, 'If wages and prices both rose by 5%, workers’[]', 'real wages would rise so they would be better-off.[]', 'real wages would be unchanged, so they would be neither better-off nor worse-off.[]', 'nominal wage would fall, so they would be worse-off.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(201, 'Shoeleather costs refer to []', 'resources people use to reduce their money holdings when inflation is high.[]', 'the tendency of some costs to rise more than others when inflation rises.[]', 'the costs incurred by people looking for better-paying jobs when inflation rises.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(202, 'Menu costs refer to the costs of []', 'comparing prices.[]', 'changing prices.[]', 'comparing alternative investments.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(203, 'If the nominal interest rate is 10%, the inflation rate is 6%, and the tax rate is 20%, what is the after-tax real rate of interest?[]', '4%[]', '3.2%[]', '2.8%[]', '2%[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(204, 'If a country suddenly and unexpectedly reduces monetary growth inflation will be unexpectedly[]', 'low and wealth is redistributed from borrowers to lenders.[]', 'low and wealth is redistributed from lenders to borrowers.[]', 'high and wealth is redistributed from lenders to borrowers.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(205, 'Who is worse-off when countries trade?[]', 'both the exporting and importing county[]', 'only the exporting country[]', 'only the importing country[]', 'neither the exporting nor importing country[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(206, 'International trade is of major importance for understanding[]', 'the nature of inflation.[]', 'the basics of the natural unemployment rate.[]', 'macroeconomics in closed economies.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(207, 'Net exports of a country are the value of goods[]', 'exported minus the value of goods imported.[]', 'imported minus the value of goods exported. []', 'and services imported minus the value of goods and services exported.[]', 'and services exported minus the value of goods and services imported.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(208, 'Peter, a Canadian citizen, sells several hundred cases of smoked salmon to a restaurant chain in the United States. By itself this sale[]', 'decreases U.S. net exports and has no effect on Canadian net exports.[]', 'decreases U.S. net exports and increases Canadian net exports.[]', 'increases U.S. net exports and has no effect on Canadian net exports.[]', 'increases U.S. net exports and decreases Canadian net exports.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(209, 'U.S. imports account for about what percentage of GDP?[]', 'less than 1 percent[]', 'about 4 percent[]', 'about 7 percent[]', 'over 10 percent[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(210, 'If a resident of the United States buys stock in a Japanese corporation, this is an example of U.S.[]', 'foreign portfolio investment.[]', 'foreign direct investment.[]', 'exports.[]', 'imports.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(211, 'Brad, a U.S. resident, builds and operates a boxing gym in Thailand. The purchase represents[]', 'U.S. foreign direct investment and U.S. domestic investment.[]', 'U.S. foreign portfolio investment and U.S. domestic investment.[]', 'investment for Brad and U.S. foreign direct investment.[]', 'investment for Brad and U.S. foreign portfolio investment.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(212, 'Paul, a U.S. citizen, opens a textbook company in Brazil. His expenditures[]', 'decrease U.S. and Brazilian net foreign investment.[]', 'increase U.S. and Brazilian net foreign investment.[]', 'increase U.S. net foreign investment, but decrease Brazilian net foreign investment.[]', 'decrease U.S. net foreign investment, but increase Brazilian net foreign investment.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(213, 'While making investment decisions, investors []', 'compare the nominal, but not the real, interest rates offered on different bonds.[]', 'compare the real interest rates offered on different bonds.[]', 'purchase the highest-priced bond available.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(214, 'Which of the following is correct?[]', 'In many countries, the government finances a much larger share of investment projects than they used to.[]', 'Foreign stock markets make up an increasing share of the value of stock worldwide.[]', 'The U.S. stock market accounts for less than 1/3 of the value of stocks worldwide.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(215, 'Which of the following is true?[]', 'NX + NFI = Y[]', 'Y = NFI – NX[]', 'NFI = NX[]', 'NFI + I = NX[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(216, 'If a U.S. shirtmaker purchases cotton from Egypt, U.S. net exports[]', 'decrease, and U.S. net foreign investment increases.[]', 'decrease, and U.S. net foreign investment decreases.[]', 'increase, and U.S. net foreign investment increases.[]', 'increase, and U.S. net foreign investment decreases.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(217, 'Which of the following is incorrect?[]', 'The total movement of capital from advanced to developing nations is a large fraction of the world’s total investment.[]', 'Growing exports of manufactured goods from South to North will lead to a net loss of northern industrial jobs only if they are not matched by growth in exports from North to South.[]', 'Exports from Third World countries of manufactured goods equal about 1 percent of First World income.[]', 'Growing exports to the newly industrialized countries have created about as many jobs as growing imports have displaced.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(218, 'Which of the following equations is correct?[]', 'S = I + C[]', 'S = I + NFI[]', 'S = I – NX[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(219, 'After 1980, U.S. Net Foreign Investment fell dramatically, but the U.S. economy did not experience a similar fall in domestic investment. Hence, saving in the United States must []', 'have decreased dramatically.[]', 'have increased dramatically.[]', 'have been about unchanged.[]', 'not necessarily have done any of the above.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(220, 'If the exchange rate changes from 30 Thai bhat per dollar to 45 Thai bhat per dollar, the dollar has []', 'depreciated and so buys more Thai goods.[]', 'depreciated and so buys fewer Thai goods.[]', 'appreciated and so buys fewer Thai goods.[]', 'appreciated and so buys more Thai goods.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(221, 'Suppose that a ton of coal costs 1500 British pounds in the UK and $2000 in the United States. If the nominal exchange rate is .75 British pounds per dollar, the real exchange rate is[]', '4/3 tons of British coal per ton of U.S. coal.[]', '1 ton of British coal per ton of U.S. coal.[]', '4/3 tons of U.S. coal per ton of British coal.[]', 'None of the above are correct.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(222, 'If the nominal exchange rate e is foreign currency per dollar, the domestic price is P, and the foreign price is P*, the real exchange rate is defined as []', 'e(P/P*).[]', 'e(P*/P).[]', 'e + P/P.[]', 'e – P/P*.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(223, 'A depreciation of the U.S. real exchange rate induces U.S. consumers to buy[]', 'fewer domestic goods and fewer foreign goods.[]', 'fewer domestic goods and more foreign goods.[]', 'more domestic goods and fewer foreign goods.[]', 'more domestic goods and more foreign goods.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(224, 'If the U.S. real exchange rate appreciates relative to the French franc, U.S. exports to France[]', 'rise, and French exports to the United States fall.[]', 'fall, and French exports to the United States rise.[]', 'and French exports to the United States rise.[]', 'and French exports to the United States fall.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(225, 'Suppose that the dollar buys more coffee in Kenya than in Brazil. Traders could make a profit by buying coffee in[]', 'Kenya and selling it in Brazil, which would tend to raise the price of coffee in Kenya.[]', 'Kenya and selling it in Brazil, which would tend to raise the price of coffee in Brazil.[]', 'Brazil and selling it in Kenya, which would tend to raise the price of coffee in Brazil.[]', 'Brazil and selling it in Kenya, which would tend to raise the price of coffee in Kenya.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(226, 'If P = domestic prices, P* = foreign prices, and e is the exchange rate, which of the following is implied by purchasing-power parity?[]', 'P = e/P*[]', 'e = P*/P[]', '1 = e/P*[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(227, 'When a country’s central bank decreases the money supply, its price level[]', 'rises and its currency depreciates relative to other currencies in the world.[]', 'falls and its currency depreciates relative to other currencies in the world.[]', 'rises and its currency appreciates relative to other currencies in the world.[]', 'falls and its currency appreciates relative to other currencies in the world.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(228, 'When a country’s central bank increases the money supply, a unit of money[]', 'loses value in terms of the domestic goods and services it can buy, but gains value in terms of the foreign currency it can buy.[]', 'loses value both in terms of the domestic goods and services it can buy and in terms of the foreign currency it can buy.[]', 'gains value both in terms of the domestic goods and services it can buy and in terms of the foreign currency it can buy.[]', 'gains value in terms of the domestic goods and services it can buy, but loses value in terms of the foreign currency it can buy. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(229, 'On behalf of your firm, you make frequent trips to Liberia. You notice that you always have to pay fewer dollars to get the local currency to have your hair styled than you have to pay for similar styling in the United States. This is []', 'inconsistent with purchasing-power parity, but might be explained by limited opportunities for arbitrage in hair styling across international borders.[]', 'consistent with purchasing-power parity if prices in Liberia are rising more rapidly than prices in the United States.[]', 'consistent with purchasing-power parity if prices in Liberia are rising less rapidly than prices in the United States.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(230, 'In 1999 Morocco exported $5.9 billion of goods and services and imported $8.4 billion. Morocco had a trade balance of about[]', '$14.3 billion.[]', '$2.5 billion.[]', '$0.[]', '–$2.5 billion.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(231, 'Which of the following would be consistent with a trade balance of $5 billion?[]', 'exports and imports each equal $2.5 billion.[]', 'exports equal $15 billion and imports equal $10 billion.[]', 'imports equal $12 billion and imports equal $17 billion.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(232, 'A Swiss firm opens a watch factory in the United States. []', 'This is Swiss foreign direct investment and by itself increases Swiss net foreign investment.[]', 'This is Swiss foreign direct investment and by itself decreases Swiss net foreign investment.[]', 'This is Swiss foreign portfolio investment and by itself increases Swiss net foreign investment.[]', 'This is Swiss foreign portfolio investment and by itself decreases Swiss net foreign investment.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(233, 'A U.S. firm opens a factory that produces camping equipment in Albania, by itself[]', 'this increases U.S. net foreign investment and decreases Albanian net foreign investment.[]', 'this decreases U.S. net foreign investment and increases Albanian net foreign investment.[]', 'increases only U.S. net foreign investment.[]', 'increases only Albanian net foreign investment.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(234, 'Suppose that the real return from operating factories in Ghana decreases relative to the real rate of return in the United States. Other things the same,[]', 'this increases U.S. net foreign investment and decreases Ghanan net foreign investment.[]', 'this decreases U.S. net foreign investment and increases Ghanan net foreign investment.[]', 'increases only U.S. net foreign investment.[]', 'increases only Ghanan net foreign investment.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(235, 'A U.S. computer maker sells computers to a German firm. The U.S. company uses all of the revenues from this sale to purchase automobiles from German firms. These transactions[]', 'increase both U.S. net exports and U.S. net foreign investment.[]', 'decrease both U.S. net exports and U.S. net foreign investment.[]', 'increase U.S. net exports but do not affect U.S. net foreign investment.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(236, 'Brazil buys railroad engines from a U.S. firm and pays for them with bolivianos (Bolivian currency). By itself this transaction[]', 'increases both U.S. net exports and U.S. net foreign investment.[]', 'decreases both U.S. net exports and U.S. net foreign investment.[]', 'increases U.S. net exports but does not affect U.S. net foreign investment.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(237, 'In which of the following situations must national saving rise?[]', 'domestic investment increases and net foreign investment decreases.[]', 'domestic investment decreases and net foreign investment increases.[]', 'both domestic investment and net foreign investment increase.[]', 'net exports decrease and domestic investment is unchanged.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(238, 'The difference between savings in an open and closed economy equals[]', 'net exports.[]', 'net foreign investment.[]', 'Both of the above are correct.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(239, 'Consider the following two actions. 1. Kohl’s, a U.S. department store chain, builds new stores in Sweden. 2. Rudy, a U.S. citizen, buys newly issued bonds from Campmore.com who uses the money to build additional warehouse space in the United States. []', 'Both 1. and 2. increase U.S. savings.[]', 'Neither 1. nor 2. increase U.S savings.[]', '1. increases U.S. savings, but 2. does not.[]', '2. increases U.S. savings, but 1. does not.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(240, 'During the twenty years or so before this text was written the United States had []', 'both positive net exports and net foreign investment.[]', 'both negative net exports and net foreign investment.[]', 'positive net exports and negative net foreign investment.[]', 'negative net exports and positive net foreign investment.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(241, 'Which of the following is a true statement? []', 'Net foreign investment always equals a nation’s net exports.[]', 'Net foreign investment equals a nation’s exports plus national saving.[]', 'National saving equals net foreign investment minus domestic investment.[]', 'National saving equals domestic investment minus net foreign investment.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(242, 'If a country has business opportunities that are relatively attractive compared to other countries, we would expect it to have[]', 'both positive net exports and positive net foreign investment.[]', 'both negative net exports and negative net foreign investment.[]', 'positive net exports and negative net foreign investment.[]', 'negative net exports and positive net foreign investment.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(243, 'In late 1999 you could purchase about 325 Greek drachma (Greek currency) for a dollar. In late 2000 you could purchase about 400 drachma for a dollar. These exchange rates are given in []', 'real terms, and over this period the dollar appreciated.[]', 'real terms, and over this period the dollar depreciated.[]', 'nominal terms, and over this period the dollar appreciated.[]', 'nominal terms, and over this period the dollar depreciated.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(244, 'In January 2000 the exchange rate was 5.6 new kwanza (Angolan currency) per dollar. In January 2001 it was 6 new kwanza per dollar.[]', 'The dollar appreciated and so other things the same was worth more Angolan goods.[]', 'The dollar appreciated and so other things the same was worth fewer Angolan goods.[]', 'The dollar depreciated and so other things the same was worth more Angolan goods.[]', 'The dollar depreciated and so other things the same was worth fewer Angolan goods.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(245, 'In the United States a three-pound can of coffee costs about $6. Suppose the exchange rate is about 50 Belgian francs per dollar and that a three-pound can of coffee in Belgium costs about 400 francs. What is the real exchange rate?[]', '4/3 cans of Belgian coffee per can of U.S. coffee.[]', '3/2 cans of Belgian coffee per can of U.S. coffee.[]', '3/4 cans of Belgian coffee per can of U.S. coffee.[]', '2/3 cans of Belgian coffee per can of U.S. coffee.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(246, 'Suppose the nominal exchange rate is 100, the domestic price index is 50, and the foreign price index is 10. The real exchange rate is: []', '1,000.[]', '500.[]', '100.[]', '50.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(247, 'Suppose that the exchange rate is 50 Bangladesh taka per dollar, that a bushel of rice costs 200 taka in Bangladesh and $3 in the United States. Then the real exchange rate is[]', 'greater than one and arbitragers could profit by buying rice in the United States and selling it in Bangladesh.[]', 'greater than one and arbitragers could profit by buying rice in Bangladesh and selling it in the United States.[]', 'less than one and arbitragers could profit by buying rice in the United States and selling it in Bangladesh.[]', 'less than one and arbitragers could profit by buying rice in Bangladesh and selling it in the United States.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(248, 'Which of the following does purchasing-power parity imply?[]', 'the purchasing power of the dollar is the same in the United States as in foreign countries.[]', 'the price of domestic goods relative to foreign goods cannot change.[]', 'the nominal exchange rate is the ratio of U.S. prices to foreign prices.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(249, 'The nominal exchange rate is about 2 Aruban florin per dollar. If a basket of goods in the United States costs $40, how many florins must a basket of goods in Aruba cost for purchasing-power parity to hold?[]', '20 florin.[]', '40 florin.[]', '80 florin.[]', '100 florin.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(250, 'The exchange rate is about 200 Kazakhstan tenge per dollar. According to purchasing power parity this exchange rate would rise if the price level in[]', 'either the United States or Kazakhstan rose.[]', 'either the United States or Kazakhstan fell.[]', 'the United States rose or the price level in Kazakhstan fell.[]', 'the United States fell or the price level in Kazakhstan rose.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(251, 'If inflation in other countries is higher than inflation in the United States over the next few months and exchange rates are given in terms of how much foreign currency a dollar buys and how many foreign goods U.S. goods buy, according to purchasing-power parity we should expect to see[]', 'both the real and nominal exchange rate appreciate.[]', 'both the real and nominal exchange rate depreciate.[]', 'only the real exchange rate depreciate.[]', 'only the nominal exchange rate appreciate.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(252, 'Suppose the dollar depreciates relative to the British pound. We know that: []', 'prices in the United States are falling.[]', 'prices in the United States are rising.[]', 'prices in Great Britain are rising.[]', 'United States dollars will buy more British pounds.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(253, 'If exchange rates are given in terms of how much foreign currency a dollar buys and how many foreign goods U.S. goods buy, then if the Fed increased the U.S. money supply other things the same, purchasing-power parity implies[]', 'both the real and nominal exchange rate depreciate.[]', 'only the real exchange rate depreciates.[]', 'only the nominal exchange rate depreciates.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(254, 'Which of the following would be inconsistent with purchasing-power parity?[]', 'Tom is traveling in Europe; he notices that he will have to give up the same amount of U.S. currency to obtain foreign currency to eat breakfast whether he eats in London or Paris.[]', 'You observe that the exchange rate is 40 French francs per dollar. Over the next year inflation is higher in France than in the United States and the exchange rate is still 40 French francs per dollar.[]', 'Both of the above are inconsistent with purchasing-power parity.[]', 'Neither of the above is inconsistent with purchasing-power parity.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(255, 'Over the past decade, the United States has []', 'usually been very near to a trade balance.[]', 'persistently had a trade deficit.[]', 'persistently had a trade surplus.[]', 'had trade deficits about as often as trade surpluses.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(256, 'In an open economy, the market for loanable funds equates national saving with []', 'domestic investment.[]', 'net foreign investment.[]', 'the sum of domestic investment and net foreign investment.[]', 'the supply of foreign currency.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(257, 'A rise in the real interest rate[]', 'encourages investment and so increases the quantity of loanable funds supplied.[]', 'encourages investment and so decreases the quantity of loanable funds demanded.[]', 'discourages investment and so increases the quantity of loanable funds supplied.[]', 'discourages investment and so decreases the quantity of loanable funds demanded.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(258, 'If the interest rate were above the equilibrium level, the []', 'shortage of loanable funds would drive the interest rate downward.[]', 'surplus of loanable funds would drive the interest rate downward.[]', 'shortage of loanable funds would drive the interest rate upward.[]', 'surplus of loanable funds would drive the interest rate upward.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(259, 'Which of the following is correct?[]', 'When U.S. net exports are negative, the purchase of capital assets abroad exceeds the sale of capital assets abroad.[]', 'When U.S. net exports are positive, Americans must be selling foreign assets.[]', 'The imbalance between exports and imports of goods and services equals the imbalance between the purchase and sale of capital assets abroad.	[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(260, 'In the market for foreign currency exchange, the amount of net foreign investment desired at each real interest rate represents the quantity of dollars[]', 'supplied for the purpose of buying assets abroad.[]', 'supplied for the purpose of selling assets domestically.[]', 'demanded for the purpose of buying U.S. net exports of goods and services.[]', 'demanded for the purpose of importing foreign goods and services.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(261, 'Net foreign investment = net exports implies that[]', 'national saving equals domestic investment.[]', 'the supply of dollars equals the demand for dollars in the foreign-currency exchange market.[]', 'the supply of loanable funds equals the demand for foreign funds in the open-economy macroeconomic model.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(262, 'An appreciation of the real exchange rate for the dollar[]', 'decreases the quantity of dollars demanded in the market for foreign-currency exchange.	[]', 'increases the quantity of dollars demanded in the market for foreign-currency exchange. []', 'shifts the demand for dollars in the market for foreign-currency exchange to the right.[]', 'shifts the demand for dollars in the market for foreign-currency exchange to the left.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(263, 'The variable that links the market for loanable funds and the foreign-currency exchange market is[]', 'national saving.[]', 'net exports.[]', 'net foreign investment.[]', 'domestic investment.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(264, 'Ceteris paribus, if the Italian real interest rate were to decrease, Italian net foreign investment []', 'would rise, while net foreign investment of other countries would fall.[]', 'would fall, while net foreign investment of other countries would rise.[]', 'and net foreign investment of other countries would rise.[]', 'and net foreign investment of other countries would fall.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(265, 'Between 1995 and 1998 Sweden decreased their budget deficit. This change shifted Sweden’s[]', 'demand for loanable funds left.[]', 'demand for loanable funds right.[]', 'supply of loanable funds left.[]', 'supply of loanable funds right.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(266, 'Which of the following increases when the budget deficit of the United States increases?[]', 'U.S. supply of loanable funds.[]', 'net foreign investment.[]', 'the real exchange rate.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(267, 'In the 1980s the U.S. budget deficit rose. At the same time the U.S. trade deficit grew larger, the real exchange rate of the dollar appreciated, and U.S. net foreign investment decreased. Which of these events is consistent with what the open-economy macroeconomic model predicts concerning the effects of an increase in the budget deficit?[]', 'The U.S. trade deficit grew.[]', 'The real exchange rate of the dollar appreciated.[]', 'U.S. net foreign investment fell.[]', 'All of the above are consistent with the predictions of the model.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(268, 'Suppose that the United States imposes an import quota on farm machinery. This shifts the[]', 'demand for dollars in the foreign-currency exchange market right.[]', 'demand for dollars in the foreign-currency exchange market left.[]', 'supply of dollars in the foreign-currency exchange market right.[]', 'supply of dollars in the foreign-currency exchange market left.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(269, 'Suppose that the United States imposes an import quota on furniture. The quota makes the real exchange rate of U.S. dollars[]', 'appreciate and the real interest rate in the United States increase.[]', 'appreciate but does not change the real interest rate in the United States.[]', 'depreciate and the real interest rate in the United States decrease.[]', 'depreciate but does not change the real interest rate in the United States.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(270, 'If U.S. citizens decide to save a larger fraction of their incomes, the real interest rate[]', 'decreases, the real exchange rate of the dollar depreciates, and U.S. net foreign investment increases.[]', 'decreases, the real exchange rate of the dollar appreciates, and U.S. net foreign investment decreases.[]', 'increases, the real exchange rate of the dollar appreciates, and U.S. net foreign investment decreases.[]', 'increases, the real exchange rate of the dollar depreciates, and U.S. net foreign investment increases.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(271, 'If U.S. firms decide to invest more domestically at each interest rate, the real interest rate in the U.S.[]', 'decreases, the real exchange rate of the dollar depreciates, and U.S. net foreign investment decreases.[]', 'decreases, the real exchange rate of the dollar appreciates, and U.S. net foreign investment increases.[]', 'increases, the real exchange rate of the dollar depreciates, and U.S. net foreign investment increases.[]', 'increases, the real exchange rate of the dollar appreciates, and U.S. net foreign investment decreases.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(272, 'Trade policies []', 'alter the trade balance because they alter imports of the country that implemented them.[]', 'alter the trade balance because they alter net foreign investment of the country that implements them.[]', 'do not alter the trade balance because they cannot alter the national saving or domestic investment of the country that implements them.[]', 'do not alter the trade balance because they cannot alter the real exchange rate of the currency of the country that implements them.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(273, 'When Mexico suffered from capital flight in 1994, Mexico’s real interest rate []', 'fell and the peso appreciated.[]', 'fell and the peso depreciated.[]', 'rose and the peso appreciated.[]', 'rose and the peso depreciated.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(274, 'When a country suffers from capital flight, the demand for loanable funds[]', 'and the supply of currency in the foreign-exchange market shifts left.[]', 'and the supply of currency in the foreign-exchange market shifts right.[]', 'shifts right while the supply of currency in the foreign-exchange market shifts left.[]', 'shifts left while the supply of currency in the foreign-exchange market shifts right.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(275, 'When Mexico suffered from capital flight in 1994, the U.S. real interest rate []', 'fell and the real exchange rate of the dollar appreciated.[]', 'fell and the real exchange rate of the dollar depreciated.[]', 'rose and the real exchange rate of the dollar appreciated.[]', 'rose and the real exchange rate of the dollar depreciated.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(276, 'Which of the following would cause the real exchange rate of the U.S. dollar to appreciate?[]', 'capital flight from the United States[]', 'if the U.S. government increases the budget surplus[]', 'if the U.S. government imposes import quotas[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(277, 'Which of the following will increase U.S. net foreign investment?[]', 'if the government increases the budget surplus[]', 'capital flight from other countries[]', 'if the United States removes import quotas[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(278, 'Which of the following concerning the open-economy macro model is correct?[]', 'It assumes that real GDP is fixed.[]', 'It assumes that the interest rate adjusts to bring the supply of and demand for money into balance.[]', 'It considers what happens simultaneously in the money market and the market for foreign currency.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(279, 'The supply of loanable funds comes from[]', 'national saving. Demand for loanable funds comes from only domestic investment.[]', 'national saving. Demand for loanable funds comes from domestic and net foreign investment.[]', 'only net foreign investment. Demand for loanable funds comes from national saving.[]', 'domestic investment and net foreign investment. Demand for loanable funds comes from national saving.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(280, 'Jack and Jill are co-owners of the U.S. firm Wells Petroleum. Jack builds an oil well in Texas. Jill builds an oil well in Venezuela.[]', 'Neither Jack’s nor Jill’s purchase of capital count as demand for loanable funds in the U.S. market.[]', 'Jack’s purchase of capital counts as demand for loanable funds in the U.S. maket; Jill’s purchase does not.[]', 'Jill’s purchase of capital counts as demand for loanable funds in the U.S. market; Jack’s purchase does not.[]', 'Both Jack’s and Jill’s purchase of capital count as demand for loanable funds in the U.S. market.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(281, 'Other things the same an increase in the U.S. real interest rate relative to real interest rates in other countries []', 'decreases the quantity of loanable funds supplied in the U.S. market.[]', 'decreases U.S. domestic investment.[]', 'increases U.S. net foreign investment.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(282, 'Which of the following would increase both the real interest rate and the quantity of loanable funds?[]', 'The supply of loanable funds shifts left.[]', 'The supply of loanable funds shifts right.[]', 'The demand for loanable funds shifts left.[]', 'The demand for loanable funds shifts right.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(283, 'Which of the following would be shown by shifting the supply of loanable funds right?[]', 'People want to save more at each interest rate.[]', 'People want to invest more domestically at each interest rate.[]', 'People want to purchase more foreign capital at each interest rate.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(284, 'In the open-economy macroeconomic model, which of the following happens in response to an appreciation of the real exchange rate?[]', 'The quantity of dollars demanded in the foreign-exchange market increases.[]', 'The quantity of dollars demanded in the foreign-exchange market decreases.[]', 'The quantity of dollars supplied in the foreign-exchange market increases.[]', 'The quantity of dollars supplied in the foreign-exchange market decreases.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(285, 'If the real interest rate in the United States falls relative to real interest rates in other countries, U.S. net foreign investment[]', 'increases, the supply of dollars in the foreign exchange market shifts right, and the real exchange rate of the dollar appreciates.[]', 'increases, the supply of dollars in the foreign exchange market shifts right, and the real exchange rate of the dollar depreciates.[]', 'decreases, the supply of dollars in the foreign exchange market shifts left, and the real exchange rate of the dollar appreciates. []', 'decreases, the supply of dollars in the foreign exchange market shifts left, and the real exchange rate of the dollar depreciates.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(286, 'In the open-economy macroeconomic model, if the real exchange rate was above the equilibrium level, which of the following would rise?[]', 'the real exchange rate[]', 'net exports[]', 'net foreign investment[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(287, 'When the supply of loanable funds shifts right, which of the following increases?[]', 'net foreign investment and the real exchange rate[]', 'net foreign investment, but not the real exchange rate[]', 'the real exchange rate, but not net foreign investment[]', 'neither the real exchange rate nor net foreign investment[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(288, 'Which of the following would increase the real exchange rate?[]', 'the demand for loanable funds shifts left[]', 'the supply of loanable funds shifts right[]', 'an increase in the demand for dollars in the foreign-currency exchange market[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(289, 'In recent years the budget deficit of Thailand has increased. According to the open- economy macroeconomic model this should have caused which curve to shift right?[]', 'the Thai supply of loanable funds[]', 'the Thai demand for loanable funds[]', 'the supply of Thai currency[]', 'None of the above shift right[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(290, 'Between 1814 and 1829 the U.S. government debt fell. This should have []', 'increased interest rates and net foreign investment.[]', 'decreased interest rates and net foreign investment.[]', 'increased interest rates and decreased net foreign investment.[]', 'decreased interest rates and increased net foreign investment.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(291, 'An increase in budget deficits will[]', 'increase the trade deficit.[]', 'decrease the trade deficit.[]', 'increase net foreign investment.[]', 'have no impact on the trade deficit.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(292, 'Suppose sheep ranchers in Tiberius convince the government to prohibit the import of wool into Tiberius. According to the open-economy macroeconomic model this will cause the Tiberian currency to[]', 'appreciate and decrease net exports.[]', 'appreciate, but have no effect on net exports.[]', 'depreciate, but have no effect on net exports.[]', 'depreciate and increase net exports.[]', 2, 1, 'hard');
INSERT INTO `econ_hard` (`Qno`, `Question`, `Option1`, `Option2`, `Option3`, `Option4`, `Answer`, `marks`, `Complexity`) VALUES
(293, 'Suppose that conservationists in Sherwood convince the government to prohibit the export of timber from Sherwood. According to the open-economy macroeconomic model this will[]', 'reduce Sherwood’s net exports, and cause their real exchange rate to appreciate.[]', 'reduce Sherwood’s net exports, and cause their real exchange rate to depreciate[]', 'have no effect on Sherwood’s net exports, and cause their real exchange rate to appreciate.[]', 'have no effect on Sherwood’s net exports, and cause their real exchange rate to depreicate.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(294, 'The restriction on imports of Japanese vehicles into the United States has: []', 'caused the real exchange rate to appreciate.[]', 'caused net exports in the United States to decline.[]', 'decreased the demand for loanable funds in the United States.[]', 'increased net foreign investment in the United States.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(295, 'Molly Price, economic detective, meets a client who wants to know why interest rates have risen and the real exchange rate appreciated. The client suspects four causes; which one is consistent with the facts?[]', 'Import quotas were imposed.[]', 'Import quotas were removed.[]', 'The budget deficit increased.[]', 'The budget deficit decreased.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(296, 'The country of Monac experiences a coup that causes capital flight from the country. As a result[]', 'net foreign investment in Monac will decrease.[]', 'the demand for loanable funds in Monac will increase.[]', 'the supply of loanable funds in Monac will increase.[]', 'the exchange rate in Monac will increase.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(297, 'Between 1992 and 1999 it is estimated that Russia had capital flight of about $150 billion. Other things the same, we would expect that this capital flight has resulted in[]', 'falling domestic interest rates and an appreciation of the Russian currency.[]', 'falling domestic interest rates and a depreciation of the Russian currency.[]', 'rising domestic interest rates and an appreciation of the Russian currency.[]', 'rising domestic interest rates and a depreciation of the Russian currency.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(298, 'If people feel that it has become riskier to buy the capital assets of some country, perhaps because of increased political instability, then interest rates []', 'rise and the local currency depreciates.[]', 'rise and the local currency appreciates.[]', 'fall and the local currency appreciates.[]', 'fall and the local currency depreciates.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(299, 'If there is capital flight[]', 'both the supply of loanable funds and the supply of the local currency in the foreign exchange market shift right.[]', 'both the supply of loanable funds and the demand for the local currency in the foreign exchange market shift left.[]', 'both the demand for loanable funds and the supply of the local currency in the foreign exchange market shift right.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(300, 'Which of the following raises interest rates and causes appreciation of the local currency?[]', 'capital flight[]', 'restrictrive trade policies[]', 'an increase in the budget deficit[]', 'All of the above are correct[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(301, 'Business cycles[]', 'are explained mostly by fluctuations in corporate profits.[]', 'no longer are very important due to government policy.[]', 'are fluctuations in real GDP and related variables over time.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(302, 'Investment is a[]', 'large part of real GDP, so it accounts for a small share of the fluctuation in real GDP.[]', 'large part of real GDP, yet it accounts for a large share of the fluctuation in real GDP.[]', 'small part of real GDP, so it accounts for a small share of the fluctuation in real GDP.[]', 'small part of real GDP, yet it accounts for a large share of the fluctuation in real GDP.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(303, 'According to classical economic theory, changes in the money supply affect[]', 'nominal variables and real variables.[]', 'neither nominal nor real variables.[]', 'real variables, but not nominal variables.[]', 'nominal variables, but not real variables.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(304, 'Most economists believe that classical economic theory is a good description of the world in[]', 'the long run, but not in the short run.[]', 'the short run, but not in the long run.[]', 'the short run and in the long run.[]', 'neither the short nor long run.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(305, 'The effect of an increase in the price level is represented by a[]', 'shift to the right of the aggregate demand curve.[]', 'shift to the left of the aggregate demand curve.[]', 'movement to the left along a given aggregate demand curve.[]', 'movement to the right along a given aggregate demand curve.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(306, 'People will spend less if the price level[]', 'rises, making the dollars they hold worth more.[]', 'rises, making the dollars they hold worth less.[]', 'falls, making the dollars they hold worth more.[]', 'falls, making the dollars they hold worth less.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(307, 'A decrease in U.S. interest rates leads to []', 'an appreciation of the dollar that leads to smaller exports.[]', 'an appreciation of the dollar that leads to greater net exports.[]', 'a depreciation of the dollar that leads to smaller net exports.[]', 'a depreciation of the dollar that leads to greater net exports.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(308, 'Suppose a stock market crash makes people feel poorer. This decrease in wealth would cause people to []', 'decrease consumption, which shifts aggregate supply left.[]', 'decrease consumption, which shifts aggregate demand left.[]', 'increase consumption, which shifts aggregate supply right.[]', 'increase consumption, which shifts aggregate demand right.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(309, 'Aggregate demand shifts right when the government []', 'institutes an investment tax credit.[]', 'raises personal income taxes.[]', 'decreases the money supply.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(310, 'The long-run aggregate supply curve shifts right if[]', 'Congress raises the minimum wage substantially.[]', 'unemployment insurance benefits are made more generous.[]', 'immigration from abroad increases.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(311, 'In the long run, technological progress[]', 'makes the price level rise, while increases in the money supply make prices fall.[]', 'makes the price level fall, while increases in the money supply make prices rise.[]', 'and increases in the money supply both make the price level rise.[]', 'and increases in the money supply both make the price level fall.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(312, 'The misperceptions theory of the short-run aggregate supply curve says that output supplied will decrease if the price level increases[]', 'more than expected so that firms believe the relative price of their output has increased.[]', 'more than expected so that firms believe the relative price of their output has decreased.[]', 'less than expected so that firms believe the relative price of their output has increased.[]', 'less than expected so that firms believe the relative price of their output has decreased.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(313, 'The sticky wage theory of the short-run aggregate supply curve says that when the price level rises more than expected, the real wage[]', 'rises, so employment falls.[]', 'rises, so employment rises.[]', 'falls, so employment falls.[]', 'falls, so employment rises.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(314, 'The sticky price theory of the short-run aggregate supply curve says that when the price level rises more than expected, some firms will have []', 'lower prices than they desire, which increases their sales.[]', 'lower prices than they desire, which depresses their sales.[]', 'higher prices than they desire, which increases their sales.[]', 'higher prices than they desire, which depresses their sales.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(315, 'Assuming that a is positive, theories of short-run aggregate supply are expressed mathematically as quantity of output supplied =[]', 'natural rate of output + a(expected price level – actual price level).[]', 'a(actual price level – expected price level) – natural rate of output.[]', 'a(expected price level – actual price level) – natural rate of output.[]', 'natural rate of output + a(actual price level – expected price level).[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(316, 'An increase in the expected price level shifts short-run aggregate supply to the[]', 'left and an increase in the actual price level shifts short-run aggregate supply to the left.[]', 'left and an increase in the actual price level does not shift short-run aggregate supply.[]', 'right and an increase in the actual price level shifts short-run aggregate supply to the right.[]', 'right and an increase in the actual price level does not shift short-run aggregate supply.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(317, 'Suppose a shift in aggregate demand creates an economic contraction. If policymakers can respond with sufficient speed and precision, they can offset the initial shift by shifting aggregate[]', 'supply left.[]', 'supply right.[]', 'demand left.[]', 'demand right.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(318, 'Suppose the economy is initially in long-run equilibrium and aggregate demand rises. Compared to where the economy was before the change in aggregate demand, in the long run prices[]', 'and output are higher.[]', 'and output are lower.[]', 'are higher and output is the same.[]', 'are the same and output is lower.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(319, 'Which of the following has been suggested as an important cause of the Great Depression?[]', 'a decline in the money supply[]', 'a large decline in government expenditures[]', 'an increase in the relative price of oil[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(320, 'During World War II[]', 'government purchases of goods and services roughly doubled.[]', 'the economy’s production increased almost fivefold.[]', 'prices rose about 20 percent.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(321, 'Suppose that there has been bad weather, a decrease in the availability of oil or some other temporary increase in firms’ costs. In the short run prices[]', 'fall and output rises.[]', 'rise and output falls.[]', 'and output rise.[]', 'and output fall.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(322, 'Which of the following would cause stagflation?[]', 'Aggregate supply shifts right.[]', 'Aggregate supply shifts left.[]', 'Aggregate demand shifts right.[]', 'Aggregate demand shifts left.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(323, 'Keynes believed that economies experiencing high unemployment should adopt policies to[]', 'increase aggregate demand.[]', 'increase aggregate supply.[]', 'reduce the money supply.[]', 'reduce government expenditures.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(324, 'According to the crowding-out effect, an increase in government purchases causes interest rates to[]', 'fall, which increases saving.[]', 'fall, which decreases investment.[]', 'rise, which increases saving.[]', 'rise, which decreases investment.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(325, 'Recession refers principally to[]', 'below average real GDP growth. []', 'negative real GDP growth. []', 'below average inflation.[]', 'negative inflation.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(326, 'Which of the following is correct? []', 'On average over the past 50 years real GDP has grown about 3% per year. []', 'Recessions occur at regular intervals.[]', 'Both of the above are correct.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(327, 'During recessions investment[]', 'and unemployment rise. []', 'and unemployment decline.[]', 'rises and unemployment declines. []', 'declines and unemployment rises. []', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(328, 'Which of the following accounts for most of the decline in value of GDP during recessions? []', 'consumption []', 'investment []', 'government expenditures[]', 'net exports []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(329, 'Long-run analysis of the macroeconomy is based on []', 'both the classical dichotomy and monetary neutrality. []', 'neither the classical dichotomy nor monetary neutrality.[]', 'the classical dichotomy, but not monetary neutrality. []', 'monetary neutrality but not the classical dichotomy. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(330, 'In the aggregate demand and aggregate supply model the price level is on the[]', 'horizontal axis and quantity of output is on the vertical axis.[]', 'vertical axis and quantity of output is on the horizontal axis. []', 'horizontal axis and unemployment is on the vertical axis.[]', 'vertical axis and unemployment is on horizontal axis. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(331, 'A fall in prices makes consumers feel more wealthy. As a result[]', 'aggregate demand shifts to the left.[]', 'aggregate demand shifts to the right.[]', 'there is a movement up a given aggregate demand curve.[]', 'there is a movement down a given aggregate demand curve.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(332, 'When prices fall, dollars are worth[]', 'less, so consumers demand a larger quantity of goods. []', 'less, so consumers demand a smaller quantity of goods.[]', 'more, so consumers demand a larger quantity of goods.[]', 'more, so consumers demand a smaller quantity of goods.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(333, 'When the price level rises, other things the same, people want to[]', 'increase money holdings, so the interest rate increases.[]', 'increase money holdings, so the interest rate decreases. []', 'reduce money holdings, so the interest rate increases. []', 'reduce money holdings, so the interest rate decreases.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(334, 'Other things the same, which of the following happens when the price level falls?[]', 'Households try to increase money holdings.[]', 'The real exchange rate appreciates. []', 'U.S. net exports increase. []', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(335, 'Which of the following tends to increase the quantity of output demanded when the price level decreases? []', 'the wealth effect []', 'the interest rate effect []', 'the exchange rate effect[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(336, 'If people decide to save more for retirement []', 'or the government raises taxes, aggregate demand will shift right. []', 'or the government raises taxes, aggregate demand will shift left. []', 'aggregate demand will shift right. If the government raises taxes, aggregate demand will shift left. []', 'aggregate demand will shift left. If the government raises taxes, aggregate demand will shift right. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(337, 'Which of the following do we expect in the short run if the money supply increases? []', 'The interest rate rises. []', 'Investment falls. []', 'The price level rises. []', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(338, 'Suppose there is a broad increase in the price of stocks which causes an increase in the real wealth of individuals. Consumption spending rises in response to the increase in wealth. This will cause the[]', 'aggregate demand curve to shift to the left.[]', 'rate of unemployment to decrease.[]', 'general price level to fall.[]', 'aggregate supply curve to shift to the right.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(339, 'Which of the following shifts the long-run aggregate supply curve to the left? []', 'an increase in the economy’s capital stock[]', 'an increase in the availability of natural resources from abroad []', 'stricter environmental regulations []', 'None of the above is correct. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(340, 'By itself technological progress tends to []', 'raise real GDP and lower the price level. []', 'raise both real GDP and the price level.[]', 'decrease both real GDP and the price level. []', 'decrease real GDP and raise the price level. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(341, 'According to the aggregate demand and aggregate supply model, in the long run an increase in the money supply []', 'increases the price level and real GDP.[]', 'increases the price level, but does not change real GDP.[]', 'increases real GDP, but does not change the price level.[]', 'decreases real GDP, but does not change the price level.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(342, 'If the price level is less than expected, producers believe their relative price has[]', 'increased and so increase production. []', 'increased and so decrease production.[]', 'decreased and so increase production. []', 'decreased and so decrease production. []', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(343, 'If wages do not adjust immediately to the price level, a higher price level []', 'reduces real wages and employment. []', 'increases real wages and employment. []', 'reduces real wages and increases employment. []', 'increases real wages and reduces employment. []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(344, 'An increase in the expected price level shifts aggregate[]', 'demand to the right.[]', 'demand to the left.[]', 'supply to the right.[]', 'supply to the left.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(345, 'A change in price expectations will shift[]', 'short-run aggregate supply, but not long-run aggregate supply.[]', 'long-run aggregate supply, but not short-run aggregate supply.[]', 'both long-run aggregate supply and short-run aggregate supply.[]', 'long-run aggregate supply and aggregate demand.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(346, 'Suppose consumers become more pessimistic concerning the future of an economy. In the short run []', 'both the price level and real GDP rise. []', 'both the price level and real GDP fall. []', 'the price level rises and real GDP falls.[]', 'the price level falls and real GDP rises. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(347, 'During the 1930s[]', 'and the 1940s U.S. aggregate demand appears to have shifted far to the left.[]', 'and the 1940s U.S. aggregate demand appears to have shifted far to the right.[]', 'U.S. aggregate demand appears to have shifted far to the right. During the 1940s aggregate demand appears to have shifted far to the left.[]', 'U.S. aggregate demand appears to have shifted far to the left. During the 1940s aggregate demand appears to have shifted far to the right.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(348, 'Which of the following is associated primarily with aggregate supply shifting far to the left?[]', 'the Great Depression[]', 'the economic boom of the 1940s[]', 'stagflation of the 1970s[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(349, 'If the economy is experiencing stagflation and the Fed increases the money supply in the short run output[]', 'increases, in the long run the price level increases.[]', 'increases, in the long run the price level decreases.[]', 'decreases, in the long run the price level increases.[]', 'decreases, in the long run the price level decreases.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(350, 'Shocks to the economy such as changes in the value of the stock market[]', 'affect aggregate demand, but changes in taxes and government expenditures do not.[]', 'and changes in taxes and government expenditures affect aggregate demand.[]', 'do not affect aggregate demand, but changes in taxes and government expenditures do.[]', 'and changes in taxes and government expenditures do not affect aggregate demand.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(351, 'Which of the following claims concerning the importance of effects that explain the slope of the aggregate demand curve is correct?[]', 'The interest-rate effect is relatively large because investment spending is very responsive to interest rate changes.[]', 'The wealth effect is relatively large because money holdings are a significant portion of most households’ wealth.[]', 'The exchange rate effect is relatively large because exports and imports comprise a large part of real GDP.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(352, 'When the interest rate decreases, the opportunity cost of holding money[]', 'increases, so the quantity of money demanded increases.[]', 'increases, so the quantity of money demanded decreases.[]', 'decreases, so the quantity of money demanded increases.[]', 'decreases, so the quantity of money demanded decreases.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(353, 'According to liquidity preference theory, if there is an excess supply of money, people will deposit[]', 'less into interest-bearing accounts, so the interest rate rises.[]', 'less into interest-bearing accounts, so the interest rate falls.[]', 'more into interest-bearing accounts, so the interest rate rises.[]', 'more into interest-bearing accounts, so the interest rate falls.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(354, 'Which list contains only things that would make people want to hold more money?[]', 'Interest rates decrease, the price level increases.[]', 'Interest rates decrease, the price level decreases.[]', 'Interest rates increase, the price level increases.[]', 'Interest rates increase, the price level decreases.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(355, 'Assume the money market is initially in equilibrium. If the price level increases, according to liquidity preference theory there is an excess[]', 'supply of money until the interest rate decreases.[]', 'supply of money until the interest rate increases.[]', 'demand for money until the interest rate decreases.[]', 'demand for money until the interest rate increases.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(356, 'According to liquidity preference theory, which of the following shifts the money demand curve to the left?[]', 'a decrease in the price level[]', 'an increase in the price level[]', 'an increase in the interest rate[]', 'Both b and c are correct.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(357, 'According to liquidity preference theory, an increase in the price level causes the interest rate to[]', 'increase, which makes investment demanded increase.[]', 'increase, which makes investment demanded decrease.[]', 'decrease, which makes investment demanded increase.[]', 'decrease, which makes investment demanded decrease.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(358, 'In the short run, a decrease in the money supply causes interest rates to []', 'decrease, and aggregate demand to shift right.[]', 'decrease, and aggregate demand to shift left.[]', 'increase, and aggregate demand to shift right.[]', 'increase, and aggregate demand to shift left.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(359, 'If the interest rate is above the Fed’s target, the Fed should[]', 'sell bonds to increase the money supply.[]', 'sell bonds to decrease the money supply.[]', 'buy bonds to increase the money supply.[]', 'buy bonds to decrease the money supply.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(360, 'If the stock market crashes, aggregate demand[]', 'increases, which the Fed could offset by selling bonds.[]', 'increases, which the Fed could offset by buying bonds.[]', 'decreases, which the Fed could offset by selling bonds.[]', 'decreases, which the Fed could offset by buying bonds.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(361, 'An increase in government spending initially and primarily shifts aggregate[]', 'supply right.[]', 'demand right.[]', 'demand left.[]', 'supply left.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(362, 'The multiplier effect is the multiplied impact on[]', 'investment of a given increase in interest rates.[]', 'the money supply of a given increase in government purchases.[]', 'aggregate demand of a given increase in government purchases.[]', 'tax revenues of a given increase in government purchases.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(363, 'Which of the following illustrates how the investment accelerator works?[]', 'An increase in government expenditures increases aggregate spending so that the Gas-and-Go convenience store chain finds it profitable to build more new stores.[]', 'An increase in government expenditures increases the interest rate so that people buy fewer stocks and bonds.[]', 'An increase in government expenditures decreases the interest rate so that the Gas-and-Go convenience store chain decides to build more new stores.[]', 'An increase in government expenditures increases the interest rate so that the Gas-and-Go convenience store chain decides to build fewer new stores.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(364, 'The government purchases multiplier is defined as []', 'MPC.[]', '1 – MPC.[]', '1/(1 – MPC).[]', '1/MPC.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(365, 'According to the crowding-out effect, an increase in government purchases causes interest rates to[]', 'fall, which increases saving.[]', 'fall, which decreases investment.[]', 'rise, which increases saving.[]', 'rise, which decreases investment.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(366, 'If taxes[]', 'increase, consumption decreases, and aggregate demand shifts left.	[]', 'increase, consumption increases, and aggregate demand shifts right.[]', 'decrease, consumption increases, and aggregate demand shifts left.[]', 'decrease, consumption decreases, and aggregate demand shifts right.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(367, 'An increase in government spending on goods to build or repair bridges and highways[]', 'shifts the aggregate demand curve to the left.[]', 'has no multiplier effect.[]', 'shifts the aggregate supply curve to the right in the long run.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(368, 'If Congress cuts spending to balance the federal budget, the Fed can act to prevent unemployment and recession while maintaining the balanced budget by[]', 'raising taxes.[]', 'cutting expenditures.[]', 'increasing the money supply.[]', 'decreasing the money supply.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(369, 'Which of the following actions is inconsistent with the Employment Act of 1946?[]', 'When there is a recession, the government increases the money supply.[]', 'When unemployment is high, the government decreases expenditures.[]', 'When there is a recession, the government cuts taxes.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(370, 'Keynes argued that aggregate demand is[]', 'stable, because the economy returns to long-run equilibrium.[]', 'stable, because changes in consumption are mostly offset by changes in investment.[]', 'unstable, because seasonal variations create fluctuations in aggregate demand.[]', 'unstable, because waves of pessimism and optimism create fluctuations in aggregate demand.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(371, 'If the government wants to stabilize output, which of the following policy alternatives would be an appropriate response to an increase in investment demand?[]', 'increase taxes[]', 'increase the money supply[]', 'increase government expenditures[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(372, 'Investment tax credits are designed to []', 'increase aggregate demand in the short run and eventually increase long-run aggregate supply.[]', 'increase aggregate demand in the short run, but eventually decrease long-run aggregate supply.[]', 'increase aggregate demand in the short run and have no impact on aggregate supply.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(373, 'During expansions, automatic stabilizers make the government’s budget move[]', 'toward deficit.[]', 'toward surplus.[]', 'toward balance.[]', 'in no particular direction.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(374, 'When the Fed lowers the growth rate of the money supply, it must take into account[]', 'only the short-run effect on production.[]', 'only the short-run effects on inflation and production.[]', 'the long-run effect on inflation as well as the short-run effect on production.[]', 'only the long-run effect on inflation.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(375, 'Of the effects that help explain why the U.S. aggregate demand curve slopes downward the[]', 'wealth effect is most important and the exchange rate effect is least important.[]', 'exchange-rate effect is most important and the interest rate effect is least important.[]', 'interest-rate effect is most important and the wealth effect is least important.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(376, 'Liquidity preference theory is most relevant to the []', 'short run and supposes that the interest rate adjusts to bring money supply and money demand into balance. []', 'short run and supposes that the price level adjusts to bring money supply and money demand into balance. []', 'long run and supposes that the interest rate adjusts to bring money supply and money demand into balance.[]', 'long run and supposes that the price level adjusts to bring money supply and money demand into balance. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(377, 'An increase in interest rates[]', 'increases the cost of holding money and increases the quantity demanded.[]', 'increases the cost of holding money and decreases the quantity demanded. []', 'decreases the cost of holding money and increases the quantity demanded. []', 'decreases the cost of holding money and decreases the quantity demanded. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(378, 'According to the theory of liquidity preference if there is a surplus of money, the interest rate will[]', 'rise and the quantity of money demanded will increase.[]', 'rise and the quantity of money demanded will decrease.[]', 'fall and the quantity of money demanded will increase.[]', 'fall and the quantity of money demanded will decrease.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(379, 'With the interest rate on the vertical axis, an increase in the price level shifts money[]', 'supply right.[]', 'supply left.[]', 'demand right.[]', 'demand left.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(380, 'Which of the following properly describes the interest-rate effect?[]', 'A higher price level leads to higher money demand, higher money demand leads to higher interest rates, and a higher interest rate increases the quantity of goods and services demanded.[]', 'A higher price level leads to higher money demand, higher money demand leads to lower interest rates, and a lower interest rate reduces the quantity of goods and services demanded.[]', 'A lower price level leads to lower money demand, lower money demand leads to lower interest rates, and a lower interest rate reduces the quantity of goods and services demanded.[]', 'A lower price level leads to lower money demand, lower money demand leads to lower interest rates, and a lower interest rate increases the quantity of goods and services demanded.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(381, 'When the money supply increases interest rates[]', 'rise and aggregate demand shifts right.[]', 'fall and aggregate demand shifts left.[]', 'rise and aggregate demand shifts left.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(382, 'Which of the following shifts aggregate demand right?[]', 'The price level rises.[]', 'The price level falls.[]', 'The money supply rises.[]', 'Both a and b are correct.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(383, 'Suppose the Federal Reserve decreases the money supply. As a result: []', 'investment, real output, and the price level are all lower.[]', 'investment is higher, real output is lower, and the price level is unchanged.[]', 'investment, real output, and the price level are all higher.[]', 'investment is lower, real output is higher, and the price level is lower.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(384, 'If the stock market booms household spending[]', 'increases. To offset the effects of this on the price level and real GDP, the Fed would increase the money supply.[]', 'increases. To offset the effects of this on the price level and real GDP, the Fed would decrease the money supply.[]', 'decreases. To offset the effects of this on the price level and real GDP, the Fed would increase the money supply.[]', 'decreases. To offset the effects of this on the price level and real GDP, the Fed would decrease the money supply.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(385, 'In early January 2000 the Fed announced that it would cut interest rates one-half percentage point. To do this requires the Fed to[]', 'increase the money supply and so increase aggregate demand.[]', 'increase the money supply and so decrease aggregate demand.[]', 'decrease the money supply and so increase aggregate demand.[]', 'decrease the money supply and so decrease aggregate demand.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(386, 'In the last quarter of 1999 German real GDP grew at a very low rate. Some economists attributed the low growth to monetary policy that by itself would have decreased real GDP. If they are correct, we should observe that the German money supply []', 'and interest rates had increased.[]', 'and interest rates had decreased.[]', 'had increased and interest rates had decreased.[]', 'had decreased and interest rates had increased.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(387, 'When the Fed decreases the money supply we expect interest rates[]', 'and stock prices to rise.[]', 'and stock prices to fall.[]', 'to rise and stock prices to fall.[]', 'to fall and stock prices to rise.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(388, 'If the government increases its expenditures the price level[]', 'and real GDP both rise.[]', 'and real GDP both fall.[]', 'rises and real GDP falls.[]', 'falls and real GDP rises.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(389, 'Suppose that the MPC is .60 and there is no investment accelerator or crowding out. Then if government expenditures increase $10 billion, aggregate demand shifts right[]', '$40 billion.[]', '$25 billion.[]', '$16 billion.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(390, 'The multiplier effect occurs because an increase in government purchases will[]', 'increase income which will result in further rounds of spending.[]', 'increase interest rates which will reduce further rounds of spending.[]', 'increase the government deficit which will decrease further rounds of spending.[]', 'stimulate monetary policy which will increase further rounds of spending.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(391, 'Which of the following correctly explains the crowding-out effect?[]', 'An increase in government expenditures decreases the interest rate and so increases investment spending.[]', 'An increase in government expenditures increases the interest rate and so reduces investment spending.[]', 'A decrease in government expenditures increases the interest rate and so increases investment spending.[]', 'A decrease in government expenditures decreases the interest rate and so reduces investment spending.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(392, 'When the government increases expenditures the money demand curve shifts[]', 'right and interest rates rise.[]', 'right and interest rates fall.[]', 'left and interest rates rise.[]', 'left and interest rates fall.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(393, 'Permanent tax cuts shift the AD curve[]', 'farther to the right than temporary tax cuts.[]', 'less to the right than temporary tax cuts.[]', 'farther to the left than temporary tax cuts.[]', 'less to the left than temporary tax cuts.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(394, 'Suppose that net exports fall. Which of the following policies is most likely to stabilize the economy?[]', 'a decrease in the money supply[]', 'a tax increase[]', 'an increase in government expenditures[]', 'None of the above would be likely to stabilize the economy.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(395, 'If the government wanted to stabilize the economy when it was in recession it would[]', 'raise interest rates and government expenditures.[]', 'decrease interest rates and government expenditures.[]', 'raise interest rates and decrease government expenditures.[]', 'decrease interest rates and increase government expenditures.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(396, 'Critics of using fiscal and monetary policies to solve economic problems believe that[]', 'it can take too long for monetary policy to have an impact on the economy.[]', 'the political process results in a lag when using fiscal policy.[]', 'economic forecasting is imprecise.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(397, 'The most important automatic stabilizer is[]', 'open market transactions.[]', 'the tax system.[]', 'unemployment compensation.[]', 'welfare benefits.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(398, 'The misery index is calculated as the[]', 'actual inflation rate minus the expected inflation rate.[]', 'natural unemployment rate plus the long-run inflation rate.[]', 'unemployment rate minus the inflation rate.[]', 'inflation rate plus the unemployment rate.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(399, 'The short-run relationship between inflation and unemployment is often called []', 'Samuelson’s dilemma.[]', 'Harrod’s knife edge.[]', 'the Phillips curve.[]', 'Barro’s conundrum.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(400, 'Phillips found a negative relation between[]', 'output and unemployment.[]', 'output and employment.	[]', 'wage inflation and output.[]', 'wage inflation and unemployment.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(401, 'Samuelson and Solow reasoned that when aggregate demand was high, unemployment was[]', 'low, so there was upward pressure on wages and prices.[]', 'low, so there was downward pressure on wages and prices.[]', 'high, so there was upward pressure on wages and prices.[]', 'high, so there was downward pressure on wages and prices.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(402, 'According to Friedman and Phelps, no matter what the Fed does to the money supply, in the long run, the[]', 'economy will have a zero inflation rate.[]', 'inflation rate will tend to its natural rate.[]', 'economy will have a zero unemployment rate.[]', 'unemployment rate will tend toward its natural rate.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(403, 'Which of the following would shift the long-run Phillips curve right?[]', 'increases in unemployment compensation[]', 'an increase in the money supply[]', 'an increase in the expected inflation rate[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(404, 'If the long-run Phillips curve shifts to the right, for any given rate of money growth and inflation the economy will have[]', 'higher unemployment and higher output.[]', 'higher unemployment and lower output.[]', 'lower unemployment and higher output.[]', 'lower unemployment and lower output.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(405, 'An increase in expected inflation shifts the []', 'long-run Phillips curve right.[]', 'long-run Phillips curve left.[]', 'short-run Phillips curve right.[]', 'short-run Phillips curve left.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(406, 'The long-run and short-run Phillips curves intersect where[]', 'the quantity of goods and services demanded equals the quantity supplied.[]', 'the quantity of labor demanded equals the quantity supplied.[]', 'expected inflation is greater than actual inflation.[]', 'expected inflation equals actual inflation.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(407, 'According to Friedman and Phelps, the unemployment rate is above the natural rate when actual inflation[]', 'is greater than expected inflation.[]', 'equals expected inflation.[]', 'is less than expected inflation.[]', 'is high.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(408, 'Faced with an adverse supply shock, policymakers can increase aggregate[]', 'supply, which increases prices and output.[]', 'supply, which decreases prices and increases output.[]', 'demand, which increases prices and output.[]', 'demand, which decreases prices and increases output.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(409, 'A favorable supply shock will cause the short-run Phillips curve to shift []', 'left, and unemployment to rise.[]', 'left, and unemployment to fall.[]', 'right, and unemployment to rise.[]', 'right, and unemployment to fall.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(410, 'An adverse supply shock will cause the short-run Phillips curve to shift []', 'right, and inflation to fall.[]', 'right, and inflation to rise.[]', 'left, and inflation to fall.[]', 'left, and inflation to rise.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(411, 'In the 1970s, the Fed accommodated[]', 'an adverse supply shock and so contributed to higher inflation.[]', 'an adverse supply shock and so contributed to lower inflation.[]', 'a favorable supply shock and so contributed to higher inflation.[]', 'a favorable supply shock and so contributed to lower inflation.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(412, 'In 1979, Fed Chair Paul Volcker decided to pursue a policy[]', 'that would lead to disinflation.[]', 'that would create falling prices.[]', 'to accommodate continuing adverse supply shocks.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(413, 'If the sacrifice ratio is 3, reducing the inflation rate from 5 percent to 2 percent would require sacrificing []', '6 percent of annual output.[]', '9 percent of annual output.[]', '10 percent of annual output.[]', '15 percent of annual output.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(414, 'In 1979, Fed Chair Paul Volcker[]', 'believed decreasing inflation would temporarily decrease output growth.[]', 'instituted an accommodating monetary policy.[]', 'believed that inflation had not yet reached unacceptable levels.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(415, 'In the late 1970s proponents of rational expectations argued that[]', 'the short run might be long because people wouldn’t go to the trouble of computing inflation expectations.[]', 'if people expected a decrease in the money supply growth rate and inflation, the decrease in the money growth would have little or no affect on output.[]', 'Friedman and Phelps were wrong about the long run, because inflation expectations would never adjust to return the economy to the natural rate of unemployment.[]', 'Friedman and Phelps were wrong because there was no short run since people always anticipated inflation correctly.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(416, 'The restrictive monetary policy followed by the Fed in the early 1980s[]', 'reduced both unemployment and inflation.[]', 'reduced inflation significantly, but at the cost of a severe recession.[]', 'reduced unemployment significantly, but at the cost of higher inflation.[]', 'raised both unemployment and inflation.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(417, 'The experience of the Volcker disinflation of the early 1980s[]', 'generally increased estimates of the sacrifice ratio.[]', 'generally decreased estimates of the sacrifice ratio.	[]', 'clearly refuted the predictions of the proponents of rational expectations.[]', 'clearly refuted the predictions of the opponents of rational expectations.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(418, 'Since 1984, the economy has experienced[]', 'no unemployment rate above the natural rate.[]', 'a severe recession during 1991 and 1992.[]', 'uninterrupted economic growth.[]', 'relatively mild fluctuations in inflation and unemployment.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(419, 'In 1999, the Phillips curve was fairly far to the[]', 'right, partly because of lower inflation expectations.[]', 'right, partly because of adverse supply shocks.[]', 'left; partly because of lower inflation expectations.[]', 'left; partly because of adverse supply shocks.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(420, 'In the late 1990s,[]', 'aggregate supply apparently shifted left.[]', 'the Phillips curve apparently shifted right.[]', 'Both a and b are correct.[]', 'Neither a nor b is correct.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(421, 'In order to reduce inflation an economy will typically endure a period of[]', 'high unemployment and low output.[]', 'high unemployment and high output.[]', 'low unemployment and low output.[]', 'low unemployment and high output.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(422, 'The Phillips curve shows the relationship between the[]', 'price level and real GDP.[]', 'price level and unemployment.[]', 'inflation rate and the price level.[]', 'inflation rate and unemployment.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(423, 'If the government decided that it wanted lower inflation it would[]', 'increase aggregate demand which would increase unemployment.[]', 'increase aggregate demand which would decrease unemployment.[]', 'decrease aggregate demand which would increase unemployment.[]', 'decrease aggregate demand which would decrease unemployment.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(424, 'Which of the following lists contains only policies that would increase inflation and decrease unemployment?[]', 'increase government expenditures, increase the money supply[]', 'increase government expenditures, decrease the money supply[]', 'decrease government expenditures, increase the money supply[]', 'decrease government expenditures, decrease the money supply[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(425, 'Friedman and Phelps argued that an inverse relation between inflation and unemployment could exist[]', 'in both the long run and the short run.[]', 'in neither the short run nor the long run.[]', 'only in the short run.[]', 'only in the long run.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(426, 'According to the long-run Phillips curve, if the Fed increases the growth rate of the money supply,[]', 'inflation and unemployment both rise.[]', 'inflation rises and unemployment falls.[]', 'only employment rises.[]', 'only inflation rises.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(427, 'Which of the following policies would shift the long-run Phillips curve to the right?[]', 'Increased use of on-line vitas and job openings decrease the time people spend searching for jobs.[]', 'The government increases the minimum wage.[]', 'The government increases the money supply.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(428, 'Which of the following explanations for an upward sloping aggregate supply curve would imply an upward-sloping short-run Phillips curve?[]', 'misperceptions of relative prices[]', 'sticky wages and prices[]', 'Both a and b are correct.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(429, 'As compared to their initial values, which of the following variables are higher in both the short and long run if the government pursues an expansionary policy?[]', 'both unemployment and inflation[]', 'only inflation[]', 'only unemployment[]', 'neither unemployment nor inflation[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(430, 'Expansionary policy[]', 'increases unemployment and inflation in the short run, but only increases inflation in the long run.[]', 'increases unemployment and reduces inflation in the short run, but increases unemployment in the long run.[]', 'reduces unemployment in the short run, but increases inflation in the short run and long run.[]', 'reduces unemployment and inflation in the short run, but increases unemployment in the long run.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(431, 'If expected inflation decreases the short-run Phillips curve shifts[]', 'right, so at any actual inflation rate, unemployment will be higher than before.[]', 'right, so at any actual inflation rate, unemployment will be lower than before.[]', 'left, so at any actual inflation rate, unemployment will be higher than before.[]', 'left, so at any actual inflation rate, unemployment will be lower than before.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(432, 'In 1973, both unemployment and inflation were higher than they had been in 1969. This can be explained by monetary policy that increased[]', 'inflation expectations and so shifted the short-run Phillips curve to the right.[]', 'inflation expectations and so shifted the short-run Phillips curve to the left.[]', 'actual inflation and so shifted the long-run Phillips curve to the right.[]', 'actual inflation and so shifted the long-run Phillips curve to the left.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(433, 'The Phillips curve would be shifted rightward by: []', 'a decline in inflationary expectations.[]', 'a decrease in oil prices.[]', 'an increase in inflationary expectations.[]', 'a leftward shift of aggregate demand.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(434, 'The oil price shock of the 1970s shifted the short-run Phillips curve[]', 'right briefly because the Fed did not accommodate the oil price shock.[]', 'right for an extended period because the Fed accommodated the oil price shock.[]', 'left briefly because the Fed did not accommodate the oil price shock.[]', 'left for an extended period because the Fed accommodated the oil price shock.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(435, 'Which of the following is a consequence of using monetary policy to fight unemployment created by a supply shock?[]', 'current inflation rises[]', 'the Phillips curve will not soon revert to its former position[]', 'Both a and b are correct.[]', 'Neither a nor b are correct.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(436, 'Suppose that a small economy that depends mostly on agriculture experiences a year with exceptionally good conditions for growing crops. The effects of the good weather would shift[]', 'both short-run aggregate supply and the short-run Phillips curve right.[]', 'both short-run aggregate supply and the short-run Phillips curve left.[]', 'the short-run aggregate supply curve to the left, and the short-run Phillips curve to the right.[]', 'the short-run aggregate supply curve to the right, and the short-run Phillips curve to the left.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(437, 'Suppose an economy with high inflation decides to decrease the money supply growth rate[]', 'both the current unemployment rate and the natural rate of unemployment fall.[]', 'both the current unemployment rate and the natural rate of unemployment rise.[]', 'the current rate of unemployment rises, but there is no change in the natural rate of unemployment.[]', 'the current rate of unemployment falls, but there is no change in the natural rate of unemployment.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(438, 'Suppose the Fed decreased the growth rate of the money supply. Which of the following would permanently decrease?[]', 'both the unemployment rate and the inflation rate[]', 'the unemployment rate, but not the inflation rate[]', 'the inflation rate, but not the unemployment rate[]', 'neither the unemployment rate nor the inflation rate[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(439, 'The annual output of the United States is currently about $10 trillion. If the sacrifice ratio is 3 and the Fed pursues a monetary policy designed to decrease inflation 2 percentage points, what is the cost of reducing inflation?[]', '$500 billion[]', '$600 billion[]', '$5 trillion[]', '$6 trillion[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(440, 'If the government’s commitment to low inflation is credible, the sacrifice ratio is[]', 'high, so the cost of inflation reduction is high.[]', 'high, so the cost of inflation reduction is low.[]', 'low, so the cost of inflation reduction is high.[]', 'low, so the cost of inflation reduction is low.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(441, 'The disinflation of the early 1980s was due to: []', 'restrictive monetary policies of the Federal Reserve.[]', 'expansionary monetary policies of the Federal Reserve.[]', 'restrictive fiscal policy.[]', 'expansionary fiscal policy.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(442, 'Consider the following two sentences. Although the Volcker disinflation came at the cost of high unemployment, the cost was less than most economists predicted. The cost of the disinflation might have been even greater if people had believed that Volcker would really reduce inflation as much as he did.[]', 'Both sentences are true.[]', 'Neither sentence is true.[]', 'Only the first sentence is true.[]', 'Only the second sentence is true.[]', 3, 2, 'hard');
INSERT INTO `econ_hard` (`Qno`, `Question`, `Option1`, `Option2`, `Option3`, `Option4`, `Answer`, `marks`, `Complexity`) VALUES
(443, 'Which of the following is helpful in explaining levels of unemployment and inflation in the late 1990s?[]', 'Decreased inflation expectations shifted the short-run Phillips curve to the right.[]', 'The U.S. economy experienced some favorable supply shocks during this period.[]', 'Both of the above are correct.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(444, '“Leaning against the wind” is exemplified by[]', 'a decrease in government expenditures when there is a recession.[]', 'an increase in the money supply when there is a recession.[]', 'a tax cut when there is an expansion.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(445, 'Those who desire that policymakers stabilize the economy would advocate which of the following when employment is above the natural rate?[]', 'increase the money supply[]', 'decrease taxes[]', 'decrease government expenditures[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(446, 'In general, the longest lag for[]', 'fiscal policy is the time it takes to change policy, while for monetary policy the longest lag is the time it takes for policy to impact aggregate demand.[]', 'monetary policy is the time it takes to change policy, while for fiscal policy the longest lag is the time it takes for policy to impact aggregate demand.[]', 'both fiscal and monetary policy is the time it takes to change policy.[]', 'both fiscal and monetary policy is the time it takes for policy to impact aggregate demand.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(447, 'The principal reason that monetary policy has lags is that it takes a long time for []', 'changes in the interest rate to change aggregate demand.[]', 'changes in the money supply to change interest rates.[]', 'the Fed to change the money supply.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(448, 'Opponents of using policy to stabilize the economy generally believe that []', 'unemployment and inflation are not cause for much concern.[]', 'neither fiscal nor monetary policy have much impact on aggregate demand.[]', 'attempts to stabilize the economy can increase the magnitude of economic fluctuations.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(449, 'The Federal Open Market Committee[]', 'is required to keep the interest rate within a range set by Congress.[]', 'operates with almost complete discretion over monetary policy.[]', 'is required to increase the money supply by a given growth rate each year.[]', 'is required by its charter to change the money supply using a complex formula that concerns the tradeoff between inflation and unemployment.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(450, ' The political business cycle refers to[]', 'changes in output associated with spending to pay for presidential campaigns.[]', 'changes in output created by the monetary rule the Fed must follow.[]', 'the potential for a central bank to increase the money supply, and so output, to help the incumbent president get re-elected.[]', 'the fact that about every four years some politician advocates greater government control of the Fed.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(451, 'A law that requires the money supply to grow by a fixed percentage each year would eliminate[]', 'the time inconsistency problem, but not political business cycles.[]', 'the political business cycle, but not the time inconsistency problem.[]', 'both the time inconsistency problem and political business cycles.[]', 'neither the time inconsistency problem nor political business cycles.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(452, 'Which of the following is true concerning the recently developed inflation-targeting policy of Brazil’s central bank?[]', 'It is very different from policies used by Britain, Canada, and New Zealand.[]', 'Because the economy is easy to predict, they will not likely miss their inflation target.[]', 'If prices are rising faster than expected, the central bank is supposed to decrease interest rates.[]', 'The policy may not work well since the central bank is not free from political pressures.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(453, 'Suppose that the central bank must follow a rule that requires it to increase the money supply when the price level falls and decrease the money supply when the price level rises. If the economy starts from long-run equilibrium and aggregate supply shifts right, the central bank must[]', 'decrease the money supply, which will move output back towards its long-run level.[]', 'decrease the money supply, which will move output further from its long-run level.[]', 'increase the money supply, which will move output back towards its long-run level.[]', 'increase the money supply, which will move output further from its long-run level.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(454, 'A successful program to reduce inflation[]', 'eventually reduces inflation expectations.[]', 'permanently decreases output.[]', 'permanently raises interest rates.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(455, 'Proponents of zero inflation argue that reducing inflation has[]', 'permanent costs and temporary benefits.[]', 'temporary costs and permanent benefits.[]', 'permanent costs and benefits.[]', 'temporary costs and benefits.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(456, 'The immediate consequences of Paul Volcker’s inflation reduction efforts were to[]', 'increase both inflation and unemployment.[]', 'reduce both inflation and unemployment.[]', 'increase inflation and reduce unemployment.[]', 'reduce inflation and increase unemployment.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(457, 'Inflation reduction has the lowest cost when the efforts are[]', 'credible so that the sacrifice ratio is low.[]', 'unexpected so that the sacrifice ratio is low.[]', 'credible so that the sacrifice ratio is high.[]', 'unexpected so that the sacrifice ratio is high.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(458, 'Some countries have had high inflation for a long time. Others have had low or moderate inflation for a long time. Which of the following, at least in theory, could explain why some countries would continue to have high inflation?[]', 'In a country where inflation has been high for a long time, people are likely to have found ways to limit the costs.[]', 'High inflation countries have relatively small sacrifice ratios and so see no need to reduce inflation.[]', 'Inflation reduction works best when it is unexpected, and people in high inflation countries would quickly anticipate any change in monetary policy.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(459, 'In the late 1990s, the U.S. government had a[]', 'deficit and a debt.[]', 'deficit, but no debt.[]', 'surplus, but no debt.[]', 'surplus and a debt.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(460, 'Part of the argument for deficit reduction is that it would[]', 'increase interest rates and investment.[]', 'decrease interest rates and investment.[]', 'increase interest rates and decrease investment.[]', 'decrease interest rates and increase investment.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(461, 'Proponents of debt reduction argue that the rise in government debt during the 1980s[]', 'can be justified since the United States was involved in major military conflicts.[]', 'was primarily the result of politicians finding it easier to raise expenditures than cut taxes.[]', 'can be justified since the United States went through serious recessions.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(462, 'Which of the following is true?[]', 'The current government debt is about $114,000 per person.[]', 'As long as the government debt grows faster than the nation’s income, there is nothing to prevent the government debt from growing forever.[]', 'If the government uses funds to pay for useful programs, on net the debt need not burden future generations.[]', 'When there is a deficit, there must also be a debt.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(463, 'Suppose the budget deficit is rising 2 percent per year and nominal GDP is rising 4 percent per year, the debt created by these continuing deficits is []', 'sustainable, but the future burden on your children cannot be offset.[]', 'sustainable, and the future burden on your children can be offset if you save for them.[]', 'not sustainable, and the future burden on your children cannot be offset.[]', 'not sustainable, but the future burden on your children can be offset if you save for them.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(464, 'Proponents of tax-law changes to encourage saving would[]', 'favor the use of means-tests for government benefits.[]', 'support a tax on consumption instead of on income.[]', 'favor all of the above programs.[]', 'favor none of the above programs.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(465, 'IRA, 401(k), 403(b), and Keogh plans[]', 'are primarily useful to those saving to buy a home.[]', 'place limits on the amount people can deposit into these programs.[]', 'allow for unlimited withdrawals with no penalty.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(466, 'A lower rate of return on saving has[]', 'income and substitution effects that decrease saving.[]', 'income and substitution effects that increase saving.[]', 'an income effect that discourages saving and a substitution effect that encourages saving.[]', 'an income effect that encourages saving and a substitution effect that discourages saving.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(467, 'A reduction in the tax rate on income from saving would []', 'increase real wages over time.[]', 'decrease the capital stock over time.[]', 'decrease productivity over time.[]', 'most directly benefit the poor in the short run.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(468, 'The five debates over macroeconomic policy exist mostly because[]', 'economists disagree over basic issues such as the importance of saving for economic growth.[]', 'people fail to clearly see the benefits or the costs of most changes.[]', 'there are tradeoffs and people disagree about the best way to deal with them.[]', 'politicians offer misleading information.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(469, 'If households and firms became more optimistic about the future real GDP[]', 'and unemployment would increase.[]', 'would increase and unemployment would decrease.[]', 'would decrease and unemployment would increase.[]', 'and unemployment would decrease.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(470, 'If unemployment increases, which of the following could the government do to try to decrease it?[]', 'decrease the money supply[]', 'decrease taxes[]', 'decrease government expendtitures[]', 'None of the above would tend to decrease unemployment.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(471, 'Which of the following actions would be considered leaning against the wind?[]', 'In response to a recession, the government leaves fiscal and monetary policy unchanged.[]', 'In response to a recession, the government decreases the money supply.[]', 'In response to a boom, the government increases taxes.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(472, 'In 1999 and 2000 the Federal Reserve raised interest rates several times. This policy implies the Fed[]', 'increased money supply growth due to concern about inflation.[]', 'increased money supply growth due to concern about unemployment.[]', 'decreased money supply growth due to concern about inflation.[]', 'decreased money supply growth due to concern about unemployment.[]', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(473, 'An increase in the money supply affects output primarily by[]', 'decreasing interest rates which increases business investment.[]', 'decreasing interest rates which decreases business investment.[]', 'increasing interest rates which increases business investment.[]', 'increasing interest rates which decreases business investment.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(474, 'The principal lag in implementing fiscal policy is the time it takes[]', 'for firms to change output in response to the change in the price level.[]', 'for fiscal policy to affect interest rates.[]', 'for government expenditures and taxes to affect consumer spending.[]', 'to pass legislation to change expenditures or taxes.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(475, 'The Federal Reserve []', 'has considerable discretion in determining monetary policy.[]', 'has little discretion, but not does not have to follow any specific rule.[]', 'must follow a monetary policy rule that requires it to be primarily concerned with inflation.[]', 'must follow a monetary policy rule that requires it to be primarily concerned with unemployment.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(476, 'When the Fed has discretion, policy is time inconsistent which means inflation expectations are[]', 'higher and the short-run Phillips curve is further to the right than otherwise.[]', 'higher and the short-run Phillips curve is further to the left than otherwise.[]', 'lower and the short-run Phillips curve is further to the right than otherwise.[]', 'lower and the short-run Phillips curve is further to the left than otherwise.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(477, 'Either a constant growth rate of the money supply monetary rule, or a rule requiring the Fed to respond to changes in real GDP would reduce or eliminate[]', 'the time inconsistency of monetary policy.[]', 'the monetary portion of the political business cycle.[]', 'both the time inconsistency of monetary policy and the monetary portion of the political business cycle.[]', 'neither the time inconsistency of monetary policy nor the monetary portion of the political business cycle.[]', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(478, 'Consider the following two sentences. If the Fed is bound by a rule to decrease the money supply when prices increase, then when aggregate supply shifts left, their actions will reduce output further. Paul Volcker’s monetary policy in 1979 caused a rise in Jimmy Carter’s popularity.[]', 'Only the first sentence is correct.[]', 'Only the second sentence is correct.[]', 'Both sentences are correct.[]', 'Neither sentence is correct.[]', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(479, 'An economist would be more likely to support a program reducing inflation to zero if she believed that []', 'shoeleather and menu costs were high.[]', 'Fed policy to reduce inflation was credible.[]', 'the short-run Phillips curve was steep.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(480, 'A policy to reduce inflation is likely to increase unemployment in[]', 'the short run and the long run.[]', 'the short run but not the long run.[]', 'the long run but not the short run.[]', 'neither the short nor long run.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(481, 'If people believe a central bank’s intention to decrease the inflation rate, the[]', 'short-run Phillips curve shifts right.[]', 'short-run Phillips curve shifts left.[]', 'long-run Phillips curve shifts right.[]', 'long-run Phillips curve shifts left.[]', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(482, 'If people in countries that have had persistently high inflation are skeptical of efforts to reduce inflation the short-run Phillips curve will remain far to the[]', 'right, and the sacrifice ratio will be low.[]', 'right, and the sacrifice ratio will be high.[]', 'left, and the sacrifice ratio will be low.[]', 'left, and the sacrifice ratio will be high.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(483, 'Which of the following is incorrect?[]', 'A credible inflation reduction program can lead to a low sacrifice ratio.[]', 'Inflation reduction programs are likely to lower employment, but unlikely to have much impact on the capital stock.[]', 'Living standards depend on productivity and not the price level.[]', 'Rewriting the tax laws could reduce some of the current costs of inflation.[]', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(484, 'From 1980 to 1999 the debt of the U.S. federal government []', 'fell by about 80%.[]', 'fluctuated but ended up about the same.[]', 'rose by about 200%.[]', 'rose by about 400%.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(485, 'Budget deficits reduce national saving causing real interest rates[]', 'and investment to fall.[]', 'and investment to rise.[]', 'to rise and investment to fall.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(486, 'Consider the following two sentences. A policy that required a balanced budget would require the government to either increase taxes or reduce expenditures during recessions, which would tend to worsen the recessions. Funding more education spending rather then reducing the government debt could, all things considered, make future generations better-off.[]', 'Only the first sentence is true.[]', 'Only the second sentence is true.[]', 'Both sentences are true.[]', 'Neither sentence is true.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(487, 'Each person’s share of the government debt is about[]', '2% of lifetime income.[]', '10% of lifetime income.[]', '25% of lifetime income.[]', '40% of lifetime income.[]', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(488, 'Suppose that a country has a real GDP growth rate of about 1% per year and an inflation rate of about 3%. If they have nominal GDP of about 100 billion units of currency, they can have a deficit of about[]', '2 billion without increasing the ratio of debt to income.[]', '3 billion without increasing the ratio of debt to income.[]', '4 billion without increasing the ratio of debt to income.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(489, 'Double taxation means that both[]', 'the profits of corporations and the dividends shareholders receive are taxed, which is currently the case in the United States.[]', 'the profits of corporations and the dividends shareholders receive are taxed, which is not currently the case in the United States.[]', 'wage income and interest income are taxed, which they currently are in the United States.[]', 'wage income and interest income are taxed, which is not currently the case in the United States.[]', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(490, 'U.S. public policy discourages saving because []', 'other things the same, taxes reduce the return from savings.[]', 'means tested programs such as Medicaid provide greater benefits to those who did not save.[]', 'at least some of the amount that parents bequest to their children is taxed.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(491, 'Assuming the substitution effect is large relative to the income effect, tax reform designed to increase saving,[]', 'decreases the interest rate and spending on capital goods.[]', 'decreases the interest rate and increases spending on capital goods.[]', 'increases the interest rate and decreases spending on capital goods.[]', 'increases the interest rate and increases spending on capital goods.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(492, 'Tax changes that reduce taxes on interest and capital income may lower tax revenues which[]', 'increases public saving and so increases national saving.[]', 'increases public saving and so decreases national saving.[]', 'decreases public saving and so increases national saving.[]', 'decreases public saving and so decreases national saving.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(493, 'Which of the following is incorrect?[]', 'Any tax change that favors people who save, tends to favor people with high income.[]', 'If saving were relatively elastic with respect to tax rates, a decrease in the tax rate on income from saving may not change saving very much.[]', 'A higher return from saving raises saving if the substitution effect is larger than the income effect.[]', 'Other things the same an increase in government surpluses would increase both public and national saving.[]', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(494, 'Demand for a commodity refers to[]', 'Need for the commodity[]', 'Desire for the commodity[]', 'Amount of the commodity demanded at a particular\n        price and at a particular time[]', 'Quantity demanded of that commodity[]', 3, 7, 'hard');
INSERT INTO `econ_medium` (`Qno`, `Question`, `Option1`, `Option2`, `Option3`, `Option4`, `Answer`, `marks`, `Complexity`) VALUES
(1, 'Which of the total cost curves is consistent with marginal cost curves and average total cost curves that are both U-shaped?[]', 'both (i.) and (ii.)[]', 'only (i.)[]', 'only (ii.)[]', 'neither (i.) nor (ii.)[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(2, '	Which of the following is true concerning the long-run average-total-cost curve?[]', 'it is likely to be U-shaped.[]', 'it is flatter than the short-run average-total-cost curves.[]', 'all the short-run average-total-cost curves lie on the long-run average-total-cost curve.[]', 'All of the above are true.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(3, 'When a firm’s long-run average cost curve exhibits economies of scale the long-run average cost[]', 'curve is horizontal.[]', 'curve is downward sloping.[]', 'curve is upward sloping.[]', 'equals the short-run average cost for all levels of output.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(4, '	Statistical studies show that as the output of banking firms expand, average total costs fall until banks reach a certain size at which point average total costs remain the same. According to this evidence, for lower levels of output banks have[]', 'constant returns to scale, while at larger levels of output they have economies of scale.[]', 'constant returns to scale, while at larger levels of output they have diseconomies of scale.[]', 'economies of scale, while at larger levels of output they have constant returns to scale.[]', 'diseconomies of scale, while at larger levels they have economies of scale.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(5, '	Economies of scale[]', 'and diseconomies of scale arise because of coordination problems.[]', 'and diseconomies of scale arise because of specialization.[]', 'arise because of coordination problems, diseconomies of scale arise from specialization.[]', 'arise because of specialization, diseconomies of scale arise from specialization.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(6, 'In a competitive market, the actions of any single buyer or seller will[]', 'have a negligible impact on the market price.[]', 'adversely affect the profitability of more than one firm in the market.[]', 'cause a noticeable change in market production and price.[]', 'have little effect on market production, but ultimately change price.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(7, 'If marginal cost is less than marginal revenue[]', 'the firm must be experiencing losses.[]', 'the firm must be earning a profit.[]', 'the firm must be maximizing profits.[]', 'a profit-maximizing firm should increase the level of production.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(8, 'Which of the following is a characteristic of a perfectly competitive market?[]', 'Firms are price setters.[]', 'There are few sellers in the market.[]', 'Firms can exit and enter the market freely.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(9, 'If a perfectly competitive firm currently produces where price is greater than marginal cost it[]', 'will increase its profits by producing more.[]', 'will increase its profits by producing less.[]', 'is making positive economic profits.[]', 'is making negative economic profits.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(10, 'When a perfectly competitive firm makes a decision to shut down, it is most likely that[]', 'price is below the minimum of average variable cost.[]', 'fixed costs exceed variable costs.[]', 'average fixed costs are rising.[]', 'marginal cost is above average variable cost.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(11, 'According to the figure, which line segment best reflects the long-run supply curve for this firm?[]', 'AB[]', 'BC[]', 'CD[]', 'None of the above, the long-run supply curve requires knowledge of the average variable cost structure.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(12, 'According to the figure, this firm will exit the market for any price on the line segment[]', 'CD.[]', 'AB.[]', 'CB.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(13, 'A profit-maximizing firm making losses (negative profit), but still producing output faces which of the following conditions?[]', 'P > ATC[]', 'P > AVC[]', 'Both of the above are correct.[]', 'Neither of the above is correct.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(14, 'The profits of a profit-maximizing firm equal[]', 'P 	 Q.[]', '(P – ATC) 	 Q.[]', '(ATC – P) c Q.[]', '(MC – AVC) 	 Q.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(15, 'When a profit-maximizing firm’s fixed costs are considered sunk in the short run it[]', 'will never show losses.[]', 'can set price above marginal cost.[]', 'maximizes profit by choosing an output level where price exceeds marginal cost.[]', 'can safely ignore fixed costs when deciding how much to produce.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(16, 'In the long run, a profit-maximizing firm will choose to exit a market when[]', 'fixed costs exceed sunk costs.[]', 'average fixed cost is rising.[]', 'revenue from production is less than total costs.[]', 'marginal cost exceeds marginal revenue at the current level of production.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(17, 'According to the figure, if there are 200 identical firms in this market, what level of output will be supplied to the market when price is $2.00?[]', '10,000[]', '20,000[]', '40,000[]', 'It cannot be determined from the information provided.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(18, 'According to the figure, when 150 identical firms participate in this market, at what price will 15,000 units be supplied to this market?[]', '$1.00[]', '$1.50[]', '$2.00[]', 'It cannot be determined from the information provided.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(19, 'When firms have an incentive to exit a competitive market, their exit will[]', 'drive down market prices.[]', 'drive down profits of existing firms in the market.[]', 'decrease the quantity of goods supplied in the market.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(20, 'In a perfectly competitive market, the process of entry or exit ends when[]', 'firms are operating with excess capacity.[]', 'firms are making zero economic profit.[]', 'firms experience decreasing marginal revenue.[]', 'price is equal to marginal cost.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(21, 'If all incumbent firms and all potential firms have the same cost curves and the market is characterized by free entry and exit, the long-run market supply curve[]', 'is equal to the sum of marginal cost curves.[]', 'slopes downward.[]', 'slopes upward.[]', 'is horizontal.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(22, 'The exit of existing firms from a competitive market will[]', 'decrease market supply and increase market prices.[]', 'decrease market supply and decrease market prices.[]', 'increase market supply and increase market prices.[]', 'increase market supply and decrease market prices.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(23, 'When firms in an industry have the same cost structure which is not changed by the entry or exit of firms,[]', 'the long-run market supply curve must be upward sloping.[]', 'the long-run market supply curve must be horizontal.[]', 'the long-run market supply curve must be downward sloping.[]', 'We can’t tell anything about the shape of the long-run market supply curve.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(24, 'According to the figures, if the market starts in equilibrium at point C in panel (b), a decrease in demand will ultimately lead to[]', 'a higher price.[]', 'a new long-run equilibrium at point D in panel (b).[]', 'fewer firms in the market.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(25, 'According to the figures, when a firm in a competitive market, like the one depicted in panel (a), observes market price rising from P1 to P2, it is most likely the result of[]', 'entrance of new firms into the market.[]', 'the exit of existing firms in the market.[]', 'an increase in market supply from Supply0 to Supply1.[]', 'an increase in market demand from Demand0 to Demand1.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(26, 'When a competitive market experiences an increase in demand that induces an increase in producer costs, which of the following is most likely to arise?[]', 'The long-run market supply curve will be upward sloping.[]', 'The condition of free entry into the market will be violated.[]', 'Producer profits must fall in the long run.[]', 'All of the above are likely to occur.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(27, 'In economics, market power refers to the[]', 'ability of a firm to influence the market price of the good it sells.[]', 'ability of the market system to efficiently allocate scare goods.[]', 'quality of a firm’s marketing efforts.[]', 'forces that operate the “invisible hand.”[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(28, 'In a competitive market individual firms take as given[]', 'the level of output they produce.[]', 'the price they receive for their output.[]', 'both the level of output they produce and the price they receive.[]', 'neither the level of output they produce nor the price they receive.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(29, 'The Not Quite Broke Ranch sells 1,000 units of beef in a competitive market and has total revenues of $200,000. From this information alone we know which of the following is $200?[]', 'average revenue[]', 'marginal revenue[]', 'price[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(30, 'Other things the same, if a competitive firm doubles its output[]', 'average revenues fall.[]', 'price falls.[]', 'total revenues rise.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(31, 'If a competitive firm finds that at the current price and level of output, its marginal revenue is less than its marginal cost, it should[]', 'increase the price of its output.[]', 'decrease the price of its output.[]', 'increase its output.[]', 'decrease its output.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(32, 'Competitive firms maximize profits by producing the quantity where[]', 'average revenue = average total cost.[]', 'price = average total cost.[]', 'marginal product = marginal cost.[]', 'marginal revenue = marginal cost.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(33, 'At Paula’s Pizza, the marginal revenue of the last pizza produced is $12. The marginal cost of the last pizza produced is $10. In order to increase profits, Paula should:[]', 'increase output.[]', 'decrease output.[]', 'not change output.[]', 'offer a different variety of pizza.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(34, 'If the price of a competitive firm’s output increased, marginal revenue[]', 'and the profit-maximizing level of output would both increase.[]', 'and the profit-maximizing level of output would both decrease.[]', 'would increase and the profit-maximizing level of output would decrease.[]', 'would decrease and the profit-maximizing level of output would increase.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(35, 'In a competitive market the individual supply curve of a competitive firm is based on its[]', 'average revenue curve.[]', 'average total cost curve.[]', 'marginal revenue curve.[]', 'marginal cost curve.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(36, 'In the short run a firm in a competitive market should[]', 'never shut down.[]', 'shut down only if price is less than average fixed cost.[]', 'shut down only if price is less than average total cost.[]', 'shut down only if price is less than average variable cost.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(37, 'In the short run a firm should[]', 'never shut down.[]', 'shut down only if total revenues are less than total cost.[]', 'shut down only if total revenues are less than variable cost.[]', 'shut down only if total revenues are less than fixed cost.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(38, 'The short-run supply curve of an individual competitive firm is its marginal cost curve above the[]', 'AFC curve.[]', 'ATC curve.[]', 'AVC curve.[]', 'point where the MC curve is downward sloping.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(39, 'Some restaurants are open for breakfast, lunch, and dinner. In which of the following cases would it necessarily make sense for a restaurant to shut down for a meal?[]', 'Total revenues are less than total costs, but greater than variable costs.[]', 'Total revenues are less than variable costs.[]', 'Total revenues are less than sunk costs.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(40, 'A firm’s shut down decision[]', 'and its exit decision are based on comparing total revenues to total cost.[]', 'and its exit decision are based on comparing total revenues to variable cost.[]', 'is based on comparing total revenues to variable cost. While its exit decision is based on comparing total revenues to total costs.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(41, 'The short-run supply curve of a competitive firm is its[]', 'average variable cost curve below the marginal cost curve. Its long-run supply curve is its average total cost curve below the marginal cost curve.[]', 'average total cost curve below the marginal cost curve. Its long-run supply curve is its average variable cost curve below the marginal cost curve.[]', 'marginal cost curve above the average total cost curve. Its long-run supply curve is its marginal cost curve above the average variable cost curve.[]', 'marginal cost curve above the average variable cost curve. Its long-run supply curve is its marginal cost curve above the average total cost curve.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(42, 'Crude oil is used to produce fiberglass boats. Supposing these boats are produced in a competitive market, an increase in the price of crude oil shifts[]', 'both the marginal cost curves of individual firms and the market supply curve right.[]', 'both the marginal cost curves of individual firms and the market supply curve left.[]', 'the marginal cost curves of individual firms right, and the market supply curve left.[]', 'the marginal cost curves of individual firms left, and the market supply curve right.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(43, 'A competitive profit-maximizing firm makes zero economic profits. Which of the following is true?[]', 'Average total cost equals price.[]', 'Marginal cost equals price.[]', 'Average total cost equals average revenue.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(44, 'In long-run equilibrium, a perfectly competitive firm produces the level of output at which[]', 'total revenue is at a maximum.[]', 'average total cost is at a minimum.[]', 'marginal cost is at a minimum.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(45, 'If firms in a competitive market are earning economic profits greater than zero, then firms[]', 'enter the market, market supply shifts right and price falls.[]', 'exit the market, market supply shifts left and price rises.[]', 'enter the market, market supply shifts right and price rises.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(46, 'This graph of a typical firm in a competitive industry indicates that firms will[]', 'exit this market, so the market supply curve will shift right.[]', 'exit this market, so the market supply curve will shift left.[]', 'enter this market, so the market supply curve will shift right.[]', 'enter this market, so the market supply curve will shift left.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(47, 'In the long run in a perfectly competitive industry, economic profits of all firms will equal zero in the long run[]', 'under no circumstances.[]', 'only if the long-run market supply curve is horizontal.[]', 'only if the long-run market supply curve is upward sloping.[]', 'whether the long-run market supply curve is horizontal or upward sloping.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(48, 'Which of the following is correct?[]', 'A decrease in the market demand of some good in a competitive market is likely to increase the profits of firms.[]', 'If firms have different costs, in the long run price reflects the costs of the highest cost firm.[]', 'If price falls in a competitive market, the lowest cost firms will be the first to exit.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(49, 'In the paper industry, as more paper makers enter the market, the price of raw materials such as pulp will be bid up. If the paper industry operates in a perfectly competitive market, then an increase in demand causes the price of paper to rise in the[]', 'short run only.[]', 'long run only.[]', 'short run and the long run.[]', 'short run, but to fall in the long run.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(50, 'The long-run supply curve in a perfectly competitive market is more elastic than in the short run because[]', 'firms can enter or exit the market.[]', 'some firms have higher costs than others.[]', 'some resources are available only in limited quantities.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(51, 'Which of the following statements about a firm’s market pricing of its product is true?[]', 'Both competitive firms and monopolies are price makers.[]', 'Both competitive firms and monopolies are price takers.[]', 'A competitive firm is a price taker and a monopoly is a price maker.[]', 'A competitive firm is a price maker and a monopoly is a price taker.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(52, 'A monopoly’s marginal cost will most likely[]', 'exceed its marginal revenue.[]', 'be less than average fixed cost.[]', 'be less than the market price of its goods.[]', 'equal average total cost.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(53, 'A fundamental source of monopoly market power arises from[]', 'availability of “free” natural resources, such as water or air.[]', 'perfectly elastic demand.[]', 'perfectly inelastic demand.[]', 'barriers to entry.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(54, 'The defining characteristic of a natural monopoly is[]', 'economies of scale over the relevant range of output.[]', 'diseconomies of scale over the relevant range of output.[]', 'marginal cost is U-shaped over the relevant range of output.[]', 'marginal cost is constant over the relevant range of output.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(55, 'Authors are allowed to be monopolists in the sale of their books in order to[]', 'satisfy literary advocacy groups that exercise their lobbying power.[]', 'encourage authors to write more and better books.[]', 'correct for the negative externalities that the internet and television impose.[]', 'promote a society that thinks for themselves and learns from whichever books they please.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(56, 'If a monopolist faces a downward-sloping market demand curve, its[]', 'marginal revenue is always less than the price of the units it sells.[]', 'marginal revenue is greater than the price of the units it sells.[]', 'average revenue is always less than marginal revenue.[]', 'average revenue is less than the price of its product.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(57, 'The monopolist’s profit-maximizing quantity of output is where[]', 'average cost equals marginal revenue.[]', 'marginal cost equals marginal revenue.[]', 'price equals marginal revenue.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(58, 'A monopolist is a price[]', 'taker, and therefore has no demand curve.[]', 'taker, and therefore has no supply curve.[]', 'setter, and therefore has no demand curve.[]', 'setter, and therefore has no supply curve.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(59, 'For a monopoly firm, which of the following equalities is true?[]', 'price = average revenue[]', 'price = marginal cost[]', 'price = marginal revenue[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(60, 'According to the figure, a profit-maximizing monopoly would have total revenues equal to[]', 'P0   Q1.[]', 'P1   Q3.[]', 'P2   Q4.[]', 'P3   Q2.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(61, 'According to the figure, a profit-maximizing monopoly would have average revenues of[]', 'P0.[]', 'P1.[]', 'P2.[]', 'P3.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(62, 'For a monopoly market, total surplus can be defined as the value of the good to the[]', 'producers minus the cost incurred by consumers.[]', 'producers plus the cost incurred by consumers.[]', 'consumers minus the cost of making the good.[]', 'consumers plus the cost of making the good.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(63, 'The inefficiency of monopolies is created by a deadweight loss due to the fact that[]', 'consumers who still buy the product at the high price are worse-off.[]', 'consumers buy fewer units at the price the monopoly sets.[]', 'high monopoly prices take money from consumers’ pockets and put it in the pocket of the monopoly owners.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(64, 'Suppose that a firm has a monopoly on the production of a prescription drug, regulating them on the basis of cost has problems because[]', 'it does not provide an incentive for the monopolist to reduce its cost.[]', 'a monopolist is still able to generate excessive economic profits.[]', 'a monopolist’s costs, by definition, are higher than costs of perfectly competitive firms.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(65, 'The legislation passed by Congress in 1890 to reduce the market power of large and powerful “trusts” is called the[]', 'Clayton Act.[]', '14th Amendment.[]', 'Sherman Act.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(66, 'If regulators require a monopoly to set price equal to average total cost[]', 'consumer surplus is maximized.[]', 'total social welfare is maximized.[]', 'Both a and b are correct.[]', 'Neither a nor b is correct.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(67, 'Since natural monopolies have a declining average cost curve, regulating natural monopolies by setting price equal to marginal cost would[]', 'maximize consumer surplus.[]', 'cause the monopolist to operate at a loss.[]', 'maximize producer surplus.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(68, 'A perfectly price-discriminating monopolist is able to[]', 'produce a level of output consistent with optimal social well-being, but not maximize profit.[]', 'exercise illegal preferences over the gender of its employees.[]', 'maximize profit and produce a level of output more consistent with optimal social well-being.[]', 'do none of the above.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(69, 'When a monopolist can price discriminate perfectly then[]', 'the price effect dominates the output effect on monopoly revenue, so profits fall.[]', 'consumer surplus and deadweight losses are transformed into monopoly profits.[]', 'consumer surplus is increased.[]', 'deadweight loss is increased.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(70, 'In theory, perfect price discrimination increases[]', 'the monopolist’s profits.[]', 'consumer surplus.[]', 'deadweight loss.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(71, 'Firms may be prevented from price discrimination, if[]', 'there are large fluctuations in the price of raw materials.[]', 'buyers can arbitrage.[]', 'firms have high fixed costs.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(72, 'OPEC often holds oil production below capacity in an effort to[]', 'compel consumers to search for oil substitutes.[]', 'compel consumers to conserve oil.[]', 'keep prices above the competitive level.[]', 'create a shift in the demand for oil.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(73, 'In which of the following industries do firms set prices?[]', 'competitive markets, but not monopoly markets[]', 'monopoly markets, but not competitive markets[]', 'competitive and monopoly markets[]', 'neither competitive nor monopoly markets[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(74, 'When a firm has a natural monopoly, other firms do not enter the market because[]', 'by definition natural monopolies are protected by the government.[]', 'the owners of natural monopolies have exclusive rights to key resources.[]', 'new firms cannot achieve the same low costs as the current monopolist.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(75, 'De Beers Diamonds is a[]', 'natural monopoly.[]', 'monopoly by virtue of a government decree.[]', 'monopoly because of ownership of key resources.[]', 'All of the above explain why De Beers Diamonds has a monopoly.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(76, 'Which of the following is a barrier to entry?[]', 'a downward-sloping demand curve[]', 'a single producer is more efficient than a large number of producers[]', 'no close substitute for a product[]', 'a homogeneous product[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(77, 'Suppose a hospital in a small isolated town has a natural monopoly. With the idea of increasing competition, the city opens a second hospital.[]', 'Both hospitals will have higher average total cost than the first hospital did when it operated alone.[]', 'Both hospitals will have lower average total cost than the first hospital did when it operated alone.[]', 'Both hospitals will have the same average total cost as the first hospital when it operated alone.[]', 'The new hospital will have higher average total cost than the first hospital did when it operated alone, but the average total cost for the second hospital will be less.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(78, 'The demand curve for an individual firm’s output is[]', 'downward sloping for both a competitive firm and a monopoly.[]', 'horizontal for both a competitive firm and a monopoly.[]', 'downward sloping for a competitive firm and horizontal for a monopoly.[]', 'horizontal for a competitive firm and downward sloping for a monopoly.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(79, 'The marginal revenue of a monopoly is[]', 'greater than price.[]', 'greater than price for low levels of output, but less than price at higher levels of output.[]', 'equal to price.[]', 'less than price.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(80, 'The average revenue of a monopoly is[]', 'greater than price.[]', 'greater than price for low levels of output, but less than price at higher levels of output.[]', 'equal to price.[]', 'less than price.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(81, 'To maximize profits, a monopolist produces the quantity where[]', 'average revenue equals average cost and then sets price equal to marginal revenue.[]', 'average revenue equals average cost and then sets price so that all output is demanded.[]', 'marginal revenue equals marginal cost and then sets price to marginal revenue.[]', 'marginal revenue equals marginal cost and then sets price so that all output is demanded.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(82, 'Which of the following is not true for a profit-maximizing monopoly?[]', 'price is greater than average revenue.[]', 'profits equal total revenue minus total cost.[]', 'marginal revenue equals marginal cost.[]', 'price is greater than marginal revenue.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(83, 'The price and output of this profit-maximizing monopoly will be:[]', '$100 and 6, respectively.[]', '$ 70 and 3, respectively.[]', '$ 50 and 4, respectively.[]', '$ 40 and 5, respectively.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(84, 'If a benevolent social planner ran a monopoly, price[]', 'and output would be higher.[]', 'and output would be lower.[]', 'would be lower and output would be higher.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(85, 'At the point where the monopolist produces, the value of the good to the marginal buyer is[]', 'greater than price.[]', 'less than price.[]', 'greater than the marginal cost to the monopolist.[]', 'less than the marginal cost to the monopolist.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(86, 'In the diagram the deadweight loss is[]', '$2.50.[]', '$5.00.[]', '$7.50.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(87, 'Which of the following concerning the social cost of monopoly is correct?[]', 'The profit a monopolist makes contributes to the deadweight loss created by monopoly.[]', 'Expenditures of a monopolist to maintain the monopoly are part of the social cost.[]', 'The source of the social cost is that a monopolist sets a price below marginal cost.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(88, 'Which of the following do antitrust laws allow for?[]', 'private lawsuits against firms employing certain anti-competitive tactics[]', 'the government to split up firms to promote competition[]', 'the  option for government to prevent mergers[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(89, 'If the government sets a natural monopoly’s price equal to marginal cost[]', 'social welfare is maximized.[]', 'price falls and quantity produced rises, but social welfare is not maximized.[]', 'the monopolist makes an even larger profit than before.[]', 'the monopolist will exit the industry unless it receives a subsidy.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(90, 'The incentive to reduce costs is eliminated or reduced if the government[]', 'operates a monopoly.[]', 'requires a monopoly to set average total cost equal to price.[]', 'Both a and b are correct.[]', 'Neither a nor b is correct.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(91, 'Mergers[]', 'may be advantageous if they allow for synergies.[]', 'may be advantageous because competitive firms have little incentive to reduce costs as their economic profits are zero.[]', 'Both of the above are correct.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(92, 'Price discrimination is the practice of:[]', 'charging lower prices in the short run than in the long run.[]', 'charging lower prices in the long run than in the short run.[]', 'selling the same good at different prices to different customers.[]', 'selling more output in one market than in another market.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(93, 'Which of the following is correct?[]', 'Monopolists have lower profits when price discrimination occurs.[]', 'Price discrimination requires being able to separate customers according to their willingness to pay.[]', 'Price discrimination always lowers economic welfare.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(94, 'Perfect price discrimination implies deadweight loss[]', 'and consumer surplus are both zero.[]', 'is zero and consumer surplus is higher than in the absence of price discrimination.[]', 'is greater than zero, but consumer surplus is less than in the absence of price discrimination.[]', 'is greater than zero, and consumer surplus is higher than in the absence of price discrimination.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(95, 'Which of the following is inconsistent with price discrimination?[]', 'Colleges and universities provide financial aid to needy students.[]', 'Price per-unit increases with the quantity a person purchases.[]', 'Charging customers willing to clip coupons a lower price.[]', 'Movie tickets are priced lower for children than for adults.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(96, 'Markets with only a few sellers, each offering a product similar or identical to the others, are typically referred to as[]', 'monopoly markets.[]', 'perfectly competitive markets.[]', 'monopolistically competitive markets.[]', 'oligopoly markets.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(97, 'Firms in industries that have competitors but, at the same time, do not face so much competition that they are price takers, are operating in either a(n)[]', 'monopoly or monopolistically competitive market.[]', 'monopolistically competitive or perfectly competitive market.[]', 'oligopoly or monopoly market.[]', 'oligopoly or monopolistically competitive market.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(98, 'Firms in the United States are typically classified as[]', 'duopolists.[]', 'imperfectly competitive.[]', 'oligopolists.[]', 'perfectly competitive.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(99, 'Which list contains all market structures having many firms?[]', 'oligopoly and perfect competition[]', 'oligopoly and monopolistic competition[]', 'perfect competition and monopolistic competition.[]', 'oligopoly, perfect competition, and monopolistic competition.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(100, 'As a group, oligopolists are always better-off collectively if they[]', 'decrease prices.[]', 'limit production.[]', 'increase production.[]', 'each operate according to their own self-interest.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(101, 'Because each oligopolist cares about its own profit rather than the collective profit of their industry[]', 'society is worse-off.[]', 'they are unable to maintain monopoly power.[]', 'they are able to maximize industry profits.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(102, 'According to this table, assume that there are two profit-maximizing digital cable TV companies operating in this market. Further assume that they are able to “collude” on price and quantity of premium digital channel subscriptions to sell. As part of their collusive agreement they decide to take an equal share of the market. How much profit will each company make?[]', '$160,000[]', '$140,000[]', '$120,000[]', '$100,000[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(103, 'According to this table, what will be the quantity produced if the market is a monopoly? What will be the quantity produced if the market is a two-firm oligopoly where the two firms are unable to collude and reach a Nash equilibrium?[]', 'monopoly production 4,000, oligopoly production 8,000[]', 'monopoly production 6,000, oligopoly production 8,000[]', 'monopoly production 8,000, oligopoly production 10,000[]', 'None of the above is correct[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(104, 'When an oligopoly market is in Nash equilibrium,[]', 'a firm’s best pricing strategy depends on the strategy of other firms.[]', 'market price will be different for each firm.[]', 'individual firms will not behave as profit maximizers.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(105, 'Cartels are often short-lived because[]', 'laws often prohibit explicit collusive agreements among competitors.[]', 'self-interest often conflicts with cooperation.[]', 'it is difficult to enforce agreements reached by cartels.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(106, 'As the number of firms in an oligopoly grows larger, price and output in that market approach[]', 'those in a competitive market.[]', 'those in a monopoly.[]', 'the Nash equilibrium of a duopoly.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(107, 'According to this decision box, if both firms follow a dominant strategy, the losses of Firm A and Firm B respectively will be[]', '–$30 b and –$25 b.[]', '–$60 b and –$15 b.[]', '–$15 b and–$60 b.[]', '–$20 b and –$20 b.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(108, 'According to this decision box, which of the following is the dominant strategies for the firms?[]', 'Firm A should reveal the site and Firm B should keep it secret.[]', 'Firm A should keep the site secret and Firm B should reveal it.[]', 'Both firms should reveal the site.[]', 'Both firms should keep the site secret.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(109, 'In a world with only two countries, the noncooperative outcome to an “arms race” game is clearly[]', 'bad for society.[]', 'the best possible outcome for society.[]', 'optimal for one player at the expense of the other.[]', 'better than the cooperative outcome.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(110, 'Very often, the reason that players can solve the prisoners’ dilemma game and reach the most profitable outcome is that[]', 'the game becomes more competitive.[]', 'they play the game not once, but many times.[]', 'each player tries to capture a large portion of the market share.[]', 'All of the above can solve the prisoners’ dilemma.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(111, 'In a two-person repeated game, a tit-for-tat strategy starts with[]', 'cooperation and then each player mimics the other player’s last move.[]', 'cooperation and then each player is unresponsive to the strategic moves of the other player.[]', 'non-cooperation and then each player pursues his or her own self-interest.[]', 'non-cooperation and then each player cooperates when the other player demonstrates a desire for the cooperative solution.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(112, 'Two students are suspected of cheating together on an exam. If both confess they each get an F on the exam. If one confesses she gets an F in the course and the other student is expelled. If neither student confesses there is no penalty. Considering only these consequences a student should[]', 'confess if he is certain the other will not confess.[]', 'never confess.[]', 'always confess.[]', 'confess if he is certain the other will confess.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(113, 'The Sherman Antitrust Act[]', 'was passed to encourage judicial leniency in the review of cooperative agreements.[]', 'was concerned with Nash equilibria dominated by self-interest in prisoners’ dilemma games.[]', 'provided tax advantages to firms who engaged in competitive behavior.[]', 'restricted the ability of competitors to engage in cooperative agreements.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(114, 'Antitrust laws in general are used to[]', 'prevent oligopolists from acting in ways that make markets less competitive.[]', 'help oligopolists resolve their version of the prisoner’s dilemma.[]', 'encourage oligopolists to pursue cooperative-interest at the expense of self-interest.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(115, 'Suppose discount electronics retailers free ride on information about products provided by nondiscount retailers. The information that is provided about products is[]', 'greater than the optimal quantity.[]', 'the optimal quantity.[]', 'less than the optimal quantity.[]', 'Not necessarily any one of the above.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(116, 'The practice of requiring someone to buy two or more items together is[]', 'illegal because it allows firms to form collusive arrangements.[]', 'not illegal because it increases the well-being of society.[]', 'illegal because it allows firms to expand their market power.[]', 'not illegal because collusive agreements are conducive to cooperative outcomes.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(117, 'The practice of selling a product to retailers and requiring the retailers to charge a specific price for the product is called[]', 'resale price maintenance.[]', 'fixed retail pricing.[]', 'unfair trade.[]', 'cost plus pricing.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(118, 'A market structure with a few firms is known as[]', 'monopoly.[]', 'oligopoly.[]', 'monopolistic competition.[]', 'perfect competition.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(119, 'Sellers are assumed to offer similar products in which type(s) of market structures?[]', 'both monopolistic competition and oligopoly[]', 'neither monopolistic competition nor oligopoly[]', 'monopolistic competition, but not oligopoly[]', 'oligopoly, but not monopolistic competition[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(120, 'Which of the following products is produced in an oligopoly market?[]', 'novels[]', 'movies[]', 'crude oil[]', 'computer games[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(121, 'Which of the following products is produced in a monopolistically competitive market?[]', 'compact discs[]', 'tennis balls[]', 'crude oil[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(122, 'Oligopolists have the[]', 'highest profits when they cooperate, which they usually do.[]', 'highest profits when they cooperate, but find it difficult to cooperate.[]', 'highest profits when they care only about their own profits, which they usually do.[]', 'same profits whether they cooperate or care only about their own profits.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(123, 'Price exceeds marginal cost[]', 'in monopoly markets and oligopoly markets.[]', 'only in monopoly markets.[]', 'only in oligopoly markets.[]', 'in neither oligopoly nor monopoly markets.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(124, 'Suppose the market for mineral water is produced at a marginal cost of zero in a duopoly market with the demand schedule shown. If the duopolists collude they will produce a total of[]', '200 units, which is more than if they did not collude.[]', '200 units, which is less than if they did not collude.[]', '160 units, which is more than if they did not collude.[]', '160 units, which is less than if they did not collude.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(125, 'Suppose the table shows the demand curve for crude oil and that the marginal cost of producing a unit of crude oil is $0.[]', 'The quantity produced in a competitive market is 600; the quantity produced by oligopolists that collude is 450.[]', 'The quantity produced in a competitive market is 600; the quantity produced by oligopolists that collude is 300.[]', 'The quantity produced in a competitive market is 450; the quantity produced by oligopolists that collude is 300.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(126, 'When oligopolists do not collude price[]', 'and output are higher than if they collude.[]', 'and output are lower than if they collude.[]', 'is higher and output is lower than if they collude.[]', 'is lower and output is higher than if they collude.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(127, 'When oligopolists do not collude[]', 'price and output are the same as in a competitive market.[]', 'price is higher and output is lower than in a competitive market.[]', 'price is lower and output is higher than in a competitive market.[]', 'both price and output are higher than in a competitive market.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(128, 'A Nash equilibrium occurs when:[]', 'oligopolists cooperate with each other.[]', 'economic actors who are interacting choose their best strategy given the strategies chosen by others.[]', 'the efficient allocation of resources is achieved by setting marginal revenue equal to marginal cost.[]', 'a monopolist is forced to produce the efficient level of output.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(129, 'If an oligopolist raises production[]', 'both the output effect and the price effect tend to raise profits.[]', 'both the output effect and the price effect tend to decrease profits.[]', 'the output effect tends to raise profits while the price effect tends to decrease profits.[]', 'the output effect tends to decrease profits while the price effect tends to raise profits.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(130, 'As the number of sellers in an oligopoly rises, the magnitude of the price effect[]', 'rises, and the output effect vanishes.[]', 'rises, but the output effect remains.[]', 'falls, and the output effect vanishes.[]', 'falls, but the output effect remains.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(131, 'The prisoners’ dilemma helps to explain why cooperation[]', 'occurs in strategic situations.[]', 'is difficult to maintain in strategic situations.[]', 'is mutually beneficial in strategic situations.[]', 'never occurs in strategic situations.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(132, 'Game theory is especially relevant to understanding[]', 'competitive markets.[]', 'monopoly markets.[]', 'oligopoly markets.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(133, 'A tit-for-tat strategy[]', 'performed the best of many strategies compared in a tournament.[]', 'requires that if one party reneges, that the other will follow her dominant strategy forever.[]', 'implies that oligopolists will produce closer to the socially efficient level than if each firm sticks to its dominant strategy.[]', 'makes it difficult for oligopolists to cooperate.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(134, 'Suppose that a manufacturer requires that the retailers handling its product enter into resale price maintenance (RPM) agreements. This:[]', 'eliminates all competition among those retailers.[]', 'enables the manufacturer to charge a higher wholesale price to the retailers than would otherwise be possible.[]', 'may increase the amount of service that customers receive.[]', 'forces the retailers to accept a lower mark-up over the wholesale price than they would obtain without RPM.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(135, 'Which of the following is incorrect?[]', 'To move the allocation of resources closer to the social optimum, policymakers should try to induce firms in an oligopoly to compete rather than cooperate.[]', 'For many centuries, judges in England and the United States have deemed agreements among competitors to reduce quantities and raise prices to be contrary to the public good.[]', 'It is unclear whether tying has adverse economic effects for society as a whole.[]', 'Predatory pricing may be considered a type of price discrimination.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(136, 'The Sherman Act[]', 'made agreements to restrain trade among competitors unenforceable.[]', 'made agreements to restrain trade among competitors a criminal conspiracy.[]', 'allowed persons who could prove that they were damaged by illegal trade to sue the conspiring firms.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(137, 'To prevent discount retailers from free riding on information provided about goods by other retailers, wholesalers may use[]', 'resale price maintenance.[]', 'predatory pricing.[]', 'price discrimination.[]', 'tying.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(138, 'Tying[]', 'has not yet been banned by the U.S. court system.[]', 'is probably used to prevent a free-rider problem.[]', 'is, according to most economists, likely used by firms to expand market power.[]', 'may be used as a form of price discrimination.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(139, 'In a monopolistically competitive industry, profit-maximizing firms are price[]', 'takers who produce a quantity where price is equal to marginal cost.[]', 'takers who produce a quantity where price is greater than marginal cost.[]', 'setters who set price equal to marginal cost.[]', 'setters who set price above marginal cost.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(140, 'When free entry is one of the attributes of a market structure, economic profits in the long run[]', 'are equal to implicit cost.[]', 'are greater than implicit cost.[]', 'are zero.[]', 'depend on whether or not firms produce identical products.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(141, 'The profit-maximizing rule for a firm in a monopolistically competitive market is to produce the quantity at which[]', 'average revenue equals average total cost.[]', 'average total cost is at its minimum.[]', 'marginal revenue is equal to marginal cost.[]', 'marginal cost is at its minimum.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(142, 'Product differentiation causes the seller of a good to face what type of demand curve?[]', 'upward sloping[]', 'downward sloping[]', 'horizontal[]', 'vertical[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(143, 'A monopolistically competitive firm chooses[]', 'the quantity of output to produce and the price of its output.[]', 'the quantity of output to produce, but the market determines price.[]', 'the price, but competition in the market determines the quantity.[]', 'only whether to enter or exit the market.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(144, 'If firms in a monopolistically competitive market are earning negative economic profits, which of the following scenarios would best reflect the change facing incumbent firms as the market adjusts to its new equilibrium?[]', 'a downward shift in their marginal cost curve[]', 'an upward shift in their marginal cost curve[]', 'a decrease in demand[]', 'an increase in demand[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(145, 'As new firms enter a monopolistically competitive market, profits of existing firms[]', 'decline and product diversity in the market increases.[]', 'decline and product diversity in the market decreases.[]', 'rise and product diversity in the market decreases.[]', 'rise and product diversity in the market increases.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(146, 'When a profit-maximizing firm in a monopolistically competitive market is producing the long-run equilibrium quantity,[]', 'its demand curve will be tangent to its average total cost curve.[]', 'it will be earning economic profits.[]', 'its average revenue will equal marginal cost.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(147, 'Since a firm in a monopolistically competitive market faces a[]', 'downward-sloping demand curve, it will always operate at efficient scale.[]', 'perfectly inelastic demand curve, it will always operate at efficient scale.[]', 'perfectly elastic demand curve, it will always operate at excess capacity.[]', 'downward-sloping demand curve, it will always operate at excess capacity.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(148, 'Monopolistically competitive firms operate at[]', 'excess capacity, so that additional production would raise average total cost.[]', 'excess capacity, so that additional production would lower average total cost.[]', 'efficient scale, so that additional production would raise average total cost.[]', 'efficient scale, so that additional production would lower average total cost.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(149, 'In the long run, a firm in a perfectly competitive market operates at[]', 'excess capacity and so do monopolistically competitive firms.[]', 'excess capacity while monopolistically competitive firm operate at efficient scale.[]', 'efficient scale and so do monopolistically competitive firms.[]', 'efficient scale while monopolistically competitive firms operate at excess capacity.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(150, 'A monopolistically competitive market could be considered inefficient because[]', 'price exceeds marginal cost.[]', 'marginal cost exceeds average revenue.[]', 'firms in monopolistically competitive markets often collude.[]', 'mark-up pricing does not occur in any other market structure.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(151, 'The deadweight loss that is associated with a monopolistically competitive market is a result of[]', 'operating in a constant cost industry.[]', 'pricing above marginal cost.[]', 'advertising costs.[]', 'pricing below marginal cost in order to increase market share.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(152, 'The administrative burden of regulating price in a monopolistically competitive market is[]', 'small because firms produce at under-capacity.[]', 'small due to economies of scale.[]', 'large because of a large number of firms that produce differentiated products.[]', 'large because price is usually below marginal cost.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(153, 'If regulators required firms in monopolistically competitive markets to set price equal to marginal cost,[]', 'firms would most likely experience economic losses.[]', 'firms would also operate at the efficient scale.[]', 'new firms would be likely to enter the market.[]', 'the most efficient firms are not likely to be affected.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(154, 'When the loss from a business-stealing externality exceeds the gain from a product-variety externality,[]', 'market efficiency is likely to be enhanced by the entry of new firms.[]', 'there are likely to be too many firms in a monopolistically competitive market.[]', 'the market structure is likely to be above the efficient scale.[]', 'firms are more likely to operate at efficient scale.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(155, 'If advertising decreases the elasticity of demand for a firm’s product, the firm is likely to[]', 'lower their advertising budget.[]', 'become more competitive.[]', 'charge a larger mark-up over marginal cost.[]', 'produce above the efficient scale.[]', 3, 1, 'medium');
INSERT INTO `econ_medium` (`Qno`, `Question`, `Option1`, `Option2`, `Option3`, `Option4`, `Answer`, `marks`, `Complexity`) VALUES
(156, 'In recent years, the courts have been[]', 'less lenient of advertising in order to enhance the ability of markets to allocate resources efficiently.[]', 'less lenient of advertising in order to decrease elasticity of demand for specific products.[]', 'more lenient of advertising in order to enhance brand loyalty.[]', 'more lenient of advertising in order to enhance competition in markets.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(157, 'When firms in a monopolistically competitive market engage in price-related advertising, defenders of advertising argue that[]', 'the quality of products sold in the market always increases.[]', 'customers are less likely to be informed about other characteristics of the product.[]', 'new firms are discouraged from entering the market.[]', 'each firm has less market power.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(158, 'Results of the study done by Lee Benham on advertising for eyeglasses suggests that[]', 'optometrists would enthusiastically endorse advertising restrictions.	[]', 'brand loyalty and market power in the eyeglass market was likely to be more pervasive in states that allowed advertising.[]', 'advertising restrictions were clearly beneficial to societal welfare.[]', 'eyeglass sales were more profitable in states that allowed advertising.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(159, 'Defenders of advertising argue that it is not rational for profit-maximizing firms to spend money on advertising for products that have[]', 'low prices.[]', 'high prices.[]', 'superior quality.[]', 'inferior quality.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(160, 'In some countries, brand name fast-food restaurants are not allowed to operate. Such restrictions are likely to[]', 'reduce barriers to entry in imperfect markets.[]', 'reduce the competitive nature of local fast-food markets.[]', 'enhance the social well-being of society.[]', 'enhance the choice set of consumers among local restaurants.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(161, 'Viola uses only Log Cabin® brand maple syrup on her pancakes. She claims that even though generic maple syrups are cheaper, that they often seem watery. In a blind taste test Viola prefers a generic maple syrup. Her behavior is consistently explained by which of the following?[]', 'Consumers of brand-name products do not know their true preferences.[]', 'Consumers may choose brand-names to ensure the general quality of the product.[]', 'Consumers of brand-name products are likely to be uninformed about the quality of competing generic products.[]', 'None of the above is consistent.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(162, 'Monopolistic competition is characterized by[]', 'few sellers and free entry.[]', 'few sellers and restricted entry.[]', 'many sellers and free entry.[]', 'many sellers and restricted entry.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(163, 'Which of the following products is likely to be sold in a monopolistically competitive market?[]', 'crude oil[]', 'electricity[]', 'wheat[]', 'furniture[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(164, 'The demand curve of a monopolistically competitive firm is[]', 'downward sloping; as it also is for a monopolist.[]', 'downward sloping; as it also is for monopolists and perfectly competitive firms.[]', 'horizontal; as it also is for a perfectly competitive firm.[]', 'horizontal; as it also is for monopolists and perfectly competitive firms.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(165, 'A monopolistically competitive firm maximizes profits by setting quantity and/or price according to the same rule as[]', 'a perfectly competitive firm.[]', 'a monopolist.[]', 'an oligopolist.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(166, 'A monopolistically competitive firm maximizes profits at the quantity where[]', 'average total cost = marginal cost.[]', 'average total cost = average revenue.[]', 'marginal revenue = average revenue.[]', 'marginal revenue = marginal cost.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(167, 'A monopolistically competitive firm maximizes its profits and has profits greater than zero if[]', 'average total cost equals average revenue and average total cost is greater than price.[]', 'average total cost equals average revenue and average total cost is less than price.[]', 'marginal revenue equals marginal cost and average total cost is greater than price.[]', 'marginal revenue equals marginal cost and average total cost is less than price.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(168, 'When price is above average total cost in a monopolistically competitive market[]', 'new firms enter the market, and the demand curves of existing firms shift left.[]', 'new firms enter the market and the demand curves of existing firms shifts right.[]', 'some firms exit the market and the demand curves of existing firms shifts left.[]', 'some firms exit the market and the demand curve of existing firms shifts right.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(169, 'When a monopolistically competitive firm is in long-run equilibrium[]', 'economic profits will be zero.[]', 'marginal cost exceeds price.[]', 'marginal revenue exceeds marginal cost.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(170, 'Which of the following is correct?[]', 'Monopolistically competitive firms are price takers.[]', 'For monopolistically competitive firms the marginal revenue curve lies above the demand curve.[]', 'Under monopolistic competition, if price exceeds average total cost, firms will enter the market.[]', 'For monopolistically competitive firms, price equals marginal cost in the long run.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(171, 'Consider the following two sentences. Because the demand curve of a monopolistically competitive firm is downward sloping, its marginal revenue is less than price. Because there is free entry into monopolistically competitive markets, in the long-run economic profits are driven to zero.[]', 'Both sentences are correct.[]', 'Both sentences are incorrect.[]', 'Only the first sentence is correct.[]', 'Only the second sentence is correct.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(172, 'Consider the following two sentences. Both perfectly competitive and monopolistically competitive firms produce at the efficient scale. Perfectly competitive firms produce where price equals marginal cost, while monopolistically competitive firms produce where price is greater than marginal cost.[]', 'Both sentences are correct.[]', 'Neither sentence is correct.[]', 'Only the first sentence is correct.[]', 'Only the second sentence is correct.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(173, 'A monopolistically competitive firm in the long run produces[]', 'a quantity less than the efficient scale.[]', 'at the efficient scale.[]', 'at a quantity above the efficient scale.[]', 'None of the above is necessarily correct, it depends on whether firms are making economic profits greater than zero.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(174, 'In the long run profit-maximizing monopolistically competitive firms charge a price[]', 'above average total cost, but less than marginal cost.[]', 'above average total cost, but greater than marginal cost.[]', 'equal to average total cost, but less than marginal cost.[]', 'equal to average total cost, but greater than marginal cost.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(175, 'Excess capacity arises under conditions of monopolistic competition because:[]', 'there is underutilization of resources and not enough firms.[]', 'the output produced does not minimize average total cost.[]', 'a monopolistically competitive firm produces more output than would be produced by a perfectly competitive firm.[]', 'there are too many goods chasing too few resources.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(176, 'Which of the externalities created by the entry of a new firm exists under both perfect competition and monopolistic competition?[]', 'only the product-variety externality[]', 'only the business-stealing externality[]', 'both the product-variety externality and the business-stealing externality[]', 'neither the product-variety externality nor the business-stealing externality[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(177, 'Requiring monopolistic competitors to set price equal to marginal cost would[]', 'be a burden because there are so many producers of differentiated products.[]', 'cause them to make losses.[]', 'Both of the above are correct.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(178, 'The number of firms in a monopolistically competitive market is likely to be too small[]', 'if the product-variety externality is larger than the business-stealing externality.[]', 'if the business-stealing externality is larger than the product-variety externality.[]', 'if there are either business-stealing externalities or product-variety externalities.[]', 'under no conditions, monopolistically competitive markets always have a larger number of firms than is socially efficient.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(179, 'Monopolistic competition results in inefficiency because[]', 'they can earn an economic profit in the short run.[]', 'price is not equal to average total cost in the long run.[]', 'firms exit the industry in response to losses.[]', 'price is greater than marginal cost.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(180, 'In which of the following markets are advertising expenditures as a percent of revenues likely to be highest?[]', 'perfect competition.[]', 'monopoly.[]', 'monopolistic competition.[]', 'None of the above is necessarily likely to spend a larger share of revenues on advertising than the others.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(181, 'Critics of advertising argue that advertising:[]', 'increases the elasticity of demand for the firm’s product.[]', 'impedes competition.[]', 'decreases demand for the firm’s product.[]', 'decreases supply of the firm’s product.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(182, 'Suppose that by advertising, fast food places are able to increase the perception that their products are unique and so foster brand loyalty. The demand curves for the products of these firms become[]', 'more elastic, so markup increases.[]', 'more elastic, so markup decreases.[]', 'less elastic, so markup increases.[]', 'less elastic, so markup decreases.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(183, 'Which of the following is incorrect?[]', 'Courts have recently concluded that restrictions on advertising by certain professions served mostly to curtail competition.[]', 'A study showed that the average price of eyeglasses was higher in states that allowed advertising than in states that did not.[]', 'By their willingness to spend money on advertising alone, firms signal that their products are not of inferior quality.[]', 'Advertising may lead to a more efficient allocation of resources.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(184, 'Brand loyalty may[]', 'provide incentive for brand names to offer products of consistently high quality.[]', 'make demand for the brand’s product more elastic.[]', 'tend to push average total cost towards price.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(185, 'Factors of production are best defined as the[]', 'wages paid to the workforce.[]', 'goods and services sold in the market.[]', 'output produced from raw materials.[]', 'inputs used to produce goods and services.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(186, 'Since a firm’s demand for a factor of production comes from its decision to supply a good in the market, we refer to this type of demand as[]', 'supplied demand.[]', 'derived demand.[]', 'secondary demand.[]', 'differentiated demand.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(187, 'Most of the total income earned in the U.S. economy is ultimately paid to households in the form of[]', 'rent.[]', 'wages.[]', 'interest.[]', 'profit.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(188, 'The production function describes the relationship between[]', 'inputs and cost.[]', 'outputs and profit.[]', 'inputs and outputs.[]', 'inputs and revenue.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(189, 'The marginal product of labor is defined as the increase in[]', 'revenue per additional unit of input.[]', 'output per additional unit of input.[]', 'revenue per additional unit of output.[]', 'output per additional unit of revenue.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(190, 'If hiring more workers causes each additional worker to contribute less to the total output,[]', 'diminishing profitability is present.[]', 'increasing marginal product is present.[]', 'diminishing marginal product is present.[]', 'diminishing marginal cost is present.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(191, 'The value of the marginal product of labor is equal to the change in[]', 'marginal cost with the addition of the last worker.[]', 'total cost with the addition of the last worker.[]', 'total profit with the addition of the last worker.[]', 'total revenue with the addition of the last worker.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(192, 'A competitive, profit-maximizing firm hires workers until[]', 'the value of the marginal product equals the wage.[]', 'unemployment rates are zero.[]', 'marginal product equals zero.[]', 'marginal revenue equals zero.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(193, 'A worker’s contribution to a firm’s revenue is measured directly by the worker’s[]', 'contribution to output.[]', 'value of marginal product.[]', 'marginal product minus his/her wage.[]', 'marginal product multiplied by his/her wage.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(194, 'A profit-maximizing competitive firm that experiences diminishing marginal product of labor is also experiencing[]', 'an upward-sloping demand for labor.[]', 'a downward-sloping demand for labor.[]', 'a perfectly elastic supply of labor.[]', 'a perfectly inelastic supply of labor.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(195, 'If one observes a profit-maximizing firm increasing employment, it is possible to infer that the[]', 'firm is increasing its market share.[]', 'marginal product is rising.[]', 'wage exceeds the value of the marginal product.[]', 'value of the marginal product exceeds the wage.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(196, 'If the price of airline tickets rises, what will happen to the demand curve for flight attendants?[]', 'It will shift to the left.[]', 'It will shift to the right.[]', 'There will be a movement along the curve.[]', 'It will remain unchanged; price changes do not shift demand curves.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(197, 'Which of the following events would cause an increase in the labor supply curve?[]', 'more married women deciding to work[]', 'a lower Social Security retirement age[]', 'fewer married men deciding to work[]', 'tighter restrictions on immigration policy[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(198, 'When labor supply increases,[]', 'profit-maximizing firms reduce employment.[]', 'the marginal productivity of workers always increases.[]', 'wages increase as long as supply is upward sloping.[]', 'wages decrease as long as labor demand is downward sloping.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(199, 'Which of the following could decrease labor demand?[]', 'an increase in migrant workers[]', 'a decrease in the labor supply[]', 'a decrease in demand for the final product produced by labor[]', 'an increase in the marginal productivity of workers[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(200, 'When firms are able to increase the amount of physical capital available to workers the[]', 'value of the marginal product of labor will decrease.[]', 'value of the marginal product of labor will increase.[]', 'final product price will increase.[]', 'marginal product of labor will decline.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(201, 'When economists refer to a firm’s capital, they are likely to be using the term to describe the[]', 'markets for final goods and services.[]', 'amount of financing provided by the equity markets.[]', 'stock of equipment and buildings used in production.[]', 'amount of bank financing used by the firm.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(202, 'The purchase price of land is[]', 'the price received from the flow of some land services.[]', 'the price a person pays to own the factor of production.[]', 'always less than the rental price.[]', 'the value of the land to the firm this time period.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(203, 'The marginal product of any factor of production depends on[]', 'the price of the final good.[]', 'the quantity of the factor used.[]', 'the demand for the final good.[]', 'whether it is used to produce a good or a service.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(204, 'As a result of severe flooding, a farmer loses one-half of his productive farmland. He should expect to see the marginal productivity of his land[]', 'increase.[]', 'decrease.[]', 'become negative.[]', 'remain unchanged.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(205, 'The change in the supply of one factor[]', 'alters the earnings of all factors.[]', 'will not alter the marginal productivity of other factors, but may lower their price.[]', 'will not lower the price of other factors, but may alter their marginal productivity.[]', 'will not change the value of marginal product for other factors.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(206, 'For the profit-maximizing competitive firm, the value of marginal product curve is[]', 'always rising.[]', 'the labor supply curve.[]', 'the labor demand curve.[]', 'falling only when marginal product is rising.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(207, 'Which of the following would be considered capital?[]', 'Tiger Woods’ golf clubs[]', 'Greg Mankiw’s Ph.D.[]', 'a West Virginia coal mine[]', 'the Kansas City Chiefs’ defensive coach[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(208, 'The most important factor of product based on income earned in the U.S. economy is[]', 'land.[]', 'labor.[]', 'capital.[]', 'profit.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(209, 'Derived demand refers to the fact that the demand for a factor of production is derived from the[]', 'supply of that factor of production.[]', 'level of a firm’s investment.[]', 'demand for the product it produces.[]', 'equilibrium price for that factor of production in the market.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(210, 'A production function shows the relationship between the quantity of[]', 'inputs used to make a good and the cost associated with those inputs.[]', 'inputs used to make a good and the quantity of output of that good.[]', 'output of a good and the amount of profit a firm makes from the sale of that good.[]', 'inputs used to make a good and the total revenue generated by the sale of that good.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(211, 'The value of the marginal product curve is downward sloping because[]', 'as firms hire additional workers, profit for the firm declines.[]', 'of the law of diminishing marginal product.[]', 'as firms hire additional workers, they are forced to hire less-qualified workers.[]', 'firms must lower the price of their product in order to sell more of it.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(212, 'The increase in the amount of output from an additional unit of labor is called[]', 'derived demand.[]', 'diminishing marginal product.[]', 'factors of production.[]', 'the marginal product of labor.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(213, 'For a profit-maximizing firm, the decision to employ an additional worker is based on how[]', 'long the worker plans to stay with the company.[]', 'profitable that worker will be to the firm.[]', 'much of the product the worker can produce.[]', 'much experience the worker has with that type of job.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(214, 'The value of the marginal product of labor is equal to[]', 'total output divided by the quantity of labor.[]', 'the price of the output the labor produced.[]', 'the marginal product of labor times the price of the output.[]', 'the supply curve for labor.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(215, 'The competitive, profit-maximizing firm’s demand for labor curve is[]', 'a horizontal line in perfectly competitive industries.[]', 'typically more elastic than the demand for the product the firms are producing.[]', 'equal to the supply of labor when markets are in equilibrium.[]', 'equal to the value of the marginal product of labor curve.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(216, 'If the price of televisions falls, the value of the marginal product of workers making televisions will[]', 'definitely fall.[]', 'definitely rise.[]', 'not change.[]', 'fall or rise; we do not have enough information to know for certain.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(217, 'If Kansans begin moving to Colorado to live because of the beautiful scenery, we would expect[]', 'firms to automatically relocate to Kansas.[]', 'the supply of labor to increase in Kansas and decrease in Colorado.[]', 'the supply of labor to increase in Colorado and decrease in Kansas.[]', 'wages to increase in Colorado and decrease in Kansas.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(218, 'Plainco Corporations sells widgets for $3 each in a market that is perfectly competitive. Increasing the number of Plainco workers from 1,000 to 1,001 would cause output to rise from 615 to 625 widgets per day. Plainco should hire the 1,001st worker only when[]', 'the wage is $30 or less per day.[]', 'the wage is more than $30 per day.[]', 'the wage is $6.25 or less per day.[]', 'workers are willing to work on a piecework basis.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(219, 'Which of the following would NOT increase the demand for labor?[]', 'an increase in the final product price[]', 'an increase in the amount of capital available for workers to use[]', 'an increase in the marginal productivity of workers[]', 'an increase in the wage labor receives[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(220, 'Each of the following is a key determinant of labor productivity EXCEPT the amount of[]', 'human capital acquired through education and training.[]', 'technological knowledge that is available.[]', 'tools and equipment that is available.[]', 'annual growth the company experiences.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(221, 'The value of the marginal product curve is also a firm’s[]', 'total revenue curve.[]', 'supply curve for labor.[]', 'demand curve for labor.[]', 'production function.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(222, 'If the price of Godiva chocolates increases, we would expect that this company’s wages will[]', 'rise and fewer workers will be hired.[]', 'fall and more workers will be hired.[]', 'rise and more workers will be hired.[]', 'fall and fewer workers will be hired.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(223, 'Workers who acquire additional training or education should expect[]', 'a wage increase, since they now should be more productive.[]', 'to be fired, since they are now overqualified for their job.[]', 'to be required to train other workers for the firm.[]', 'to have less need for physical capital associated with their job.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(224, 'An orange grower in Florida who loses most of his orange trees to a hard freeze should expect the marginal productivity of his capital to[]', 'increase.[]', 'decrease.[]', 'stay the same.[]', 'be negative.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(225, 'An upward-sloping supply curve means that[]', 'workers prefer to work less when wages are high.[]', 'workers prefer to buy more leisure time when their incomes increase.[]', 'an increase in wages causes workers to increase the quantity of labor they supply.[]', 'workers will attempt to buy more leisure time and supply more labor when wages rise.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(226, 'Given a downward-sloping demand for labor curve, if the supply of labor increases, we would expect[]', 'firms will choose to hire fewer workers.[]', 'a shortage of workers in most industries.[]', 'the equilibrium wage to fall.[]', 'the value of the marginal product of labor to rise.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(227, 'The price paid to any factor of production[]', 'decreases when the demand for that factor increases.[]', 'is equal to the value of the marginal product of that factor.[]', 'increases as more of the factor is used in the production process.[]', 'will be greater than the value of the marginal product of that factor if the firm is a profit-maximizer.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(228, 'When wage differentials are observed in competitive labor markets, the neoclassical theory of labor markets would predict[]', 'market discrimination.[]', 'that wage differences reflect social status.[]', 'that wages will converge over time.[]', 'a difference in the value of marginal product of labor.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(229, 'The job of night watchman at the Punxsutawny Phil Groundhog museum is known to have a high wage. This is likely to be partially explained by the fact that the job[]', 'is likely to be incredibly dull.[]', 'is likely to be difficult.[]', 'is likely to require specialized skills.[]', 'provides plenty of time for self-reflection.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(230, 'The term “compensating differential” refers to[]', 'the fact that workers that do similar work should be paid the same wage.[]', 'a wage difference that arises from nonmonetary characteristics of different jobs.[]', 'a wage difference that is distinguishable on the basis of monetary characteristics.[]', 'all of the above.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(231, 'A recent law school graduate is considering two offers to practice law, one in California and one in Mississippi. Rumor has it that it is very difficult to pass the Mississippi bar exam and meet other certification requirements required by the Mississippi Attorney Association. Assuming all other things are equal, the attorney would expect[]', 'wages in California and Mississippi to be identical.[]', 'to make a lower wage in Mississippi.[]', 'to make a higher wage in Mississippi.[]', 'to be unable to predict the wage difference between Mississippi and California.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(232, 'Public schoolteachers are known to have low wages. This is likely to be partially explained by the fact that[]', 'public schoolteacher jobs are easy.[]', 'public schoolteachers need very little money to live.[]', 'public schoolteachers are required to be college graduates.[]', 'many people perceive the job of public schoolteacher to have a high element of personal satisfaction.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(233, 'Workers that have invested in human capital are[]', 'universally less productive in “dull” jobs.[]', 'likely to have a higher value of marginal product.[]', 'likely to have a lower value of marginal product.[]', 'not likely to have changed the value of their marginal product.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(234, 'By 1998, the earnings gap between both men and women college graduates in the United States and those with only a high school diploma increased to[]', '118 percent for men and 98 percent for women.[]', '66 percent for men and 55 percent for women.[]', '85 percent for men and 40 percent for women.[]', '98 percent for men and 118 percent for women.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(235, 'The statement “the rich get richer and the poor get poorer” is evident in the fact that[]', 'developing countries do not pay workers the value of their marginal product.[]', 'developed economies export high-skill jobs to developing countries.[]', 'the poor must shoulder an increasing amount of the public debt.[]', 'the earnings gap between high-skill jobs and low-skill jobs has increased over the last several years.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(236, 'Economists who study labor markets have discovered that[]', 'ability, effort, and chance are likely to be significant contributors to wage differences.[]', 'only about 5 percent of wage differences are related to chance.[]', 'ability is not difficult to measure, but is largely insignificant in explaining wage differences.[]', 'work effort is difficult to measure, but is not likely to contribute much to an explanation of wage differences.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(237, 'Empirical analysis of wage differences has found evidence[]', 'of a minor role played by omitted variables.[]', 'of a direct correlation between wages and attractiveness.[]', 'that the physical appearance of people in identical jobs is not likely to impact their wages.[]', 'that suggests that physical appearance-related wage differentials among males are vastly different than differentials among females.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(238, 'According to the human capital view, education[]', 'alters work ethic.[]', 'leads to lower lifetime earnings.[]', 'enhances productivity.[]', 'is an indicator of raw intellect.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(239, 'The fact that women are more likely to interrupt their careers to raise children reflects[]', 'further evidence that labor markets discriminate against women.[]', 'evidence that society under-values the role of women in the market place.[]', 'a potential market-based reason why average wages for men exceed those for women.[]', 'evidence that markets are inefficient at allocating labor resources.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(240, 'Evidence suggests that business owners are generally[]', 'interested in profits, only when discrimination is illegal.[]', 'more interested in discrimination than in making a profit.[]', 'unable to determine the link between discrimination and profitability.[]', 'more interested in making a profit than in discriminating against a particular group.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(241, 'Discriminatory hiring practices can be expected, even if markets are competitive, as a result of[]', 'lower costs of hiring.[]', 'customer preferences.[]', 'a perfectly elastic market demand.[]', 'unrestricted entry and exit in markets.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(242, 'The issue of comparable worth is one in which[]', 'all workers should receive the same wages in an economy.[]', 'markets are allowed to determine a worker’s rate of compensation.[]', 'workers with “comparable” education, experience, responsibility, and working conditions would be compensated at similar wage rates.[]', 'all workers should be provided an opportunity to make a comparable contribution to the economy.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(243, 'Which of the following scenarios would serve to decrease the demand for unskilled labor in our country?[]', 'increased international trade with countries where unskilled labor is more plentiful[]', 'increased demand for goods produced by unskilled labor[]', 'increased productivity gains among the unskilled laborers[]', 'increased supply of migrant workers[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(244, 'Why do major league baseball players get paid more than minor league players?[]', 'The higher wage reflects a compensating differential.[]', 'Major league players are better athletes.[]', 'The higher wage is often due to educational discrepancies.[]', 'Playing in the major leagues is less pleasant than playing in the minor leagues.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(245, 'Which of the following statements represents the idea behind signaling in education?[]', 'Education can turn an unproductive person into a productive person.[]', 'The more naturally productive someone is the more they are inclined to educate themselves.[]', 'Most college graduates wouldn’t be half as productive if it were not for the years they spend in the classroom.[]', 'all of the above[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(246, 'Studies have shown that nonunion workers earn about[]', '10 to 20 percent less than union workers.[]', '10 to 20 percent more than union workers.[]', '40 to 50 percent more than union workers.[]', '40 to 50 percent less than union workers.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(247, 'How does the theory of efficiency wages explain above-equilibrium wages?[]', 'Employers are forced to pay higher wages in efficient markets.[]', 'Workers get a raise in wage when they prove they are increasing their productivity.[]', 'Workers demand higher wages to compensate for poor fringe benefits.[]', 'Employers give their workers a higher wage in the hopes that it will lead to increased productivity.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(248, 'Racial segregation of streetcars in the southern cities was largely opposed by[]', 'streetcar firms.[]', 'government officials.[]', 'Sherman antitrust laws.[]', 'all of the above.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(249, 'What was the main reason the gender gap did not narrow during the post-war years?[]', 'Women added more to marginal product than men.[]', 'Employers were required to pay men more to do the same job women were doing.[]', 'Many of the women who entered the labor force had not worked for quite some time and therefore lacked experience.[]', 'all of the above[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(250, 'Economists would argue that the gender wage gap is narrowing because of[]', 'efficiency wages.[]', 'comparable worth legislation.[]', 'decreased productivity among male workers.[]', 'increased training among women.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(251, 'Laws across the United States have provided a way for economists to study the effects of education on wages because of differences from state-to-state in[]', 'antitrust laws.[]', 'minimum wage laws.[]', 'the legal age requirement for school drop-outs.[]', 'legalized gambling.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(252, 'Students who are required to finish more schooling have been found to[]', 'earn a higher wage.[]', 'be happier with their career choices.[]', 'suffer from unemployment volatility.[]', 'be more likely to feel the effects of minimum wage increases.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(253, 'Tiger Woods, a famous golfer, earns more than a university professor. The neoclassical theory of labor markets would suggest that[]', 'Although many university professors play golf, it is just a hobby and not a profession.[]', 'Tiger Woods has received more formal education than a university professor.[]', 'Tiger Woods and university professors each earn a wage equal to the value they contribute to the economy.[]', 'Sports are generally considered more important in an economy than education.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(254, 'Which of the following statements is NOT true?[]', 'The wage for difficult jobs exceeds that for easy jobs.[]', 'The wage for fun jobs exceeds that for dull jobs.[]', 'The wage for dangerous jobs exceeds that for safe jobs.[]', 'The wage for skilled jobs exceeds that for unskilled jobs.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(255, 'Receptionists generally have low paying jobs because[]', 'receptionist jobs are considered difficult.[]', 'receptionists are required to have a college degree.[]', 'receptionist jobs are perceived to be relatively easy.[]', 'many people perceive the job as having an element of personal satisfaction.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(256, 'A high-rise construction worker is typically paid a higher wage than a carpenter who builds residential housing primarily because[]', 'carpenters are more likely to work a standard day shift where high-rise construction workers generally work at night.[]', 'carpenter jobs are perceived as fun and easy.[]', 'high-rise construction jobs are potentially more dangerous than carpenter jobs.[]', 'high-rise construction jobs require years of training while building residential housing requires no special training.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(257, 'If the night-shift workers at a Ford assembly plant make more than the day-shift workers at the same plant, this is because of[]', 'an inefficient labor market in the car industry.[]', 'a compensating differential.[]', 'a discriminatory wage practice.[]', 'a negative externality in this labor market.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(258, 'Human capital[]', 'is a form of economic rent.[]', 'is a new term economists have devised for robotics technology.[]', 'claims that employers make hiring decisions solely on the basis of education credentials.[]', 'is knowledge and skill acquired through education and training.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(259, 'The wage difference between jobs that require education and those that don’t[]', 'is not likely to be related to productivity differences.[]', 'encourages workers to bear the cost of acquiring education.[]', 'is a barrier to obtaining an education.[]', 'does not affect the supply of workers in the different labor markets.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(260, 'Skill differences account for some of the differences in wages across occupations because[]', 'high-skilled workers are more pleasant to work with than low-skilled workers.[]', 'international trade has altered the relative demand for skilled and unskilled labor.[]', 'there is an inverse relationship between human capital and economic rent.[]', 'lower skilled workers are suffering from discrimination.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(261, 'Studies have documented that the earnings gap between low-skill workers and high-skill workers has[]', 'increased over the past two decades.[]', 'not changed as the wages of both groups have steadily increased.[]', 'remained relatively constant over the past two decades.[]', 'decreased over the past two decades because of lower college enrollments.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(262, 'Which of the following would NOT explain the “beauty premium?”[]', 'Beauty is an indirect measure of other types of ability.[]', 'Physical beauty is associated with a worker’s marginal productivity in every occupation.[]', 'Good looks are useful in any job in which workers present themselves to the public.[]', 'Beauty is a type of discrimination.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(263, 'The human capital view of education is that it[]', 'can reduce job discrimination.[]', 'enhances productivity.[]', 'will decrease job mobility.[]', 'is a signal of natural intelligence or ability.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(264, 'The signaling view of education is that it[]', 'alters work ethic.[]', 'signals natural ability.[]', 'enhances productivity.[]', 'always leads to high-wage jobs.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(265, 'When differences in average wages occur in a labor market, economists agree that these differences[]', 'occur solely because of differences in productivity between genders and races.[]', 'do not alone provide conclusive evidence of discrimination.[]', 'are exclusively an economic, rather than political, phenomenon.[]', 'provide conclusive evidence of broad patterns of discrimination on the basis of gender and race.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(266, 'When employers in competitive product markets choose to discriminate when hiring workers, they will[]', 'likely go out of business.[]', 'have a larger pool of potential employees from which to choose.[]', 'have an opportunity to drive out competitors and increase market share.[]', 'realize an increase in economic profit because of the low cost of labor.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(267, 'Factors that affect a worker’s wage but are difficult to measure include[]', 'ability, effort and chance.[]', 'gender and race.[]', 'education level, age and job characteristics.[]', 'years of experience and geographic location.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(268, 'Streetcar seating that was segregated by race was opposed by firms that ran the streetcars because[]', 'railroad companies were not required to segregate by race.[]', 'streetcar drivers could not remember who sat where.[]', 'white passengers complained because they were required to sit in the back of the cars.[]', 'segregated seating was less profitable than streetcar seating that didn’t have restrictions.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(269, 'A 1988 study of the professional basketball players’ market found that[]', 'sports with strong player associations do not experience wage discrimination.[]', 'consumer driven wage discrimination between black and white basketball players may exist.[]', 'the marginal product of basketball players could not be determined since it is a team sport.[]', 'wage discrimination in basketball may be eliminated with government regulations.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(270, 'Which of the following is a valid economic criticism of comparable worth?[]', 'There is no employment discrimination in the United States.[]', 'Comparable worth distorts labor market signals, thereby creating labor surpluses and shortages.[]', 'Comparable worth may attract males into traditionally female-dominated occupations.[]', 'Women are less likely than men to be heads of households.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(271, 'The idea behind signaling in education is that[]', 'education can turn an unproductive person into a productive person.[]', 'more productive people are more inclined to educate themselves.[]', 'many college graduates attended college in an attempt to land an “easier” job.[]', 'most college graduates wouldn’t be half as productive if it were not for the years they spend in the classroom.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(272, 'The superstar phenomenon occurs in markets[]', 'that can limit the supply of participants in the market so that competition is diminished.[]', 'that make it possible for the best producer to supply every customer at low cost.[]', 'where technology is not allowed to assist or improve the natural ability of the superstar.[]', 'where the ability and effort of market participants are relatively equal.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(273, 'Each of the following tend to create above-equilibrium wages as well as a shortage of jobs EXCEPT[]', 'unions.[]', 'efficiency wages.[]', 'education.[]', 'minimum wage laws.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(274, 'Economists are skeptical that discrimination is employer driven because[]', 'employers are profit maximizers.[]', 'there is a cost advantage for the non-discriminating firm.[]', 'if there is no difference in productivity, employers choose to hire the cheapest labor available.[]', 'All of the above are reasons.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(275, 'Factors which are likely to have influenced the declining gender wage gap include each of the following EXCEPT:[]', 'Women are gaining more continuous work experience.[]', 'Women are delaying marriage.[]', 'Women are working jobs that have more favorable working conditions.[]', 'Fertility rates have fallen.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(276, 'Wage differences that exist between well-educated workers and less-educated workers can be thought of as[]', 'unfair by most economists.[]', 'another form of discrimination in the labor market.[]', 'a compensating differential for the cost of becoming educated.[]', 'difficult to explain in a market economy.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(277, 'A natural experiment which allows economists to examine the effect of education on wages and productivity exists because of[]', 'minimum wage laws.[]', 'government-subsidized higher education.[]', 'anti-discrimination legislation.[]', 'differences in state laws for school attendance.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(278, 'A person’s earnings depends on[]', 'how well the economy is doing.[]', 'whether or not the economy is experiencing inflation.[]', 'the supply and demand for that person’s labor.[]', 'how much profit that person’s employer is able to make.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(279, 'Labor earnings make up what part of total income in the U.S. economy?[]', 'all of it[]', 'three-fourths[]', 'one-half[]', 'one-fourth[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(280, 'If income were equally distributed across all families,[]', 'all families would more likely be rich than poor.[]', 'the relative share of income would decline as the number of families are increased.[]', 'the relative share of income would increase as the number of families are increased.[]', '75 percent of the families would receive exactly 75 percent of the income.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(281, 'Based on data from 1998, what percent of all income in the United States did the top fifth of all families receive?[]', '4 percent[]', '32 percent[]', '47 percent[]', '78 percent[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(282, 'Evidence suggests that the women’s movement has[]', 'increased income inequality across households.[]', 'decreased income inequality across households.[]', 'had no effect on the distribution of income across households.[]', 'decreased the importance of traditional measures of income inequality.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(283, 'In the United States the poverty rate is a measure of the[]', 'number of people whose annual income is less than $18,000.[]', 'number of people whose annual household income is less than $39,000.[]', 'percentage of people whose income falls below an identified income standard.[]', 'percentage of government expenditures spent on programs to relieve poverty.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(284, 'Over the past few years, growth in average income has[]', 'eliminated poverty.[]', 'failed to decrease the poverty rate.[]', 'decreased the poverty rate.[]', 'increased the poverty rate in some years, and decreased it in other years.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(285, 'Measures of poverty that fail to account for the value of in-kind transfers[]', 'overstate the actual poverty rate.[]', 'understate the actual poverty rate.[]', 'have little effect on the validity of reported poverty rates.[]', 'are generally more reliable in accounting for annual variation in actual poverty rates.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(286, 'The life cycle effect characterizes a life-time income profile in which income[]', 'falls during the early years of market activity and peaks at retirement.[]', 'rises as a worker gains maturity and experience.[]', 'rises and falls in conjunction with the business cycle.[]', 'tends to follow a seasonal pattern.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(287, 'Saving and borrowing behavior is indicative of a family[]', 'that is most likely to be poor.[]', 'that has a difficult time balancing its standard of living.[]', 'that is most likely to be on the upper end of the income distribution.[]', 'adjusting its standard of living to reflect transitory changes in income.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(288, 'A family’s ability to buy goods and services depends largely on its[]', 'permanent income.[]', 'in-kind transfers.[]', 'lifetime income.[]', 'transitory income.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(289, 'Economic mobility refers to the[]', 'movement of people among income classes.[]', 'movement of resources from one industry to another.[]', 'ability of families to freely relocate to find good jobs.[]', 'government’s attempt to distribute monetary assistance to areas most in need.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(290, 'Whether or not policymakers should try to make our society more egalitarian is largely a matter of[]', 'egalitarian principles.[]', 'economic efficiency.[]', 'political philosophy.[]', 'enhanced opportunity.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(291, 'According to utilitarians, the ultimate objective of private and public actions is to[]', 'enhance the income of the rich.[]', 'provide for the betterment of the poor.[]', 'maximize the sum of individual utility.[]', 'ensure an egalitarian distribution of income.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(292, 'The utilitarian case for redistributing income is based on the assumption of[]', 'rising marginal utility.[]', 'collective consensus.[]', 'a notion of fairness engendered by equality.[]', 'diminishing marginal utility.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(293, 'When the government taxes income as part of a redistribution program[]', 'the poor pay higher taxes.[]', 'incentives to earn income are diminished.[]', 'the rich always benefit more than the poor.[]', 'incentives for the poor to work are enhanced.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(294, 'In the parable of the leaky bucket, a fundamental problem with government redistribution programs is identified. As long as the government only has “leaky buckets” at its disposal[]', 'equality of economic opportunity is an unattainable goal.[]', 'affirmative action programs are doomed to failure.[]', 'it should not try to reach complete equality in income.[]', 'full egalitarian policies will always dominate competing policy options.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(295, 'Liberalism is founded on a premise that behind a “veil of ignorance”[]', 'no one would be considered in an “original position.”[]', 'justice is a matter of political philosophy.[]', 'justice can never be agreed upon.[]', 'everyone would agree to “just” rules to reallocate income.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(296, 'The liberalism rule called the maximin criterion suggests that the focus of social policy would be to[]', 'elevate the well-being of those at the bottom of income distribution.[]', 'elevate the well-being of all workers.[]', 'ensure an egalitarian distribution of income.[]', 'expropriate the factors of production from the capitalist class.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(297, 'A libertarian is likely to argue that[]', 'society is responsible for ensuring an equal distribution of income.[]', 'outcomes always dominate processes.[]', 'government has no role in the economy.[]', 'only individual members of society can earn income.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(298, 'Minimum wage laws[]', 'increase the efficiency of labor markets.[]', 'force a market imbalance between the supply and demand for labor.[]', 'are typically associated with a rise in employment among the poor.[]', 'are most effective at alleviating poverty when labor demand is highly elastic.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(299, 'Evidence suggests that[]', 'the longer a family is on welfare, the harder it is to get off welfare.[]', 'legislation designed to limit the time a family can be on welfare will never be passed.[]', 'the best way to deter immigrants is to make legal aliens ineligible for many welfare benefits.[]', 'welfare dependency is embraced by over 80% of new welfare recipients.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(300, 'Proponents of welfare reform claim that programs for the poor which do not establish a time limit on recipient benefits harm children by[]', 'forcing mothers to work outside the home.[]', 'encouraging child abuse by absent fathers.[]', 'encouraging a psychological dependency on government programs.[]', 'all of the above.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(301, 'A negative income tax system would[]', 'eliminate tax progressivity.[]', 'make taxes more regressive.[]', 'sever the link between tax policy and income distribution.[]', 'collect from high-income households and give transfers to low-income households.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(302, 'Assume that the government proposes a negative income tax that calculates taxes owed by the formula, TAXES OWED = (1/3 / INCOME) – 10,000. A family that earns an income of $60,000 will[]', 'pay $10,000 in taxes.[]', 'receive a subsidy of $3,000.[]', 'receive an income subsidy of $10,000.[]', 'neither pay taxes nor receive an income subsidy.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(303, 'Three-fourths of total income in the U.S. economy comes from[]', 'rental income.[]', 'labor earnings.[]', 'returns to capital.[]', 'corporate profit.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(304, 'One way to describe the distribution of income in the economy is to[]', 'calculate the bell curve that exists in any economy.[]', 'use the International Income Distribution Standards that were established in 1992.[]', 'divide the population into two categories—the rich and the poor.[]', 'calculate the percentage of families that fall into each of seven income categories.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(305, 'U.S. income data from 1998 show that the bottom one-fifth of all families received[]', '4 percent of all income.[]', '10 percent of all income.[]', '22 percent of all income.[]', '36 percent of all income.[]', 1, 2, 'medium');
INSERT INTO `econ_medium` (`Qno`, `Question`, `Option1`, `Option2`, `Option3`, `Option4`, `Answer`, `marks`, `Complexity`) VALUES
(306, 'Over the past several decades, the women’s movement may be responsible for[]', 'less inequality in family incomes.[]', 'high-income men marrying low-income women.[]', 'rich households becoming poorer.[]', 'more inequality in family incomes.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(307, 'When the income distribution of the U.S. is compared to that of other countries, it shows that the U.S. has a[]', 'distribution that is one of the most equal income distributions.[]', 'distribution that is one of the most unequal income distributions.[]', 'distribution that is somewhere in the middle of the pack.[]', 'higher percentage of poor families, and a higher percentage of rich families than most countries.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(308, 'The poverty line is equal to the[]', 'average income of the bottom one-fifth of all income recipients.[]', 'average income of the bottom one-tenth of all income recipients.[]', 'cost of an adequate diet for a family multiplied by six.[]', 'cost of an adequate diet for a family multiplied by three.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(309, 'The annual adjustment to the poverty line reflects[]', 'family size.[]', 'price changes.[]', 'changes in what foods are included in an adequate diet.[]', 'the number of people currently on public assistance.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(310, 'The number of families living in poverty in the U.S. tends to be overstated by about[]', '2 percent.[]', '5 percent.[]', '10 percent.[]', '15 percent.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(311, 'In-kind transfers[]', 'can only be provided by the Federal government.[]', 'are goods and services given to the poor rather than cash.[]', 'increase the number of families below the poverty line since no money is given.[]', 'are taken into account when determining the degree of income inequality in the economy.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(312, 'Transitory income refers to[]', 'the regular pattern of income variation over a person’s life.[]', 'a person’s normal income.[]', 'the regular pattern of income variation that peaks around age 50.[]', 'temporary increases and decreases in income.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(313, 'Income and saving rates are highest for people who are[]', 'retired.[]', 'middle-aged.[]', 'young and single.[]', 'married with young children.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(314, 'The life-cycle theory would suggest that because people can borrow and save to smooth out changes in income, their standard of living depends more on[]', 'lifetime income rather than annual income.[]', 'annual income rather than lifetime income.[]', 'annual family income rather than annual personal income.[]', 'average monthly income rather than annual income.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(315, 'The new formula being considered by the U.S. Census Bureau to compute the income threshold for the poverty line would[]', 'not change the poverty line, but the formula would be easier to compute.[]', 'decrease the poverty line and decrease the number of families below the poverty line.[]', 'increase the poverty line and increase the number of families below the poverty line.[]', 'increase the poverty line, but the number of families considered poor would not change since the cost of living is continuously rising.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(316, 'A family’s ability to buy goods and services depends largely on its normal or average income which is its[]', 'transitory income.[]', 'in-kind transfers.[]', 'permanent income.[]', 'lifetime income.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(317, 'Studies have shown that if a father earns 20 percent above his generation’s average income, his son will most likely earn[]', 'relatively the same income as his father.[]', 'less than his father since the son has less incentive to work with a wealthy father.[]', '22 percent below his generation’s average income.[]', '8 percent above his generation’s average income.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(318, 'Evidence indicates that[]', 'most of the poor are poor for short periods of time.[]', 'education is unrelated to poverty.[]', 'most of the poor are elderly.[]', 'working does not reduce one’s chance of being poor.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(319, 'The political philosophy according to which the government should punish crimes and enforce voluntary agreements but not redistribute income is[]', 'liberalism.[]', 'utilitarianism.[]', 'communism.[]', 'libertarianism.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(320, 'Because of diminishing marginal utility,[]', 'the rich receive more satisfaction than the poor from the last dollar they spend since the rich have more to spend.[]', 'more of something is always preferred to less of something, especially money.[]', 'the poor are less efficient at spending money than the rich.[]', 'the poor receive more satisfaction than the rich from the last dollar they spend.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(321, 'Because of distorted incentives, when the government tries to maximize total utility in the economy by redistributing income, the policy will[]', 'always achieve a full egalitarian society in a market economy.[]', 'always fall short of a full egalitarian society.[]', 'can only be achieved with a progressive income tax system.[]', 'achieve a full egalitarian society only if sufficient funds are transferred from the rich to the poor.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(322, 'Rawl’s maximin criterion suggests that income transferred from the rich to the poor should aim to[]', 'promote an egalitarian distribution of income.[]', 'maximize the well-being of the worst off person in society.[]', 'maximize the well-being of each person in society.[]', 'reduce the disincentives to work and save that redistribution policy creates.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(323, 'Libertarians would condone government involvement in an economy to ensure[]', 'a distribution of income as equal as possible.[]', 'equal opportunity, but not an equal distribution of income.[]', 'the well-being of the least fortunate in society.[]', 'an objectively-determined just society.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(324, 'Government welfare programs are often criticized because[]', 'studies have shown that these programs encourage single-parent households.[]', 'the government spends more each year on welfare programs than it does on national defense.[]', 'most people on the welfare roles today are actually ineligible to receive the benefits.[]', 'they create incentives for people to become needy.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(325, 'Opponents of the 1996 law that limits the time a family can receive welfare benefits believe that[]', 'children will become innocent victims of this law.[]', 'any money saved by lowering welfare roles will be diverted to defense spending.[]', 'welfare is the best system the government has to distribute income to the really poor.[]', 'little evidence exists that staying on welfare for long periods of time is detrimental to a family.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(326, 'Assume that the government proposes a negative income tax that calculates taxes owed by the formula, TAXES OWED = (1/2 / INCOME) – 15,000. For a family earning $20,000 of income, how would this negative income tax affect them?[]', 'They will receive an income subsidy of $10,000.[]', 'They will receive an income subsidy of $5,000.[]', 'They will pay a tax of $5,000.[]', 'They will not be required to pay any tax.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(327, 'Almost everyone agrees that the more equally policymakers attempt to divide the “pie” the[]', 'more likely the middle class will be to “starve.”[]', 'larger the “pie” becomes.[]', 'smaller the “pie” becomes.[]', '“fatter” the rich become.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(328, 'The slope of the budget constraint is determined by the[]', 'level of income of the consumer.[]', 'relative price of commodities represented on the axes.[]', 'preferences of a consumer.[]', 'endowment of productive resources.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(329, 'Consumer preferences are typically represented by[]', 'cost curves.[]', 'supply curves.[]', 'indifference curves.[]', 'budget constraints.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(330, 'The slope of an indifference curve is[]', 'constant.[]', 'positive, since indifference curves slope upward.[]', 'equal to the marginal rate of substitution.[]', 'the same as the slope of the budget constraint at every point.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(331, 'The amount of a good an individual has []', 'is only affected by prices.[]', 'is only affected by income.[]', 'will not affect the marginal rate of substitution.[]', 'affects the rate at which she is willing to trade.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(332, 'As long as a consumer is on the same indifference curve[]', 'she is unable to decide which bundle of goods to choose.[]', 'she is indifferent among the points on that indifference curve.[]', 'her preferences will not affect the marginal rate of substitution.[]', 'she is indifferent to all points which lie on any other indifference curves.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(333, 'When indifference curves are bowed inward toward the origin,[]', 'it is unlikely that consumers will be willing to engage in trade.[]', 'people can only increase satisfaction by consuming more of all commodities.[]', 'people are less inclined to trade away goods that they have an abundance of.[]', 'the marginal rate of substitution decreases as a consumer moves down an indifference curve.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(334, 'The highest indifference curve that a consumer can reach is the one[]', 'farthest from the origin.[]', 'that intersects the budget constraint in at least two places.[]', 'that is tangent to the budget constraint.[]', 'all of the above.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(335, 'Which of the following is NOT a property of indifference curves?[]', 'Lower indifference curves are preferable to higher indifference curves.[]', 'Indifference curves are bowed inward toward the origin.[]', 'Indifference curves do not cross.[]', 'Indifference curves are downward sloping.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(336, 'When two goods are perfect substitutes they will have []', 'linear indifference curves.[]', 'indifference curves that cross.[]', 'indifference curves that are right angles.[]', 'indifference curves with a positive slope.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(337, 'When economists describe preferences, they sometimes use the concept of []', 'income.[]', 'utility.[]', 'prices.[]', 'markets.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(338, 'An optimizing consumer will select a consumption bundle in which the[]', 'utility exceeds price.[]', 'marginal rate of substitution is equal to income.[]', 'ratio of expenditure shares equals the marginal rate of substitution.[]', 'marginal rate of substitution is equal to the relative price.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(339, 'At the optimum[]', 'the budget constraint would have a slope of 1.[]', 'it is still possible for the consumer to increase his consumption of both goods.[]', 'the slope of the indifference curve is equal to the slope of the budget constraint.[]', 'the indifference curve would intersect the budget constraint at its center.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(340, 'When a budget constraint shifts out[]', 'the consumer is worse off.[]', 'the consumer can now reach a higher indifference curve.[]', 'it could only have been caused by an increase in income.[]', 'it could only have been caused by an increase in the price of one of the goods.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(341, 'Assume that a college student purchases Diet Coke and Snickers. The substitution effect associated with a decrease in the price of a Snickers will result in[]', 'only a decrease in the consumption of Diet Coke.[]', 'only an increase in the consumption of Snickers.[]', 'a decrease in the consumption of Snickers and an increase in the consumption of Diet Coke.[]', 'an increase in the consumption of Snickers and a decrease in the consumption of Diet Coke. []', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(342, 'Violations to the law of demand are assumed to occur[]', 'only when goods are Giffen goods.[]', 'commonly.[]', 'only when the substitution effect dominates the income effect.[]', 'All of the above are possible answers.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(343, 'If an in-kind transfer forces the recipient to consume more of the good than he would choose with a cash transfer of equal value, then the recipient[]', 'would prefer the in-kind transfer over a cash transfer of equal dollar value.[]', 'would prefer a cash transfer of equal dollar value.[]', 'is indifferent between a cash transfer and an in-kind transfer.[]', 'Not enough information about the consumer is given to answer this question. []', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(344, 'The theory of consumer choice provides a more complete understanding of demand by examining []', 'the tradeoffs people face in their role as consumers.[]', 'the role of suppliers and how they attempt to maximize profits.[]', 'individuals who are unaware of how to maximize their well-being.[]', 'individuals who make irrational consumption decisions.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(345, 'A budget constraint shows[]', 'consumption bundles that makes a consumer equally satisfied.[]', 'the prices a consumer must pay for two products he consumes.[]', 'the rate at which a consumer is willing to trade one good for another.[]', 'the various consumption bundles that a consumer can afford with a given income. []', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(346, 'A point outside a consumer’s budget constraint[]', 'cannot be reached given the consumer’s current income.[]', 'shows that the consumer is not spending all of her income.[]', 'would represent the consumer’s optimum. []', 'means that one of the two goods must be an inferior good.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(347, 'Which of the following leads to a parallel shift of the budget line?[]', 'a 10 percent increase in the price of both goods[]', 'a 20 percent reduction in the price of both goods[]', 'a 30 percent increase in income[]', 'a 10 percent increase in the price of one of the goods only[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(348, 'The relative price of two goods equals[]', 'the marginal rate of substitution.[]', 'the slope of an indifference curve.[]', 'the slope of the budget constraint.[]', 'consumer optimum.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(349, 'For a consumer, any point on the same indifference curve yields[]', 'different levels of satisfaction.[]', 'constraints faced by the consumer.[]', 'the same level of satisfaction.[]', 'an income level sufficient to make an individual happy.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(350, 'A consumer who reduces his consumption of one good will remain on the same indifference curve only if he[]', 'doesn’t change his consumption of another good.[]', 'reduces his consumption of another good.[]', 'increases his consumption of another good.[]', 'He will not be able to stay on the same indifference curve if he reduces his consumption of one good.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(351, 'The marginal rate of substitution[]', 'measures the rate at which a consumer is willing to trade one good for another.[]', 'is always constant.[]', 'is the slope of a consumer’s budget constraint.[]', 'identifies the point where the budget constraint and the indifference curve are tangent.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(352, 'Because consumers prefer more consumption to less, they[]', 'prefer indifference curves with positive slopes.[]', 'prefer lower indifference curves to higher indifference curves.[]', 'prefer higher indifference curves to lower indifference curves.[]', 'are generally unable to place all consumption bundles on an indifference curve.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(353, 'Indifference curves are bowed inward because people are []', 'unwilling to substitute one good for another.[]', 'more willing to give up goods that they have in abundance.[]', 'less willing to give up goods that they have in abundance.[]', 'generally willing to consume more of one good over another.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(354, 'Two goods that are perfect complements will have indifference curves that are[]', 'right angles.[]', 'intersecting.[]', 'straight lines.[]', 'upward sloping.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(355, 'When a consumer reaches the highest indifference curve possible, she has maximized her[]', 'income.[]', 'utility.[]', 'preferences.[]', 'substitution effect.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(356, 'The consumer’s optimum occurs where the[]', 'highest attainable indifference curve is just tangent to the budget line.[]', 'consumer maximizes his satisfaction and has some income left over.[]', 'consumer buys equal amounts of both goods.[]', 'consumer will be on the indifference curve lying closest to the origin.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(357, 'An inferior good is any good that[]', 'is of lesser quality than a normal good.[]', 'an increase in income increases consumption of the good.[]', 'an increase in income decreases consumption of the good.[]', 'a rational consumer would not generally choose to buy.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(358, 'Economic theory suggests that demand curves can sometimes slope upward []', 'if a good is a strongly inferior good with a dominant income effect.[]', 'when the supply curve for the good is downward sloping.[]', 'when consumers no longer prefer more to less.[]', 'if a good is a normal good with a dominant income effect.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(359, 'A Giffen good has[]', 'an upward-sloping demand curve.[]', 'a downward-sloping demand curve.[]', 'a horizontal demand curve.[]', 'a vertical demand curve.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(360, 'The theory of consumer choice can be used to []', 'understand producers’ response to demand.[]', 'derive a demand curve.[]', 'clarify why consumers generally prefer less of a good to more.[]', 'show how individuals’ activities determine the preferences of a society.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(361, 'If an individual’s labor supply curve is backward bending this would suggest that he will[]', 'work more as wage rates rise.[]', 'work less as wage rates rise.[]', 'work the same no matter what the wage rate.[]', 'demand more leisure as wage rates fall.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(362, 'Rational consumers who are saving for retirement may choose to save less when interest rates rise if []', 'they are likely to inherit a large sum of money.[]', 'they realize that they will need much less money after retirement to maintain the same standard of living. []', 'the substitution effect dominates the income effect.[]', 'the income effect dominates the substitution effect.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(363, 'Macroeconomics is the study of[]', 'market regulation.[]', 'money and financial markets.[]', 'economy-wide phenomena.[]', 'how households and firms make decisions and how they interact.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(364, 'For the economy as a whole[]', 'expenditure exceeds income because of taxes.[]', 'income must equal expenditure.[]', 'income exceeds expenditure because of saving.[]', 'expenditure exceeds income because of the government budget deficit.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(365, 'A circular-flow diagram is used to describe []', 'how banks create money.[]', 'how weather patterns affect the economy.[]', 'the most efficient organization of the work process.[]', 'the flow of income and expenditures in an economy.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(366, 'Gross Domestic Product is defined as the market value of[]', 'all final goods and services produced by a country’s citizens in a given period of time.[]', 'every good and service produced within a country in a given period of time.[]', 'all final goods and services produced within a country in a given period of time.[]', 'all goods and services produced by a country’s citizens in a given period of time.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(367, 'Goods and services produced and sold illegally are[]', 'excluded from GDP.[]', 'included in GDP.[]', 'included in GDP only if income from the sales is reported on income tax returns.[]', 'included in GDP to the extent that they can be measured.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(368, 'Latrell decides to hire Cynthia to mow his lawn, instead of mowing it himself, as he is accustomed to doing. As a result of this transaction, GDP[]', 'will decrease.[]', 'will increase.[]', 'will be unaffected because the same service would be performed in either case.[]', 'could increase or decrease, depending on whether Cynthia mows Latrell’s lawn as well as Latrell could mow it himself.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(369, 'The value of intermediate goods that are sold is[]', 'not added to GDP.[]', 'added to GDP if they were produced in a previous year.[]', 'added to GDP if they were produced and sold in the current year.[]', 'added to GDP unless they are sold at a loss.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(370, 'An American company owns a fast-food store in Lima, Peru. The value of the goods and services produced in the store are included[]', 'in both Peruvian GDP and U.S. GDP.[]', 'in Peruvian GDP, but not U.S. GDP.[]', 'in U.S. GDP, but not Peruvian GDP.[]', 'partly in Peruvian GDP and partly in U.S. GDP.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(371, 'National income is defined as []', 'all income produced within a country.[]', 'the income received by the national government.[]', 'the total income earned by a nation’s residents from the production of goods and services within the borders of the country.[]', 'the total income earned by a nation’s residents in the production of goods and services.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(372, 'The government reports that GDP “increased by 2 percent in the last quarter.”[]', 'GDP increased by 10 percent for the year.[]', 'GDP increased at an annual rate of 2 percent during the last quarter.[]', 'GDP increased at an annual rate of 8 percent during the last quarter.[]', 'GDP increased at an annual rate of .5 percent during the last quarter.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(373, 'The four components of GDP are consumption,[]', 'money supply, government purchases, and exports.[]', 'investment, transfer payments, and imports.[]', 'investment, government purchases, and net exports.[]', 'investment, government purchases, and foreign exchange.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(374, 'In macroeconomics, investment is spending on[]', 'real estate and financial assets.[]', 'capital equipment, inventories, and structures, including new housing.[]', 'stocks, bonds, and other financial assets.[]', 'capital equipment, inventories, and structures, excluding household purchases of new housing.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(375, 'Government purchases include spending on goods and services by []', 'local, state and federal governments.[]', 'the federal government only.[]', 'local and state governments, but not the federal government.[]', 'state and federal governments only.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(376, 'If exports are smaller than imports, net exports[]', 'are positive.[]', 'are negative.[]', 'will increase GDP.[]', 'are larger than imports.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(377, 'Transfer payments are[]', 'included in GDP because they represent income to individuals.[]', 'not included in GDP unless they represent unemployment compensation.[]', 'included in GDP because the income will be spent for consumption.[]', 'not included in GDP because they do not represent payments for currently produced goods or services.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(378, 'In 1998, U.S. GDP was about[]', '$85 trillion.[]', '$8.5 trillion.[]', '$850 billion.[]', '$85 billion.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(379, 'If total spending rises from one year to the next, then[]', 'net exports must be falling.[]', 'prices at which goods and services are sold must be higher.[]', 'the economy must be producing a larger output of goods and services.[]', 'either the economy must be producing a larger output of goods and services, or the prices at which goods and services are sold must be higher, or both.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(380, 'The best measure of a country’s production of goods and services is[]', 'real GDP.[]', 'real NNP.[]', 'nominal GDP.[]', 'nominal GNP.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(381, 'Real GDP is the production of goods and services valued at[]', 'current year prices.[]', 'future year prices.[]', 'constant prices.[]', 'the ratio of current year prices to constant year prices.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(382, 'The GDP deflator is the ratio of[]', 'nominal GDP to real GDP.[]', 'real GDP to nominal GDP.[]', 'nominal GDP to real GDP multiplied by 100.[]', 'real GDP to nominal GDP multiplied by 100.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(383, 'If the GDP deflator is 150 and nominal GDP is $9,000 billion, then real GDP is[]', '$135 billion.[]', '$1,350 billion.[]', '$600 billion.[]', '$6,000 billion.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(384, 'If the GDP deflator was 100 in the base year of 2000, and was 105 in 2002, we can say that[]', 'the price level increased by 5 percent from 2000 to 2002.[]', 'the price level increased by 105 percent from 2000 to 2002.[]', 'the price level increased by 205 percent from 2000 to 2002.[]', 'we cannot judge price increases from changes in the GDP deflator.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(385, 'GDP is used as the basic measure of a society’s economic well-being. A better measure of the economic well-being of individuals in society is[]', 'the consumption component of GDP.[]', 'GDP per person.[]', 'government expenditures per person.[]', 'the level of business investment.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(386, 'GDP per person is not a perfect measure of the well-being of individuals in society because it excludes[]', 'the role of government.[]', 'the value of investment in real capital.[]', 'the value of money.[]', 'things like leisure time, the value of goods and services produced at home, and environmental quality.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(387, 'International studies of the relationship between GDP per person and quality of life measures, such as life expectancy and literacy rates show that larger GDP per person is associated with[]', 'longer life expectancy and higher levels of illiteracy.[]', 'shorter life expectancy and higher levels of illiteracy.[]', 'longer life expectancy and lower levels of illiteracy.[]', 'shorter life expectancy and lower levels of illiteracy.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(388, 'Microeconomics is the study of[]', 'the government and its role in the economy.[]', 'how households and firms make decisions, and how they interact in markets.[]', 'economy-wide topics such as inflation, unemployment and economic growth.[]', 'economics as if you were looking at the economy with a telescope to get the big picture.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(389, 'GDP can measures both an economy’s total income and total expenditure because they are[]', 'always equal because rules in accounting always make things equal.[]', 'equal only when all goods and services produced are sold.[]', 'equal because only households purchase goods and services.[]', 'always equal since every transaction has both a buyer and a seller.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(390, 'Which of the following represents GDP?[]', 'C + I + G[]', 'G + I + NX[]', 'I + C + NX[]', 'C + I + G + NX[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(391, 'Which of the following would be counted in the calculation of GDP?[]', 'the sale of a rare coin to a coin collector[]', 'homes that are rebuilt after being completely destroyed by a hurricane[]', 'the sale of a 1966 Ford Fairmont.[]', 'the sale of cocaine in the black market.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(392, 'Aaron and Adam, who are both full-time students, have each been doing work on their own cars. Then Adam decides to hire Aaron to do his oil changes, and in turn, Aaron hires Adam to keep his car clean. As a result of this change, GDP[]', 'rises.[]', 'falls.[]', 'is unaffected because the same work is being done as before.[]', 'is unaffected because Adam and Aaron are full-time students.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(393, 'The largest component of GDP is[]', 'net exports.[]', 'consumption.[]', 'government purchases.[]', 'investment.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(394, 'If the value of intermediate goods were used to calculate GDP instead of final goods, then GDP would be[]', 'over-estimated, because of double counting.[]', 'under-estimated because of all the goods and services missed in the calculations.[]', 'too difficult to measure because of all the goods and services produced in the economy each year.[]', 'the same, since it doesn’t matter whether intermediate goods or final goods are used in the calculations.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(395, 'Jim buys a new Mustang in August 1999 and then sells it to John in June 2001. As a result,[]', 'the value of the car will be included in 2001 GDP only, since that was the year of the last sale.[]', '1999 GDP will include the value of the car, and 2001 GDP will include the value of the car minus depreciation.[]', '1999 GDP will include the value of the car, but 2001 GDP will not.[]', 'both 1999 GDP and 2001 GDP will include the value of the car since it was sold in both years.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(396, 'Which two of the following are considered measures of income for an economy?[]', 'gross national product and net national product[]', 'net national profits and personal income[]', 'gross national product and net national investment[]', 'disposable personal income and personal profits[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(397, 'Personal income is defined as[]', 'after-tax proprietors’ income.[]', 'the total income earned by a nation’s permanent residents.[]', 'the income that households and non-corporate businesses receive.[]', 'the total income earned by a nation’s residents minus depreciation.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(398, 'Retained earnings are the part of income that[]', 'households retain after paying taxes.[]', 'business retain after paying taxes.[]', 'corporations pay to their owners in the form of dividends.[]', 'corporations do not pay to their owners in the form of dividends.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(399, 'If the government reports that “GDP increased at an annual rate of 4.0 percent for the fourth quarter of 2000,” then GDP increased by []', '1.0 percent during 2000.[]', '16.0 percent during 2000.[]', '4.0 percent during the fourth quarter of 2000.[]', '1.0 percent during the fourth quarter of 2000.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(400, 'If you buy a carton of chocolate chip cookie dough ice cream in your favorite grocery store[]', 'both GDP and consumption spending will be higher.[]', 'GDP will be higher, but consumption spending will be unchanged.[]', 'GDP will be unchanged, but consumption spending will be higher.[]', 'since your spending on the ice cream became the store’s income, GDP would not change.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(401, 'Net exports will be positive when[]', 'imports are larger than exports.[]', 'exports are larger than imports.[]', 'imports are equal to exports.[]', 'GDP increases.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(402, 'Transfer payments are []', 'paychecks which are automatically deposited in bank accounts.[]', 'on-line bill payment services offered by many large banks.[]', 'moving expenses when a worker is transferred by an employer to a new location.[]', 'government spending that does not reflect payment for currently produced goods or services.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(403, 'If Hallmark builds a plant in Mexico, the production from that plant would be []', 'included in U.S. GNP but not GDP.[]', 'included in U.S. GDP but not GNP.[]', 'included in both U.S. GDP and GNP.[]', 'not included in either U.S. GDP or GNP but only in Mexico’s production.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(404, 'If a construction company in Japan purchases a U.S. built bulldozer from Caterpillar, U.S. GDP[]', 'is the same but U.S. GNP increases.[]', 'increases since exports are included in GDP.[]', 'is unaffected since exports are not included in GDP.[]', 'decreases since the bulldozer could have been purchased by a U.S. company.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(405, 'In 1998, U.S. GDP was[]', '$850 billion.[]', '$1,367 billion.[]', '$5,808 billion.[]', '$8,511 billion.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(406, 'Real GDP []', 'evaluates current production at current prices.[]', 'evaluates current production at prices in some base year.[]', 'is not a valid measure of the economy’s performance.[]', 'is a measure of the value of goods only, but not services.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(407, 'GDP is a good but not perfect measure of economic well-being because it leaves out each of the following EXCEPT[]', 'leisure.[]', 'volunteer work.[]', 'medical services.[]', 'the quality of the environment.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(408, 'If nominal GDP is $10 trillion and the GDP deflator is 125, real GDP is[]', '$6 trillion.[]', '$8 trillion.[]', '$10 trillion.[]', '$12.5 trillion.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(409, 'If we want to know the amount of expenditures for an average individual in a country, we should look at[]', 'real GDP.[]', 'nominal GDP.[]', 'GDP per person.[]', 'current GDP.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(410, 'International GDP data show that[]', 'a nation’s GDP is closely associated with its citizens’ standard of living.[]', 'there is no relationship between GDP and the economic well-being of citizens.[]', 'poor nations actually might enjoy a higher standard of living than do rich nations.[]', 'there are few real differences in living standards around the world, in spite of the large differences in GDP among nations.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(411, 'It is especially difficult to measure GDP in Russia because[]', 'no consistent national income accounting standards exist.[]', 'the statisticians believe that producers are exaggerating the size of output.[]', 'a large part of the economy is underground and hidden from the statisticians.[]', 'only government officials are allowed access to statistics on the economy.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(412, 'When the consumer price index rises, a typical family[]', 'can spend fewer dollars to maintain the same standard of living.[]', 'finds that its standard of living is not affected.[]', 'has to spend more dollars to maintain the same standard of living.[]', 'None of the above answers is necessarily correct.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(413, 'The inflation rate is defined as the[]', 'cost of inflation. []', 'cost of borrowing. []', 'percentage change in real GDP from the previous period.[]', 'percentage change in the price level from the previous period.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(414, 'The CPI is a measure of the overall cost of []', 'producer inputs.[]', 'personal imports.[]', 'goods and services bought by a typical consumer.[]', 'goods and services produced in the economy. []', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(415, 'The CPI is computed using all goods and services[]', 'produced in the economy. []', 'used to produce other goods. []', 'that typical producers buy.[]', 'that typical consumers buy. []', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(416, 'In computing the CPI, the base year is the []', 'year against which this years price index is compared to find the inflation rate during the year. []', 'benchmark against which other years are compared. []', 'current year.[]', 'year with the lowest prices.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(417, 'For any given year, the CPI is the price of the basket of goods and services in the[]', 'given year divided by the price of the basket in the base year, then multiplied by 100.[]', 'base year divided by the price of the basket in the base year, then divided by 100.[]', 'base year divided by the price of the basket in the given year, then divided by 100.[]', 'base year divided by the price of the basket in the given year, then multiplied by 100. []', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(418, 'Categories of U.S. consumer spending used in the CPI, ranked from largest to smallest are:[]', 'food and beverages, housing, and medical care.[]', 'food and beverages, medical care, and housing.[]', 'housing, food and beverages, and medical care.[]', 'housing, medical care, and food and beverages.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(419, 'Substitution causes the increase in the cost of living from one year to the next to be[]', 'neither overstated or understated by the CPI because the CPI is based on the price of all goods.[]', 'overstated by the CPI because the basket of goods used to compute the CPI changes from year to year and so does not take into account the fact that as prices rise people purchase more of the goods they like less. []', 'understated by the CPI because the CPI changes from year to year and so does not take into account the fact that people substitute higher quality goods for lower quality ones as income increases. []', 'overstated by the CPI because the CPI is based on a fixed basket of goods that does not reflect increases in the purchases of goods that become relatively cheap.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(420, 'Unmeasured quality change is a problem in the CPI because[]', 'if the quality of a good deteriorates, the purchasing power of a dollar increases even if the price of the good remains the same. []', 'the Bureau of Labor Statistics does not attempt to account for any quality changes that affect the standard of living. []', 'if the quality of a good improves, the purchasing power of a dollar increases even if the price of the good remains the same.[]', 'Both a and b are correct.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(421, 'Which of the following statements best represents economists’ beliefs about the bias in the CPI as a measure of the cost of living? []', 'Economists agree on the severity of the CPI bias, but there is still debate on what to do about it.[]', 'Economists debate both the severity of the CPI bias and what to do about it.[]', 'Economists agree that the bias in the CPI is a very serious problem. []', 'Economists agree that the bias in the CPI is not a serious problem. []', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(422, 'Most, but not all, soccer balls used in the United States are imported from other nations. If the price of soccer balls increases, the GDP deflator will[]', 'increase, but the consumer price index will not increase.[]', 'increase less than will the consumer price index.[]', 'increase more than will the consumer price index. []', 'not increase, but the consumer price index will increase. []', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(423, 'An Egyptian company produces sweaters in the United States and exports all of them to Lithuania. Other things the same, if the price of these sweaters increases, the GDP deflator[]', 'increases and the CPI is unchanged. []', 'and the CPI are unchanged.[]', 'and the CPI both increase.[]', 'is unchanged and the CPI increases.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(424, 'The basket of goods in the consumer price index changes[]', 'occasionally, while the basket of goods in the GDP deflator changes each time it is computed.[]', 'each time it is computed, while the basket of goods in the GDP deflator changes occasionally.[]', 'occasionally, as does the basket of goods in the GDP deflator.[]', 'each time it is computed, as does the basket of goods in the GDP deflator.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(425, 'What is the purpose of measuring the overall level of prices in the economy? []', 'to allow consumers to know what kinds of prices to expect in the future[]', 'to allow the measurement of GDP []', 'to allow comparison between dollar figures from different points in time[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(426, 'Babe Ruth’s 1931 salary was $80,000. The price index for 1931 is 15.2 and the price index for 1999 is 166. Ruth’s 1931 salary was equivalent to a 1999 salary of about[]', '$8,700.[]', '$87,000. []', '$870,000. []', '$8,700,000.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(427, 'Craig is offered a $120,000 per year job in Los Angeles, and a $90,000 per year job in Akron. The CPI for Los Angeles is 160 and the CPI for Akron is 120. What is the Los Angeles job’s purchasing power in “Akron dollars”?[]', '$160,000[]', '$120,000[]', '$90,000[]', '$65,000[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(428, 'A COLA automatically raises the wage rate when[]', 'real GDP increases. []', 'the labor force increases.[]', 'taxes increase.[]', 'the consumer price index increases. []', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(429, 'The nominal interest rate is[]', 'the interest rate paid or charged by a bank. []', 'the interest rate as usually reported without a correction for the effects of inflation. []', 'both a and b above.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(430, 'Which of the following is the most accurate statement about the relationship between the nominal interest rate and the real interest rate? []', 'The real interest rate is the nominal interest rate minus the rate of inflation.[]', 'The real interest rate is the nominal interest rate divided by the price level.[]', 'The real interest rate is the nominal interest rate times the price level.[]', 'The real interest rate is the nominal interest rate times the expected price level divided by the current price level.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(431, 'If the nominal interest rate is 8% and rate of inflation is 2%, the real interest rate is[]', '16%. []', '10%. []', '6%. []', '4%.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(432, 'The nominal interest rate tells you[]', 'how fast the purchasing power of your bank account rises over time.[]', 'how fast the number of dollars in your bank account rises over time.[]', 'the number of dollars in your bank account.[]', 'the purchasing power of your bank account.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(433, 'The real interest rate tells you[]', 'the number of dollars in your bank account.[]', 'the purchasing power of your bank account.[]', 'how fast the number of dollars in your bank account rises over time.[]', 'how fast the purchasing power of your bank account rises over time.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(434, 'Which of the following is the most accurate statement about nominal and real interest rates?[]', 'Nominal and real interest rates often do not move together.[]', 'Nominal and real interest rates always move together.[]', 'Nominal and real interest rates never move together.[]', 'Nominal and real interest rates are identical.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(435, 'Samantha deposits $1,000 in a saving account that pays an annual interest rate of 4%. Over the course of a year the inflation rate is 1%. At the end of the year Samantha has []', '$40 more in her account, and her purchasing power has increased $30.[]', '$30 more in her account and her purchasing power has increased $50.[]', '$50 more in her account, and her purchasing power has increased $30.[]', '$40 more in her account, and her purchasing power has increased $40.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(436, 'In the late 1970s, nominal interest rates were high and inflation rates were very high. As a result, real interest rates were[]', 'very high.[]', 'moderately high.[]', 'low, but never negative.[]', 'low, and in some years they were negative.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(437, 'Suppose the CPI in 1990 is 125. The CPI in 1999 is 155. What is the rate of inflation over the period? []', '24 percent[]', '25 percent[]', '30 percent[]', '52 percent[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(438, 'Which of the following has the greatest weight in the CPI?[]', 'food and beverages[]', 'housing[]', 'medical care[]', 'All of the above have equal weights in the CPI.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(439, 'The consumer price index is based on []', '100,000s of prices.[]', '10,000s of prices.[]', '1,000s of prices.[]', '100s of prices.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(440, 'Consider the following two sentences. The producer price index measures the cost of a basket of goods and services purchased by firms. Changes in the producer price index are thought to be useful in predicting consumer prices.[]', 'Both sentences are true.[]', 'Only the first sentence is true.[]', 'Only the second sentence is true.[]', 'Neither sentence is true.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(441, 'Which of the following is true considering substitution bias?[]', 'When prices change from one year to the next, they do not all change proportionately.[]', 'Substitution bias tends to make the CPI overstate the cost of living from one year to the next.[]', 'When the price of a good rises, its weight in the consumer price index will be higher than its weight in the basket of goods people actually buy.[]', 'All of the above are true.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(442, 'Consider the following two sentences. The creation of new goods makes each dollar more valuable. Yet because the CPI is based on a fixed basket of goods and services, it does not reflect this decrease in the cost of living.[]', 'Both sentences are true.[]', 'Only the first sentence is true.[]', 'Only the second sentence is true.[]', 'Neither sentence is true.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(443, 'Which of the following is correct?[]', 'The CPI makes no adjustment for quality changes.[]', 'Research by the Bureau of Labor Statistics shows that over the last 18 years the elderly have experienced more rapid increases in the cost-of-living than the general population.[]', 'Although there are problems measuring the cost-of-living accurately, there is no reason to believe that on net the CPI either overstates or understates the true inflation rate.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(444, 'If the price of apples increases more than the price of other goods, the weight of the apples in the CPI[]', 'increases.[]', 'decreases.[]', 'stays the same, but should increase to accurately reflect the change in the cost-of-living.[]', 'stays the same, but should decrease to accurately reflect the change in the cost-of-living. []', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(445, 'Suppose that the price of French wine imported to the US increases, other things the same this[]', 'increases both the CPI and the GDP in the United States.[]', 'increases the CPI but does not change the GDP deflator in the U.S.[]', 'increases the GDP deflator, but does not change the CPI in the U.S.[]', 'changes neither the CPI nor the GDP deflator in the U.S.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(446, 'If the price of oil decreases, the CPI[]', 'decreases more than the GDP deflator decreases.[]', 'decreases less than the GDP deflator decreases.[]', 'decreases, but the GDP deflator does not change.[]', 'does not change, but the GDP deflator decreases.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(447, 'Which of the following is correct?[]', 'Both the CPI and GDP deflator use fixed weights.[]', 'Neither the CPI nor GDP deflator use fixed weights.[]', 'The CPI, but not the GDP deflator uses fixed weights.[]', 'The GDP deflator, but not the CPI uses fixed weights.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(448, 'The inflation rate computed from the CPI is[]', 'always somewhat greater than that computed from the GDP deflator.[]', 'always somewhat less than that computed from the GDP deflator.[]', 'sometimes greater and sometimes less, but generally moves in the opposite direction as the rate computed from the GDP deflator.[]', 'sometimes greater and sometimes less, but generally moves with the rate computed from the GDP deflator.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(449, 'In the late 1970s []', 'both the GDP deflator and CPI showed high rates of inflation; in the 1990s both showed low inflation rates.[]', 'both the GDP deflator and CPI showed low rates of inflation; in the 1990s both showed high inflation rates.[]', 'and the 1990s both the GDP deflator and CPI showed high rates of inflation.[]', 'and the 1990s both the GDP deflator and CPI showed low rates of inflation.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(450, 'In 1949 Sycamore, Illinois built a hospital for about $500,000. In 1987 the county restored the courthouse for about $2.4 million. A price index for nonresidential construction was 14 in 1949, 92 in 1987, and 114.5 in 2000. According to these numbers the hospital cost about[]', '$3.6 million in 2000 dollars, which is less than the cost of the courthouse restoration in 2000 dollars.[]', '$3.6 million in 2000 dollars, which is more than the cost of the courthouse restoration in 2000 dollars.[]', '$4.1 million in 2000 dollars, which is less than the cost of the courthouse restoration in 2000 dollars.[]', '$4.1 million in 2000 dollars, which is more than the cost of the courthouse restoration in 2000 dollars.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(451, 'Your grandparents tell you that in 1960 they paid $0.35 for admission to a movie. The price index in 1960 was 30. The price index in today is 171. What is the price your grandparents paid in today’s dollars? []', '$1.05[]', '$1.99[]', '$3.01[]', '$5.98[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(452, 'In 1970 Professor Fellswoop made $12,000, in 1980 he earned $24,000, in 1990 he earned $36,000. If the CPI was 40 in 1970, 60 in 1980, 100 in 1990 in terms of 1999 dollars, Professor Fellswoop’s salary was highest in []', '1970, and lowest in 1980.[]', '1990, and lowest in 1980.[]', '1980, and lowest in 1970.[]', '1990, and lowest in 1970.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(453, 'Indexation refers to []', 'a process of adjusting the nominal interest rate so that it is equal to the real interest rate.[]', 'using a law or contract to automatically correct a dollar amount for the effects of inflation.[]', 'using a price index to deflate dollar values.[]', 'an adjustment made by the Bureau of Labor Statistics to the CPI so that the index is in line with the GDP deflator.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(454, 'Mavis Corporation has an agreement with its workers to completely index the wage of their employees to inflation in the CPI. Mavis currently pays its production line workers $7.50 an hour and is scheduled to index their wages today. If the CPI is currently about 130 and was 120 a year ago Mavis should increase the hourly wages of its workers by about[]', '7.5 cents []', '10 cents[]', '58 cents[]', '62.5 cents[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(455, 'Suppose that the real interest rate is 3% and the inflation rate is 1%.[]', 'The dollar value of savings increases at 3%, and the value of savings in goods increases at 1%.[]', 'The dollar value of savings increases at 1%, and the value of savings in goods increases at 2%.[]', 'The dollar value of savings increases at 2%, and the value of savings in goods increases at 3%.[]', 'The dollar value of savings increases at 4%, and the value of savings in goods increases at 3%.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(456, 'Sluggo puts money in the bank and earns a 5% nominal interest rate, if the inflation rate is 3%, in one year Sluggo will have[]', '3% more money that will purchase 2% more goods.[]', '3% more money that will purchase 8% more goods.[]', '5% more money that will purchase 2% more goods.[]', '5% more money that will purchase 8% more goods.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(457, 'In Japan in 2000 nominal interest rates were 1.5% and the inflation rate was –.5%. The real interest rate was[]', '–2%.[]', '–1%.[]', '1%.[]', '2%.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(458, 'A nation’s standard of living is measured by its[]', 'real GDP.[]', 'real GDP per person.[]', 'nominal GDP.[]', 'nominal GDP per person.[]', 2, 3, 'medium');
INSERT INTO `econ_medium` (`Qno`, `Question`, `Option1`, `Option2`, `Option3`, `Option4`, `Answer`, `marks`, `Complexity`) VALUES
(459, 'Over the past century in the United States, average income as measured by real GDP per person has grown about[]', '4 percent per year, which implies a doubling about every 20 years.[]', '3 percent per year, which implies a doubling about every 25 years.[]', '2 percent per year, which implies a doubling about every 35 years.[]', '1 percent per year, which implies a doubling about every 65 years.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(460, 'In the length of one generation, which of the following countries has gone from being among the poorest countries in the world to being among the richest?[]', 'Chad[]', 'Ethiopia[]', 'Ghana[]', 'Singapore[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(461, 'In comparison to other countries, Japan had a high growth rate over the last 100 years. Japan’s average annual growth rate of real GDP per person was a bit less than []', '0.5 percent.[]', '1.0 percent.[]', '2.0 percent[]', '3.0 percent.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(462, 'Compounding refers to the[]', 'geometric smoothing of productivity data.[]', 'accumulation of a growth rate over a period of time.[]', 'increase in a growth rate over a period of time.[]', 'adjustment made to GDP meant to take out the effects of inflation.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(463, 'When Ben Franklin died he left $5,000 to be invested for a period of 200 years to benefit medical students and scientific research. According to the “rule of 70,” how often would this money have doubled if it grew 7 percent per year every year?[]', 'about every 10 years[]', 'about every 7 years[]', 'about every 5 years[]', 'about every 3.5 years[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(464, 'According to the rule of 70, if some variable grows at a rate of g percent per year, then that variable doubles in approximately[]', '70/g years.[]', '70g years.[]', '70/2g years.[]', '2g/70 years.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(465, 'Both Elmo and Anna work eight hours a day. Elmo can produce four baskets of goods per hour while Anna can produce three baskets of the same goods per hour. It follows that Elmo’s[]', 'productivity is greater than Anna’s.[]', 'output is greater than Anna’s.[]', 'standard of living is higher than Anna’s.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(466, 'Which of the following would be considered physical capital?[]', 'paper used to make cardboard for boxes of chocolate[]', 'the skills and knowledge of a film director[]', 'boats owned by a shrimp company[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(467, 'Which of the following is human capital?[]', 'a company’s cafeteria[]', 'employees’ knowledge of the production process[]', 'the exercise equipment in a company’s gym[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(468, 'In a market economy, scarcity of resources is reflected in[]', 'supply only.[]', 'demand only.[]', 'prices.[]', 'the quantity traded.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(469, 'Your company discovers a better way to produce DVDs, but how you do this is not apparent from the DVDs themselves. Your knowledge of how to more efficiently produce DVDs is[]', 'common technological knowledge.[]', 'common, but not technological knowledge.[]', 'proprietary technological knowledge.[]', 'proprietary, but not technological knowledge.[]', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(470, 'If there are constant returns to scale, the production function can be written as []', 'xY = 2xAF(L, K, H, N).[]', 'Y/L = A F(xL, xK, xH, xN).[]', 'L = AF(Y, K, H, N).[]', 'Y/L = A F( 1, K/L, H/L, N/L).[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(471, 'Which of the following would increase productivity? []', 'an increase in the amount of equipment per-worker[]', 'an increase in the knowledge and skills of workers[]', 'the discovery of new raw materials[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(472, 'Across countries, investment and growth rates are[]', 'unrelated.[]', 'negatively related.[]', 'negatively related for rich countries, but positively related for poor countries.[]', 'positively related.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(473, 'If there are diminishing returns to capital, []', 'capital produces fewer goods as it ages.[]', 'increases in the capital stock eventually decrease output.[]', 'the smaller the capital stock, the less an increase in the capital stock increases output.[]', 'the larger the capital stock, the less an increase in the capital stock increases output.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(474, 'The logic behind the catch-up effect is that[]', 'workers in countries with low income will work harder than workers in countries with high incomes.[]', 'new capital adds more to production in a country that doesn’t have much capital than in a country that already has much capital.[]', 'the capital stock in rich countries deteriorates more rapidly than the capital stock in poor countries.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(475, 'In the 1800s, Europeans purchased stock in American companies that used the funds to build railroads and factories. The Europeans made[]', 'foreign portfolio investments.[]', 'indirect domestic investments.[]', 'bilateral domestic investments.[]', 'foreign indirect investments.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(476, 'Which of the following is generally an opportunity cost of investment in human capital?[]', 'forgone wages at present []', 'increased earning potential[]', 'future job security[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(477, 'Generally, the main cause of famine is[]', 'a shortage of food.[]', 'excessive population.[]', 'an inadequate distribution of food.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(478, 'Outward-oriented policies[]', 'have led to high growth rates for the countries that pursued them.[]', 'prevent countries from taking advantage of gains from trade.[]', 'seem good in theory, but have not increased economic growth in practice.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(479, 'A large and sudden increase in the number of workers is likely to []', 'raise real GDP per person, but decrease real GDP.[]', 'decrease both real GDP and real GDP per person.[]', 'raise both real GDP and real GDP per person.[]', 'raise real GDP, but decrease real GDP per person.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(480, 'The primary reason that U.S. living standards are higher today than they were a century ago is that []', 'human capital has increased.[]', 'physical capital per worker has increased.[]', 'technological knowledge has increased.[]', 'more productive natural resources have been discovered.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(481, 'From 1973 to 1998, U.S. productivity growth was slower than from 1959 to 1973. Which of the following is correct?[]', 'This continues a downward trend as output growth was higher in periods before 1959.[]', 'It appears that this may be attributed to a slowdown in technological progress.[]', 'This slowdown is unique to the United States.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(482, 'Typically, countries in Africa[]', 'have high tax rates.[]', 'have laws and geography that make international trade easy.	[]', 'had low but positive growth of real GDP per person between 1978 and 1994.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(483, 'In the last 100 years U.S. per-capita real GDP grew about []', '2% per year, so that it is about two times as high.[]', '2% per year, so that it is about eight times as high.[]', '4% per year, so that it is about two times as high.[]', '4% per year, so that it is about eight times as high.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(484, 'Per-capita real GDP in China is about equal to per-capita real GDP in the United States in[]', '1870, and 1/2 that in the United States today.[]', '1870, and 1/8 that in the United States today.[]', '1920, and 1/2 that in the United States today.[]', '1920, and 1/8 that in the United States today.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(485, 'Of countries listed in the text, the per-capita real GDP growth rates over the last 100 years ranged from about []', '0%-5%.[]', '1%-3%.[]', '2%-5%.[]', '3%-6%.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(486, 'Suppose an economy that was roughly the size of Australia had a population of 19 million and real GDP of about 380,000 million U.S. dollars in 1998. Suppose further that in 1999 population was about 19.5 million and real GDP was about 401,500 million dollars. What are the approximate growth rates of real GDP and of real GDP per-capita?[]', '5.7%, 5.3%[]', '5.7%, 3%[]', '3%, 5.7%[]', '5.3%, 3%[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(487, 'Which of the following is correct?[]', 'If a country has a per-capita real GDP growth rate of 7%, its per-capita real GDP will double about every 14 years.[]', 'The current level of per-capita real GDP in the United States is about $19,450.[]', 'Although 100 years ago the United Kingdom had greater per-capita real GDP than the United States and Canada, it now has lower per-capita real GDP than both of them.[]', 'All of the above are correct.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(488, 'Productivity is the[]', 'growth rate of real GDP.[]', 'average amount a worker produces per hour.[]', 'level of real GDP.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(489, 'Suppose that factory output rose from 50,000 units to 55,000 units while labor hours rose from 1100 to 1200. Which of the following is true? []', 'Labor productivity remained unchanged.[]', 'Labor productivity increased slightly.[]', 'Labor productivity decreased slightly.[]', 'Labor productivity increased sharply.[]', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(490, 'The productivity of U.S. workers is higher than that of workers in many countries that have less capital. Which of the following arguments concerning these facts is logically consistent?[]', 'This contradicts the idea of diminishing marginal product. If U.S. workers have more capital, they should have lower productivity.[]', 'Productivity in the United States is higher because the United States has more workers than those countries having low productivity.[]', 'The United States could have greater productivity because its workers have both more human capital and physical capital per worker.[]', 'None of the above is logically consistent.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(491, 'Engineering students learn long-established methods for constructing bridges, in and of itself this learning increases[]', 'human capital.[]', 'physical capital.[]', 'technological knowledge.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(492, 'If there are constant returns to scale then[]', 'a doubling of all inputs doubles real GDP.[]', 'technological progress does not affect per-capita real GDP.[]', 'doubling labor would leave per-capita real GDP unchanged.[]', 'an increase in capital per worker would leave per-capita real GDP unchanged.[]', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(493, 'Which of the following is incorrect?[]', 'Bulldozers are an example of physical capital.[]', 'Students can be viewed as workers who have the important job of producing human capital that will be used in future production.[]', 'A forest is a non-renewable resource.[]', 'Technological progress may reduce our dependence on nonrenewable resources.[]', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(494, 'Human capital is[]', 'the number of workers in the economy.[]', 'the number of workers divided by the population.[]', 'the amount of physical capital per worker.[]', 'society’s understanding of the best way to produce output.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(495, 'Consider the following two sentences. The wealth of some countries derives primarily from the natural resources they own. However, countries with few natural resources can be highly productive.[]', 'Both sentences are true.[]', 'Only the first sentence is true.[]', 'Only the second sentence is true.[]', 'Neither sentence is true.[]', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(496, 'Once adjusted for inflation the price of most natural resources []', 'rose because of increasing demand from a growing population.[]', 'rose because their supply is declining.[]', 'were stable or falling because of government price controls.[]', 'None of the above is correct.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(497, 'In the long run a higher savings rate leads to[]', 'a higher level of per-capita income.[]', 'a higher level of productivity.[]', 'an increase in the growth rate of income.[]', 'A and B, but not C.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(498, 'Consider the following two sentences. According to the data, countries with higher investment relative to GDP, tend to have higher growth rates of real GDP per person. This relation is not perfect though, because an increase in the physical capital stock increases output per person more in a country with much capital than in a similar country with less capital.[]', 'Both sentences are true.[]', 'Both sentences are false.[]', 'Only the first sentence is true.[]', 'Only the second sentence is true.[]', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(499, 'The catch-up effect is the[]', 'tendency for countries that start off poor to grow more rapidly than countries that start off rich.[]', 'property whereby the benefits of an extra unit of an input declines as the quantity of the input increases.[]', 'tendency for the growth rate of the capital stock of a country to match its population growth rate.[]', 'property whereby the benefits of different inputs move toward each other over time.[]', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(500, 'Which of the following is incorrect?[]', 'Controlling for other variables such as the percentage of GDP devoted to investment, poor countries tend to grow faster than rich countries.[]', 'The growth that arises from capital accumulation is not a free lunch.[]', 'Countries such as Singapore and Japan, that devoted a large share of GDP to investment from 1960-1991 tended to have higher growth rates over this period.[]', 'The United States and Korea devoted similar shares of real GDP to investment from 1960-1991, but the United States had a higher growth rate.[]', 4, 3, 'medium');
INSERT INTO `gov_easy` (`Qno`, `Question`, `Option1`, `Option2`, `Option3`, `Option4`, `Answer`, `marks`, `Complexity`) VALUES
(1, 'There is a tremendous gap between youth and the elderly in all of the following EXCEPT[][]', 'political knowledge.[]', 'political participation.[]', 'political interest.[]', 'volunteering.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(2, 'Political knowledge[][]', 'is greater among youth than the elderly.[]', 'fosters political tolerance.[]', 'is generally high in the United States.[]', 'none of the above []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(3, 'Voter turnout matters because[][]', 'federal funds are allocated on the basis of the number of voters in a congressional district.[]', 'better candidates are selected when more people vote.[]', 'politicians pay more attention to those who vote than to those who do not vote.[]', 'it makes our country look better. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(4, 'Government is defined as the[][]', 'organization that brings problems to the attention of public officials.[]', 'body that is concerned with economic problems while leaving social problems to other institutions of society.[]', 'agency that implements policies that have been enacted by other institutions of the political system.[]', 'institutions and processes through which public policies are made for society. []', 5, 1, 'easy'),
(5, 'The policymaking institutions of the American national government include all of thefollowing EXCEPT[][]', 'the Supreme Court.[]', 'the presidency.[]', 'political parties.[]', 'the Senate. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(6, 'One advantage of the Internet for democracy is that it[][]', 'provides less information than newspapers.[]', 'makes it easy to avoid political topics.[]', 'makes it easier for citizens to communicate directly with government.[]', 'none of the above []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(7, 'Things that are indivisible, nonexclusive, and that everyone can share are called[][]', 'intangible property.[]', 'socialized.[]', 'community property.[]', 'public goods. []', 5, 1, 'easy'),
(8, 'Governments in the modern world, whether democratic or not, are similar in doing all of thefollowing EXCEPT[][]', 'protecting citizens ¹ civil liberties.[]', 'providing public goods.[]', 'collecting taxes.[]', 'providing public services. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(9, 'A public good is defined as[][]', 'something in which any member of society can share.[]', 'a choice that government makes in response to a political issue.[]', 'a public policy that is good for the nation as a whole.[]', 'all of the above []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(10, 'Which of the following statements about public goods is FALSE?[][]', 'The government usually provides public goods.[]', 'Public goods are things that everyone can share.[]', 'Individuals have powerful incentives to provide public goods.[]', 'Public goods are indivisible and nonexclusive. []', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(11, 'All governments[][]', 'provide public goods and socialize citizens into the political and social system.[]', 'maintain national parks and a national defense.[]', 'guarantee a capitalist economy and collect taxes.[]', 'hold elections. []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(12, 'All governments[][]', 'have written constitutions.[]', 'are elected.[]', 'have a legislature.[]', 'provide services.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(13, 'Which of the following statements about taxes is TRUE?[][]', 'One out of every three dollars earned by an American citizen is used to pay taxes.[]', 'About one-tenth of the average American citizen\'s salary goes to taxes.[]', 'The tax burden in the United States is higher than in most other democratic nations.[]', 'All of these are true. []', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(14, 'An interest group so single-minded that its members often vote on only one issue, ignoring apolitician\'s stand on everything else, is known as[][]', 'a one-issue group.[]', 'a uni-issue group.[]', 'a hot-button group.[]', 'a single-issue group.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(15, 'When compared with the rest of the world, America has a relatively low[][]', 'number of offices up for election.[]', 'number of candidates who seek office.[]', 'frequency of elections.[]', 'voter turnout in elections.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(16, 'Many politicians believe that single-issue groups[][]', 'stimulate the political system to solve public policy problems.[]', 'are essential to democracy.[]', 'complicate efforts to seek the middle ground on various issues.[]', 'do not affect policymaking. []', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(17, 'Politics is defined by Harold Lasswell as[][]', 'conflict in society.[]', 'the exercise of power.[]', 'the resolution of conflict in a way that serves the public.[]', 'who gets what, when, and how.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(18, 'Single-issue groups[][]', 'are rapidly losing prominence in American politics.[]', 'usually run their own candidates for public office.[]', 'have little sympathy for compromising.[]', 'are highly regarded by political scientists for their contributions to democracy. []', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(19, 'Which of the following statements best describes voter turnout in the United States?[][]', 'Among democratic nations, the United States leads the world in voter turnout.[]', 'Voter turnout in the United States is constitutionally mandated.[]', 'Voters are usually a microcosm of the entire body of American citizens.[]', 'The United States has one of the lowest voter turnout rates in the world. []', 5, 2, 'easy'),
(20, 'The list of problems to which political leaders are paying serious attention is a(n)[][]', 'problem set.[]', 'policy agenda.[]', 'legislative package.[]', 'none of the above []', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(21, '________ is the process by which policy comes into being and evolves over time.[][]', 'Democracy[]', 'A policymaking system[]', 'The bureaucracy[]', 'Government []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(22, 'The process from above is[][]', 'a policymaking system.[]', 'a policy agenda.[]', 'a government.[]', 'a linkage institution. []', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(23, 'An example of public policymaking would be[][]', 'Congress and the president deciding not to act on the AIDS crisis.[]', 'the president meeting with the heads of oil companies.[]', 'the press creating public concern about racial discrimination.[]', 'all of the above []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(24, 'All of the following are parts of the policymaking system EXCEPT[][]', 'public goods.[]', 'linkage institutions.[]', 'people\'s political interests.[]', 'policy. []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(25, 'Which of the following statements about a government\'s policy agenda is FALSE?[][]', 'When you vote, you are partly looking at whether a candidate shares your agenda or not.[]', 'Bad news gets an issue on the policy agenda more quickly than good news.[]', 'When people confront government officials with problems to be solved, they are trying to influence the government\'s policy agenda.[]', 'A government\'s policy agenda tends to remain constant over time.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(26, 'A political party is a key ________ in America¹s democratic system.[][]', 'stimulus-response[]', 'linkage institution[]', 'majoritarian inhibitor[]', 'output []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(27, 'In a democratic society, parties, elections, interest groups and the media are all examples of ________ between the preferences of citizens and the government\'s policy agenda.[][]', 'cross-pollination[]', 'inputs and outputs[]', 'ideological bridges[]', 'linkage institutions []', 5, 1, 'easy'),
(28, 'Which of the following is NOT a linkage institution?[][]', 'political parties[]', 'the media[]', 'interest groups[]', 'Congress[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(29, 'Which of these is a linkage institution?[][]', 'USA Today[]', 'the House of Representatives[]', 'the ambassador to France[]', 'all of the above []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(30, 'Parties and interest groups[][]', 'determine which issues are on the policy agenda.[]', 'are not particularly interested in the policy agenda.[]', 'work hard to get the issues they want on the policy agenda.[]', 'determine the congressional agenda. []', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(31, 'A choice that government makes in response to some issue on its agenda is called[][]', 'public policy.[]', 'a law.[]', 'stimulus-response.[]', 'rational choice theory. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(32, '________ arise when people disagree about a problem or a public policy choice made tocombat a problem.[][]', 'Revolutions[]', 'Political issues[]', 'Governments[]', 'Wars []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(33, 'A key question that confronts government regarding different public policy choices is[][]', 'whether an appropriate linkage institution is willing to frame a policy.[]', 'which is the most complicated one to deal with.[]', 'which is the least complicated one to deal with.[]', 'whether or not government should do anything about them.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(34, 'Public policy is defined as a[][]', 'policy directed at more than one person.[]', 'course of action to solve a problem.[]', 'set of rules and regulations issued by a government agency.[]', 'choice that government makes in response to an issue. []', 5, 2, 'easy'),
(35, 'Political issues[][]', 'are always acted upon by the government.[]', 'arise when people disagree about a problem or public policy choices made to combat a problem.[]', 'usually emerge out of group consensus on a problem.[]', 'all of the above []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(36, 'Karl Marx and Friedrich Engels published[][]', 'The Communist Manifesto.[]', 'The Federalist Papers.[]', 'Poor Richard\'s Almanac.[]', 'War and Peace. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(37, 'One type of linkage institution is[][]', 'an interest group.[]', 'a bureaucracy.[]', 'a legislature.[]', 'all of the above []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(38, 'The effects a policy has on people and problems is called[][]', 'policy outputs.[]', 'policy implementation.[]', 'policy issues.[]', 'policy impacts.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(39, 'The writers of the United States Constitution[][]', 'were distrustful of democracy.[]', 'were interested in promoting equality above all else.[]', 'patterned our government after Britain\'s except for the King.[]', 'believed in majority rule. []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(40, 'A means of selecting policymakers and or organizing government so that policy representsand responds to the public\'s preferences is[][]', 'government.[]', 'politics.[]', 'public administration.[]', 'democracy.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(41, 'Which of these is NOT a criterion of traditional democratic theory, as formulated by RobertDahl?[][]', 'freedom of speech and press[]', 'One person gets one vote.[]', 'Citizenship must be open to all within a nation.[]', 'Citizens must make rational choices. []', 5, 2, 'easy'),
(42, 'Which of the following is NOT one of the cornerstones of an ideal democracy?[][]', 'a constitution[]', 'effective participation[]', 'citizen control of the agenda[]', 'economic equality[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(43, 'Two of the most important principles of democratic theory are majority rule and[][]', 'the plurality rule.[]', 'judicial review.[]', 'minority rights.[]', 'Roberts ¹ Rules of Order. []', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(44, 'Which of the following takes the most positive view of democracy in the United States?[][]', 'democratic centralism[]', 'pluralist theory[]', 'democratic positivism[]', 'elite theory []', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(45, 'All of the following are ingredients of a pluralistic democracy EXCEPT[][]', 'group competition for policy benefits.[]', 'bargaining and compromise.[]', 'majority rule.[]', 'separation of powers. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(46, 'The most fundamental element of democratic theory is[][]', '  power to the people!  []', 'government efficiency.[]', 'equality.[]', 'majority rule.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(47, 'Representation refers to[][]', 'majority rule.[]', 'all policy views being included in political debate.[]', 'the protection of minority rights in a pluralist system.[]', 'the correspondence between the few leaders and the many followers in a democracy. []', 5, 3, 'easy'),
(48, 'Which of the following individuals have suggested that pluralist theory is less descriptive ofAmerican politics than in the past?[][]', 'Anthony King[]', 'Robert Dahl[]', 'Alexis de Tocqueville[]', 'Robert Putnam[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(49, 'American government is viewed most positively by the[][]', 'socialist theory.[]', 'pluralist theory.[]', 'hyperpluralist theory.[]', 'elite and class theory. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(50, 'A system in which many groups make themselves heard and felt somewhere in the policyprocess is[][]', 'pluralistic.[]', 'hyperpluralistic.[]', 'elitist.[]', 'bureaucratic. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(51, 'The theory that argues that group competition results in a rough approximation of the publicinterest in public policy is[][]', 'hyperpluralist theory.[]', 'balance of power theory.[]', 'elite and class theory.[]', 'pluralist theory.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(52, 'Which of the following is NOT a contemporary theory of democracy?[][]', 'hyperpluralism[]', 'class theory[]', 'democratic centralism[]', 'elite theory []', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(53, 'Robert Putnam\'s claim that Americans are now   bowling alone   is a criticism of[][]', 'pluralism.[]', 'hyperpluralism.[]', 'social network theory.[]', 'none of the above []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(54, 'Which of the following is most fundamentally critical of American democracy?[][]', 'traditional democratic theory[]', 'democratic negativism[]', 'pluralist theory[]', 'elite and class theory []', 5, 2, 'easy'),
(55, 'Many elite and class theorists believe that ________ of Americans control most governmentpolicy decisions.[][]', '5 percent[]', 'a majority[]', 'the vast middle class[]', '1 percent[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(56, 'Over a third of America\'s wealth is owned by[][]', 'the United States government.[]', 'one percent of the population.[]', 'seven percent of the population.[]', 'Japanese investors. []', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(57, 'At the center of all theories of elite domination of politics is[][]', 'big business.[]', 'the nouveau riche.[]', 'the Trilateral Commission.[]', 'the president. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(58, 'Elite and class theory holds that[][]', 'all societies are divided along class lines and that an upper-class elite will rule.[]', 'in a democracy the majority class must overthrow the government and rule by itself if government is to be freed from the control of the rich.[]', 'there is little consensus in policymaking among elites.[]', 'politics is the basis of elite power. []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(59, 'The theory that sees wealth as the basis of power is the[][]', 'democratic theory.[]', 'hyperpluralist theory.[]', 'Jeffersonian theory.[]', 'elite and class theory.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(60, 'Hyperpluralists believe that the dominant player in American politics is[][]', 'groups.[]', 'the government.[]', 'the media.[]', 'rich individuals. []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(61, 'In evaluating American democracy, hyperpluralists[][]', 'claim that competing groups vying for power make for generally efficient, honest government.[]', 'claim that society is governed solely by an upper-class elite.[]', 'claim that too many influential groups cripple government\'s ability to govern.[]', 'none of the above []', 3, 3, 'easy'),
