(172, 'The system of checks and balances in the Constitution means that[][]', 'a majority can easily manipulate the system, but a minority cannot.[]', 'changes in government policy can be made with relative ease, with few obstacles to stop a popular new force.[]', 'we have a direct democracy, with all branches equally accessible to strong public pressure.[]', 'change usually comes slowly, if at all, and moderation and compromise are typical in our political system.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(173, 'The Madisonian requirement that each branch of government acquire the consent of the othersfor many of its actions created a system of[][]', 'confederated government.[]', 'checks and balances.[]', 'cross-cutting requirements.[]', 'separation of powers. []', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(174, 'The Madisonian system[][]', 'is a form of direct democracy.[]', 'encourages change.[]', 'has a conservative bias favoring the status quo.[]', 'both C and D []', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(175, 'Under the Madisonian model, people desiring change[][]', 'find a government that is highly responsive and acts quickly and decisively.[]', 'must usually have a sizable majority.[]', 'need only win at one point in the policymaking process.[]', 'need just a simple majority over 50 percent. []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(176, 'The Federalist Papers were[][]', 'essays in support of ratification of the constitution.[]', 'newspapers which backed the Federalist party in early United States elections.[]', 'the original name of the constitution written by the Constitutional Convention.[]', 'the notes that George Washington took at the Constitutional Convention. []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(177, 'Ratification of the Constitution[][]', 'needed the approval of nine states.[]', 'occurred when it was approved by the delegates to the Constitutional Convention.[]', 'needed the approval of all the states.[]', 'was by two-thirds vote of the Continental Congress. []', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(178, 'Which of the following statements about the Anti-Federalists is FALSE?[][]', 'The Anti-Federalists were basically unpatriotic and un-American.[]', 'The Anti-Federalists believed that the new government was an enemy of freedom.[]', 'The Anti-Federalists believed the new government would erode fundamental liberties.[]', 'The Anti-Federalists believed the new Constitution was a class-based document. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(179, 'Opposition to ratification of the Constitution was based on the belief that it would[][]', 'provide for elite control, endanger liberty, and weaken the states.[]', 'give too much power to the states.[]', 'promote pluralism, which would threaten liberty.[]', 'all of the above []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(180, 'The Bill of Rights was added to the Constitution[][]', 'during the ratification process, before final ratification of the constitution.[]', 'during the Constitutional Convention, at the insistence of Thomas Jefferson.[]', 'after the ratification process was complete, and partly to fulfill a promise to those who supported ratification.[]', 'piece by piece during the first hundred years of its operation. []', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(181, 'Ratification of the Constitution was done by[][]', 'the voters in each state casting open ballots.[]', 'special conventions in each state.[]', 'approval by the Supreme Court.[]', 'majority vote of the delegates at the Constitutional Convention. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(182, 'The Constitution was ratified by[][]', 'popular vote in each of the states.[]', 'special conventions in each of the states.[]', 'state representatives to the Constitutional Convention.[]', 'the state legislatures. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(183, 'The amendments that have been added to the Constitution have made it[][]', 'more egalitarian and democratic.[]', 'more protective of property rights.[]', 'weaker and less significant to American society.[]', 'much more like the European constitutions it originally condemned. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(184, 'Constitutional amendments are usually ratified by[][]', 'state conventions called by two-thirds vote in Congress.[]', 'a national convention.[]', 'a majority of the Supreme Court.[]', 'legislatures of three-fourths of the states. []', 5, 3, 'easy'),
(185, 'The most important effect of the constitutional amendments has been to[][]', 'expand liberty and equality.[]', 'expand the powers of the states.[]', 'strengthen the capitalist economy.[]', 'all of the above []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(186, 'Which of the following statements about the Equal Rights Amendment (ERA) is FALSE?[][]', 'The ERA was opposed by many southern states.[]', 'The ERA was proposed by Congress in 1978.[]', 'Public opinion polls showed little support for the ERA after 1960.[]', 'The ERA never became part of the Constitution. []', 3, 2, 'easy');
INSERT INTO `gov_easy` (`Qno`, `Question`, `Option1`, `Option2`, `Option3`, `Option4`, `Answer`, `marks`, `Complexity`) VALUES
(187, 'To propose a formal amendment to the Constitution, one needs to have a[][]', 'three-quarters vote in Congress.[]', 'national convention requested by half of the states.[]', 'majority vote of the Supreme Court.[]', 'two-thirds vote in Congress.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(188, 'The failure of the Equal Rights Amendment showed that[][]', 'Congress was unwilling to support a measure opposed by a strong minority of the public.[]', 'a national majority in favor of an amendment is not sufficient to add it to the Constitution.[]', 'we are a democracy, and majority opinion prevails.[]', 'men are pigs, still unwilling to grant women equal rights. []', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(189, 'Which of the following is established by the written Constitution?[][]', 'the right to an abortion[]', 'media coverage of the House and Senate[]', 'political parties[]', 'None of these are mentioned in the written Constitution. []', 5, 2, 'easy'),
(190, 'Informal changes to the Constitution have reflected changes in all of the following EXCEPT[][]', 'technology.[]', 'political practice.[]', 'judicial interpretation.[]', 'constitutional amendments.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(191, 'How has the electoral college changed from the original intent of the framers?[][]', 'Affirmative action programs have made the student body much more diverse, although standards have also been lowered.[]', 'The president must now be elected by two-thirds vote of the electoral college rather than a simple majority.[]', 'The number of electors has decreased dramatically.[]', 'Almost all electors now vote for the presidential candidate who wins the most popular votes in their state.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(192, 'The Supreme Court in Marbury v. Madison (1803) asserted the power of the Court to[][]', 'check the actions of the other branches through judicial review.[]', 'confirm presidential appointments.[]', 'determine its own size and makeup.[]', 'impeach the president. []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(193, 'Political parties are an important example of the[][]', 'Third Amendment.[]', 'formal amendment process.[]', 'unwritten constitution.[]', 'rigidity of the Constitution. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(194, 'Which of the following statements about judicial interpretation is FALSE?[][]', 'Judicial interpretation can profoundly affect how the Constitution is understood.[]', 'The power of judicial review gives courts the right to decide whether legislative actions are in accord with the Constitution.[]', 'The power of judicial interpretation is explicitly stated in the Constitution.[]', 'none of the above []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(195, 'The development of the two-party system is an example of informal constitutional changethrough[][]', 'political practice.[]', 'judicial interpretation.[]', 'increasing demands on policymakers.[]', 'all of the above []', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(196, 'The United States Constitution[][]', 'lists the executive departments that are required to advise the president.[]', 'does not prescribe the function and structure of government in detail.[]', 'gives particular detail to the function of the judiciary.[]', 'was modeled on the British Constitution. []', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(197, 'Which of the following is FALSE about the Constitution?[][]', 'It creates many government access points where groups can attempt to initiate or block policy changes.[]', 'It discourages hyperpluralism.[]', 'It protects individual liberty.[]', 'It creates government gridlock and inaction. []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(198, 'Some scholars have suggested that a consequence of separation of powers and checks andbalances has been[][]', 'the inability of groups to get their grievances heard.[]', 'fragmented policymaking processes.[]', 'streamlined, but hasty, government decision making.[]', 'political instability. []', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(199, 'The separation of powers and the checks and balances established by the Constitution[][]', 'allow almost all groups some place in the political system where their demands for public policy can be heard.[]', 'have made the United States one of the most democratic countries in the world.[]', 'create so many obstacles that groups have no place for their policy demands to be heard.[]', 'are basically undemocratic since only elites can formulate policies within the system. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(200, 'The government\'s responses in the wake of Hurricane Katrina underscores[][]', 'the neccesity of complying with the letter and the spirit of the Third Amendment.[]', 'the tensions between Congress and the president.[]', 'the ability of the U.S. military to mobilize and deploy quickly.[]', 'the complexity of American federalism.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(201, 'Federalism is[][]', 'a system of shared power by the state and national governments.[]', 'sole government authority in the national government.[]', 'sole government authority in the states.[]', 'a three-branch government with a system of checks and balances. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(202, 'Federalism is[][]', 'unique to the United States alone.[]', 'practiced by about half the nations worldwide.[]', 'practiced in about half the American states.[]', 'practiced by fewer than 20 nations worldwide. []', 5, 3, 'easy'),
(203, 'The workings of the federal system are sometimes called[][]', 'internal relations.[]', 'intergovernmental relations.[]', 'interstate relations.[]', 'international relations. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(204, 'Which of the following is NOT true?[][]', 'Few countries have federal systems.[]', 'Most federal systems are democracies.[]', 'Authoritarian regimes generally do not use federalist systems.[]', 'No unitary governments are democratic.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(205, 'Most of the governments in the world today are ________, in which all power resides in thecentral national government.[][]', 'unitary[]', 'nationalist[]', 'confederations[]', 'fiscal []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(206, 'Which of the following statements is TRUE?[][]', 'The American states have unitary governments.[]', 'Great Britain has a federal system.[]', 'Most European countries are confederations.[]', 'none of the above []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(207, 'Which of the following is an example of a confederation?[][]', 'state governments in the United States[]', 'the United Nations[]', 'Britain[]', 'France []', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(208, 'How is a unitary system different from a federal one?[][]', 'The national government can coin money, conduct foreign relations, and declare war.[]', 'The national government can change the boundaries of states, or abolish them.[]', 'Administrative subunits, such as states, can collect taxes, conduct elections, and make laws independently of the national government.[]', 'both B and C []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(209, 'Federalism is a way of organizing a nation so that[][]', 'power is centralized in state and local government.[]', 'both national and state levels of government have authority over the same land and people.[]', 'power is centralized in the national government.[]', 'there are three branches of government and a system of checks and balances. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(210, 'Which one of the following countries has federalism as its method of governing?[][]', 'Canada[]', 'France[]', 'Kenya[]', 'No other country uses federalism. []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(211, 'The federal system[][]', 'decreases judicial power.[]', 'centralizes our politics.[]', 'decreases opportunities for political participation.[]', 'decentralizes our politics. []', 5, 1, 'easy'),
(212, 'Which of the following is NOT an effect of federalism?[][]', 'It simplifies the governmental system.[]', 'It decentralizes political power.[]', 'It creates more access points to government.[]', 'It increases bureaucracy. []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(213, 'The power to directly regulate such things as drinking ages, marriage and divorce, and sexualbehavior has been granted[][]', 'to all governments by the Bill of Rights.[]', 'to the national government.[]', 'to the president.[]', 'to state governments.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(214, 'States are responsible for most public policies dealing with each of the following issuesEXCEPT[][]', 'economic issues.[]', 'police powers.[]', 'family issues.[]', 'moral issues. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(215, 'Laws that directly regulate abortion, drinking ages, marriage and divorce, or sexual behaviorare policy prerogatives that belong to[][]', 'the bureaucracy.[]', 'the states.[]', 'local governments.[]', 'federal courts. []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(216, 'All of the following are examples of how federalism decentralizes our policies EXCEPT[][]', 'federal income tax.[]', 'death penalty.[]', 'funding of education.[]', 'homeland security. []', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(217, 'Which of these is NOT among the factors that tend to lead to the creation of a federal form ofgovernment in a country?[][]', 'large population[]', 'diverse population[]', 'large land area[]', 'industrialization []', 5, 2, 'easy'),
(218, 'In our federal system, the powers of the state governments are ultimately granted by[][]', 'their state\'s Supreme Court.[]', 'the people of their state.[]', 'their state legislature.[]', 'the United States Constitution.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(219, 'From clean-air legislation to welfare reforms, the states constitute a ________ to develop andtest public policies and share the results with other states and the national government.[][]', 'major roadblock[]', 'national laboratory[]', 'last chance[]', 'severe reluctance []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(220, 'Almost every policy the national government has adopted has originated with[][]', 'the Senate.[]', 'the states.[]', 'the Supreme Court.[]', 'the president. []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(221, 'Which of the following statements about federalism is FALSE?[][]', 'Federalism was hotly debated at the Constitutional Convention.[]', 'There was no other practical choice in 1787 but to create a federal system of government.[]', 'Loyalty to state governments was so strong that the Constitution would have been resoundingly defeated had it tried to abolish them.[]', 'None of the above; all are TRUE. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(222, 'The supremacy clause of the Constitution states that all of the following are the supreme lawof the land, EXCEPT[][]', 'laws of the national government (when consistent with the Constitution).[]', 'the United States Constitution.[]', 'state constitutions.[]', 'both C and D []', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(223, 'The Constitution\'s supremacy clause[][]', 'does not apply to state and local matters.[]', 'gives the states superiority over the national government\'s Constitution and laws.[]', 'made the Constitution, the laws of the national government, and the national government\'s treaties the supreme law of the land.[]', 'makes the president supreme in any constitutional conflicts with the other two branches. []', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(224, 'The efforts of Candy Lightner and Mothers Against Drunk Driving (MADD) to raise the legaldrinking age to 21 are an example of[][]', 'the supremacy of state government to regulate its own affairs.[]', 'the constitutional authority of the national government to impose policies on state governments.[]', 'states acting as policy innovators.[]', 'the ability of the national government to influence state policy. []', 5, 1, 'easy'),
(225, 'In the Constitution, the powers to coin money, to enter into treaties, and to regulate commercewith foreign nations and among the states were given to[][]', 'neither the individual states nor the national government.[]', 'the national government.[]', 'the Senate only.[]', 'both the individual states and the national government. []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(226, 'Only the national government is allowed to[][]', 'levy taxes.[]', 'regulate commerce with foreign nations.[]', 'make and enforce laws.[]', 'all of the above []', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(227, 'What was the main criticism of the national bank created by the United States government?[][]', 'It was printing too much worthless paper money which debtors were using to pay off their debts.[]', 'It was charging exorbitant interest rates on its loans.[]', 'It was borrowing too much money, putting the United States government hopelessly in debt.[]', 'It was an instrument of the elite and gave the national government too much control of the economy.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(228, 'In its McCulloch v. Maryland decision, the Supreme Court ruled in favor of[][]', 'judicial restraint.[]', 'judicial review.[]', 'the supremacy of the national government over the states.[]', 'Maryland in a dispute with the national government. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(229, 'The McCulloch v. Maryland case dealt with what specific grievance?[][]', 'a state taxing a national bank[]', 'the location of Maryland\'s capital city[]', 'a state coining its own money[]', 'import taxes on goods made in other states []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(230, 'The principle of the supremacy of federal law over state law was affirmed in[][]', 'Marbury v. Madison.[]', 'the Tenth Amendment.[]', 'United States v. Darby.[]', 'McCulloch v. Maryland.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(231, 'The Supreme Court case of McCulloch v. Maryland (1819)[][]', 'established Baltimore as the capital of Maryland.[]', 'stated that the Constitution gave Congress implied powers.[]', 'established the supremacy of state governments.[]', 'recognized that Congress was limited to its enumerated powers. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(232, 'The principle that the national government has certain implied powers that go beyond itsenumerated powers was first elaborated in the Supreme Court\'s decision in[][]', 'United States v. the States.[]', 'Gibbons v. Ogden.[]', 'Miranda v. Arizona.[]', 'McCulloch v. Maryland.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(233, 'The enumerated powers of Congress and the national government are those[][]', 'specifically spelled out in the Constitution.[]', 'involving taxes, spending, and fiscal policy.[]', 'not specifically spelled out in the Constitution, but nonetheless acknowledged.[]', 'requiring ratification by the states. []', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(234, 'Federal policies to regulate food and drugs, build interstate highways, protect consumers, tryto clean up dirty air and water, and do many other things are all justified as ________ ofCongress.[][]', 'implied powers[]', 'constitutionally specified powers[]', 'reserved powers[]', 'enumerated powers []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(235, 'The Constitution\'s provision that Congress has the right to   make all laws necessary andproper for carrying into execution   its powers is often referred to as the[][]', 'enumerated powers.[]', 'heart of fiscal federalism.[]', 'Unwritten Amendment.[]', 'elastic clause.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(236, 'The Constitution states that Congress has the power to establish post offices. This is anexample of[][]', 'enumerated powers.[]', 'implied powers.[]', 'reserved powers.[]', 'shared powers. []', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(237, 'Which of the following federal policies exemplifies the implied powers of Congress?[][]', 'environmental protection law[]', 'the regulation of interstate commerce[]', 'the provision of an army and a navy[]', 'all of the above []', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(238, 'Federal policies to regulate food and drugs, build interstate highways, and protect consumersare all justified as[][]', 'presidential prerogatives.[]', 'enumerated powers of Congress.[]', 'delegated powers of Congress.[]', 'implied powers of Congress.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(239, 'The Supreme Court case of Gibbons v. Ogden[][]', 'defined the meaning of the elastic clause.[]', 'settled the contested presidential election of 1824.[]', 'defined commerce as virtually every form of commercial activity.[]', 'established the supremacy of the national government. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(240, 'Enumerated powers are those that are[][]', 'reserved for the states.[]', 'stated in the Constitution.[]', 'involving money matters.[]', 'granted specifically to the president. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(241, 'Abraham Lincoln announced in his 1861 inaugural address that he would willingly support aconstitutional amendment to[][]', 'prohibit states from seceding from the Union.[]', 'return the United States to a confederation, with greater powers given to the states.[]', 'establish the United States as a unitary system, where states would have to obey all national government decisions.[]', 'guarantee slavery. []', 5, 2, 'easy'),
(242, 'In the 1950s and 1960s, the proclamation of states ¹ rights was usually made by those opposingthe national government\'s efforts in the area of[][]', 'the Vietnam War.[]', 'abortion rights.[]', 'civil rights for African Americans.[]', 'the Korean War. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(243, 'The Constitution requires that states give ________ to the public acts, records, and civil judicialproceedings of every other state.[][]', 'privileges and immunities[]', 'due process[]', 'full faith and credit[]', 'extradition []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(244, 'Contracts between business firms can be enforced across state boundaries as part of theconstitutional provision of[][]', 'interstate compacts.[]', 'privileges and immunities.[]', 'implied powers of the states.[]', 'full faith and credit. []', 5, 1, 'easy'),
(245, 'A marriage license issued in one state is valid and honored in all states under theconstitutional provision of[][]', 'separation of powers.[]', 'full faith and credit.[]', 'national licensure.[]', 'privileges and immunities. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(246, 'The fact that a driver\'s license from one state is valid in other states is an example of[][]', 'privileges and immunities.[]', 'extradition.[]', 'implied powers.[]', 'full faith and credit.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(247, 'The constitutional requirement that the states return a person charged with a crime in anotherstate to that state for trial or imprisonment is known as[][]', 'forfeiture.[]', 'extradition.[]', 'full faith and credit.[]', 'the elastic clause. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(248, 'One recently controversial application of the   full faith and credit   provision of theConstitution is for[][]', 'extradition.[]', 'birth certificates.[]', 'same gender marriages.[]', 'abortion []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(249, 'Extradition is the requirement that states[][]', 'provide sanctuary for federal criminals.[]', 'cannot discriminate against citizens of other states.[]', 'recognize each others public acts, records, and civil judicial proceedings.[]', 'must return a person charged with a crime in another state to that state for trial or imprisonment.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(250, 'In ________ federalism, the powers and policy assignments of the different levels ofgovernment are distinct, like a layer cake.[][]', 'fiscal[]', 'dual[]', 'cooperative[]', 'anti- []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(251, 'The national government has exclusive control over foreign and military policy, the postalsystem, and monetary policy, while the states have exclusive control over other specific areas.This division of responsibilities reflects[][]', 'dual federalism.[]', 'tripartite federalism.[]', 'cooperative federalism.[]', 'fiscal federalism. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(252, 'In Saenz v. Roe, the Supreme Court ruled that[][]', 'California was required to recognize the legality of same sex marriages.[]', 'California could not require a new resident to wait one year before being eligible for welfare benefits.[]', 'California was required to offer bilingual education programs in the public elementary schools.[]', 'California could not provide welfare benefits to illegal immigrants. []', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(253, 'A tuition difference between in-state and out-of-state students is an example of[][]', 'dual federalism.[]', 'federal exceptions to the full faith and credit provision.[]', 'full faith and credit being extended to all students.[]', 'how states make exceptions to the privileges and immunities clause.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(254, 'If the allocation of power in a cooperative federal system were compared to a cake it would bemost like[][]', 'a layer cake with two distinct layers.[]', 'a single-layer cake.[]', 'a cake walk: who gets what is random.[]', 'fifty marbled cupcakes.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(255, 'If the allocation of power under dual federalism were compared to a cake it would be mostlike[][]', 'a marbled cake where the flavors blend into each other.[]', 'an angel food cakeî€„fluffy with little substance.[]', 'New York cheesecakeî€„heavy and crushing under its own weight.[]', 'a layer cake, with two distinct layers.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(256, 'Over time, there has been a gradual change from a dual federalism to a(n) ________federalism.[][]', 'unitary[]', 'single[]', 'tripartite[]', 'cooperative[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(257, 'In ________ federalism, the powers and policy assignments of different levels of governmentare like a marble cake, with mingled responsibilities and blurred distinctions between layers ofgovernment.[][]', 'fiscal[]', 'mixed[]', 'dual[]', 'cooperative[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(258, 'In dual federalism,[][]', 'the state governments assume greater fiscal responsibility.[]', 'there are only two branches of government.[]', 'the federal government assumes greater fiscal responsibility.[]', 'states and the national government each remain supreme within their own spheres. []', 5, 1, 'easy'),
(259, 'In cooperative federalism,[][]', 'states and the national government each remain supreme within their own spheres.[]', 'responsibilities are mingled and distinctions are blurred between the levels of government.[]', 'states are supreme over the national government.[]', 'both A and B []', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(260, 'Since the ratification of the Constitution, American federalism has gradually changed from[][]', 'cooperative to dual federalism.[]', 'state domination to national domination.[]', 'dual to cooperative federalism.[]', 'a federal system to a unitary one. []', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(261, 'Which of the following statements about federalism is false?[][]', 'In cooperative federalism, sometimes even blame is shared when programs do not work well.[]', 'The American system has always been neatly separated into purely state and purely national responsibilities.[]', 'Cooperative federalism today rests on several standard operating procedures.[]', 'None; all are true. []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(262, 'Federal support for public education is an example of a[][]', 'pragmatic federalism.[]', 'dual federalism.[]', 'cooperative federalism.[]', 'separation of powers []', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(263, 'Funding for the interstate highway system is an example of[][]', 'dual federalism.[]', 'cooperative federalism.[]', 'a unitary system of government.[]', 'national federalism. []', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(264, 'The National Defense Education Act, the Elementary and Secondary Education Act, and theInterstate Highway System are all examples of[][]', 'dual federalism.[]', 'cooperative federalism.[]', 'layer cake federalism.[]', 'unitary federalism []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(265, 'Which of the following is NOT a standard operating procedure of cooperative federalismtoday?[][]', 'distinctly separated powers of state and national governments[]', 'shared administration of programs[]', 'shared financing of government[]', 'federal guidelines imposed on states []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(266, 'Which of the following does NOT characterize the standard operating procedure ofcooperative federalism today?[][]', 'federal guidelines[]', 'grants-in-aid[]', 'shared costs[]', 'separate and distinct roles for the national and state governments[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(267, 'Standard operating procedures in cooperative federalism include each of the followingEXCEPT[][]', 'shared administration.[]', 'shared costs.[]', 'federal funding with no strings attached.[]', 'categorical and block grants. []', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(268, 'In cooperative federalism, in order to qualify for federal grant money, cities and states must[][]', 'match federal funding dollar for dollar.[]', 'propose standard operating procedures.[]', 'allow federal agencies to administer the funds.[]', 'follow federal guidelines for adopting and enforcing federal laws.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(269, 'Federal regulation of state governments is usually accomplished through[][]', 'United States Supreme Court decisions.[]', 'presidential decrees.[]', 'attaching conditions to grants it gives them.[]', 'direct, executive orders. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(270, 'About ________ of the funds state and local governments spend comes from the federalgovernment.[][]', '33 percent[]', '25 percent[]', '75 percent[]', '90 percent []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(271, 'Federal aid to state and local governments accounts for how much of federal spending?[][]', '33 percent[]', '50 percent[]', '2 percent[]', '18 percent[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(272, 'The main instrument the national government uses to influence state governments is[][]', 'grants-in-aid.[]', 'judicial review.[]', 'the Tenth Amendment.[]', 'presidential decrees. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(273, 'The pattern of spending, taxing, and providing grants in the federal system is called[][]', 'economic federalism.[]', 'dual federalism.[]', 'cooperative federalism.[]', 'fiscal federalism.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(274, 'The main instrument the national government uses for both aiding and influencing states andlocalities is[][]', 'judicial decisions.[]', 'politics.[]', 'grants-in-aid.[]', 'revenue sharing. []', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(275, 'Of all the funds spent by state and local governments, federal aid accounts for about[][]', 'two-thirds.[]', 'one-half.[]', 'one-fourth.[]', 'one-third. []', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(276, 'The principal type of federal aid for states and localities is[][]', 'categorical grants.[]', 'revenue sharing.[]', 'block grants.[]', 'urban renewal grants. []', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(277, 'Which of the following is NOT true about categorical grants?[][]', 'The federal government is less likely to apply conditions to these grants today than in the 1970s.[]', 'Virtually every one is enshrouded in rules and regulations for its use.[]', 'A project grant is the most typical type of categorical grant.[]', 'Categorical grants are monies that can be spent in broad categories of functions. []', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(278, 'The main type of federal aid to state and local governments is in the form of[][]', 'block grants.[]', 'formula grants.[]', 'categorical grants.[]', 'revenue sharing. []', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(279, 'The requirement of a drinking age provision before states can receive federal highway aid isan example of[][]', 'a string attached to categorical grants.[]', 'a project grant supported by the interest groups.[]', 'the efforts of state agencies to get federal funds.[]', 'an unfunded mandate. []', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(280, 'The most common type of categorical grant is[][]', 'block grants.[]', 'a rescission fund.[]', 'project grants.[]', 'revenue sharing. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(281, 'Programs such as Medicaid and Aid for Families with Dependent Children, where applicantsautomatically qualify for aid if they meet the requirements, are examples of[][]', 'dual federalism.[]', 'project grants.[]', 'formula grants.[]', 'welfare. []', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(282, 'In contrast to the Democratic Congress of recent decades, the new Republican majority inCongress is passing more federal aid in the form of[][]', 'revenue sharing.[]', 'categorical grants.[]', 'block grants.[]', 'tax expenditures. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(283, 'In response to complaints from state and local governments about the paperwork andrequirements attached to most grants, Congress has established ________ to support programsin areas like community development and social services.[][]', 'formula grants[]', 'block grants[]', 'categorical grants[]', 'computerized grant applications []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(284, 'On the whole, federal grant distribution follows the principle of[][]', 'universalism.[]', 'cronyism.[]', 'to the victors go the spoils.[]', 'needs-testing. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(285, 'Project grants[][]', 'have no strings attached.[]', 'are awarded on the basis of competitive applications.[]', 'are automatically given to states and communities.[]', 'all of the above []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(286, 'Grants for specific programs distributed according to community demographic factors, such aspopulation or income, are[][]', 'formula grants.[]', 'revenue sharing grants.[]', 'project grants.[]', 'block grants. []', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(287, 'Medicaid and Aid for Families with Dependent Children are examples of[][]', 'categorical grants.[]', 'formula grants.[]', 'state grants.[]', 'block grants. []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(288, 'Grants that are given more or less automatically to states or communities, which havediscretion in deciding how to spend the money are called[][]', 'project grants.[]', 'discretionary grants.[]', 'formula grants.[]', 'block grants. []', 5, 1, 'easy'),
(289, 'A broad program for community development would most likely be supported through a(n)[][]', 'formula grant.[]', 'enterprise zone.[]', 'project grant.[]', 'block grant. []', 5, 2, 'easy'),
(290, 'Which of the following statements about federal block grants is FALSE?[][]', 'Block grants were created to lessen the paperwork and strings attached to many grants-in-aid.[]', 'Congress has established an unlimited number of block grants to support narrowly defined programs.[]', 'States have discretion in deciding how to spend block grant money.[]', 'They provide the states more flexibility in spending. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(291, 'The largest percentage of federal grants to states and localities is in the area of[][]', 'defense.[]', 'health.[]', 'education.[]', 'homeland security. []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(292, 'Expansions of mandated programs by the national government present especially difficultfunding problems for[][]', 'Congress.[]', 'federal taxpayers.[]', 'state and local governments.[]', 'the recipient of the service or program. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(293, 'In 1995, the Republican majority in Congress, in contrast to previous Democratic Congresses,[][]', 'limited the use of unfunded mandates.[]', 'limited the use of block grants.[]', 'avoided funded mandates.[]', 'all of the above []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(294, 'Medicaid is an example of[][]', 'a federal grant program that produces considerable competition between the states.[]', 'a federal grant program that receives little support from the political parties.[]', 'a federal block grant.[]', 'a federal grant program that puts an economic strain on the states.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(295, 'Which of the following is most equitably distributed in America?[][]', 'income[]', 'access to education[]', 'taxes[]', 'federal aid to states and cities []', 5, 3, 'easy'),
(296, 'Which of the following statements is TRUE?[][]', 'Federal grants can put an unwanted financial burden on states.[]', 'Congress decreased funding of Medicaid in the 1980s to relieve state financial burdens.[]', 'States are always seeking increases in grant programs.[]', 'all of the above []', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(297, '________ have usually found the individual state governments to be more sympathetic thanthe national government to their demands.[][]', 'Feminists[]', 'Civil rights advocates[]', 'Business interests[]', 'Supporters of organized labor []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(298, 'Sometimes states tackle problems that are generally considered national problems. This ismost likely to occur when the federal government acts in a way that most state residents donot like. An example of this is[][]', 'state funding for stem cell research in California.[]', 'collecting taxes on purchases made on the Internet.[]', 'restrictions on the chemicals that can be used for developing digital photographs.[]', 'local school board policies about which textbooks are appropriate. []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(299, 'Business interests have traditionally found their demands received most favorably by[][]', 'state governments.[]', 'Congress.[]', 'the president.[]', 'cities. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(300, 'Federalism is advantageous for democracy for each of the following reasons EXCEPT[][]', 'allows for a greater diversity of opinion to be reflected in public policies.[]', 'increases the number of decisions and compromises made at the national level.[]', 'allows more opportunities for political participation.[]', 'allows customization of policies for local needs. []', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(301, 'Federalism contributes to democracy by each of the following ways EXCEPT[][]', 'easing the burdens on the national government so it can function more effectively.[]', 'increasing the opportunities for government to be responsive to demands for policies.[]', 'increasing access to government.[]', 'providing a means for unified public policy. []', 5, 3, 'easy'),
(302, 'As a result of our federal form of government, the death penalty in the United States[][]', 'is mandatory.[]', 'is in violation of the Eighth Amendment.[]', 'is permissible at the federal level, but banned at the state level.[]', 'varies substantially by state.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(303, 'Spending on public education illustrates[][]', 'cooperation between states and federal government for unified policy.[]', 'the advantages of fiscal federalism.[]', 'the diversity in the quality of education among states as a result of federalism.[]', 'advantages of relying on states to supply public services. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(304, 'How many governments are there in the United States?[][]', '538[]', 'over 100,000[]', 'one[]', '50 []', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(305, 'Which of the following statements is FALSE?[][]', 'The federal government has given billions of dollars in subsidies to private industries.[]', 'The national government took a direct interest in economic affairs from the very founding of the republic.[]', 'As the country became more industrialized many interests asked the national government to restrain monopolies and encourage open competition.[]', 'As the country became more industrialized and urbanized, economic interest groups turned to the state governments rather than the federal government for help.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(306, 'Over the last 125 years the people of the United States have turned increasingly to the nationalgovernment to solve problems or provide assistance because[][]', 'the Tenth Amendment gave increased power to the national government.[]', 'a problem or policy often requires the authority and resources of the national government.[]', 'we have a unitary government.[]', 'of persistent corruption in state and local government. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(307, 'America\'s ________ society makes it more sensible to have Social Security administered on anational rather than a state-by-state basis.[][]', 'electronic[]', 'free enterprise[]', 'mobile[]', 'aging []', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(308, 'Today, the national government spends roughly ________ of the gross domestic product.[][]', '15 percent[]', '20 percent[]', '9 percent[]', '44 percent []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(309, 'The proportion of the United States gross national product spent by state and localgovernments has ________ since 1929.[][]', 'increased at a much faster rate compared to the national government[]', 'increased, but not nearly as fast as the national government\'s[]', 'remained steady[]', 'dropped slightly []', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(310, 'Today, roughly ________ of the gross domestic product is spent by state and localgovernments.[][]', '7.5 percent[]', '25 percent[]', '10 percent[]', '1 percent []', 5, 2, 'easy'),
(311, 'Since 1929, the national government\'s share of American governmental expenditures has[][]', 'dropped.[]', 'remained the same.[]', 'approached nearly 100 percent.[]', 'grown rapidly.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(312, 'Today, the national government spends about[][]', 'a tenth of our gross domestic product.[]', 'a half of our gross domestic product.[]', '100 percent of our gross domestic product.[]', 'a fifth of our gross domestic product.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(313, 'Which of the following statements about the state governments is accurate?[][]', 'They carry out virtually all the functions they always have, while the national government has taken on new functions.[]', 'The national government has taken away about half the functions the states used to perform.[]', 'There has been a sharp decrease in the proportion of gross national product spent by states and localities since 1929.[]', 'Their policy functions have nearly been taken over by the national government. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(314, 'Civil liberties are[][]', 'freedoms that are not specified in the Constitution or in statutory laws, but make up the Unwritten Constitution.[]', 'the rights to vote and participate in the political process in a democracy.[]', 'laws that provide and set limits on one\'s freedoms.[]', 'individual legal and constitutional protections against the government. []', 5, 1, 'easy'),
(315, 'Americans ¹ civil liberties are set down in[][]', 'the Declaration of Independence.[]', 'the Bill of Rights.[]', 'no written document or law.[]', 'the Preamble to the Constitution. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(316, 'The ________ is the final interpreter of the content and scope of Americans ¹ civil liberties.[][]', 'president[]', 'Congress[]', 'Supreme Court[]', 'Constitution []', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(317, 'At the time of the ratification of the Constitution,[][]', 'all states had bills of rights but there was no national Bill of Rights.[]', 'there were no bills of rights in the United States.[]', 'both the national government and the states had bills of rights.[]', 'the national government had a Bill of Rights but, there were no state bills of rights. []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(318, 'The Bill of Rights was written and proposed by[][]', 'the United States Supreme Court in 1796.[]', 'the First Congress of the United States in 1789.[]', 'President George Washington in 1789.[]', 'President Thomas Jefferson in 1801. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(319, 'The Bill of Rights was adopted primarily in response to[][]', 'the Spanish Inquisition.[]', 'British abuses of the colonists ¹ civil liberties.[]', 'the horrors of the French Revolution.[]', 'Shays ¹ Rebellion. []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(320, 'Which of the following statements about the Bill of Rights is FALSE?[][]', 'The Bill of Rights was written by the First Congress of the United States.[]', 'The Bill of Rights consists of the first ten amendments to the Constitution.[]', 'Most state constitutions did not have a Bill of Rights at the time of the Constitutional Convention.[]', 'The Constitution of 1787 contained no Bill of Rights. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(321, 'In the case of ________, the Supreme Court ruled that the Bill of Rights restrained only thenational government, not states and cities.[][]', 'Miranda v. Arizona[]', 'Barron v. Baltimore[]', 'Engel v. Vitale[]', 'Gitlow v. New York []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(322, 'The great freedoms of speech, press, religion, and assembly are contained in the[][]', 'First, Second, Third and Fourth Amendments.[]', 'Fourth Amendment.[]', 'Second Amendment.[]', 'First Amendment. []', 5, 3, 'easy'),
(323, 'The Supreme Court decision in Barron v. Baltimore (1833) maintained that the Bill of Rightsintended to prevent[][]', 'both the national and state governments from violating civil rights.[]', 'cities from taking private property without due process.[]', 'only the national government from abridging civil liberties.[]', 'the United States government from granting titles of royalty. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(324, 'Today, ________ apply to the states.[][]', 'all of the Bill of Rights except the First Amendment[]', 'all of the Bill of Rights[]', 'none of the Bill of Rights[]', 'all but five provisions or amendments of the Bill of Rights []', 5, 3, 'easy'),
(325, 'Beginning with the case of ________ in 1925, the Supreme Court began to rule that the Bill ofRights applied directly to the states, as well as to the national government.[][]', 'United States v. Bill of Rights[]', 'Miranda v. Arizona[]', 'Engel v. Vitale[]', 'Gitlow v. New York []', 5, 2, 'easy'),
(326, 'In deciding to incorporate parts of the Bill of Rights into state laws since 1925, the SupremeCourt has relied on the due process clause of the[][]', 'First Amendment.[]', 'Twenty-sixth Amendment.[]', 'Fourteenth Amendment.[]', 'Eighteenth Amendment. []', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(327, 'The ________ includes the clause   Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment ofreligion.  [][]', 'Fifth Amendment[]', 'First Amendment[]', 'Religious Rights Amendment[]', 'Fourteenth Amendment []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(328, 'The incorporation doctrine involves[][]', 'application of the Bill of Rights to the states.[]', 'the procedures for creating a city government.[]', 'the interpretation of the commerce clause.[]', 'the extension of judicial review to state courts. []', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(329, 'Thomas Jefferson argued that the First Amendment created a   wall of separation   between[][]', 'the government and the people.[]', 'the Congress, the president, and the Supreme Court.[]', 'the people and the Supreme Court.[]', 'church and state.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(330, 'Unlike Great Britain and many other nations, the United States does not have an ________church that is officially supported by the government and recognized as a national institution.[][]', 'ecclesiastical[]', 'adjudicated[]', 'imperial[]', 'established []', 5, 1, 'easy'),
(331, 'Today, ________ have (has) an established church that is officially supported by thegovernment.[][]', 'the United States[]', 'no nation[]', 'Great Britain[]', 'both the United States and Great Britain []', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(332, 'In Gitlow v. New York (1925), the decision that states could not abridge the freedoms ofexpression protected by the First Amendment was based on the[][]', 'Fifth Amendment.[]', 'New York State Constitution.[]', 'Fourteenth Amendment.[]', 'exclusionary rule of the judiciary. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(333, 'The significance of Gitlow v. New York (1925) was that[][]', 'a provision of the Bill of Rights was applied to the states for the first time.[]', 'a state constitution had precedence over the United States Constitution within that state.[]', 'the Bill of Rights was interpreted as restraining only the national government and not cities or states.[]', 'the U.S. Constitution has precedence over the state constitution within the state. []', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(334, 'Aid to parochial schools was first passed in the 1960s at the request of[][]', 'Richard M. Nixon.[]', 'Jimmy Carter.[]', 'John F. Kennedy.[]', 'Lyndon Johnson.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(335, 'In Lemon v. Kurtzman, the Supreme Court established that aid to church -related schools mustdo all of the following EXCEPT[][]', 'have a secular purpose.[]', 'inhibit religion.[]', 'not create excessive government entanglement with religion.[]', 'treat all religions equally. []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(336, 'The abridgment of citizens ¹ freedom to worship, or not to worship, as they please is prohibitedby the[][]', 'due process clause.[]', 'establishment clause.[]', 'free exercise clause.[]', 'Second Amendment. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(337, 'In dealing with First Amendment cases involving religion, the Supreme Court has ruled that[][]', 'the Constitution does not protect anti-religious beliefs and practices.[]', 'such questions should be resolved at the state and local levels of government.[]', 'while all religious beliefs are constitutionally protected, all religious practices are not.[]', 'none of the above []', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(338, 'In the Lemon v. Kurtzman decision of 1971, the Supreme Court ruled that[][]', 'any aid of any sort to church-related schools is not constitutional, because it violates church-state separation.[]', 'aid to church-related schools is fully constitutional, and can be used for any purposes needed by the schools.[]', 'spoken prayers in public schools were unconstitutional.[]', 'aid to church-related schools must be for secular purposes only, and cannot be used to advance or inhibit religion.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(339, 'In the Engel v. Vitale case of 1962, the Supreme Court ruled that ________ was (were)unconstitutional.[][]', 'prayers done as classroom exercises in public schools[]', 'segregation[]', 'prior restraint[]', 'police search or seizure without an authorized warrant []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(340, 'The Supreme Court has interpreted the establishment clause of the First Amendment as[][]', 'grounds for denying federal aid to children attending parochial schools.[]', 'merely preventing the establishment of a national church.[]', 'prohibiting school-organized Bible-reading and prayer in public schools.[]', 'all of the above []', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(341, 'In Lemon v. Kurtzman (1971), the Supreme Court ruled that[][]', 'states can prohibit pornography despite the freedom of the press.[]', 'aid to church-related schools must have a secular legislative purpose.[]', 'an official prayer at a public-school graduation violated the constitutional separation of church and state.[]', 'voluntary prayer in public schools is unconstitutional. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(342, 'The Supreme Court has ruled that government aid to church -related schools[][]', 'is acceptable for things such as field trips and teacher salaries, but not for textbooks or transportation to school.[]', 'is permitted when the aid is for a non-religious purpose.[]', 'violates the Establishment Clause.[]', 'does not constitute an establishment of religion. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(343, 'Government aid to religious schools has been a major issue[][]', 'since the Civil War.[]', 'since the colonial era.[]', 'since the mid 1960s.[]', 'since the growth of the fundamentalist movement in the 1980s. []', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(344, 'Which of the following is NOT a free exercise issue?[][]', 'animal sacrifice[]', 'religious use of peyote[]', 'teacher led prayers in public schools[]', 'none of the above []', 3, 3, 'easy'),
(345, 'In 2005, the Supreme Court found that two Kentucky counties violated the establishmentclause of the First Amendment by[][]', 'establishing English as the   official first language of the State of Kentucky.  []', 'by posting the Ten Commandments as a way of promoting religion.[]', 'banning   intelligent design   from the curriculum[]', 'requiring students to say the Pledge of Allegiance. []', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(346, 'During the 1980s, the Supreme Court ________ the displaying of Christmas nativity scenes andHanukkah menorahs on public property.[][]', 'refused to hear cases challenging[]', 'first permitted and then prohibited[]', 'upheld the constitutionality of[]', 'encouraged []', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(347, 'In free exercise cases, the Supreme Court[][]', 'allows the government to interfere with religious practices as long as it is not specifically aimed at religion.[]', 'prohibits prayer in public schools but permits government aid to religious schools.[]', 'prohibits the government from interfering with religious practices.[]', 'never allows the government to interfere with religious practices. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(348, 'In regard to the free exercise clause, the Supreme Court has made each of the following rulingsEXCEPT[][]', 'polygamy may be justified for Mormons on religious grounds.[]', 'Amish parents may take their children out of school after the eighth grade.[]', 'people could become conscientious objectors to war on religious grounds.[]', 'public schools cannot require Jehovah\'s Witnesses to attend flag saluting ceremonies. []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(349, 'Freedom of expression[][]', 'has sometimes been limited when it conflicts with other rights and values.[]', 'is an absolute right protected by the First Amendment.[]', 'includes freedom of speech and press, but not actions.[]', 'would not protect a political rally to attack an opposition candidate\'s stand on issues. []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(350, '________ refers to a government\'s censorship of material before it is published.[][]', 'The exclusionary rule[]', 'Probable cause[]', 'Equal protection[]', 'Prior restraint[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(351, 'In what case did the Supreme Court rule that a newspaper, no matter how outrageous itsopinions, must be allowed to publish without prior restraint?[][]', 'Wisconsin v. Yoder[]', 'Miranda v. Arizona[]', 'Near v. Minnesota[]', 'Mapp v. Ohio []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(352, 'The extent of an individual\'s or group\'s freedom from prior restraint depends on[][]', 'whether the nation is at war.[]', 'nothingî€„it is absolute.[]', 'the moods of the Supreme Court justices.[]', 'who the individual or group is.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(353, 'The Supreme Court has permitted prior restraint of which of the following?[][]', 'high school newspapers[]', 'the Pentagon Papers[]', 'a newspaper that called local officials   Jewish gangsters  []', 'It has permitted prior restraint of all of these. []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(354, 'The Pentagon Papers dealt with[][]', 'a documented history of United States involvement in the Vietnam War which the government wanted kept secret.[]', 'prisoners of war from World War II.[]', 'secret agreements between the United States and the Soviet Union.[]', 'all of the above []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(355, 'Which of the following elements of the Bill of Rights was extended to the states by theSupreme Court case of Near v. Minnesota?[][]', 'freedom of speech[]', 'freedom of the press[]', 'grand jury requirement[]', 'right to privacy []', 2, 2, 'easy'),
(356, 'Time and time again, the Supreme Court has protected freedom of the press by[][]', 'ruling in favor of strict libel laws.[]', 'striking down prior restraint.[]', 'relaxing due process procedures.[]', 'all of the above []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(357, 'The case of Near v. Minnesota (1931)[][]', 'ruled that newspapers could not publish secret information that threatens national security.[]', 'ruled that states cannot prohibit animal sacrifice.[]', 'held that government had illegally issued a prior restraint.[]', 'upheld Minnesota\'s right to close down a newspaper making slanderous remarks. []', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(358, 'Prior restraint is most often considered acceptable on the grounds of[][]', 'libel.[]', 'obscenity.[]', 'national security.[]', 'religious freedom. []', 3, 1, 'easy');
INSERT INTO `gov_easy` (`Qno`, `Question`, `Option1`, `Option2`, `Option3`, `Option4`, `Answer`, `marks`, `Complexity`) VALUES
(359, 'In the case of New York Times v. United States in 1971, the Supreme Court ruled[][]', 'against permitting racy advertisements for massage parlors, saunas, and escort services which could be deemed obscene.[]', 'against prior restraint in the case of the Pentagon Papers, which allowed them to be published.[]', 'in favor of permitting racy advertisements for massage parlors, saunas, and escort services as freedom of speech.[]', 'in favor of prior restraint in order to prevent publication of the Pentagon Papers. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(360, 'In Schenck v. United States (1919), Justice Holmes said that speech can be restricted when it[][]', 'is uttered by government officials in an effort to establish a religion.[]', 'provokes   a clear and present danger   to people.[]', 'is spoken rather than non-verbal or symbolic.[]', 'is expressed on private property. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(361, 'Constitutional protections of free speech are ________ on private property .[][]', 'completely invalidated[]', 'fully protected[]', 'diminished[]', 'unchanged []', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(362, 'A shield law[][]', 'gives reporters the right to withhold information from the courts.[]', 'protects certain religious practices not covered by Supreme Court rulings.[]', 'prevents the courts from closing criminal trials to the press.[]', 'prevents reporters from disclosing secret government information. []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(363, 'The Supreme Court ruled in Branzburg v. Hayes (1972) that in the absence of shield laws,[][]', 'the right of a free trial preempts the reporter\'s right to protect sources.[]', 'that reporters have more rights than other citizens.[]', 'judges can bar cameras from the courtroom.[]', 'none of the above []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(364, 'The principle that   obscenity is not within the area of constitutionally protected speech orpress   was established in[][]', 'Roth v. United States.[]', 'Miller v. California.[]', 'United States v. Snepp.[]', 'Ohio v. Pussycat Theater. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
(365, 'Obscenity is[][]', 'equated with nudity by the Supreme Court.[]', 'clearly defined as it pertains to both freedom of the press and freedom of speech.[]', 'prohibited in the First Amendment.[]', 'not protected under the Constitution. []', 5, 2, 'easy'),
(366, 'In Zurcher v. Stanford Daily, the Supreme Court ruled that[][]', 'the Stanford Daily had complete control over its photograph files.[]', 'the Stanford Daily must cease publication of military strategy papers.[]', 'the Stanford Daily must open its files for use as police evidence.[]', 'the Stanford Daily is controlled by the University president, not state laws. []', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(367, 'In ________, the Court clarified its doctrine of what was obscene, including such gauges aswhether material appealed to merely a prurient interest in sex, and whether it lacked seriousartistic, literary, political or scientific merit.[][]', 'Osborne v. Ohio[]', 'Engel v. Vitale[]', 'Miller v. California[]', 'Federal Communications Commission v. Stern []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(368, 'In Miller v. California (1971), the Court ruled that decisions regarding whether or not materialwas obscene should generally be made by[][]', 'Congress, through statutory law.[]', 'lower federal judges as they see fit, but in conformance with the First Amendment.[]', 'local communities, with some guidelines provided by the Court itself about how to make such judgments.[]', 'individual persons in their own private lives. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(369, 'Miller v. California (1973)[][]', 'achieved a workable definition of legal obscenity.[]', 'abolished pornographic material only when it involved children.[]', 'resulted in uniform state laws regulating obscenity.[]', 'stated that local communities should have more responsibility over deciding what constitutes obscenity.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(370, 'The Communications Decency Act banning obscene material and criminalizing thetransmission of indecent speech or images to anyone under the age of 18 was[][]', 'affirmed by the Court.[]', 'opposed by Christian groups.[]', 'overturned by the Supreme Court.[]', 'none of the above []', 3, 2, 'easy'),
(371, 'At the urging of feminists and conservative Christians, some cities have banned pornographyon the grounds it dehumanizes and endangers women. How have the courts dealt with thesebans?[][]', 'They have upheld them based on the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment.[]', 'They have refused to review them.[]', 'They have struck them down as violations of the First Amendment.[]', 'The courts have been erratic, allowing some ordinances and revoking others. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(372, 'The publication of statements known to be false that are malicious and tend to damage aperson\'s reputation is called[][]', 'obscenity.[]', 'symbolic.[]', 'slander.[]', 'libel.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(373, 'What happened when Jacksonville, Florida, tried to ban movies with nudity in them frombeing shown at drive-in theaters on grounds of obscenity?[][]', 'The Court upheld the ban to protect citizens ¹ rights to privacy.[]', 'The Supreme Court ruled that all nudity cannot be deemed obscene.[]', 'The Court ruled that X-rated movies were protected under the First Amendment.[]', 'a riot []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(374, 'The principle that statements about public figures are libelous only if made with malice andreckless disregard for the truth was established in[][]', 'Texas v. Johnson.[]', 'New York Times v. Sullivan.[]', 'the Anti-Defamation Act of 1952.[]', 'Hustler Magazine v. Falwell. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(375, 'Which of the following statements regarding libel is FALSE?[][]', 'Public figures are protected against libel since publications must prove that what they wrote is true and not malicious.[]', 'Libel laws do inhibit the press to some extent.[]', 'General William Westmoreland failed to prove libel.[]', 'It is more difficult for a public figure than a private individual to win a libel suit. []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(376, 'Wearing an arm band and burning a United States flag are examples of ________: actions thatdo not consist of speaking or writing but that express an opinion.[][]', 'commercial speech[]', 'symbolic speech[]', 'the free exercise clause[]', 'unspoken speech []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(377, 'Symbolic speech[][]', 'consists of speech criticizing the symbols of government.[]', 'cannot be prohibited because it is too vague for government to legislate against.[]', 'has been ruled as disruptive and as a criminal activity.[]', 'consists of action that expresses an opinion.[]', 4, 2, 'easy'),
(378, 'Advertising is considered a form of ________, and, according to the decisions of the SupremeCourt, is subject to greater restrictions on free speech than religious or political speech.[][]', 'symbolic speech[]', 'paid speech[]', 'imaged expression[]', 'commercial speech []', 5, 3, 'easy'),
(379, 'Commercial speech on radio and television is regulated by[][]', 'state and local governments.[]', 'no government agency, as such would be a violation of the freedom of speech.[]', 'the Federal Communications Commission.[]', 'the Federal Trade Commission.[]', 4, 3, 'easy'),
(380, 'One of the most regulated forms of speech is[][]', 'symbolic speech.[]', 'obscenity.[]', 'libel.[]', 'commercial speech. []', 5, 1, 'easy'),
(381, 'In 2000, the Supreme Court ruled that[][]', 'government had a legitimate interest in protecting sexually explicit material on cable stations.[]', 'government had no right to regulate sexually explicit material on cable stations.[]', 'government had a legitimate interest in prohibiting sexually explicit material on cable stations.[]', 'government regulation of sexually explicit material on cable stations must be narrowly tailored to promote the government\'s interest in protecting children.[]', 4, 1, 'easy'),
(382, 'Freedom of assembly includes the right to do all of the following EXCEPT[][]', 'riot.[]', 'protest.[]', 'picket.[]', 'demonstrate. []', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(383, 'In the case of ________, the Supreme Court ruled that requiring an organization to turn overits membership lists was an unconstitutional restriction on freedom of association.[][]', 'Planned Parenthood v. Casey[]', 'NAACP v. Alabama[]', 'Mapp v. Ohio[]', 'United States v. Communist Party []', 2, 1, 'easy'),
(384, 'In the case of NAACP v. Alabama (1958), the Supreme Court ruled that[][]', 'Alabama could not require segregated schools.[]', 'the First Amendment\'s freedom of assembly does not include freedom of association.[]', 'the state of Alabama was unlawfully restricting the NAACP\'s freedom of association.[]', 'the NAACP had to turn over its membership list to the government. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(385, 'Most of the wording of the Bill of Rights concerns[][]', 'the rights of people accused of crimes.[]', 'freedom of religion and the establishment clause.[]', 'freedom of speech and freedom of the press.[]', 'freedoms of expression. []', 1, 1, 'easy'),
