(493, 'In the case of Craig v. Boren, the Supreme Court ruled that[][]', 'sex classifications would be treated by the Court as inherently suspect.[]', 'racial classifications were constitutional if they have a compelling, legitimate, and rational purpose.[]', 'it would employ a   medium scrutiny   standard: sex discrimination would be treated as neither valid nor invalid.[]', 'all sex classifications were unconstitutional. []', 3, 1, 'easy'),
(494, 'The Supreme Court has voided each of the following sexual discrimination laws EXCEPT lawsthat[][]', 'provided for alimony payments to women only.[]', 'made statutory rape a crime for men only.[]', 'closed a state\'s nursing school to men.[]', 'provided child support for women only. []', 2, 3, 'easy'),
(495, 'Which of the following is TRUE?[][]', 'Many sex discrimination cases have involved men seeking equality with women.[]', 'The Supreme Court has so far struck down only a handful of laws for discriminating on the basis of gender.[]', 'All of these are true.[]', 'None of these are true. []', 1, 2, 'easy'),
(496, 'The Equal Rights Amendment failed because[][]', 'it was vetoed by the President.[]', 'the Supreme Court voided it as unconstitutional.[]', 'it did not win the required two-thirds vote in each chamber of Congress.[]', 'it fell three states short of sufficient ratification. []', 5, 2, 'easy'),
(497, 'The ________ banned gender discrimination in employment by law.[][]', 'Civil Rights Act of 1964[]', 'Supreme Court ruling in National Organization for Women v. Bank of America[]', 'Nineteenth Amendment[]', 'Gender Equity Act of 1972 []', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(498, 'Which of the following statements about the Equal Rights Amendment (ERA) is FALSE?[][]', 'The ERA was ratified in 1982.[]', 'The ERA battle stimulated vigorous anti-feminist activity.[]', 'The ERA was first introduced in the 1920s.[]', 'Congress passed the ERA in 1972. []', 1, 3, 'easy'),
(499, 'The United States Supreme Court has handed down each of the following decisionsconcerning gender discrimination in employment and business activity EXCEPT[][]', 'requiring the federal government to give women equal pay for jobs of comparable worth.[]', 'voiding laws and rules barring women from jobs through arbitrary height and weight requirements.[]', 'protecting women from being required to take mandatory pregnancy leaves from their jobs.[]', 'None of the above; the court has handed down each of the decisions above. []', 1, 1, 'easy');
INSERT INTO `gov_hard` (`Qno`, `Question`, `Option1`, `Option2`, `Option3`, `Option4`, `Answer`, `marks`, `Complexity`) VALUES
(1, 'Over the last five decades, voting based primarily on party identification has[][]', 'completely disappeared.[]', 'declined sharply.[]', 'increased.[]', 'increased sharply. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(2, 'Research by Rosenberg and McCafferty discovered that[][]', 'a candidate\'s image and appearance is the most important factor in how a person votes.[]', 'less educated voters are more likely to view candidates in terms of their personal attributes.[]', 'it is possible to manipulate a candidate\'s appearance in a way that affects voters ¹ choices.[]', 'none of the above []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(3, 'Which of these is the least important dimension of a candidate\'s image?[][]', 'intelligence[]', 'reliability[]', 'competence[]', 'experience []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(4, '________ occurs when people base their choices in an election on their own issue preferences.[][]', 'Civic duty[]', 'Suffrage[]', 'Retrospective voting[]', 'Policy voting[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(5, 'A voter supporting a candidate based specifically on comparing the candidate\'s stances on theissues of abortion rights, health care, and government aid to education to the voter\'s ownpreferences on such issues is an example of[][]', 'retrospective voting.[]', 'policy voting.[]', 'initiative.[]', 'agenda setting. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(6, 'Research has found that those most likely to view the candidates in terms of their personalattributes are[][]', 'minority voters.[]', 'college-educated voters.[]', 'women voters.[]', 'non-voters. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(7, 'Which of the following is TRUE about the electoral college?[][]', 'On very rare occasions, an elector has voted differently from the popular vote winner of his state.[]', 'It is used in nearly half of the democratic nations around the world.[]', 'An elector has never voted differently from the popular vote winner of his state.[]', 'none of the above []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(8, 'As provided in the Constitution, how are electoral votes allocated for each state?[][]', 'Each state has as many electoral votes as it has members in the House of Representatives.[]', 'Each state has as many electoral votes as it has members in both the House and the Senate.[]', 'Each state has as many electoral votes as it has members in the Senate.[]', 'Each state casts two electoral votes. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(9, 'If no candidate receives an electoral college majority,[][]', 'a runoff election is held nationwide between the top two vote-getters.[]', 'the candidate with the plurality of electoral votes is automatically elected.[]', 'the House of Representatives chooses among the top three electoral vote winners.[]', 'Congress is free to elect the president. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(10, 'Except in Maine and Nebraska, the electoral college system operates in each state on theprinciple of allocating electoral votes on the basis of[][]', 'winner-take-all.[]', 'allocating electoral votes based on the winner in each congressional district.[]', 'a mixture of winner-take-all and proportional representation.[]', 'majority rule. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(11, 'Which of the following statements about the electoral college is FALSE? w[][]', 'Each state has as many electoral votes as it has United States senators and representatives.[]', 'Every state has a winner-take-all system where electors vote as a bloc for the winner.[]', 'If no candidate receives an electoral majority, then the election is thrown into the House of Representatives.[]', 'Some states have a winner take all system where electors vote as a bloc for the winner. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(12, 'If a presidential candidate does not receive a majority of electoral college votes, then thepresident is chosen[][]', 'by popular vote.[]', 'by the Justices of the Supreme Court.[]', 'by the House with one vote for each state.[]', 'by majority vote of the entire Congress in a joint session. []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(13, 'Research on voting behavior has shown that[][]', 'policy voting has become somewhat easier than in the past.[]', 'Americans tend to identify with the underdog.[]', 'party identification has become more important in voting decisions.[]', 'policy voting has become harder than in the past. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(14, 'Which is FALSE regarding the electoral college?[][]', 'Whoever wins the most votes in the electoral college wins, even if that isn ¹t a majority.[]', 'Electors can vote for whomever they want, regardless of how their state\'s voters voted.[]', 'In most states ALL the electors vote for whomever won the most votes in their state, even if that wasn ¹t a majority.[]', 'The electors themselves are selected by state parties. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(15, 'The greater the policy differences between the candidates,[][]', 'the closer the election.[]', 'the more likely voters will be able to steer government policies by their choices.[]', 'the more likely voters will make choices based on personality traits.[]', 'the higher the voter turnout in the election. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(16, 'In ________, incumbents who provide desired results are rewarded; those who fail to do so arepunished.[][]', 'indirect primaries[]', 'initiatives[]', 'referendums[]', 'retrospective voting[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(17, 'If engaged in retrospective voting, an individual would ask:[][]', 'What have you done for me lately?[]', 'Who is the more attractive candidate?[]', 'Why should I vote at all?[]', 'Who will be lowering taxes? []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(18, 'When President Herbert Hoover and the Republicans were crushed in the election of 1932,voters were responding to the severity of the Great Depression under Hoover\'s presidency by[][]', 'retrospective voting.[]', 'direct primary voting.[]', 'initiative.[]', 'irrational choice voting. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(19, 'The type of public policy that seems to have the greatest effect on elections today is[][]', 'foreign policy.[]', 'social policy.[]', 'economic policy.[]', 'racial policies. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(20, 'Elections have a tendency to expand the scope of government because[][]', 'so many people become involved in the process.[]', 'voters like to feel that they are sending a message to government to accomplish something.[]', 'elections open opportunities for more government employment.[]', 'because they are so expensive to conduct. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(21, 'While the threat of electoral punishment constrains policymakers, it also helps to increasegeneralized support for[][]', 'the private sector.[]', 'individualistic, rather than, collective policy solutions.[]', 'government and its powers.[]', 'unelected government officials in the bureaucracy. []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(22, 'The case involving Eli Lilly and Company illustrates how[][]', 'little influence special interests actually have on Congress.[]', 'special interests can still bribe members of Congress.[]', 'special interests ¹ campaign contributions can influence congressional action.[]', 'the increasing importance of multinational corporations. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(23, 'According to James Madison in Federalist Paper No. 1, the way to prevent any one group fromhaving too much power is to[][]', 'eliminate most groups.[]', 'increase the scope and number of groups.[]', 'make them unconstitutional.[]', 'none of the above []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(24, 'Since the 1960s, the number of interest groups has[][]', 'remained constant.[]', 'risen rapidly.[]', 'declined sharply.[]', 'fluctuated up and down as new issues developed and others faded away. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(25, 'The right of interest groups to organize is[][]', 'protected by the Constitution.[]', 'protected by the Federal Election Campaign Act.[]', 'protected by state laws.[]', 'protected by the Bill of Rights.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(26, 'An organization of people with similar policy goals entering the political process to try toachieve those aims is called[][]', 'a political party.[]', 'a political action committee.[]', 'an interest group.[]', 'a political corporation. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(27, 'Which of the following is NOT typical of American interest groups?[][]', 'They frequently look to the bureaucracy or the judicial process to achieve their policy goals.[]', 'They run their own slate of candidates for office in many parts of the country.[]', 'Unlike political parties, they are not faced with the constraint of trying to appeal to everyone.[]', 'They mostly represent diffuse, non-economic interests. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(28, 'American political parties differ from interest groups in that parties[][]', 'are policy specialists.[]', 'are policy generalists.[]', 'do not take positions on policy issues.[]', 'have a narrower scope than interest groups. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(29, 'One of the main differences between American political parties and interest groups is that[][]', 'interest groups are concerned with more issues.[]', 'interest groups concentrate on only one policy arena.[]', 'political parties run candidates for office.[]', 'political parties are policy specialists. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(30, 'An interest group is more likely to form its own political party where[][]', 'voters choose their legislators in single-member districts.[]', 'voters choose their legislators in dual-member districts.[]', 'voters choose their legislators using proportional representation.[]', 'there is a strong two-party system, and the major parties ignore their demands. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(31, 'According to ________ theorists, interest groups compete and counterbalance one another inthe political marketplace.[][]', 'elitist[]', 'hyperelitist[]', 'pluralist[]', 'free market []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(32, 'Which of the following statements is FALSE?[][]', 'With proportional representation systems, all it takes is between one and five percent of the vote for a party to win seats in the national legislature.[]', 'In many Scandinavian countries, farmers ¹ parties have long been in existence.[]', 'Many new interest groups in Europe have formed parties on the basis of shared values.[]', 'Green parties in Europe have never been able to win enough votes to enter the national legislature.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(33, 'The successes of civil rights and women\'s rights groups in redirecting the course of publicpolicy, once they were organized, is pointed to as evidence to support the ________ theory thatAmerican politics is open and not a problem.[][]', 'pluralist[]', 'elite[]', 'hyperelitist[]', 'free market []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(34, 'The group theory of politics offered by pluralist theorists argues all of the following EXCEPT[][]', 'groups provide a key link between people and government.[]', 'no one group is likely to become too dominant.[]', 'groups are all of equal strength.[]', 'different groups win at different times. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(35, 'The idea that just a few groups have all the power is associated with[][]', 'elite theory.[]', 'hyperpluralist theory.[]', 'democratic theory.[]', 'syndicalism. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(36, 'The idea that interest group activity brings representation to all is associated with[][]', 'elite theory.[]', 'pluralist theory.[]', 'democratic theory.[]', 'republicanism. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(37, 'Which of the following theories offers the most positive interpretation of the effect of interestgroups on American democracy?[][]', 'pluralist[]', 'elite[]', 'hyperelitist[]', 'free market []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(38, 'Pluralists argue that lobbying[][]', 'is dominated by wealthy corporations and the wealthiest individuals and is a danger to the democratic system.[]', 'is open to all and is therefore not to be regarded as a problem.[]', 'must be suspended until tighter regulations can be put into place to protect the public interest.[]', 'has no effect on policymaking. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(39, '________ theorists are impressed by how insignificant most organized interest groups are.[][]', 'Pluralist[]', 'Hyperpluralist[]', 'Elitist[]', 'Deconstruction []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(40, 'The ________ theorists argue that the power of the few is fortified by an extensive system ofinterlocking directorates, and that wealthy corporations prevail when it comes to majordecisions by government.[][]', 'pluralist[]', 'hyperpluralist[]', 'elitist[]', 'pyramid []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(41, 'The presence and power of multinational corporations illustrates[][]', 'elite theory.[]', 'pluralist theory.[]', 'hyperpluralist theory.[]', 'global unity theory. []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(42, 'Elite theorists emphasize the power of[][]', 'subgovernments.[]', 'business leaders.[]', 'public interest lobbies.[]', 'presidents. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(43, 'Interest group liberalism is criticized especially by ________ theorists.[][]', 'pluralist[]', 'hyperpluralist[]', 'hyperelitist[]', 'social-conservative []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(44, 'Interest group liberalism is promoted by[][]', 'ideologically liberal interest groups and not conservative groups.[]', 'one group winning and another losing in the competition for government action or funding.[]', 'subgovernments.[]', 'all of the above []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(45, 'The criticism that government refuses to make tough choices between X or Y, insteadpretending there is no need to choose and trying to favor both is most often made by ________theorists.[][]', 'pluralist[]', 'hyperpluralist[]', 'hyperelitist[]', 'rational choice []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(46, 'The idea that too many groups are getting too much of what they want is associated with[][]', 'elite theory.[]', 'pluralist theory.[]', 'hyperpluralist theory.[]', 'proliferation theory. []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(47, 'All subgovernments have the same goal[][]', 'protecting the public interest.[]', 'attacking the government head-on.[]', 'protecting their self-interest.[]', 'to join the main government. []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(48, 'Subgovernments are composed of key interest group leaders interested in policy X, thegovernment agency in charge of administering policy X, and the ________ handling policy X.[][]', 'congressional committees and subcommittees[]', 'public relations officers[]', 'political candidates[]', 'local governments []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(49, 'Which of the following is NOT one of the major elements of the subgovernment system at thenational level?[][]', 'interest group[]', 'congressional committee[]', 'federal court[]', 'bureaucrats []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(50, 'A hyperpluralist interpretation of group politics would maintain that[][]', 'groups weak in one resource can substitute other resources to influence policy decisions.[]', 'groups have become so powerful that government ends up aiding every possible interest.[]', 'groups provide a key linkage between people and government.[]', 'All of these are true. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(51, 'Which of the following ideas is NOT associated with hyperpluralism?[][]', 'Groups have become too powerful in the political process.[]', 'Interest group liberalism is aggravated by numerous subgovernments.[]', 'Trying to please every group results in contradictory and confusing policy.[]', 'Political power is highly concentrated.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(52, 'A(n) ________ group is composed of all people who might be group members because theyshare some common interest.[][]', 'potential[]', 'actual[]', 'single-issue[]', 'latent []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(53, 'The free-rider problem refers to[][]', 'unrelated amendments being added to a piece of legislation in order to bypass usual procedures.[]', 'potential members of a group failing to join the actual group, as they know they will receive the same benefits whether they are active members or not.[]', 'mass transit scofflaws who endanger government aid to subways, buses, and commuter trains by not being officially counted.[]', 'welfare fraud and the costs it imposes on government and taxpayers. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(54, 'Part of Olson\'s Law of Large Groups is the argument that[][]', 'the larger the potential group, the less likely potential members are to contribute.[]', 'potential group size does not have any measurable affect on the willingness of potential members to contribute.[]', 'an actual group and a potential group are virtually the same when it comes to effectiveness.[]', 'the smaller the group the less likely the potential members are to contribute. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(55, 'According to Olson\'s Law of Large Groups,[][]', 'the larger the group, the further it will fall short of providing an optimal amount of a collective good.[]', 'the more levels of authority within a group, the more faith its members will have in it.[]', 'the more levels of authority within a group, the less faith its members will have in it.[]', 'the larger the group, the more likely it is to win. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(56, '________ helps to explain why public interest lobbies have relatively small proportions ofactual members.[][]', 'The free-rider problem[]', 'The rise of political action committees[]', 'Tougher regulation of all lobbyists[]', 'Olson\'s Law of Large Groups []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(57, 'According to Olson\'s Law of Large Groups,[][]', 'the larger the group, the more effective it will be.[]', 'the smaller the group, the more effective it will be.[]', 'all groups have a life cycle of birth, growth, maintenance, and decline, although many never decline completely.[]', 'large groups are more democratic. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(58, 'Consumer organizations suffer from[][]', 'amicus curiae briefs.[]', 'class action suits.[]', 'Olson\'s Law of Large Groups.[]', 'hyperpluralism. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(59, 'The biggest obstacle to the effectiveness of large groups is the[][]', 'difficulty of finding effective leadership.[]', 'problem of raising funds and attracting government support.[]', 'discrepancy between potential and actual membership.[]', 'government regulations on lobbying activities. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(60, 'All people who might be group members because they share some common interest make up[][]', 'an actual group.[]', 'a potential group.[]', 'an interest group.[]', 'a probable group. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(61, 'Which of the following groups has the largest potential membership?[][]', 'National Association for the Advancement of Colored People[]', 'National Organization for Women[]', 'Air Transport Association of America[]', 'American Political Science Association []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(62, 'Which of the following groups claims the smallest share of its potential members?[][]', 'National Consumers League[]', 'Tobacco Institute[]', 'Air Transport Association[]', 'American Medical Association []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(63, 'A   collective good   refers to[][]', 'goods and services that are publicly owned.[]', 'benefits that accrue to the group that sought them.[]', 'something of value that benefits both the actual and potential members of a group.[]', 'goods and services collected for the needy. []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(64, 'An example of a collective good is[][]', 'food.[]', 'employment.[]', 'clean air.[]', 'all of the above []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(65, 'The free-rider problem refers to the difficulty of[][]', 'small groups in raising enough money to influence policy.[]', 'groups in organizing all their potential members.[]', 'potential groups in receiving their share in collective goods.[]', 'all taxpayers having to pay for public services and payments that go only to the poor. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(66, 'According to Mancur Olson, small interest groups generally are ________ compared to allother groups.[][]', 'insignificant[]', 'incoherent[]', 'less focused[]', 'more democratic []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(67, 'An advantage of single-issue groups is their[][]', 'financial resources.[]', 'pool of potential members.[]', 'pool of actual members.[]', 'intensity.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(68, 'A single-issue group is one that is all of the following EXCEPT[][]', 'focused on narrow interest.[]', 'unable to compromise.[]', 'organizes on the national level only.[]', 'intensely committed to a policy goal. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(69, 'Single-issue groups[][]', 'include members with narrow, uncompromising interests.[]', 'mainly focus on the issue of abortion.[]', 'are not taken seriously because they lack a large constituency.[]', 'tend to focus on their specific economic interest rather than on collective social issues. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(70, 'Single-issue group politics has been especially emotional over the issue of[][]', 'consumerism.[]', 'equality.[]', 'abortion.[]', 'affirmative action. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(71, 'One of the major inducements of the American interest group system is that it[][]', 'provides too much representation.[]', 'distracts government officials.[]', 'is biased toward the wealthy.[]', 'is dominated by single-issue groups. []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(72, 'By 2000, the number of groups listed in the Encyclopedia of Associations was over[][]', '5,000.[]', '1,000.[]', '10,000.[]', '20,000.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(73, 'Which of the following statements about interest groups is FALSE?[][]', 'The majority of groups now have their headquarters in Washington, D.C.[]', 'There are an enormous number of highly specialized and seemingly trivial groups.[]', 'Almost every group has a staff and publications.[]', 'The growth rate of interest groups has slowed in recent years.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(74, 'Technological improvements in communication have caused interest groups to[][]', 'consolidate.[]', 'sharply increase in number.[]', 'move out of Washington, D.C.[]', 'form broad coalitions to expand their clout. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(75, '________ is a communication by someone other than a citizen acting on his or her own behalf,directed to a government decision maker, particularly in the legislative and executive branch,with the hope of influencing his or her decision.[][]', 'Electioneering[]', 'An amicus curiae brief[]', 'Lobbying[]', 'Campaigning []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(76, 'Three basic strategies employed by interest groups are all of the following EXCEPT[][]', 'lobbying.[]', 'implementation.[]', 'litigation.[]', 'going public. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(77, 'Which of the following is NOT one of the basic interest group strategies in America?[][]', 'lobbying[]', 'running candidates for office[]', 'electioneering[]', 'implementation []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(78, 'A   communication by someone other than a citizen acting on his or her own behalf, directed toa governmental decision maker with the hope of influencing his or her decision   is a definitionof[][]', 'campaigning.[]', 'lobbying.[]', 'litigation.[]', 'a policy output. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(79, 'Which of the following is NOT a way in which a lobbyist can help a member of Congress?[][]', 'obtaining group support for the politician\'s reelection[]', 'introducing legislation in Congress[]', 'helping with political strategy[]', 'assisting with the cost of traveling between their home district and Washington, D.C. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(80, 'According to the text, one of the most common function of lobbyists is to[][]', 'provide information and ideas to members of Congress.[]', 'convert members of Congress to the point of view the lobbyists represent.[]', 'actually introduce new legislation.[]', 'raise funds for preferred political candidates. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(81, 'The text identifies two types of lobbyists,[][]', 'full-time employees and consultants.[]', 'attorneys and non-attorneys.[]', 'those based in Washington, D.C., and those based elsewhere.[]', '  old school   and   modern style   lobbyists. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(82, 'Many interest groups involve themselves in ________ to help get those they consider to be theright people into office or to keep them there.[][]', 'lobbying[]', 'electioneering[]', 'policymaking[]', 'recruitment []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(83, 'Lobbyists provide members of Congress all of the following EXCEPT[][]', 'help with accomplishing their legislative goals.[]', 'information.[]', 'campaign strategy and organizational help.[]', 'None of the above; lobbyists provide all of the above to members of Congress. []', 5, 1, 'hard'),
(84, 'According to the text, the least effective activity of lobbyists in Congress is[][]', 'contributing to campaigns.[]', 'providing information.[]', 'activating members of Congress to vote on legislation.[]', 'converting members of Congress to the lobbyists ¹ positions.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(85, 'According to the text, lobbying works best[][]', 'with people who are undecided about a policy.[]', 'when large amounts of money are involved.[]', 'on people already committed to the lobbyist\'s policy position.[]', 'when the lobbyist starts crying and pleading. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(86, 'Political action committee (PAC) money goes overwhelmingly to[][]', 'Independents.[]', 'challengers.[]', 'incumbents.[]', 'Republicans. []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(87, 'Political Action Committees are primarily a means used by interest groups for[][]', 'lobbying.[]', 'electioneering.[]', 'policymaking.[]', 'political action. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(88, 'Interest groups seeking to exert influence on the electoral process can honestly and openlyfunnel money into the campaign coffers of their supporters through[][]', 'lobbying.[]', 'electioneering.[]', 'Political Action Committees.[]', 'electronic banking. []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(89, 'Most PAC money goes overwhelmingly to incumbents because incumbents[][]', 'need more money due to the restraints of being in office.[]', 'have already been   bought off   by interest groups.[]', 'have already become friends and supporters of lobbyists.[]', 'are the most likely to be able to return the investment.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(90, 'Which of the following is NOT true about Political Action Committees?[][]', 'There are far more PACs now than there were in 1974.[]', 'Most PAC money goes to challengers rather than incumbents.[]', 'Only a handful of candidates have completely resisted the lure of PAC money.[]', 'PACs contribute before and after elections. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(91, 'The most successful tactic that civil rights and environmental groups have used to influencepolicy is[][]', 'litigation.[]', 'lobbying.[]', 'media advertising.[]', 'protest demonstrations. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(92, '________ are written arguments submitted to the courts in support of one side of a case.[][]', 'Class action lawsuits[]', 'Litigations[]', 'Amicus curiae briefs[]', 'Opening arguments []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(93, 'Literally, amicus curiae means[][]', 'legal opinion.[]', 'legal argument.[]', 'friend of the court.[]', 'let the decision stand. []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(94, '________ enables a group of similarly situated plaintiffs to combine similar grievances into asingle suit.[][]', 'An amicus curiae brief[]', 'A public interest suit[]', 'Olson\'s Law of Large Groups[]', 'A class action lawsuit[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(95, 'Flight attendants won a(n) ________ against the airline industry\'s regulation that allstewardesses had to be unmarried.[][]', 'amicus curiae brief[]', 'writ of habeas corpus[]', 'bill of attainder[]', 'class action lawsuit[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(96, 'In   going public   interest groups[][]', 'extend membership to a broader range of people.[]', 'use advertising and public relations to enhance their image.[]', 'issue stock.[]', 'open their decision-making meetings to the general public. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(97, 'Which of the following statements about interest groups going public is FALSE?[][]', 'Interest groups carefully cultivate their public images.[]', 'Interest groups market not only their stand on issues but their reputations as well.[]', 'More and more organizations have launched expensive public relations efforts.[]', 'The public relations of most groups tend to be characterized by hard sell and bias.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(98, 'Which of the following statements is FALSE?[][]', 'In the American economy, government directly determines wages, prices, and profits.[]', 'Even a minor change in government regulatory policy can cost industries a great deal or bring increased profits.[]', 'How the tax code is written determines whether people and producers pay a lot or a little of their incomes to the government.[]', 'B and D only []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(99, 'Economic groups[][]', 'are those which require individuals to pay dues to be members.[]', 'consist only of corporations, rather than individuals, as members.[]', 'are those groups interested in wages, prices, and profits.[]', 'are those groups that provide information to Congress. []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(100, 'Right-to-work laws are most strongly supported by[][]', 'unemployed citizens.[]', 'business groups.[]', 'the feminist and civil rights movements.[]', 'illegal immigrants. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(101, 'The union shop[][]', 'serves as the headquarters of an organized labor group.[]', 'sells only goods made by laborers affiliated with a union.[]', 'requires that all employees in a unionized business join the union.[]', 'both B and D []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
