(327, 'Changes in presidential approval levels appear to be due primarily to[][]', 'the president\'s personality.[]', 'how the media treat the president.[]', 'the financial elites ¹ responses to presidential policies.[]', 'the public\'s evaluation of how the president is handling policy areas.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(328, '  Rally events  [][]', 'are specific and dramatic events that relate to international relations, directly involving the United States and the president.[]', 'involve economic upsurges that dramatically increase presidential popularity.[]', 'have no effect on presidential popularity even though presidents use them for that purpose.[]', 'occur frequently during a president\'s administration. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(329, 'The surge in President George Bush\'s approval ratings during and immediately following theGulf War in 1991 was an example of[][]', 'the bandwagon effect.[]', 'a rally event.[]', 'presidential coattails.[]', 'a pocket veto. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(330, 'The ultimate weapon in the president\'s arsenal of resources to influence Congress is probably[][]', 'media support.[]', 'interest group support.[]', 'her/his fundraising ability.[]', 'mobilization of the public.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(331, 'Presidential press conferences[][]', 'give the president a chance to be spontaneous.[]', 'have not been used since the Nixon administration.[]', 'are not very useful means of eliciting information.[]', 'are small, intimate meetings with the president. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(332, 'The president\'s ________ serves as the principal conduit of information from the White Houseto the press on a daily basis.[][]', 'press secretary[]', 'Chief of Staff[]', 'Secretary of Information[]', 'Domestic Policy Advisor []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(333, 'The individual who conducts daily press briefings and serves as a conduit of information fromthe White House is the[][]', 'National Security Advisor.[]', 'Minister of Information.[]', 'president\'s secretary.[]', 'press secretary. []', 5, 3, 'hard'),
(334, 'Most of the news coverage of the White House[][]', 'is class analysis that seeks to explain which socio-economic groups are benefiting from or being injured by the latest policies.[]', 'focuses on the most visible layer of presidents ¹ personal and official activities.[]', 'is concerned with the substance of policies.[]', 'is concerned with foreign policy issues. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(335, 'A large number of studies have concluded that the news media are[][]', 'moderately biased toward liberal ideology.[]', 'not biased on any systematic basis, and the news is typically characterized by neutrality.[]', 'strongly biased toward the Democrats.[]', 'slightly biased toward the Republicans. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(336, 'News coverage of presidents and their activities[][]', 'usually focuses on the personality of the president.[]', 'is not systematically biased in any direction.[]', 'has a heavy liberal bias.[]', 'is typically unfavorable toward the White House. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(337, 'Which of the following statements about the presidency and democracy is FALSE?[][]', 'There is little prospect of the presidency being a threat to democracy.[]', 'From the time the Constitution was written there has been a fear that the presidency would degenerate into a monarchy.[]', 'Concerns over presidential power are generally closely related to policy views.[]', 'Concerns about a tyrannical presidency were prevalent in the Reagan administration due to his ability to impose his will on Congress.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(338, 'A budget deficit occurs when expenditures exceed[][]', 'revenues.[]', 'appropriations.[]', 'authorizations.[]', 'inflation. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(339, 'Most of today\'s federal debt was run up by government borrowing during[][]', 'World War II.[]', 'the 1980s.[]', 'the Great Depression.[]', 'the Cold War (1947-1989). []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(340, 'Approximately what percentage of the annual federal budget pays interest on the nationaldebt?[][]', '13[]', '15[]', '21[]', '9[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(341, 'Which of the following is NOT currently one of the major sources of federal revenue?[][]', 'personal income taxes[]', 'social insurance taxes[]', 'borrowing[]', 'excise taxes[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(342, 'A(n) ________ is a policy document allocating taxes and expenditures, or a series of goals withprice tags attached.[][]', 'balance sheet[]', 'procurement[]', 'fiscal register[]', 'budget []', 5, 1, 'hard'),
(343, 'A budget is[][]', 'a blueprint for what the government should do.[]', 'a policy determination of how much to spend.[]', 'a policy document allocating burdens (taxes) and benefits (expenditures).[]', 'none of the above []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(344, 'Congress was officially given the power to levy an income tax through the[][]', 'Sixteenth Amendment.[]', 'revenue clause of the original Constitution.[]', 'Internal Revenue Act.[]', 'Balanced Budget Amendment. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(345, 'Which of the following is NOT the responsibility of the Internal Revenue Service?[][]', 'investigating and prosecuting thousands of errant taxpayers or nonpayers of federal taxes[]', 'establishing the annual tax rates that Americans of different incomes must pay[]', 'collecting the federal income tax[]', 'All of these are the IRS\'s responsibilities. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(346, 'Income taxes[][]', 'provide the largest source of federal revenue.[]', 'were declared constitutional in Pollock v. Farmer\'s Loan and Trust Co.[]', 'yield about 11 cents of every federal revenue dollar.[]', 'All of these are true. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(347, 'In order of decreasing amounts, the sources of federal revenue include[][]', 'individual income tax, excise tax, corporate income tax, and social insurance receipts.[]', 'individual income tax, social insurance receipts, borrowing and corporate income tax.[]', 'corporate income taxes, personal income taxes, borrowing and social insurance taxes.[]', 'borrowing, individual income tax, social insurance receipts, and corporate income tax. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(348, 'Corporations today pay[][]', 'income taxes which account for most federal revenue.[]', 'income taxes which account for more federal revenue than individual income taxes.[]', 'income taxes which account for much less federal revenue than individual income taxes.[]', 'capital gains taxes and property taxes instead of income taxes. []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(349, 'The income tax is generally progressive, meaning that[][]', 'it increases incrementally on an annual basis.[]', 'those with more income pay higher rates of tax on their income.[]', 'it is a newer form of taxation than excise and sales taxes.[]', 'it is better than a flat tax. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(350, 'Social Security taxes are[][]', 'paid for by employees and employers.[]', 'paid for by employers only.[]', 'taxes paid on Social Security benefits.[]', 'levied and collected by state governments. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(351, 'Social insurance taxes[][]', 'are earmarked for a specific purpose.[]', 'go into the government\'s general money fund.[]', 'are paid only by employers.[]', 'all of the above []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(352, 'The fastest growing source of federal revenue has been[][]', 'fees for services.[]', 'Social Security taxes.[]', 'borrowing.[]', 'corporate income taxes. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(353, 'The government borrows money principally by[][]', 'selling bonds.[]', 'printing more currency.[]', 'obtaining loans from foreign governments.[]', 'obtaining loans from the Federal Reserve. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(354, 'Who can purchase United States government bonds?[][]', 'financial institutions[]', 'citizens[]', 'corporations[]', 'all of the above []', 5, 1, 'hard'),
(355, 'The federal debt[][]', 'consists of all the money borrowed over the years by the national government and still outstanding.[]', 'is all money borrowed over the years by the federal government and owed to state governments.[]', 'is the difference between the amount of annual tax receipts and government expenditures.[]', 'is money owed by taxpayers to the United States government, but never paid. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(356, 'The federal debt in the United States[][]', 'is the difference between federal government revenues and expenditures in a given year.[]', 'has increased due to the budget deficit caused by the difference between revenues and expenditures.[]', 'consists of the interest that government must pay on the budget deficit.[]', 'is just under $1,000,000,000. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(357, 'Unlike state and local governments, the federal government is borrowing primarily for[][]', 'its day-to-day expenses.[]', 'military defense.[]', 'printing money.[]', 'its capital needs. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(358, '________ are revenue losses attributable to provisions of the federal tax laws which allow aspecial exemption, exclusion, or deduction.[][]', 'Tax dividends[]', 'Fiscal seepages[]', 'Treasury bills[]', 'Tax expenditures []', 5, 2, 'hard'),
(359, 'Tax expenditures consist of[][]', 'the way taxes are spent by the federal government.[]', 'tax exemptions, deductions, and exclusions.[]', 'direct grants-in-aid to individuals by the government.[]', 'the amount of deficit caused by revenue shortfalls. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(360, 'The federal income tax deduction for mortgage interest on an owner -occupied home is anexample of a[][]', 'tax rebate.[]', 'negative income tax.[]', 'federally guaranteed loan.[]', 'tax expenditure.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(361, 'An example of a tax expenditure is[][]', 'a lower tax rate for lower income families.[]', 'direct government support of a charity.[]', 'the social security system.[]', 'a tax deduction for the mortgage interest paid by homeowners.[]', 4, 2, 'hard');
INSERT INTO `gov_hard` (`Qno`, `Question`, `Option1`, `Option2`, `Option3`, `Option4`, `Answer`, `marks`, `Complexity`) VALUES
(362, 'The Office of Management and Budget estimates that the total tax expenditures is more than________ of the federal government\'s total receipts.[][]', '30 percent[]', '25 percent[]', '40 percent[]', '50 percent []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(363, 'Tax expenditures tend to most benefit[][]', 'lower-income people and the poor.[]', 'lower-middle class people and small businesses.[]', 'the government.[]', 'middle- and upper-income people and corporations.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(364, 'Which of the following statements about President Reagan\'s 1981 tax cut is FALSE?[][]', 'Taxes were indexed to the cost of living.[]', 'Corporate taxes were increased.[]', 'It provided new tax incentives for personal saving and investment.[]', 'none of the above []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(365, 'Which of the following statements about President Reagan\'s 1981 tax cut is TRUE?[][]', 'It reduced the federal government\'s tax expenditures.[]', 'It provided new tax incentives for personal saving and investment.[]', 'It led to a major reduction in the federal deficits.[]', 'It helped curb inflation. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(366, 'Which of the following was NOT a provision of President Reagan\'s 1985 tax simplificationprogram?[][]', 'It removed several million low-income individuals from the tax rolls.[]', 'It eliminated or reduced the value of many tax deductions.[]', 'It increased the number of tax expenditures available to businesses.[]', 'none of the above []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(367, 'Beginning in 1985, federal income taxes were ________ to the cost of living, so thatgovernment no longer got a larger percentage when inflation pushed incomes into higherbrackets while the tax rates stayed the same.[][]', 'raised[]', 'added[]', 'indexed[]', 'flat-rated []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(368, 'President Reagan\'s 1981 tax cuts were most beneficial to[][]', 'low-income families.[]', 'the middle class.[]', 'the government.[]', 'high-income families.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(369, 'In 1993, Congress agreed to President Clinton\'s proposal to[][]', 'cut Social Security expenditures.[]', 'decrease the top corporate income tax rate.[]', 'raise the income tax rate for families in the highest income brackets.[]', 'establish national health insurance []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(370, 'The United States government\'s annual budget is now approximately[][]', '$2.75 trillion.[]', '$775 billion.[]', '$12 trillion.[]', '$11.3 trillion. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(371, 'Compared to most other countries with developed economies, the national, state, and localgovernments in the United States tax[][]', 'about twice as heavily.[]', 'about one and a half times as much per capita.[]', 'about four times as heavily.[]', 'less.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(372, 'Which of the following countries have the smallest total tax revenues as a percentage of theirgross domestic product?[][]', 'Sweden[]', 'Canada[]', 'Germany[]', 'United States[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(373, 'The federal budget consumes ________ of America\'s gross domestic product.[][]', '20 percent[]', '30 percent[]', '50 percent[]', '12 percent []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(374, 'In order of decreasing amounts, federal expenditures include[][]', 'national defense, interest on the national debt, and direct payments to individuals.[]', 'interest on the national debt, national defense, and direct payments to individuals.[]', 'national defense, direct payments to individuals, and state and local grants.[]', 'none of the above []', 5, 1, 'hard'),
(375, 'America\'s national, state and local governments spend an amount equal to ________ of theGDP.[][]', '20 percent.[]', '50 percent.[]', '25 percent.[]', '12 percent. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(376, 'During the 1950s and early 1960s, over half the federal budget was spent every year on[][]', 'agricultural subsidies and programs.[]', 'Medicare.[]', 'the interstate highway program.[]', 'the Department of Defense.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(377, 'From the mid-1960s to the early 1980s, the biggest change in government spending was the[][]', 'ratification and implementation of the Twenty-eighth Amendment, the Balanced Budget Amendment.[]', 'abandonment of the gold standard and the creation of the Federal Reserve System.[]', 'growth of new budgeting techniques such as zero-based budgeting.[]', 'increase in social service expenditures and decline in defense spending.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(378, 'The military industrial complex refers to[][]', 'the global network of bases that the Department of Defense maintains.[]', 'the close relationship between defense officials and the corporations that supply their hardware needs.[]', 'the government-owned industries that manufacture military weapons and large equipment.[]', 'the Pentagon and the buildings that surround it. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(379, 'The budget of the Department of Defense[][]', 'decreased in the 1990s.[]', 'constitutes over half of all federal expenditures.[]', 'is the driving force in the expansion of the federal budget.[]', 'has increased despite the end of the Cold War. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(380, 'The purchasing of military hardware is known as[][]', 'regalia.[]', 'procurement.[]', 'appropriations.[]', 'mobilization. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(381, 'The biggest expenditure in the federal budget today is[][]', 'foreign aid programs.[]', 'welfare programs for the poor.[]', 'interest on the debt.[]', 'income security programs.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(382, 'The Social Security Act, which set up the Social Security system, was passed in[][]', '1935.[]', '1865.[]', '1962.[]', '1929. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(383, 'The Social Security Act was passed under the administration of President[][]', 'Franklin D. Roosevelt.[]', 'Herbert Hoover.[]', 'Lyndon Johnson.[]', 'Abraham Lincoln. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(384, 'In 1965, ________ was added to the Social Security program to provide hospital and physiciancoverage to the elderly.[][]', 'Medplan[]', 'Healthmark[]', 'Medicare[]', 'disability []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(385, 'Medicare[][]', 'is given only to those who do not have private insurance.[]', 'is administered separately from the social security system.[]', 'provides only hospital coverage to the poor.[]', 'provides both hospital and physician coverage to the elderly. []', 5, 3, 'hard'),
(386, 'The biggest slice of the federal budget pie belongs to[][]', 'law enforcement.[]', 'national defense.[]', 'education aid.[]', 'income security expenditures.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(387, 'By 1990, the Social Security system was financed by a payroll tax of[][]', '2 percent.[]', '5 percent.[]', '7.5 percent.[]', 'over 15 percent.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(388, 'A major feature of incremental budgeting is that it[][]', 'provides small increases in the current budget over the previous year\'s budget.[]', 'fragments the budget into many small items, making it hard to plan a unified budget.[]', 'reduces current budgets by small amounts over successive years.[]', 'reevaluates the budgetary base on which past budgets were built. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(389, 'An example of incremental budgeting is[][]', 'reviewing an agency\'s budget to establish a lower base.[]', 'Carter\'s zero-based budgeting.[]', 'reducing an agency\'s budget a little each year.[]', 'giving an agency a little more than it had last year.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(390, '________ refers to the concept that in the spending appropriations process, the best predictorof this year\'s budget is last year\'s budget plus a little bit more.[][]', 'Inflation-plus budgeting[]', 'Indexing[]', 'Program Planning-Budgeting Systems[]', 'Incrementalism[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(391, 'The most prevalent model of budgetary decision making in practice is[][]', 'program-planning budgeting.[]', 'incrementalism.[]', 'line-item budgeting.[]', 'rational party bargaining. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(392, 'Which of the following is NOT associated with incremental budgeting?[][]', 'An agency or program must prove it still merits its very existence every year.[]', 'Agencies and programs tend to safely assume they will receive at least what they had last year.[]', 'The budget for any given agency tends to grow a bit every year.[]', 'Agencies often pad their budgets a little bit. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(393, 'Budget items mandated by law or by a previous obligation are known as[][]', 'uncontrollable expenditures.[]', 'fiscal mandates.[]', 'bearer bonds.[]', 'procurements. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(394, 'Social Security payments are an example of a(n)[][]', 'increment.[]', 'indexing.[]', 'apportionment.[]', 'entitlement. []', 5, 2, 'hard'),
(395, 'An   uncontrollable   expenditure in the federal budget is defined as[][]', 'expenditures exceeding revenues so as to require borrowing to cover the difference.[]', 'an expenditure that is required by current law or a previous government obligation to people automatically eligible for some benefit.[]', 'one in which more money must be appropriated to handle a national crisis.[]', 'the government\'s allowance for meeting budget requests. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(396, 'Social Security programs, interest on the national debt, and military pensions are examples of[][]', 'tax expenditures.[]', 'uncontrollable expenditures.[]', 'tax loopholes.[]', 'incremental expenditures. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(397, 'The biggest uncontrollable expenditure in the federal budget is[][]', 'government retirement benefits.[]', 'interest on the national debt.[]', 'veterans aid.[]', 'the Social Security system. []', 5, 1, 'hard'),
(398, 'An estimated ________ of the federal budget is considered uncontrollable, unless Congresschanges a law or existing benefit levels.[][]', 'two-thirds[]', 'one-half[]', 'one-third[]', 'one-fifth []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(399, 'Approximately what percentage of the federal budget is uncontrollable?[][]', 'one-fourth[]', 'two-thirds[]', 'one-half[]', 'one-third []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(400, 'The ultimate power to determine how much the government will tax and spend, and what itwill spend taxes for, lies with[][]', 'the Treasury Department.[]', 'the courts.[]', 'the president.[]', 'Congress.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(401, 'In the House of Representatives, it is the ________ Committee that writes tax codes, subject tothe approval of Congress as a whole.[][]', 'Ways and Means[]', 'Budget[]', 'Revenue[]', 'Finance []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(402, 'Agencies invariably pad their budget requests because[][]', 'they want the almost inevitable budget cuts to be bearable.[]', 'it is an accepted part of zero-based budgeting.[]', 'their constituencies expect more benefits.[]', 'cost overruns almost always put them over budget. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(403, 'In the Senate, the ________ Committee is responsible for writing tax codes, subject to theapproval of Congress as a whole.[][]', 'Revenue[]', 'Budget[]', 'Appropriations[]', 'Finance []', 5, 3, 'hard'),
(404, 'The budget cycle begins in the executive branch ________ months before the fiscal year begins.[][]', '11[]', '19[]', 'seven[]', '24 or more []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(405, 'The Director of the Office of Management and Budget[][]', 'is a career official.[]', 'is elected by the Council of Economic Advisors.[]', 'is a congressional appointee.[]', 'is a presidential appointee requiring approval of the Senate.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(406, 'The ________ is responsible for supervising preparation of the federal budget and advising thepresident on budgetary matters.[][]', 'Treasury Department[]', 'Office of Management and Budget[]', 'General Accounting Office[]', 'Bureau of the Budget []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(407, 'The heads of executive agencies send their budget requests to the[][]', 'Office of Management and Budget.[]', 'president.[]', 'Treasury Department.[]', 'Congressional Budget Office. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(408, 'Agencies ¹ behavior and budgets are audited, monitored, and evaluated for Congress by the[][]', 'Congressional Budget Office.[]', 'president.[]', 'Internal Revenue Service.[]', 'General Accounting Office. []', 5, 1, 'hard'),
(409, 'The Office of Management and Budget parcels out money to government agencies and isaccountable to[][]', 'the Internal Revenue Service.[]', 'Congress.[]', 'the secretary of the treasury.[]', 'the president.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(410, 'Which of the following statements about the Office of Management and Budget (OMB) isFALSE?[][]', 'The OMB advises the president on budgetary matters.[]', 'The OMB is one of the few government agencies created by the Constitution.[]', 'Government agencies send their budget estimates to the OMB.[]', 'none of the above []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(411, 'Once the Office of Management and Budget has prepared the federal budget,[][]', 'it is sent to the Treasury Department for implementation.[]', 'the president makes revisions and submits it to Congress.[]', 'Congress must vote it up or down as a package within ten days.[]', 'it immediately becomes law. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(412, 'According to the Constitution, all federal appropriations must be authorized by[][]', 'the General Accounting Office.[]', 'the Office of Management and Budget.[]', 'the president.[]', 'Congress.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(413, 'The Congressional Budget and Impoundment Control Act of 1974 set up all of the followingEXCEPT[][]', 'a Budget Committee in each house of Congress.[]', 'the Congressional Budget Office.[]', 'the Office of Management and Budget.[]', 'both A and B []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(414, 'The congressional equivalent of the Office of Management and Budget is the[][]', 'Congressional Office of Finance.[]', 'Joint Committee on Ways and Means.[]', 'Joint Committee on the Budget.[]', 'Congressional Budget Office. []', 5, 1, 'hard'),
(415, 'One of the important purposes of the Congressional Budget Act of 1974 is to[][]', 'require the federal government to balance its budget.[]', 'force Congress to consider the budget as a whole rather than in terms of individual appropriations.[]', 'delegate effective budgetary authority to the president.[]', 'give Congress almost exclusive control over the federal budget. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(416, 'The main purpose of the Congressional Budget Office is to[][]', 'advise Congress on the consequences of its budget decisions.[]', 'prepare Congress ¹ own operating budget for salaries and supplies.[]', 'receive reports and recommendations from committees.[]', 'advise the president on congressional priorities in the budget. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(417, 'To set a limit on total government spending, both houses of Congress are required to pass a(n)________ every April, binding Congress to a total expenditure level, or bottom line, of allfederal spending for all programs.[][]', 'budget[]', 'budget resolution[]', 'circumscription bill[]', 'authorization bill []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(418, 'A budget resolution[][]', 'revises program authorizations to achieve required savings.[]', 'resolves the differences between House and Senate versions of the budget.[]', 'is an act of Congress that establishes a discretionary government program or an entitlement.[]', 'sets limits on expenditures based on revenue projections. []', 5, 1, 'hard'),
(419, 'Congress attempts to bind itself to a total expenditure level that should form the bottom line ofall federal spending for all programs by passing[][]', 'a zero-based binding resolution.[]', 'a budget reconciliation.[]', 'a budget resolution.[]', 'an authorization bill. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(420, 'Budget ________ revises program authorizations to achieve required savings.[][]', 'impoundment[]', 'realignment[]', 'closure[]', 'reconciliation []', 5, 2, 'hard'),
(421, 'A budget reconciliation[][]', 'reconciles the differences between House and Senate versions of the budget.[]', 'revises program authorizations to achieve required savings.[]', 'must be passed to actually fund programs established by authorization bills.[]', 'sets limits on expenditures based on revenue projections. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(422, 'An ________ bill is an act of Congress that establishes a discretionary government program oran entitlement, or that continues or changes such programs.[][]', 'omnibus[]', 'authorization[]', 'appropriations[]', 'enabling []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(423, 'To actually fund a program, Congress must pass an ________ bill.[][]', 'authorization[]', 'expenditure[]', 'appropriations[]', 'impoundment []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(424, 'Which of the following would be a specific example of an appropriations bill?[][]', 'Congress voting to discontinue the federal income tax[]', 'a budget resolution passed by both Houses of Congress[]', 'a bill funding the Department of the Interior for the fiscal year[]', 'a bill establishing a national health insurance system []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(425, 'Failing to meet its own budget timetable, Congress has frequently resorted to ________, whichare laws that allow agencies to spend at the previous year\'s level.[][]', 'reconciliations[]', 'revenue extensions[]', 'appropriations[]', 'continuing resolutions[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(426, 'An authorization bill[][]', 'provides the funding for discretionary programs.[]', 'authorizes the president to spend specific line-item amounts in the final budget.[]', 'covers only one year at a time.[]', 'establishes, continues, or changes a discretionary program or an entitlement. []', 5, 1, 'hard'),
(427, 'In order to actually fund programs established by authorization bills, Congress must pass[][]', 'a budget resolution.[]', 'a budget reconciliation.[]', 'an appropriations bill.[]', 'a continuing resolution. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(428, 'The Balanced Budget and Emergency Deficit Control Act called for the president to order________, if Congress failed to meet specific deficit-reduction goals.[][]', 'reconciliations[]', 'defunding directives[]', 're-authorizations[]', 'sequestrations []', 5, 2, 'hard'),
(429, 'The Gramm-Rudman-Hollings Act[][]', 'mandated maximum allowable deficit levels for each year until 1993, when the budget was to be balanced.[]', 'froze all United States government expenditures at their 1988 levels for three years in an effort to eliminate the budget deficits.[]', 'allowed agencies to spend at the previous year\'s level.[]', 'called for tax increases to pay for federal spending. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(430, 'In 1990, Congress split discretionary spending into three categories. Which of the followingwas NOT one of the three categories?[][]', 'domestic[]', 'defense[]', 'debt service[]', 'None of the above; debt service is a part of domestic expenditures. []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(431, 'Near the end of 1990, Congress approved a major change in the making of budget policy thatshifted the focus from cutting spending to[][]', 'controlling increases in spending.[]', 'increasing taxes.[]', 'increasing non-tax revenues.[]', 'controlling the size of the deficit. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(432, 'By 2002, the budget deficit had increased again due to[][]', 'decreased tax revenues.[]', 'income tax cut of 2001.[]', 'the first Iraq war.[]', 'none of the above []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(433, 'Some economists argue that less affluent voters will always use their votes to support publicpolicies that[][]', 'cut all tax rates.[]', 'redistribute benefits from the rich to the poor.[]', 'keep taxes low.[]', 'increase spending on foreign aid and international programs. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(434, '________ are not unwilling victims of big government and its big taxes in a democracy, theyare at least its co-conspirators.[][]', 'Citizens[]', 'Presidents[]', 'Bureaucrats[]', 'Political parties []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(435, 'Research has found that the public sector expands principally[][]', 'as a result of liberal political parties controlling the government.[]', 'as a result of Federal Reserve Board monetary policies influencing interest rates and currency reserves.[]', 'as a function of increased international economic competition.[]', 'in response to changes in economic and social conditions that affect the public\'s preferences for government activity.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(436, 'Economists Allen Meltzer and Scott Richard argue that the cost of government grows because[][]', 'democracy works best at the federal level.[]', 'big government is necessary for the maintenance of a capitalist system.[]', 'democracy is by nature an expensive form of government to operate.[]', 'people in a democracy use the government to secure benefits.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(437, 'Each bureaucratic agency is created initially by[][]', 'constitutional provision.[]', 'the president.[]', 'the bureaucracy itself.[]', 'Congress.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(438, 'Which of the following is TRUE about the federal bureaucracy?[][]', 'Most federal bureaucrats work in Washington, D.C.[]', 'The state and local governments have far more employees than the federal bureaucracy.[]', 'Most Americans are dissatisfied with their encounters with bureaucrats.[]', 'all of the above []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(439, 'Studies have found that most Americans[][]', 'dislike bureaucrats.[]', 'are indifferent about bureaucracies and bureaucrats.[]', 'are satisfied with the help received from bureaucrats.[]', 'want the government bureaucracy dismantled. []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(440, 'Which of the following statements about the size of bureaucracies is FALSE?[][]', 'State and local public employees far outnumber civilian federal government employees.[]', 'As a percentage of America\'s total work force, federal government employment has been growing.[]', 'Federal government employment amounts to about three percent of all civilian jobs.[]', 'None of the above; all of the above statements are TRUE. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(441, 'As a percentage of the total work force, federal government employment is[][]', 'rapidly becoming greater than employment in the private sector.[]', 'greater than state and local government employment.[]', 'rising.[]', 'declining.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(442, 'The classic conception of a bureaucracy was advanced by ________, who argued that thebureaucracy was a   rational   way for a modern society to conduct its business.[][]', 'Max Weber[]', 'John Locke[]', 'Charles L. Schultze[]', 'James Madison []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(443, 'In addition to a hierarchical authority structure, Max Weber argued that a bureaucracyinvolves all of the following EXCEPT[][]', 'extensive rules.[]', 'an incentive system.[]', 'the merit principle.[]', 'hierarchical authority structure. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(444, 'The Weberian theory of bureaucracies views them in the most positive light as[][]', 'acquisitive.[]', 'inefficient.[]', 'monopolistic.[]', 'hierarchical.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(445, 'The Weberian model views bureaucracies as[][]', 'promoting good monopolies.[]', 'loosely organized and loosely run.[]', 'largely self-serving.[]', 'efficient and necessary.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(446, 'Which of the following would NOT be considered part of the Weberian model of bureaucracy?[][]', 'task specialization[]', 'decentralized authority structure[]', 'impersonality[]', 'A and D only []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(447, 'Which of the following statements about bureaucracies is FALSE?[][]', 'Bureaucracies are simply a way of organizing people to perform work.[]', 'The vast majority of tasks carried out by governments are noncontroversial.[]', 'Bureaucracies receive very little credit when they function well.[]', 'Government bureaucracies have been shown to be less efficient and effective than private bureaucracies.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(448, 'The ________ employs about one -fourth of all federal civilian workers, more than any otherdepartment or agency.[][]', 'Department of Education[]', 'Department of Health and Human Services[]', 'Department of Defense[]', 'Department of Labor []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(449, 'There are roughly ________ civilian and military federal government employees[][]', '800,000[]', '3,000,000[]', '2,100,000[]', '4,000,000[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(450, 'As a whole, the permanent federal bureaucracy is[][]', 'less diverse in terms of the type of jobs than the private sector.[]', 'dominated by white males.[]', 'more broadly representative of the American people than the rest of the federal government.[]', 'now employing 15 percent of the American work force. []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(451, '________ is a hiring and promotion system based on knowing the right people, working in anelection campaign, making large political donations, and/or having the right connections towin jobs with the government.[][]', 'The patronage system[]', 'The bureaucracy[]', 'The golden gate[]', 'Administrative discretion []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(452, 'Patronage is a hiring and promotion system based on[][]', 'knowing the right people.[]', 'talent and skill.[]', 'the Pendelton Act.[]', 'the merit principle. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(453, 'Until the late-nineteenth century, most government employees got their jobs through[][]', 'the patronage system.[]', 'hereditary preferences.[]', 'civil service testing.[]', 'a lottery system. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(454, 'The ________ Act was passed partly as a memorial to the memory of President James Garfield,who was assassinated in 1881.[][]', 'Pendleton Civil Service[]', 'Voting Rights[]', 'Hatch[]', 'Interstate Commerce []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(455, 'The Pendleton Act established the[][]', 'patronage system.[]', 'federal civil service.[]', 'plum book.[]', 'Interstate Commerce Commission. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(456, 'The rationale for all civil service systems is based on[][]', 'patronage.[]', 'the merit principle.[]', 'the plum book.[]', 'voluntary service. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(457, 'The Hatch Act, passed in 1940,[][]', 'established the patronage system for federal employment.[]', 'prohibited the president from firing the heads of independent executive agencies.[]', 'prohibits federal civil service employees from active participation in partisan politics.[]', 'established the federal civil service. []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(458, 'Once hired into the federal bureaucracy, a person is assigned a ________ rating, whichdetermines one\'s salary range.[][]', 'Federal Register[]', 'Weber[]', 'General Schedule[]', 'plum book []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(459, 'The federal civil service was created by[][]', 'Article IV of the Constitution.[]', 'an executive order of President Arthur.[]', 'the Office of Management and Budget.[]', 'the Pendleton Act. []', 5, 3, 'hard'),
(460, 'The rationale for the civil service rests on the[][]', 'goal of centralizing government employment at the federal level.[]', 'desire to create a nonpartisan government service and promotion on the basis of merit.[]', 'the need to separate military institutions from civilian institutions to prevent undue military influence.[]', 'need for job replacements when a new party comes to power. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(461, 'Federal employees are prohibited from active participation in partisan politics through the[][]', 'Twenty-fifth Amendment.[]', 'Pendleton Act.[]', 'Supreme Court ruling in Democratic National Committee v. Hayes.[]', 'Hatch Act.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(462, 'Which of the following is a legitimate criticism of the federal civil service?[][]', 'Firing incompetents is extremely difficult.[]', 'It does not operate on the merit principle.[]', 'Too many federal civil servants are actively involved in partisan politics.[]', 'all of the above []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(463, 'Which of the following would be included in a plum book?[][]', 'doctors at a Veteran\'s Administration hospital[]', 'postal carriers[]', 'the phone numbers of a Congress member\'s sex partners[]', 'Cabinet secretaries []', 5, 3, 'hard'),
(464, 'Which of the following statements about the hiring and firing of civil servants is FALSE?[][]', 'The Office of Personnel Management has elaborate rules about hiring, promotion, and firing of civil servants.[]', 'The top of the civil service is composed of about 9,000 members of the Senior Executive Service.[]', 'Once hired, civil servants are assigned a General Schedule ranging from GS-1 to GS-18.[]', 'Due to the merit system, it is easy to fire incompetent civil servants.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(465, 'The plum book lists[][]', 'all federal contracts available for bid.[]', 'top federal jobs available by Presidential appointment.[]', 'job openings in the prestigious Office of Personnel Management.[]', 'appeals filed with the Merit Systems Protection Board. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(466, 'Which of the following statements about plum book appointees is FALSE?[][]', 'Most presidents seek appointees with sympathy for similar policy positions.[]', 'Ambassadorship appointments often go to large campaign contributors.[]', 'Plum book appointees are often instrumental in changing and reforming their agencies.[]', 'none of the above []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(467, 'Which of the following is NOT true about presidential appointees to bureaucracies?[][]', 'They often do not know their own agency subordinates very well, much less people in other agencies.[]', 'They must be recommended by the Office of Personnel Management\'s   rule of three.  []', 'They tend to spend fewer years in their positions than those in the civil service.[]', 'none of the above []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(468, 'According to Hugh Heclo, the plum book system of recruiting federal employees tends toresult in the appointment of[][]', 'talented experts with proven party loyalty.[]', 'people with access to the Internet, but not necessarily the most qualified people.[]', 'senior civil servants to sensitive posts.[]', 'administrators who do not stay long enough in their appointed position to be effective.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(469, 'Which Cabinet department is charged with overseeing the nation\'s national resources?[][]', 'Homeland Security[]', 'Environmental Protection Agency[]', 'Defense[]', 'Interior []', 5, 2, 'hard'),
(470, 'The real work of a Cabinet department is done[][]', 'by the entire Cabinet.[]', 'by the president\'s staff.[]', 'by the undersecretaries.[]', 'in the bureaus. []', 5, 3, 'hard'),
(471, 'The largest federal agency based on dollars spent is the[][]', 'Department of Defense.[]', 'Department of Justice.[]', 'State Department.[]', 'Social Security Administration. []', 5, 1, 'hard'),
(472, 'Which of these is the newest government agency?[][]', 'Drug Enforcement Agency[]', 'Social Security Administration[]', 'Drug Interdiction Agency[]', 'Cyberspace Commission []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(473, 'The Cabinet department that has the largest budget is the Department of[][]', 'Health and Human Services.[]', 'Commerce.[]', 'the Treasury.[]', 'Education. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(474, 'Bureaus in the federal bureaucracy are also known as all of the following EXCEPT[][]', 'an administration.[]', 'an office.[]', 'a department.[]', 'none of the above []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(475, 'The Interstate Commerce Commission and the Federal Reserve Board are examples of[][]', 'dependent presidential boards.[]', 'independent regulatory agencies.[]', 'Cabinet departments.[]', 'independent executive agencies. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(476, 'Which of the following statements about independent regulatory commissions is FALSE?[][]', 'Regulatory commission members cannot be fired by the president.[]', 'Regulatory commissions consist of five to ten members.[]', 'Regulatory commission members are appointed by the president and confirmed by the Senate.[]', 'Regulatory commission members may not be drawn from the ranks of present or former employees of the regulated industry.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(477, 'The parts of the federal bureaucracy with responsibility for different sectors of the economy,and making and enforcing rules designed to protect the public interest, are the[][]', 'independent executive agencies.[]', 'independent regulatory agencies.[]', 'government corporations.[]', 'Cabinet departments. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(478, 'The General Services Administration and the National Aeronautical and Space Administrationare examples of[][]', 'government corporations.[]', 'independent regulatory agencies.[]', 'Cabinet departments.[]', 'independent executive agencies. []', 5, 1, 'hard'),
(479, 'Independent regulatory agencies have[][]', 'complete independence from the president, but their policymakers are appointed by Congress.[]', 'powerful rule-making, dispute-settling, and enforcement authority.[]', 'no formal ties to either the president or the Congress.[]', 'governing commissions composed of long-time federal Civil Service employees. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(480, 'Amtrak and the United States Postal Service are examples of[][]', 'government corporations.[]', 'Cabinet departments.[]', 'executive commercial agencies.[]', 'independent regulatory agencies. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(481, 'Government corporations[][]', 'operate an airline, manufacture steel, and provide health insurance.[]', 'provide services and charge for them.[]', 'are independent regulatory agencies.[]', 'sell stock and pay dividends. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(482, 'An obstacle to the successful implementation of public policy is[][]', 'the failure of Congress to pass authorizing legislation.[]', 'the over-specialization of civil service employees.[]', 'competition between the private and public sectors.[]', 'unclear policy goals and poorly designed policies.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(483, 'Once a policy decision has been made, such as by passing a legislative act or issuing anexecutive order, the bureaucracy is responsible for[][]', 'its ratification.[]', 'its implementation.[]', 'funding it.[]', 'judging its merits. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(484, 'The main job of federal bureaucrats is to[][]', 'advise the president and Cabinet on internal affairs.[]', 'countervail the power of private corporations, especially monopolies.[]', 'compete with the private sector for monopoly power.[]', 'implement and regulate government policies. []', 5, 1, 'hard'),
(485, 'Creating new agencies, developing guidelines, and coordinating resources to achieve a policygoal is called[][]', 'bureaucratization.[]', 'regulation.[]', 'implementation.[]', 'policymaking. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(486, 'Which of the following is NOT a reason that policy implementation sometimes breaks down inthe federal bureaucracy?[][]', 'fragmentation of responsibilities[]', 'lack of standard operating procedures[]', 'faulty program design[]', 'lack of resources []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(487, 'Vigorous disputes over the implementation of Title IX of the Education Amendments of 1972in regard to funding for women\'s athletic programs arose primarily due to[][]', 'faulty program design.[]', 'lack of clarity in the original policy decision.[]', 'fragmentation of responsibilities.[]', 'all of the above []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(488, 'Section 844 of Title IX of the Education Amendments of 1972[][]', 'was declared unconstitutional by the Supreme Court.[]', 'specifically prohibits sex discrimination in college sports.[]', 'was supported by most colleges and universities.[]', 'was vaguely written, eventually resulting in scores of court cases.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(489, 'A major complaint of the Food and Drug Administration is[][]', 'its lack of clarity.[]', 'the fragmentation of responsibilities.[]', 'that there is no administrative discretion.[]', 'the shortage of personnel. []', 5, 1, 'hard'),
(490, 'Which of the following is NOT true about standard operating procedures?[][]', 'They provide routine rules to help bureaucrats make numerous everyday decisions.[]', 'Each federal department and agency has a plum book which lists its standard operating procedures.[]', 'They are referred to as   red tape   by those who find them burdensome.[]', 'They are used by street-level bureaucrats. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(491, 'Standard operating procedures[][]', 'usually prove to be unjust and discriminatory when followed to the letter.[]', 'save time and bring uniformity to complex organizations.[]', 'give authority to administrative actors to select among various responses to a given problem.[]', 'are frustrating and inappropriate in addressing most situations. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(492, 'Standard operating procedures accomplish all of the following EXCEPT[][]', 'bring uniformity to complex organizations.[]', 'save time.[]', 'make personnel interchangeable.[]', 'reduce red tape.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(493, '________ is the authority of administrative actors to select among various responses to a givenproblem.[][]', 'Standard operating procedure[]', 'Administrative discretion[]', 'Executive power[]', 'Deregulation []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(494, 'Standard operating procedures become frustrating to citizens and obstacles to action whenthey[][]', 'do not directly apply to a particular situation.[]', 'are not specifically codified.[]', 'transfer personnel to different posts.[]', 'are not closely followed. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(495, 'The authority of administrative actors to select among various responses to a given problem iscalled[][]', 'policy implementation.[]', 'selective management.[]', 'the merit principle.[]', 'administrative discretion. []', 5, 3, 'hard'),
(496, 'Administrative discretion is greatest when[][]', 'rules and regulations are not written down.[]', 'when standard operating procedures are used.[]', 'an agency has elaborate rules and regulations.[]', 'rules do not fit a case. []', 5, 3, 'hard'),
(497, 'The Federal Aviation Administration\'s protocol for for hijackings assumed that[][]', 'the pilot would be able to radio air traffic controllers and alert them to the problem.[]', 'the FAA would be able to pinpoint the aircraft involved.[]', 'there would be enough time for the government to formulate a response.[]', 'All of the above []', 5, 1, 'hard'),
(498, 'Those civil service employees who are in constant contact with the public (often a hostile one)and have considerable discretion are known as[][]', 'street-level bureaucrats.[]', 'General Schedule foot soldiers.[]', 'the Senior Executive Service.[]', 'civil servants. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(499, 'Administrative personnel who exercise discretion, pay attention to routine, and deal directlywith clients,[][]', 'are called street-level bureaucrats.[]', 'implement federal policies.[]', 'are part of the Senior Executive Service.[]', 'are usually dismissed for not following standard operating procedures. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(500, 'Which of the following would not be considered a street-level bureaucrat?[][]', 'a municipal court judge[]', 'an assistant secretary in the Department of Transportation[]', 'a mail carrier who delivers mail exclusively in a high-rise building[]', 'a police officer []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(501, 'When bureaucrats are asked to execute orders with which they do not agree,[][]', 'they usually ignore the orders.[]', 'they are likely to lose their jobs if they do not follow through with the orders.[]', 'they can file a Conflict Of Interest Form and will be exempted from that duty by their boss.[]', 'slippage is likely to occur between policy decisions and performance. []', 5, 2, 'hard'),
(502, 'Which of the following statements is FALSE?[][]', 'Bureaucrats are often fired for using too much administrative discretion.[]', 'Removing appointed officials may be politically embarrassing to the president.[]', 'A government agency cannot expand just because it is performing a service effectively and efficiently.[]', 'none of the above []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(503, 'The diffusion of responsibility within the bureaucracy[][]', 'makes the coordination of policies both time-consuming and difficult.[]', 'allows for a diversity of opinion thus facilitating effective administration.[]', 'helps diminish the use of administrative discretion.[]', 'facilitates the use of inter-bureaucracy standard operating procedures. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(504, 'Proposals to reorganize the government in order to solve the problem of bureaucraticfragmentation[][]', 'are often opposed by agencies not wanting to be submerged within a broader bureaucratic unit.[]', 'are opposed by congressional committees, fearing they will be given greater responsibility to oversee larger and more diverse agencies.[]', 'are supported by interest groups, who feel they could better control the regulatory programs of a reorganized bureaucracy.[]', 'are supported and opposed for all of these reasons. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(505, 'The Voting Rights Act of 1965[][]', 'was very difficult to implement because of the fragmentation of responsibility for implementing it.[]', 'was successfully implemented thanks to its clear goal, its clear methods to achieve the goal, and its lack of bureaucratic fragmentation.[]', 'was impossible to implement because of a lack of clarity in the legislation.[]', 'All but D are true. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(506, 'The Voting Rights Act of 1965 was successful for all of the following reasons EXCEPT[][]', 'its goal was clear.[]', 'its implementation was straightforward.[]', 'the authority of the implementors was plain.[]', 'it was universally supported.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(507, 'The use of government authority to control or change some practice in the private sector isknown as[][]', 'socialism.[]', 'regulation.[]', 'executive review.[]', 'public administration. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(508, 'The use of governmental authority to control or change some practice in the private sector iscalled[][]', 'regulation.[]', 'administrative discretion.[]', 'policy implementation.[]', 'public administration. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(509, 'Which of the following statements about government regulation in America is accurate?[][]', 'The Constitution set up only six regulatory agencies; the others have been created within the past 100 years or so.[]', 'The Federal Communications Commission was the first independent regulatory agency.[]', 'Until 1887, the federal government made almost no regulatory policies and had no regulatory agencies.[]', 'both A and C []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(510, 'In the case of Munn v. Illinois, decided in 1877, the United States Supreme Court[][]', 'ruled that states could not impose corporate income taxes.[]', 'ruled that the Civil Service System was constitutional.[]', 'outlawed the patronage system.[]', 'upheld the right of government to regulate the business operations of a firm. []', 5, 3, 'hard'),
(511, 'Until 1887, the federal government[][]', 'had almost no regulatory policies.[]', 'owned and operated most of the major industries in the country.[]', 'forbade the states from passing regulatory policies.[]', 'was involved only in economic regulation. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(512, 'The Supreme Court case of Munn v. Illinois (1877)[][]', 'declared that regulation was not within the realm of state powers.[]', 'first established the right to own property as one of the rights of the Bill of Rights.[]', 'set the precedent for deregulation.[]', 'upheld the right of government to regulate the business operations of a firm.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(513, 'Most regulatory agencies adopt specific ________ to carry out a policy, based on what theybelieve was the intended purpose of the specific policy at hand.[][]', 'guidelines[]', 'incentive systems[]', 'mandates[]', 'merit principles []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(514, 'Whatever strategy Congress permits a regulatory agency to use, all regulation contains thefollowing elements EXCEPT[][]', 'some means of enforcing compliance.[]', 'a grant of power and set of directions from Congress.[]', 'a set of rules and guidelines by the regulatory agency itself.[]', 'an incentive system to maximize performance by those regulated.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(515, 'All regulations contain each of the following elements EXCEPT[][]', 'a grant of power and set of directions from Congress[]', 'some means of enforcing compliance with congressional goals and agency regulations[]', 'presidential oversight and control of enforcement[]', 'All of these are elements of the regulatory process. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(516, 'When Congress passes regulatory legislation for which it has established goals, it then[][]', 'grants power to regulatory agencies to develop guidelines and enforce compliance.[]', 'establishes the guidelines that regulatory agencies must implement.[]', 'grants interest groups the power to develop the rules governing the new policy.[]', 'authorizes the president to use his administrative discretion to implement the legislation. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(517, 'One proposed solution to the   problem   of the proliferation of regulatory agencies and policieshas been[][]', 'deregulation.[]', 'budget cuts.[]', 'standard operating procedures.[]', 'the incentive system. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(518, 'Deregulation has resulted, at least in part, in each of the following EXCEPT[][]', 'environmental damage.[]', 'the proliferation of government agencies.[]', 'an expensive bailout of the savings and loan industry.[]', 'less government oversight in some key areas. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(519, 'Which of the following is NOT an accusation made against the regulatory system?[][]', 'Excessive regulation contributed to the savings and loan industry disaster of the 1980s.[]', 'Regulations do not always work well, and they simply create massive regulatory bureaucracies.[]', 'Other nations have laxer regulations on pollution, worker safety, and other business practices, thus American exports often cost more.[]', 'All of these have been criticisms of regulation. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(520, 'Each of the following is a criticism of regulation EXCEPT that it[][]', 'lowers prices.[]', 'distorts market forces.[]', 'is too complex.[]', 'gives bureaucrats too much power. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(521, 'Most of the government is composed of[][]', 'regulators.[]', 'lawyers.[]', 'bureaucrats.[]', 'politicians. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(522, 'Executive orders are issued by[][]', 'independent regulatory agencies.[]', 'any federal agency or department.[]', 'Congress.[]', 'the president. []', 5, 3, 'hard'),
(523, 'Which of the following is NOT a method a president can use to control the bureaucracy?[][]', 'issue executive orders or more informal requests[]', 'rewrite statutes to make instructions clearer as to how policies are intended[]', 'tinker with an agency\'s recommended budget[]', 'request a congressional oversight hearing []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(524, 'Which of the following statements about Congress and the bureaucracy is FALSE?[][]', 'Bureaucracies can help Congress find answers to policy problems.[]', 'Bureaucracies help provide services to constituents.[]', 'Members of Congress often find a big bureaucracy congenial.[]', 'Congress has found it easy to control the bureaucracy.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(525, 'Congress tries to control the bureaucracy through each of the following EXCEPT[][]', 'rewriting legislation.[]', 'influencing the appointment of agency heads.[]', 'holding hearings.[]', 'issuing congressional orders.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(526, 'Congress tries to control the bureaucracy through[][]', 'rewriting laws and budgets and holding hearings.[]', 'the use of executive orders and appointments.[]', 'the creation of   iron triangles.  []', 'all of the above []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(527, 'To limit bureaucratic discretion and make its instructions clearer, Congress can[][]', 'deregulate.[]', 'write new and more detailed legislation.[]', 'reregulate.[]', 'threaten to cut an agency\'s budget. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(528, 'As the oversight powers of Congress in regard to the bureaucracy have become morevigorous,[][]', 'Congress is increasingly the policy-implementation branch of government.[]', 'it has become easier to rein in the bureaucracy.[]', 'they have also become more fragmented.[]', 'the amount of government corruption has decreased dramatically. []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(529, 'A major problem for presidents and Congress in controlling bureaucracies is the existence of[][]', 'the plum book.[]', 'Supreme Court rulings curbing the scope of their oversight.[]', '  iron triangles.  []', 'the incentive system. []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(530, 'An   iron triangle   is also referred to as[][]', 'a government corporation.[]', 'a reverse diagonal.[]', 'a subgovernment.[]', 'an issue network. []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(531, 'A(n) ________ consists of an administrative agency, an interest group, and a congressionalcommittee or subcommittee.[][]', 'issue network[]', 'independent executive agency[]', 'triumvirate[]', '  iron triangle   []', 5, 2, 'hard'),
(532, '  Iron triangles   face challenges from a growing number of[][]', 'street-level bureaucrats.[]', 'subgovernments.[]', 'plastics and softer metals.[]', 'issue networks. []', 5, 3, 'hard'),
(533, 'Subgovernments promote[][]', 'centralization of authority.[]', 'strong executive branch control of policymaking.[]', 'the control of the bureaucracy by Congress.[]', 'decentralized and fragmented policymaking.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(534, 'A group of participants in bureaucratic policymaking with technical policy expertise andintellectual and emotional commitment to the issue is called[][]', 'a government corporation.[]', 'an   iron triangle  .[]', 'a subgovernment.[]', 'an issue network.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(535, 'Which of the following is NOT an area in which an   iron triangle   has controlled federal policyover the past several decades?[][]', 'nuclear power policy[]', 'environmental policy[]', 'smoking & tobacco policy[]', 'none of the above []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(536, 'Which of the following is NOT true about   iron triangles  ?[][]', 'They present tremendous difficulties for Congress and the president when they attempt to control the bureaucracy.[]', 'They add a strong decentralizing and fragmenting element to the government\'s policymaking process.[]', 'They are also known as subgovernments.[]', 'They are indestructible.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(537, '  Iron triangles   are composed of[][]', 'primarily iron, but also metallic, alloys.[]', 'bureaucratic agencies, interest groups, and congressional committees.[]', 'congressional committees, state governments, and bureaucratic agencies.[]', 'senators, governors, and department heads. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(538, 'In 1887, Congress established the first regulatory agency, the ________, and charged it withregulating the railroads, their prices, and their services to farmers.[][]', 'Department of Transportation[]', 'Railroad Commission[]', 'American Railway Union[]', 'Interstate Commerce Commission []', 5, 2, 'hard');
INSERT INTO `gov_hard` (`Qno`, `Question`, `Option1`, `Option2`, `Option3`, `Option4`, `Answer`, `marks`, `Complexity`) VALUES
(539, 'Which of the following statements about bureaucracies and the scope of government isFALSE?[][]', 'When the president and Congress chose to deregulate certain areas of the economy or cut taxes, the bureaucracy prevented them from doing so.[]', 'The bureaucracy is now expected to play an active role in dealing with social and economic problems.[]', 'The federal bureaucracy has not grown over the past two generations.[]', 'none of the above []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(540, 'The great majority of America\'s judicial business is transacted in[][]', 'state courts of original jurisdiction.[]', 'Supreme Courts.[]', 'the United States courts of appeal.[]', 'federal courts of original jurisdiction. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(541, 'Which of the following statements about the courts is FALSE?[][]', 'Supreme Court decisions may directly shape people\'s lives.[]', 'Most of American judicial policy is made in the Supreme Court.[]', 'The Supreme Court decides a handful of key issues each year.[]', 'The judicial system in the U.S. is, at least in principle, an adversarial one. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(542, 'One of the differences between criminal law and civil law is that in civil law[][]', 'there is no charge that a law has been violated.[]', 'the case cannot be appealed.[]', 'the government cannot be one of the litigants.[]', 'common law takes precedent over statutory law. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(543, 'Litigants are[][]', 'the attorneys.[]', 'the plaintiff and the defendant.[]', 'the defendant and the defendant\'s attorney.[]', 'plaintiffs. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(544, 'Not everyone can challenge a law. Litigants must have what is called ________, meaning thatthey must have a serious personal stake in the case, typically determined by whether or notthey have sustained or are in danger of an injury.[][]', 'standing to sue[]', 'stare decisis[]', 'original jurisdiction[]', 'legal prerogative []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(545, 'Class action suits[][]', 'are those which have to do with constitutional issues, thus broadening the standing to sue.[]', 'are filed by students seeking to force a school district to offer additional sections of perpetually over-enrolled courses.[]', 'permit a small number of people to sue on behalf of all other people similarly situated.[]', 'are routinely filed by teachers ¹ groups to prepare the way for legal strikes. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(546, 'Courts may only decide ________ disputes.[][]', 'civil[]', 'constitutional[]', 'justiciable[]', 'class action []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
