(889, 'America\'s principal foreign policy strategy toward the Soviet Union throughout the Cold War,proposed by the foreign policy strategist George Kennan in 1947, was[][]', 'isolationism.[]', 'containment.[]', 'covert operations.[]', 'laissez faire. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(890, 'The Marshall Plan[][]', 'warned European nations to stay out of Latin America.[]', 'poured billions of dollars into war-ravaged European nations after World War II.[]', 'imposed democratic constitutions on Germany and Japan in the wake of World War II.[]', 'created NATO. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(891, 'The containment doctrine was[][]', 'intended to prevent Soviet expansion after World War II.[]', 'the Soviet policy of building the Iron Curtain and Berlin Wall to hold American influence to Western Europe after World War II.[]', 'first proposed as a military maneuver during the Korean War as a means to prevent Chinese advances.[]', 'the policy of cooperation and relaxation of tensions with the Soviet Union. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(892, 'Almost immediately following World War II, the United States entered into ________ with theSoviet Union.[][]', 'the Korean War[]', 'the Cuban Missile Crisis[]', 'a Cold War[]', 'a lend lease plan []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(893, 'During the 1950s, John Foster Dulles, the Secretary of State under Eisenhower, proclaimed apolicy of ________ in America\'s dealings with the Soviet Union.[][]', 'containment Â´[]', 'detente[]', 'peaceful coexistence[]', 'brinkmanship[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(894, 'Fear of a serious communist conspiracy in the United States during the early years of the ColdWar led to the rise of a near panic that communism was infiltrating American government andcultural institutions, and became known as[][]', 'brinkmanship.[]', 'McCarthyism. Â´[]', 'isolationism.[]', 'the Deep Freeze. []', 2, 1, 'hard'),
(895, 'McCarthyism was strongest during[][]', 'World War II.[]', 'the Vietnam War.[]', 'the Korean War. Â´[]', 'World War I. []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(896, 'The cold war led to all of the following EXCEPT[][]', 'an arms race between the United States and the Soviet Union.[]', 'the use of atomic weapons.[]', 'mutual assured destruction.[]', 'none of the above []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(897, 'The growth of the military budget during the 1950s under President Eisenhower led him toremark at the end of his second term that[][]', 'although the Soviets were not aware of it yet, the United States had won the Cold War.[]', 'atomic bombs should be dropped on the Soviet Union.[]', 'the military-industrial complex that had developed between private defense contractors and the Pentagon was worrisome.[]', 'none of the above []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(898, 'By the mid-1950s, defense expenditures[][]', 'declined below World War II levels.[]', 'gave way to expenditures on social-welfare policies.[]', 'grew to be the largest component of the federal budget.[]', 'shifted to the Middle East to protect American oil supplies. []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(899, 'The rise of detente and the first Strategic Arms Limitation Treaty (SALT) were brought aboutunder President[][]', 'Harry Truman.[]', 'Dwight Eisenhower.[]', 'Ronald Reagan.[]', 'Richard Nixon.[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(900, 'The relaxation of tensions between the United States and the Soviet Union throughout the1970s was known asÂ´[][]', 'detente.[]', 'the Strategic Defense Initiative.[]', 'glasnost.[]', 'New Thinking. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(901, 'In detente,[][]', 'nuclear rearmament was emphasized.[]', 'diplomacy and propaganda replaced the threat of force.[]', 'international relations shifted from a multipolar to a bipolar world.[]', 'international relations shifted from a bipolar to a multipolar world. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(902, 'A product of detente was the[][]', 'end of the Korean War.[]', 'start of the Strategic Arms Limitation Talks.[]', 'creation of the United Nations.[]', 'all of the above []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(903, 'The United States and Soviet Union agreement on SALT I reflected[][]', 'a policy of containment.[]', 'brinkmanship. Â´[]', 'a policy of detente.[]', 'the two nations ¹ first effort to coordinate the development of a natural resource. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(904, 'The largest increase in peacetime defense spending occurred under President ________, whoargued that the Soviets had used arms control agreements to gallop ahead of the United Statesin military spending.[][]', 'Gerald Ford[]', 'Jimmy Carter[]', 'Richard Nixon[]', 'Ronald Reagan[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(905, 'President Ronald Reagan proposed a massive new spending program called the ________ tocreate a global umbrella in space, wherein computers would scan the skies and use varioushigh-tech devices to destroy invading missiles.[][]', 'brinkmanship[]', 'Superpatriot Missile Shield[]', 'Strategic Defense Initiative[]', 'Early Warning System []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(906, 'During the early years of his administration, Reagan\'s foreign and defense policiesemphasizedÂ´[][]', 'detente.[]', 'anticommunism.[]', 'nuclear disarmament.[]', 'international free trade agreements. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(907, 'The cold war ended[][]', 'spontaneously with freedom and self-determination erupting in Eastern Europe.[]', 'with the American occupation of Eastern Europe in 1945.[]', 'shortly after Chinese students held peaceful protests for democracy in Tiananmen Square.[]', 'with Iraq\'s defeat in Kuwait in 1991. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(908, 'One of the few spots where violence and brutal government force crushed a pro-democracyreform movement in 1989 and allowed the communist government to endure was inTiananmen Square in[][]', 'Warsaw.[]', 'Beijing.[]', 'Quito.[]', 'Ho Chi Minh City. []', 2, 2, 'hard'),
(909, 'The use of violence to demoralize and frighten a country\'s population or government isreferred to as[][]', 'isolationism. Â´[]', 'detente.[]', 'mutual assured destruction.[]', 'terrorism.[]', 4, 1, 'hard');
INSERT INTO `gov_hard` (`Qno`, `Question`, `Option1`, `Option2`, `Option3`, `Option4`, `Answer`, `marks`, `Complexity`) VALUES
(910, 'In response to the terrorist acts of September 11, 2001, the George W. Bush administration hasdeveloped a new foreign policy emphasizing[][]', 'negotiation.[]', 'deterrence. Â´[]', 'detente.[]', 'preemptive strikes.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(911, 'What errors did the United States make in planning post-war Iraq?[][]', 'The U.S. believed that the American soldiers would be welcomed as liberators.[]', 'The U.S. believed that Iraqi oil revenues would pay for most reconstruction costs.[]', 'The U.S. believed Iraqis had the skill and infrastructure to do most of the rebuilding.[]', 'all of the above[]', 4, 2, 'hard'),
(912, 'The Unites States originally pursued a   decapitation   strategy for confronting al -Qaida. Whatdid this strategy propose to do?[][]', 'attack the root causes of terrorism, namely poverty[]', 'reduce America\'s cultural influence on the Muslim world[]', 'eliminate a small number of al-Qaida leaders[]', 'spread democracy to the Middle East []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(913, 'The threat posed by terrorist groups and the hostile states supporting them has causedAmerica to[][]', 'reconsider basic principles of its foreign policy.[]', 'emphasize the principles of deterrence and containment in foreign policy.[]', 'make dramatic cuts in domestic expenditures to pay for the new war on terrorism.[]', 'shift back to isolationism. []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(914, 'Defense spending now makes up about ________ of the federal budget.[][]', 'one-fifth[]', 'one-half[]', 'three-fifths[]', 'one-fourth []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(915, 'The phrase   guns and butter   refers to[][]', 'politicians who promise money for both military and domestic spending programs.[]', 'the general economic improvement accompanying the nation\'s involvement in a major war, though at a high human cost.[]', 'what many scholars claim is the trade-off a nation faces between defense spending and social spending.[]', 'the economic impact of foreign countries with large defense industries. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(916, 'In general, American conservatives argue that the breakup of the communist regimes inEastern Europe and the demise of the Soviet Union were principally due to[][]', 'the serious defects of the Soviet economyî€„the inertia, the wastefulness, and the corruption inherent in the system.[]', 'Mikhail Gorbachev\'s unexpected and unyielding commitment to glasnost and perestroika.[]', 'America\'s defense build-up during the 1980s which the Soviet Union could not match and eventually toppled it.[]', 'political revolution in the Soviet Union. []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(917, 'Which of the following statements about defense spending is FALSE?[][]', 'Evidence indicates that as defense spending increases, domestic spending decreases.[]', 'Conservatives fight deep cuts in defense spending in order to maintain readiness at a high level.[]', 'Liberals maintain that the Pentagon wastes money and that the United States buys too many guns and too little butter.[]', 'Defense spending now comprises half of the federal budget. []', 1, 2, 'hard'),
(918, 'Liberals argue that the most crucial aspect of national defense is[][]', 'diplomacy.[]', 'a strong military capability.[]', 'a strong economy.[]', 'nuclear deterrence. []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(919, 'Whatever their ideology, members of Congress tend to support military spending mostconsistently[][]', 'when it means jobs for their constituents.[]', 'if they are asked to do so by the president.[]', 'once a project has already begun and needs additional funding.[]', 'during election years. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(920, 'The structure of America\'s defenses has been based on[][]', 'complete control of the sea and large overseas bases.[]', 'military control of outer space.[]', 'strategic nuclear air command and a small but specialized standing army.[]', 'a large standing military force and a triad of strategic nuclear weapons.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(921, 'Which of the following is NOT part of America\'s triad of nuclear weapons delivery systems?[][]', 'Strategic Defense Initiative[]', 'strategic bombers[]', 'submarine-launched ballistic missiles[]', 'both A and C []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(922, 'The first American president to sign a treaty to actually reduce current levels of nuclearweapons in the United States arsenal was[][]', 'Dwight Eisenhower.[]', 'Richard Nixon.[]', 'Jimmy Carter.[]', 'Ronald Reagan.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(923, 'Arms reduction talks were pushed onto the agenda of discussions between the twosuperpowers in the late 1980s due to all of the following reasons EXCEPT[][]', 'the rapid drive toward democracy in Eastern Europe.[]', 'Moscow\'s economic torpor.[]', 'the Pentagon\'s budgetary squeeze. Â´[]', 'President Reagan\'s consistent policy of detente.[]', 4, 1, 'hard'),
(924, 'The first American president to sign a treaty to reduce existing levels of nuclear weapons was[][]', 'Richard Nixon.[]', 'Jimmy Carter.[]', 'Ronald Reagan.[]', 'Bill Clinton. []', 3, 3, 'hard'),
(925, 'The Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty was the first accord[][]', 'on nuclear weapons signed between the United States and the Soviet Union.[]', 'to reduce current levels of nuclear weapons.[]', 'mandating the elimination of many long-range nuclear missiles.[]', 'to be rejected by the United States Senate. []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(926, 'The first American president to unilaterally dismantle some United States nuclear weaponswas[][]', 'Jimmy Carter.[]', 'Ronald Reagan.[]', 'George Bush.[]', 'Richard Nixon. []', 3, 1, 'hard'),
(927, 'An agreement between President Bush and President Yeltsin in January 1993 called for[][]', 'the total elimination of nuclear weapons in Europe.[]', 'elimination of over two-thirds of their long-range nuclear weapons.[]', 'a ban on all intermediate-range nuclear weapons.[]', 'an indefinite freeze on overall levels of nuclear weapons. []', 2, 3, 'hard'),
(928, 'Which instrument of foreign policy used to guarantee world dominance but no longer doesso?[][]', 'military strength[]', 'diplomacy[]', 'none of the above[]', 'all of the above []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(929, 'Economic sanctions are[][]', 'non-military sanctions imposed on a foreign government in an attempt to modify its behavior.[]', 'accomplished through the use of tariffs and quotas.[]', 'typically used as a second resort in an escalating military conflict.[]', 'an example of a last resort sanction. []', 1, 1, 'hard'),
(930, 'The primary means the United States has used to keep rogue nations from acquiring nuclearweapons has been by[][]', 'successful monitoring of the international arms market.[]', 'dramatically increasing foreign aid to rogue nations.[]', 'infiltrating the intelligence communities of the rogue nations.[]', 'encouraging nations to agree that they would not acquire, or at least test, nuclear weapons.[]', 4, 3, 'hard'),
(931, 'All of the following countries have agreed to give up their nuclear weapons EXCEPT[][]', 'Argentina.[]', 'Sweden.[]', 'North Korea.[]', 'Norway. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
(932, 'All of the following countries are seeking to acquire nuclear weapons EXCEPT[][]', 'Algeria.[]', 'Iraq.[]', 'North Korea.[]', 'none of the above []', 1, 3, 'hard'),
(933, 'The international economy today is one characterized by[][]', 'independence.[]', 'isolationism.[]', 'interdependence.[]', 'protectionism. []', 3, 2, 'hard'),
