(398, 'Which of the following did the Federal Election Campaign Act NOT do?[][]', 'require disclosure of campaign contributions by all candidates for federal offices[]', 'provide public financing for the presidential nominees of both major parties[]', 'provide public financing of House and Senate races[]', 'provide public financing of Senate races []', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(399, 'The administration of the campaign finance laws and the enforcement of compliance withtheir requirements is handled by the[][]', 'Fair Political Practices Commission.[]', 'Campaign Finance Bureau of the Department of the Treasury.[]', 'Department of Justice.[]', 'Federal Election Commission.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(400, 'The group responsible for administering and enforcing the Federal Election Campaign Act isthe[][]', 'Federal Election Commission (FEC).[]', 'Political Action Committee (PAC).[]', 'Federal Unethical Campaign Kommisars.[]', 'electoral college. []', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(401, 'According to the Federal Election Campaign Act, candidates must[][]', 'disclose who contributed to their campaigns, and how the money was spent.[]', 'apply for federal funds if they are running in a presidential election.[]', 'raise their own campaign funds.[]', 'all of the above []', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(402, 'The 1974 Federal Election Campaign Act[][]', 'placed legal limits on total campaign contributions.[]', 'placed legal limits on presidential campaign spending.[]', 'prohibited disclosure of campaign fund sources.[]', 'all of the above []', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(403, 'The funds allocated to public financing of presidential campaigns based on income taxcheck-offs have[][]', 'stayed at about the same level.[]', 'been ruled unconstitutional.[]', 'increased substantially.[]', 'decreased substantially.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(404, '________ resulted from an amendment in 1979 to the original Campaign Reform Act, whichallows parties to raise and spend money on voter registration and other campaign materialswithout limits on spending or the size of contributions that they can accept.[][]', 'Party discretionary funding[]', 'The party expenditure exemption[]', 'Soft money[]', 'Institutional assistance []', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(405, 'Donating $200,000 to a political party to help its presidential nominee in somewhat indirectways is[][]', 'legal, and known as soft money.[]', 'illegal under the McCain-Feingold Act.[]', 'legal, and known as a PAC contribution.[]', 'illegal under the Federal Election Campaign Act (FECA). []', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(406, 'One of the provisions of the McCain-Feingold Act of 2002 was to[][]', 'increase the limit on individual contributions to $5,000.[]', 'increase the amount of federal money presidential candidates can spend.[]', 'increase the limit on   soft money   contributions.[]', 'increase the limit on individual contributions from $1,000 to $2,000.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(407, 'Soft money consists of money[][]', 'provided through public financing.[]', 'for voter registration drives and campaign material at the grass-roots level.[]', 'that individuals contribute to their own campaign.[]', 'given directly to a candidate. []', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(408, 'The hydraulic theory says that money always finds a way to get around legal obstacles. Thus,when the soft money loophole was closed, how did money continue to find its way intopolitical campaigns?[][]', 'through the McCain-Feingold loophole[]', 'through dense money[]', 'through 527 Groups[]', 'through buying bulk purchases of books to avoid limits on campaign contributions []', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(409, 'PAC is an acronym for[][]', 'the Partisan Activities Commission.[]', 'political access conveyance.[]', 'political action committee.[]', 'positive action campaign. []', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(410, 'The McCain-Feingold Act of 2002 did all of the following EXCEPT[][]', 'barred groups from running   issue ad   within 60 days of a general election if they refer to a federal candidate and are not funded through a PAC.[]', 'banned soft money contributions.[]', 'increased the amount that individuals could give to candidates form $1,000 to $2,000.[]', 'none of the above []', 5, 2, 'medium'),
(411, 'PACs are[][]', 'committees formed to lobby government officials in behalf of their interests.[]', 'state commissions organized to reform campaign financing practices.[]', 'committees organized by interest groups to channel money to parties and candidates.[]', 'groups organized by political activists to increase voter participation. []', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(412, 'A very important ground rule concerning the behavior of political action committees is[][]', 'they are not allowed to contribute to presidential campaigns.[]', 'there are strict limits on the number of candidates each PAC can contribute to.[]', 'all expenditures must be meticulously accounted for to the FEC.[]', 'both A and D []', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(413, 'Critics of the PAC system are concerned that[][]', 'PACs are not regulated.[]', 'they tend to support only Republican candidates.[]', 'PACs are too weak and ineffective to contribute to a strong democracy.[]', 'PACs may control what the electoral winners do once in office. []', 5, 3, 'medium'),
(414, 'Defenders of PACs point out that they[][]', 'are limited to contributing only $1,000 per candidate.[]', 'can potentially buy votes.[]', 'have been very effective at enforcing campaign reform laws and reducing unethical campaign practices.[]', 'tend to support those who agree with them in the first place.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(415, 'Most PACs give money to[][]', 'candidates who disagree with them, but who are likely to be   bought.  []', 'candidates of only one political party.[]', 'candidates who already agree with them in the first place.[]', 'challengers trying to unseat incumbents. []', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(416, 'According to political scientist Gary Jacobson\'s research, a Congressional incumbent whospends a tremendous amount of money to get reelected[][]', 'is more likely to lose.[]', 'is likely to win by a landslide of over 70 percent of the vote.[]', 'is likely to get a higher percentage of the vote.[]', 'is no more or less likely to win than a candidate spending little money. []', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(417, 'Which of the following statements about Political Action Committees (PACs) is FALSE?[][]', 'All PAC expenditures must be meticulously accounted for to the FEC.[]', 'PACs have proliferated in recent years.[]', 'The influence of PACs is particularly important in presidential campaigns.[]', 'PACs contribute money before and after elections. []', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(418, 'The use of PAC money in presidential campaigns is[][]', 'particularly influential.[]', 'less important than in Congressional campaigns.[]', 'unregulated.[]', 'illegal. []', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(419, 'Research has shown that the cost of American election campaigns is[][]', 'high compared to other countries.[]', 'decreasing when the rising cost of living is taken into account.[]', 'per person, about the same as a DVD movie.[]', 'a national scandal. []', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(420, 'What bothers politicians most about the rising costs of high-tech campaigning is[][]', 'that fund-raising has come to take up so much of their precious time, distracting them from legislation.[]', 'they feel like whores who will do anything for a campaign contribution.[]', 'the increasing influence of PACs.[]', 'the declining number of PACs that they relied on for large campaign contributions. []', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(421, 'The relationship between campaign spending and electoral success is that[][]', 'spending more than your opponent does not assure victory.[]', 'the more incumbents spend, the more likely they are to be reelected.[]', 'the amount of money spent and winning are entirely unrelated.[]', 'none of the above []', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(422, 'Who opposes public financing of campaigns the most?[][]', 'liberals[]', 'conservatives[]', 'challengers[]', 'incumbents[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(423, 'Many political scientists believe that[][]', 'the size of a campaign war chest is the sole determinant of who wins elections.[]', 'most voters are immune to reinforcement or activation in a campaign, but are susceptible to conversion.[]', 'politicians overestimate the power of how important a good campaign is to victory.[]', 'politicians underestimate the power of how important a good campaign is to victory. []', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(424, 'Campaigns strengthen voter commitment to the usual party or the candidate they previouslysupported by emphasizing ________ as part of their campaign strategy.[][]', 'conversion[]', 'reinforcement[]', 'persuasion[]', 'direct mail []', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(425, 'Which of the following have been found to be most successfully affected by campaigns?[][]', 'conversion[]', 'reinforcement and activation[]', 'reinforcement and conversion[]', 'activation and conversion []', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(426, 'Campaigns are most effective in[][]', 'getting people to contribute time and money.[]', 'converting voters from one candidate to another.[]', 'reinforcing existing preferences toward candidates.[]', 'shaping how the media will portray a candidate to the public. []', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(427, 'Most people pay little attention to campaigns,[][]', 'and are as unfamiliar with the names of incumbents, as with the names of challengers.[]', 'and do not care about party identification of candidates.[]', 'and have a selective perception about events and candidates.[]', 'All of these are true. []', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(428, 'Which of the following factors weaken political campaigns ¹ effects on voters?[][]', 'selective perception, party identification, and incumbent name recognition[]', 'campaign expenditures, party identification, and incumbent name recognition[]', 'selective mobilization, party identification, and incumbent name recognition[]', 'selective mobilization, negative advertising and incumbent name recognition []', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(429, 'The selective perception of most voters means that they[][]', 'are susceptible to having their minds changed fairly easily by effective campaigns.[]', 'make rational choices about the purposive benefits to themselves of voting for a particular candidate.[]', 'keep a fairly open mind regarding the candidates during the election campaign, and choose based on rational analysis.[]', 'pay most attention to things they already agree with, and interpret events according to their own predispositions.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(430, 'America\'s party nomination system could best be described as[][]', 'open and entrepreneurial.[]', 'informal, but rational.[]', 'a meritocracy.[]', 'an apprenticeship system. []', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(431, 'The process of selecting America\'s leaders has almost no downtime before it revs up all overagain. This is referred to as[][]', 'the permanent campaign.[]', 'revolving elections.[]', 'election mania.[]', 'accountability. []', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(432, 'Throughout American history, presidential campaigns have become[][]', 'dirtier and dirtier.[]', 'shorter and shorter.[]', 'more and more secretive.[]', 'more and more democratic.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(433, 'Compared to most other democratic systems, nominations and campaigns in the United States[][]', 'require less commitment of time on the part of the candidate.[]', 'are decided more by party bosses than the general public.[]', 'tend to be more open.[]', 'involve less money. []', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(434, 'Party outsiders have ________ getting elected in the United States than in other countries.[][]', 'about the same chance of[]', 'no chance of[]', 'a much easier time[]', 'a much less likely chance of []', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(435, 'The fact that candidates must tailor their appeals to the particular interest of each major statetends to result in[][]', 'numerous campaign promises adding up to new government programs.[]', 'limiting the scope of government.[]', 'a more open and democratic process.[]', 'a tilt toward states ¹ rights at the expense of the national government. []', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(436, 'Legitimacy in terms of American elections means[][]', 'the public is satisfied with the qualifications and the policy positions of the candidates.[]', 'the public is nearly unanimously happy with the results.[]', 'the election is nearly unanimously accepted as a fair and free method to select political leaders.[]', 'the best candidate is selected. []', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(437, 'Elections in the United States perform which of the following functions?[][]', 'make or ratify legislation[]', 'select party nominees[]', 'select officeholders from among party nominees[]', 'all of the above []', 5, 3, 'medium'),
(438, 'Which of the following functions do elections LEAST serve?[][]', 'selecting public officials[]', 'making and coordinating public policy[]', 'providing legitimacy to the political system[]', 'connecting citizens to government officials []', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(439, 'California\'s famous Proposition 13, in which voters frustrated by a lack of action by theirlegislature forced an issue on the ballot and voted to limit the rise in property taxes, was anexample of[][]', 'a direct primary.[]', 'an indirect primary.[]', 'an initiative.[]', 'a voter override. []', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(440, 'California\'s Proposition 209, which intended to end affirmative action programs in the state, isan example of[][]', 'a direct primary.[]', 'an indirect primary.[]', 'an initiative.[]', 'a voter override. []', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(441, 'Daniel Smith argues that initiatives typically stem from[][]', 'broad public demand for the policy.[]', 'the actions of a dedicated policy entrepreneur.[]', 'responsive elected officials, working in coalition.[]', 'none of the above []', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(442, 'The initiative is put on the ballot as a result of[][]', 'the governor\'s order.[]', 'a Supreme Court ruling.[]', 'a petition signed by a certain percentage of the voters in the previous election.[]', 'a special, legally constituted convention voting to place it there. []', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(443, 'Of the following, which is the most direct form of democracy?[][]', 'initiative[]', 'direct primary[]', 'presidential election[]', 'recall []', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(444, 'Examples of issues addressed in recent initiatives include all of the following EXCEPT[][]', 'ending affirmative action.[]', 'setting maximum claim sizes.[]', 'paying college graduates to reside in a state for a number of years.[]', 'election day registration.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(445, 'An election whereby voters are given the chance to approve or disapprove some legislative actor constitutional amendment is called[][]', 'a referendum.[]', 'a direct primary.[]', 'a direct election.[]', 'a ratification election. []', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(446, 'Which of the following is NOT true about elections in American society?[][]', 'They socialize and institutionalize political activity.[]', 'They provide regular access to political power.[]', 'They are accepted as legitimate, fair, and free methods to select political leaders.[]', 'The vast majority of eligible citizens cast ballots, even for local races.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(447, 'In the 1800 election presidential candidates were nominated by[][]', 'their parties ¹ elected representatives in Congress.[]', 'their parties ¹ voters in primary elections.[]', 'the electoral college.[]', 'the president. []', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(448, 'Which of the following statements about the 1800 presidential election is TRUE?[][]', 'The 1800 election was ultimately decided in the House of Representatives.[]', 'For the first time the focus of the 1800 election was on the citizen voters.[]', 'The candidates in the 1800 election vigorously campaigned in each of the states.[]', 'all of the above []', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(449, 'The election of 1800 was[][]', 'decided by the direct vote of the people.[]', 'decided by the electoral college.[]', 'decided by the House of Representatives.[]', 'decided by the full Congress. []', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(450, 'The presidential election of 1800 was[][]', 'the first use of direct primaries in the United States.[]', 'decided by the House of Representatives after a tie in the electoral college.[]', 'notable for the importance of key convention speeches to swing the votes in the electoral eollege.[]', 'the first transition of power between parties accomplished by voters ¹ ballots in the history of the world.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(451, 'The presidential election of 1800 represents the first[][]', 'use of party nominating conventions.[]', 'time the Senate elected the president.[]', 'use of the electoral college.[]', 'peaceful transfer of power in the world between parties via the electoral process.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(452, 'In the original constitutional system,[][]', 'each presidential elector cast two ballots and the top vote-getter was named president and the runner-up became vice president.[]', 'each presidential elector cast one ballot for one of the president/vice president teams running.[]', 'the state legislatures elected the president and vice president, with the candidate getting the second most votes becoming vice president.[]', 'the president, once elected by the electoral college, chose the vice president. []', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(453, 'Which of the following is TRUE of the presidential election of 1800?[][]', 'The candidates traveled throughout the smaller number of United States at the time to campaign for votes.[]', 'It was a gentlemanly contest in which partisans on both sides showed respect for the opposition.[]', 'It was carefully and objectively covered in the newspapers of the day, with logical reasoning and respect for both candidates in articles and editorials.[]', 'It was the first peaceful transfer of power between parties via the electoral process in the history of the world.[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(454, 'In the electoral college vote in the election of 1800, there was a tie between[][]', 'Thomas Jefferson and John Adams.[]', 'John Adams and James Madison.[]', 'John Adams and Aaron Burr.[]', 'Thomas Jefferson and Aaron Burr.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(455, 'The issue of free silver (to increase the amount of currency in circulation) was championed inthe election of 1896 by ________, whose most famous oration was his   Cross of Gold   speech atthe Democratic national convention.[][]', 'Grover Cleveland[]', 'William McKinley[]', 'William Jennings Bryan[]', 'Woodrow Wilson []', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(456, 'In 1896, who liked silver money?[][]', 'debtors[]', 'exporters[]', 'Eastern manufacturers[]', 'coin collectors and dealers []', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(457, 'The first peaceful transfer of power between parties via the electoral process in the history ofthe world occurred as a result of the presidential election of[][]', '1796.[]', '1800.[]', '1896.[]', '1789. []', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(458, 'The election of 1896 was largely fought over the issue of[][]', 'war.[]', 'economics.[]', 'government corruption.[]', 'the ownership of land in the west. []', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(459, 'Which of the following statements about the election of 1896 is FALSE?[][]', 'The main issue in the election of 1896 was the gold standard and tariffs.[]', 'William Jennings Bryan broke with tradition and campaigned extensively in person.[]', 'The election resulted in the Democrats becoming firmly entrenched as the majority party in the Northeast and Midwest.[]', 'none of the above []', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(460, 'The winner of the presidential election of 1896 was[][]', 'Theodore Roosevelt.[]', 'William McKinley.[]', 'William Jennings Bryan.[]', 'Ulysses Grant. []', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(461, 'The election of 1896 left a legacy of a political alignment that endured for several decades,wherein[][]', 'the Democrats won the more populous Northeast and Midwest, and the Republicans won in the South and West.[]', 'the Democrats won the South and West, while the Republicans won in the more populous Northeast and Midwest.[]', 'the Democrats won in the Northeast and West, while the Republicans won in the Northeast and South.[]', 'the Republicans swept the South, and the Democrats won in all other regions. []', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(462, 'Because Bush\'s lead over Gore in the initial count was less than one-tenth of one percent,Florida law mandated[][]', 'that the Florida state legislature vote to declare Bush the winner.[]', 'the outcome of the election be determined by the Florida Supreme Court.[]', 'the Secretary of State to certify the results.[]', 'an automatic recount.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(463, 'In Bush v. Gore (2000), the United States Supreme Court ruled that[][]', 'the Florida Supreme Court did not have jurisdiction over the presidential election legal issues.[]', 'although a recount was legal, the same (or more precise) standards for evaluating ballots would have to be applied in all counties.[]', 'the time used to recount ballots could extend past December 12, when the Florida electors would meet.[]', 'punch card ballots were illegal if not used in all counties. []', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(464, 'According to exit polls, ________ was a major reason voters selected Bush in 2004.[][]', 'welfare reform[]', 'health care reform[]', 'the war on terrorism[]', 'strategic voting []', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(465, 'In the 2004 election, John Kerry won votes among those most concerned with[][]', 'the economy, health care, and education.[]', 'the environment, the economy, and transportation issues.[]', 'the environment and urban affairs.[]', 'civil rights, the environment, and the economy. []', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(466, 'Suffrage means[][]', 'the right to vote.[]', 'voting for the winner.[]', 'voting for the loser.[]', 'the struggle for equal rights for women. []', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(467, 'Which of the following is TRUE about American elections over the past 100 years?[][]', 'The suffrage has broadened, and the turnout has increased.[]', 'The suffrage has broadened, and the turnout has decreased.[]', 'The suffrage has narrowed, and the turnout has decreased.[]', 'Suffrage has broadened, but there has been no change in turnout. []', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(468, 'Suffrage refers to[][]', 'a type of election unique to the United States.[]', 'the right to vote.[]', 'voter turnout rates.[]', 'voting procedures in the electoral college. []', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(469, 'As the right to vote has been extended,[][]', 'voter turnout has increased proportionately.[]', 'proportionately fewer of those eligible have chosen to vote.[]', 'voter turnout has actually remained about the same.[]', 'the scope of American government has shrunk. []', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(470, 'The nearly two centuries of American electoral history has been characterized by[][]', 'consistently close elections.[]', 'increasing voter turnouts.[]', 'expansion of the right to vote.[]', 'all of the above []', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(471, 'The high point of voter turnout in the United States was in[][]', '1896.[]', '1972.[]', '1968.[]', '1960. []', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(472, 'People are more likely to vote for all of the following reasons EXCEPT if they[][]', 'have a high sense of civic duty.[]', 'have a high sense of political efficacy.[]', 'are able to see policy differences that affect their interests.[]', 'believe that some policies of one party are balanced by other policies of the other party.[]', 4, 3, 'medium'),
(473, 'Anthony Downs ¹ theory of rational voting behavior predicts that people will vote if they[][]', 'can afford the time and energy to do so.[]', 'think one party will give them more policy benefits than the other.[]', 'identify with a particular candidate, even though they doubt that one vote can make a difference.[]', 'feel obligated to do so. []', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(474, 'Those largely indifferent to the results of an election, but who decide to vote anyway to showsupport for democratic government are called ________ voters.[][]', 'guilt-driven[]', 'civic-duty[]', 'patriotic disaffected[]', 'disaffected []', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(475, 'The greater one\'s sense of political efficacy, the[][]', 'less likely one is to vote.[]', 'more likely one is to vote.[]', 'less likely one is to view the election process in the United States as legitimate.[]', 'more likely one is to see differences between the parties. []', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(476, 'Political efficacy refers to the belief that[][]', 'the costs of voting outweigh the benefits.[]', 'significant policy differences exist between the parties.[]', 'one should always support democratic government.[]', 'ordinary people can influence the government.[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(477, 'Largely to prevent corruption associated with stuffing ballot boxes, states adopted ________around the turn of the twentieth century.[][]', 'the electoral college[]', 'primary elections[]', 'voting machines[]', 'voter registration[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(478, 'Voter registration was begun around the turn of the twentieth century[][]', 'to encourage voting through advance notice.[]', 'by party bosses to discourage people from voting.[]', 'to make elections more ethical.[]', 'to discourage patronage. []', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(479, 'Compared to other countries, the United States holds ________ elections for various offices.[][]', 'far fewer[]', 'somewhat fewer[]', 'about the same number of[]', 'more[]', 4, 2, 'medium'),
(480, 'A major reason cited for America\'s level of voter turnout compared to other industrializedcountries is[][]', 'bad weather in certain parts of the United States on election day.[]', 'greater interest in democracy in the United States.[]', 'registration is more cumbersome in the United States.[]', 'Americans ¹ high sense of political efficacy. []', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(481, 'Compared to other industrialized democracies, the United States has a ________ voter turnout.[][]', 'much higher[]', 'slightly higher[]', 'slightly lower[]', 'much lower[]', 4, 1, 'medium'),
(482, 'Which of the following countries has a lower voter turnout rate than the United States?[][]', 'Australia[]', 'Great Britain[]', 'Switzerland[]', 'France []', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(483, 'Which of the following countries has the lowest voter turnout rate?[][]', 'Australia[]', 'United States[]', 'France[]', 'Bulgaria []', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(484, 'Voter turnout in the United States is much lower than in other countries in part because[][]', 'of the unique American requirement of voter registration.[]', 'Americans vote for fewer political offices and lack a sense of political efficacy.[]', 'the choice offered Americans is greater than in other countries, which confuses potential voters.[]', 'of the strident positions taken by the parties, which alienate middle-of-the-road voters. []', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(485, 'Which of the following statements is FALSE?[][]', 'Unlike the United States, the governments of most democracies take the responsibility of seeing to it that all of their eligible citizens are on the voting lists.[]', 'American government asks citizens to vote far more often than most democracies.[]', 'Americans are expected to vote for a much narrower range of political offices than most democracies.[]', 'none of the above []', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(486, 'Which of these would be most likely to vote?[][]', 'a well-educated, middle-aged government worker[]', 'a well-educated senior citizen who used to work for a big corporation[]', 'a young southern high school teacher[]', 'a middle-aged professor at a private university []', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(487, 'Which of the following is INCORRECT?[][]', 'Congress requires voter registration nationwide.[]', 'In North Dakota, you don ¹t have to register to vote.[]', 'In a few states, you can register to vote on election day.[]', 'Some states let you register at supermarkets. []', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(488, 'Among the states that allow voter registration at the polls on election day, voter turnout ratesare[][]', 'higher than in other states.[]', 'no different than in other states.[]', 'lower than the national average.[]', 'declining over time and at a higher rate than in other states. []', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(489, 'Approximately how many states allow voters to register at the polls on election day?[][]', '6[]', '34[]', '44[]', '49 []', 1, 2, 'medium'),
(490, 'The impact of the Motor Voter Act of 1993 was evidenced in[][]', 'higher registration and higher turnout in 1996 and 2000.[]', 'higher registration and lower turnout in 1996 and 2000.[]', 'lower registration and higher turnout in 1996 and 2000.[]', 'none of the above []', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(491, 'The group of people with the lowest voter turnout rate is[][]', 'college graduates.[]', 'young people.[]', 'senior citizens over 70.[]', 'union members. []', 2, 2, 'medium'),
(492, 'According to the text, the most important factor affecting voter turnout is[][]', 'education.[]', 'ideology.[]', 'race.[]', 'geography. []', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(493, 'Highly educated individuals are more likely to vote because[][]', 'they are smarter.[]', 'they see more policy differences between candidates.[]', 'most of them are white males.[]', 'they have more influence. []', 2, 3, 'medium'),
(494, 'Which of the following statements about voter participation is FALSE?[][]', 'As people age, their likelihood of voting increases.[]', 'Minority groups with high levels of income and education have a higher turnout rate than whites with comparable status.[]', 'Men are more likely to vote than women.[]', 'none of the above []', 3, 1, 'medium'),
(495, 'Which of the following characteristics would make one more likely to vote in an election?[][]', 'having a college degree[]', 'having a low income[]', 'being a college student[]', 'bring a welfare recipient []', 1, 3, 'medium'),
(496, 'The mandate theory of elections[][]', 'is based on the economic theory of rational decision making.[]', 'explains voters ¹ decisions according to an evaluation of the candidates ¹ personality.[]', 'says that people vote for candidates because they want them to carry out certain policies.[]', 'is based on the sociological theory of irrational behaviorism. []', 3, 3, 'medium'),
(497, 'The mandate theory of elections is most often cited as the proper way to view elections by[][]', 'the defeated candidate.[]', 'the winning candidate.[]', 'everybody.[]', 'the media. []', 2, 1, 'medium'),
(498, 'The mandate theory of elections is the idea that[][]', 'a candidate must get at least sixty percent of the vote to win.[]', 'a candidate must get a majority of the votes cast (fifty percent plus one) in order to take office.[]', 'the election winner has authorization from the voters to carry out his or her promised policies.[]', 'a candidate must get at least seventy-five percent of the vote to win. []', 3, 2, 'medium'),
(499, '________ are crucial for many voters because they provide a regular perspective throughwhich voters can view the political world.[][]', 'Party identifications[]', 'Direct primary elections[]', 'Initiative petitions[]', 'Party platforms []', 1, 1, 'medium'),
(500, 'Political scientists tend to focus on each of the following major elements of voters ¹ decisionsEXCEPT[][]', 'voters ¹ party identification.[]', 'voters ¹ ideology and world view.[]', 'the match between voters ¹ policy positions and those of the candidates and parties.[]', 'none of the above []', 2, 2, 'medium');
